<title>Jan_1993: Re: Suicide and Adventism</title>
<h1>Re: Suicide and Adventism</h1>
Marcus Stringer (<i>marcuss@microsoft.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 20 Jan 93 23:17:40 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#76">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#76">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#76">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#76">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0077.html">Ron Vyhmeister: "Directory"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0075.html">Ralf Simonsson: "Re: Suicide and Adventism"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0060.html">Ralf Simonsson: "Suicide and Adventism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Some of our colleges attempt to offer support through their counseling <br>
centers or Social Work departments.  There's a stigma to that however.  <br>
We expect everyone to be perfect, so very few cash in on these services <br>
because that is admitting that we aren't perfect.  Another obstacle is <br>
that many counselors fear to give alternative suggestions which are not <br>
sanctioned by the church (constituents would threaten to take their <br>
funds out of the college or academy), and their jobs would be at risk.<br>
So we end up with cowardly counseling, slaves to what others say they <br>
should do.  Our pastors aren't adequately trained (and shouldn't be <br>
required to) in the indepth details of every issue.  God gives others <br>
gifts to fill that responsibility.<br>
<p>
However, because we give seminarians, a crash course in Christian <br>
ethics, just short of graduation (after we've entangled them in years <br>
of redisposing scripture to what the church has already make a <br>
conclusion on), and expect them to be competent  counselors in all <br>
issues, in addition to being on their knees in prayer for the saints, <br>
and visiting everyone, and heading all the church boards; we end up <br>
giving our children pat answers to complex issues (band-aids for <br>
ulcers).  This is a PASSIONATE issue<br>
for me because I quit two of our schools Social Work programs because <br>
of it.  I love my church,<br>
many times I'm happy with it, many times I'm angry with it.  And this <br>
love is the reason that I pray this system of denial, and <br>
"holier-than-thou-ness" find a swift death.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
