<title>Jan_1993: inspiration</title>
<h1>inspiration</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 20 Jan 1993 18:35:39 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#81">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#81">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#81">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#81">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0082.html">Steven Timm: "Mailing list management programs"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0080.html">Russell Grau: "Re: Directory"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[A message from Sherman Cox]<br>
	I would like to know if anyone has read the book "Inspiration" by<br>
Alden Thompson.  In it he talks of the implications of our belief<br>
in thought inspiration.  I believe sometimes we as adventists give<br>
lip service to the idea of thought inspiration, but in reality when<br>
we speak about our ideas it realy is verbal inspiration.  <br>
<p>
	I may be speaking out of turn since the things that are being<br>
discussed right now is abortion and suicide.  If so please <br>
forgive me.<br>
<pre>
-- 
<p>
"All things are possible to him that believeth."
<p>
Sherman H. Cox, II       scox@uahcs2.cs.uah.edu
<p>
[Inspiration is always in order to discuss around here, you need never feel
that you must wait your turn to bring up a topic.  I have read and enjoyed
Alden Thompson's book.  An earlier attempt to discuss it here never got 
off the ground.  Let's try again.  SCT]
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
