<title>Jan_1993: Mailing list management programs</title>
<h1>Mailing list management programs</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 20 Jan 1993 18:42:21 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#82">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#82">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#82">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#82">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0083.html">Steven Timm: "Help us find these people"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0081.html">Steven Timm: "inspiration"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
My experience of a couple weeks ago, recovering from a corrupted list, <br>
has given me a desire to automate the process somewhat so the chance <br>
for human error will be reduced next time.  Of course the quintessential<br>
mailing list program is LISTSERV, which is used by SDA-L, but I'm <br>
not aware of a version of this that's available for a unix platform such<br>
as the ones I use.  If one were available, SDA-L would now be running <br>
out of LaSierra instead of LLUVM.<br>
<p>
Typical tasks would include adding and deleting users, managing vacations,<br>
printing out a directory automatically, (instead of manually with all <br>
the associated typos).  If anyone is aware of such a program, please let<br>
me know, otherwise it will be time to dust off the C I never yet have learned<br>
and work on one for myself.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
