<title>Jan_1993: Verbal Inspiration</title>
<h1>Verbal Inspiration</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 21 Jan 1993 22:24:07 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#86">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#86">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#86">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#86">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0087.html">Steven Timm: "Inspiration"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0085.html">Steve Hix: "Re: inspiration"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0092.html">Tim Swensen: "Re:  Verbal Inspiration"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In Alden Thompson's book _Inspiration_ there is a revealing section in <br>
which a book by M. Wilcox about inspiration in the 1920's is compared <br>
with what Ellen G. White herself wrote about inspiration.  Wilcox<br>
holds to a strict verbal inspiration view, while Ellen G. White did not.<br>
It's clear that after the death of Ellen G. White in the 1910's and 1920's,<br>
Seventh-day Adventism became much more fundamentalist than before, following<br>
the rise of fundamentalism in general.  These were the days of the Red Scare<br>
and the Monkey Trial, days in which G. MacReady Price rose up to attack <br>
evolution.  Unfortunately the chapters on inspiration from Selected Messages,<br>
vol I. weren't published until the 1950's, I believe.  MAybe the church<br>
wasn't ready for them.<br>
<p>
It is difficult to argue positions like this, because when one admits<br>
that a writing is not verbally inspired, it becomes more difficult to <br>
use that writing as a club against someone else.  You can never club <br>
someone into tolerance.<br>
<p>
Alden Thompson's book deals mostly with examples from the Bible.<br>
Without telling you what he says about the topic, I suggest that you <br>
turn to each of the four Gospels and read the recorded inscription<br>
on the cross.<br>
<p>
One of his major points is to be sure to not make claims for the Bible<br>
that it does not make for itself.  One of my major points is that<br>
even the claims that the Bible does make for itself should not be taken<br>
as postulates, but rather put into practice and proven.  In this,<br>
unfortunately, I differ with the Statement of Fundamental Beliefs,<br>
which takes as its starting postulate the inspiration of the Bible.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
