<!-- name="Steven Timm" -->
<!-- email="st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<!-- subject="Inspiration" -->
<!-- id="8fLqLeW00YUoILRF8V@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Jan_1993: Inspiration</title>
<h1>Inspiration</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 21 Jan 1993 22:11:38 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#87">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#87">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#87">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#87">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0088.html">Steven Timm: "SDA-L: Updated Directory, one more time"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0086.html">Steven Timm: "Verbal Inspiration"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[A message from Paul Johnston sent through Sharon Johnston's account<br>
and edited by me to shorten the too-long lines  SCT]<br>
<p>
Sherman Cox, you may be onto something.  There's been a vague but<br>
annoying puzzle on my mind.  You've nicely articulated it, and I'm<br>
grateful.  After reading Alden Thomson's book on inspiration, you<br>
wondered if--though we Adventists officially believe in a more general<br>
thought inspiration--we actually presuppose specific, verbal inspiration<br>
of scripture when discussing particular issues.<br>
     Our theological documents, especially statements about biblical<br>
inspiration, are models of a moderate or centrist position.  But so many<br>
of us look like, behave like, demand like, think simplistically and<br>
concretely like rightist fundamentalists.  I've long wondered why.  Your<br>
rhetorical question illuminates the discrepancy.<br>
     I guess what's scary for some people is that, the further you get<br>
away from a fundamentalist view of inspiration, the more one has to deal<br>
with interpretation.  And THAT is the human component of the<br>
communication process.  The human component, of course, is also the more<br>
variable and fallible one.<br>
     This has all sorts of fallout.  If there's room for a good deal of<br>
variability or misunderstanding in interpreting divine texts, then the<br>
reader has to be awfully humble about the hermeneutical task.  It's much<br>
easier to be dogmatic if you're a fundamentalist.  It's much easier to<br>
feel the call to expunge the errors of others if you believe there's<br>
little room for error in your interpretive process.<br>
     For a few months, our congregation here in Pittsburgh had a Bible<br>
worker assisting the pastors.  He was from the South and is one of our<br>
more fundamentalist Adventist brothers.  Sharon and I had him over for<br>
dinner.  He and I had in common our backgrounds as journalists and a<br>
love for music.  Good thing.  Because it was almost impossible for us to<br>
discuss religion.  The gulf was wide.<br>
     I tried to avoid discussing religion with him.  But there were so<br>
many burning convictions with this fellow, he couldn't keep quiet.  Yet,<br>
whatever the topic was, we kept coming to one unavoidable issue.  That<br>
was how it is that divinity and humanity interact in the reading of<br>
scripture.<br>
     He said over and over again, "Bruthuh, when ah read the Bible, it<br>
is the Word of God speaking to me.  It's not interpretion."<br>
     "But," said I, "our cultural backgrounds are different.  Our life<br>
experiences have shaped us into two distinctly different people with<br>
different needs and priorities.  We'll see things differently, including<br>
the Bible."<br>
     He countered, "The Holy Spirit anoints our eyes when we read the<br>
Word.  He..." it was a HE "...will show me what's important.  He has<br>
shown the whole church what is important.  It's there in black and<br>
white."<br>
     "No," I said, "the Spirit works on you when you read the Bible and<br>
the Spirit works on me when I read the Bible.  It's the same Spirit,<br>
isn't it?  It's the same Bible, isn't it?  But we come to varied<br>
conclusions on some questions that are important to you.  There are even<br>
differences in what we think the important questions are."  (He'd said<br>
Adventist ministers are off the mark these days because "they are<br>
preaching too much Ephesians and not enough Revelation."  I wondered if<br>
the reverse was true.)  "So," I continued, "the Holy Spirit isn't<br>
misleading one of us.  It's simply that our experiences and needs are<br>
leading us to different, ummm, interpretations."<br>
     "But then you must be wrong.  The Bible is the Word of God.  The<br>
Holy Spirit isn't going to tell you and me different things."  We were<br>
back where we'd started.<br>
     Most of the conflict between the denomination and independent<br>
Adventist organizations is similar to his and mine--but less amiable,<br>
unfortunately.  The NAD document discussed on SDAnet by David, Randell,<br>
Tony, and others is in the end less about tithe and even about<br>
ecclesiastical authority and more about the nature of inspiration and<br>
the nature of dogma.<br>
     Gilbert Bailey was less clumsy in his summary than me.  But, yeah,<br>
he caught one important theme:  tolerating diversity.  I, too, read that<br>
document as a plea for toleration.  (Get this straight--my<br>
interpretation is the right one here.)  As the son of a seminary<br>
professer, I have to tell you it's great for a change.  That used to be<br>
our theologians' plea to officialdom.<br>
     On the other hand, I can understand why people may want to tighten<br>
a few nuts and bolts doctrinally.  Because, as I've said before on this<br>
network, distinctiveness and identity are pretty much the same thing. <br>
And it's hard for an organization to grow if it has an identity crisis. <br>
We certainly do have one.<br>
     Catching up on the net's correspondence, it seems many of us are<br>
trying to identify "church," especially our church, and to suggest ways<br>
out of our quandry.<br>
     Marcus, you suggest that "these 'devisive' groups have sprung up<br>
because the church has failed to move in meeting the needs of the<br>
people."  Why should we consider something a failure if it has indeed<br>
met the needs of SOME people?  Do we Adventists have to so often assume<br>
that one church--our church--should do it all?<br>
     Bill Nickless, why does the church have to be "the true church" to<br>
merit our support?  I support Shadyside Seventh-Day Adventist Church in<br>
Pittsburgh.  I also support St. Andrew's Episcopal Church.  I support<br>
them both, not because they are true, but because they are good.  They<br>
fulfil different needs in my spiritual walk.  I like them.<br>
     Another suggested applying a number of principles from "our<br>
prophet."  For instance, we were admonished to remember that "those who<br>
are inclined to regard their individual judgement as supreme are in<br>
grave peril."  I have never met anyone who considered his or her<br>
judgement as supreme.  But--and this brings us back to the topic of<br>
inspiration--it seems one's judgment is supremely unavoidable.<br>
     I for one would hate to see SDA members adopting a Mormon-like view<br>
of leadership and unity.  It does not, as one networker suggested, "make<br>
everything simpler."  It only makes things more totalitarian and<br>
uniform.  I speak as a former resident of Salt Lake City and employee of<br>
Brigham Young University (of which I have numerous FOND memories as<br>
well).<br>
     No.  The tension of unity and diversity has been with the Church<br>
since St. Paul's day at least.  It has to remain with us as we ride the<br>
shifting paradigms of social and intellectual evolution.  Do you think<br>
our denomination can find a niche?  Survive?  Thrive?<br>
     Sorry.  That's not a rhetorical question.<br>
<p>
Paul Johnston<br>
WQED-FM, Pittsburgh<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
