<title>Jan_1993: Inspiration/Interpretation</title>
<h1>Inspiration/Interpretation</h1>
Gilbert Bailey (<i>gilbertb@lsid.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 22 Jan 93 11:15:45 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#91">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#91">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#91">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#91">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0092.html">Tim Swensen: "Re:  Verbal Inspiration"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0090.html">Fred Christiansen: "sources for OnLine Bible (excellent PC freeware)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
1 Cor 13:12, in part, says "now we see through a glass darkly, but then<br>
face to face".  To me this darkness is in part caused by our life experiences.<br>
In other words, the distortion (interpretation) of the 'truth' on the other<br>
side of the glass is subject to our life experiences.  This is why we ought<br>
to tolerate differing views.  It seems to me that the sum of differing views<br>
is a clearer picture, although not perfect, of the 'whole truth' than any<br>
single view alone.  That the SDA church with it's cultural, social and <br>
economic diversity can agree on major doctrinal points after prayerful<br>
study lends support to the truth of those doctrines.<br>
<p>
To me a dogmatic approach, by providing absolute answers, eliminates <br>
questioning that can lead to positive spiritual growth.  It also could<br>
lead to the rejection of 'new light'.<br>
<p>
I'm really enjoying the posts on inspiration.  Keep it up everyone !!!<br>
<p>
I've also enjoyed the 'biographical/autobiographical sketches' of SDAnet    <br>
subscriber's. Here's mine, and I would encourage all share their own.<br>
Maybe Steve could include them in the SDAnet directory.<br>
<p>
I'm process suppport technician at the Lake Stevens Instrument Div. of<br>
Hewlett Packard, in Everett, WA.  My major responsibility at HP is the <br>
development of hardware and software for incircuit/functional test of printed<br>
circuit assemblies.  My home church is Marysville, WA.  Lynda, my wife, and I<br>
have lived in Marysville/Lake Stevens since graduation from Walla Walla College<br>
in 1982 (BS BioMedical Electronics).  We have two children, Greg (5) and <br>
Stephanie (3).<br>
<p>
<pre>
--
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
| Gilbert Bailey                         Mail Stop: 35                       |
| Hewlett Packard Co.                    (206) 335-2290 TELNET 335-2290      |
| Lake Stevens Instrument Div.           UNIX: gilbertb@hplsla.lsid.hp.com   |
| 8600 Soper Hill Rd.                    DoD#3006, '83 Honda GL650           |
| Everett, WA.  98205-1298               N7WVH in the great NorthWET !!!     |
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
