<title>Jan_1993: Re:  Verbal Inspiration</title>
<h1>Re:  Verbal Inspiration</h1>
Tim Swensen (<i>swensen@ecn.purdue.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 22 Jan 93 10:54:05 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#92">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#92">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#92">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#92">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0093.html">Sherman Cox: "health"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0091.html">Gilbert Bailey: "Inspiration/Interpretation"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0086.html">Steven Timm: "Verbal Inspiration"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0094.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  Verbal Inspiration"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve,<br>
<p>
I have read more than once on this net your statement that we should not<br>
postulate that which may be proven.  In principle, this is very appealing.<br>
The system with fewer axioms, and more theorems is to be preferred.  But as<br>
a practical matter, how are we to prove (deduce, or whatever other term <br>
you choose to use) the inspiration of the Bible?  Would an acceptable<br>
method of proof be to follow all principles given in scripture and <br>
personally experience the results promised therin?  Would this be sufficient<br>
as a proof?  Is it always necessary to see the promised benefits accrue?  <br>
<p>
It seems to me that God invites us "prove" the truthfulness of his word by<br>
comparing it to our own experience.  (O taste and see that the Lord is good.)<br>
However, there are times when faith in His word will be necessary to <br>
see beyond present difficulties.  So is a proof based on experience (ours and<br>
others') enough?  Or is it even desireable to view the inspiration of<br>
scripture as a theorem (proveable) rather than as an axiom (accepted without<br>
proof).<br>
<p>
Please elaborate Steve.<br>
<p>
Thanks,<br>
Tim Swensen<br>
swensen@ecn.purdue.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
