Tim Swensen writes:<br>
<i>&gt;I have read more than once on this net your statement that we should not</i><br>
<i>&gt;postulate that which may be proven.  In principle, this is very appealing.</i><br>
<i>&gt;The system with fewer axioms, and more theorems is to be preferred.  But as</i><br>
<i>&gt;a practical matter, how are we to prove (deduce, or whatever other term </i><br>
<i>&gt;you choose to use) the inspiration of the Bible?  Would an acceptable</i><br>
<i>&gt;method of proof be to follow all principles given in scripture and </i><br>
<i>&gt;personally experience the results promised therin?  Would this be sufficient</i><br>
<i>&gt;as a proof?  Is it always necessary to see the promised benefits accrue?  </i><br>
<p>
I think you have hit on something here, Tim.  Surely this is a sufficient<br>
condition but maybe it is not necessary.  I would not suggest that <br>
because some have tried this and failed, that God's word is not true.<br>
However, there are many in the world who would say this.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;It seems to me that God invites us "prove" the truthfulness of his word by</i><br>
<i>&gt;comparing it to our own experience.  (O taste and see that the Lord is good.)</i><br>
<i>&gt;However, there are times when faith in His word will be necessary to </i><br>
<i>&gt;see beyond present difficulties.  So is a proof based on experience (ours and</i><br>
<i>&gt;others') enough?  Or is it even desireable to view the inspiration of</i><br>
<i>&gt;scripture as a theorem (proveable) rather than as an axiom (accepted without</i><br>
<i>&gt;proof).</i><br>
<p>
I agree that sometimes faith is necessary.  I believe, however, that faith<br>
is built up by just such a procedure of tasting and seeing.  We trust God's<br>
word in those things which we cannot verify because we have proven it to <br>
be effective in those areas which we can test it out.<br>
<p>
Furthermore, the act of proving God's Word itself requires faith.  God<br>
does not say "I will show you all the evidence you need to believe."<br>
The postulate of inspiration of the Word must be replaced with the <br>
postulate "He that cometh  to God must believe that He is, and that He<br>
is a rewarder of them that diligently seek Him."<br>
<p>
In short faith in the Bible as God's Word can be gained by experiential<br>
proof, but experiential proof is available only to those who have faith <br>
in God.<br>
<p>
On a related note, another postulate we often make when studying the <br>
Bible is assuming that the whole structure of Western logic holds true <br>
lock, stock, and barrel.  Really there's no reason why it should.<br>
After all, Christ's call "Blessed are those who have not seen, and yet<br>
believed" is essentially a call to circular reasoning.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
