<title>Jan_1993: Re:  Verbal Inspiration</title>
<h1>Re:  Verbal Inspiration</h1>
Dave Thomas (<i>umsfdtho@deimos.oscs.montana.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 22 Jan 93 21:31:57 -0700</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#96">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#96">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#96">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#96">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0097.html">David Plaisted: "Inspiration"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0095.html">David E. Johnson: "SDA-L: Updated Directory, one more time"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0086.html">Steven Timm: "Verbal Inspiration"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
One of the more astonishing discoveries of 20th century mathematics<br>
was made by Kurt Godel in the 1950's (I think):  any axiomatic<br>
system complex enough to generate logical statements comparable<br>
in complexity to arithmetic is also incapable of answering every<br>
properly posed question in that system.  In other words, axiomatic<br>
systems are incomplete once they get powerful enough to ask<br>
interesting questions.  What that means is that there are some<br>
interesting questions for which no clear answer is possible.  <br>
<p>
I have a hunch that this fundamental limitation to axiomatic<br>
thinking is one reason why any attempt to "prove" God's<br>
existence or reliability invariably leads to circular reasoning<br>
or other types of failures.  In some sense, truth is larger than<br>
deduction.  Reality is bigger than objective science can know.<br>
<p>
Godel proved that we can never answer all our questions using<br>
logic alone.  That makes me nervous, because as a mathematician<br>
I view the vast majority of people I know as profoundly<br>
illogical and therefore unpredictable.  Of course, I'm the same<br>
way myself even if I don't like admitting it.<br>
<p>
So, I believe that logic and proof are helpful but not sufficient<br>
guides in life.  Sometimes, subjective reality is more compelling<br>
and more satisfying.  It seems to me that God is especially<br>
interested in that part of our being.<br>
<p>
Dave Thomas<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
