<title>Jan_1993: Inspiration</title>
<h1>Inspiration</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 24 Jan 93 12:31:05 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#97">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#97">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#97">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#97">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0098.html">Steven Timm: "Oxalis"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0096.html">Dave Thomas: "Re:  Verbal Inspiration"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
My impression of discussions of this topic by Adventist<br>
intellectuals, is that supposed minor discrepancies in the<br>
Bible are brought out in order to argue against verbal<br>
inspiration.  However, in reality what happens is that<br>
this causes many to lose their confidence in the Bible<br>
altogether.  There is a great body of apologetic literature<br>
about the Bible that has grown up over the centuries and<br>
it would be very easy for these writers to include some if<br>
it to increase people's confidence in the Bible.  Today<br>
with the Dead Sea Scrolls and discoveries in archaeology<br>
we have some additional confirmations.  So I'm disturbed<br>
at the frequent failure to include such faith-building<br>
material.<br>
<p>
I would also like to recommend that people study how the<br>
Old Testament and New Testament writers, and Jesus,<br>
regarded and used Scripture.  We should use it in a way<br>
similar to the way they used it.  I submit that if one<br>
compares the way that modern intellectuals use the Scriptures<br>
with the way in which the Bible writers did, one will find<br>
a great discrepancy.<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
