<title>Jan_1993: Oxalis</title>
<h1>Oxalis</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 24 Jan 1993 16:43:32 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#98">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#98">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#98">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#98">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0099.html">Steven Timm: "Herbalism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0097.html">David Plaisted: "Inspiration"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0106.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Oxalis"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[A message from David Plaisted  (plaisted@cs.unc.edu)]<br>
Here's a natural remedy that a friend of mine in the church has<br>
mentioned to me several times.  She and two or three others<br>
have used it repeatedly with success.  It's an old Indian<br>
remedy for skin cancer, sold to a white settler by an Indian<br>
for $25.00 several generations ago and then passed down.<br>
<p>
Oxalis is a common weed.  Grind it up, get the juice, set it<br>
in the sun to dry.  Make a powder out of it.  Put this on<br>
the skin, and keep it moist.  Use a cloth or vaseline to keep<br>
it in place.  The skin will swell where cancer may be present,<br>
and the cancerous growths will loosen and come out, pretty<br>
much in their original shape.<br>
<p>
This lady has used this on her husband a number of times;  both<br>
are good friends of mine.  It was also used on another lady in<br>
my former SDA church with success.  Supposedly someone at Duke<br>
knows about it (the medical school) but they have not<br>
investigated it.  Of course, I'm not recommending that you n ot<br>
see your doctor.<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<p>
[This begs several questions:  First, how are we to recognize the <br>
so-called common weed called Oxalis (esp. under three feet of snow).<br>
Second, how are we to know if we have a skin cancer to which it <br>
ought to be applied.  There are others, but I will ask them in <br>
a post of my own.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
