<title>Jan_1993: Herbalism</title>
<h1>Herbalism</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 24 Jan 1993 21:22:52 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#99">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#99">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#99">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#99">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0100.html">Steven Timm: "Re: health"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0098.html">Steven Timm: "Oxalis"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I know it is a mistake to judge a movement by those who misapply it.<br>
I know that herbal remedies come well recommended by Ellen G. White<br>
and others, and the best way to find out where they were recommended would<br>
be to state that this was not the case and let everyone else dig.<br>
(My library was trapped in Pittsburgh when I moved to the Chicago area <br>
recently.)   Nevertheless I cannot resist commenting on the philosophy<br>
of herbalism.<br>
<p>
While still at Andrews University I got involved in helping my boss do <br>
a desktop publishing project for a friend of his.  The book was "The <br>
Gospel Of Health" and was written by a woman who claimed to have an M.S.<br>
in nutrition.  (After reading the book, how she got it is a mystery to me.)<br>
Prominent in the book was a large section on herbal remedies, including<br>
some herbs that are actually poisonous and that Mrs. White wrote against.<br>
The author told me that she had gotten this information from another book.<br>
(her book was devoid of footnotes of any sort.)  <br>
<p>
When I go to my local branch of Apple Valley "Natural" Foods, I see a whole<br>
wall of pill bottles that purport to be "natural" remedies that will help<br>
me live more naturally.  From time to time they send me a newsletter <br>
touting the virtues of same.  A friend of mine got into the "Sunrider Foods"<br>
business recently.  These people convinced him that "whole foods" are the <br>
best kind to eat and then proceeded to sell him a set of pills with five <br>
different whole foods ground up into them.<br>
<p>
Wasn't the whole idea of the health message to have simplicity before<br>
anything else?  Some of the very herbs now being touted as "natural"<br>
were the drugs that Ellen White wrote against in her time.  When an <br>
institution of the church (which Apple Valley Market is) sends me a<br>
newsletter touting various hom(l)eopathic remedies, it makes me wonder<br>
how far we have turned from the original ideas.<br>
<p>
But there is two far more important questions which these experiences <br>
bring up, and they are related:<br>
<p>
(1) Does the church at large have a responsibility to reach out to the <br>
far-right herbalistic fringe and keep them from hurting or killing themselves<br>
with herbalism and other excesses of a misunderstood health message?<br>
<p>
(2) Are SDA's more gullible than the population at large?  I can think of <br>
at least ten people in my local congregation, who upon reading the "Oxalis"<br>
article earlier today, would go out and look for some oxalis right away, <br>
think up a supposed skin cancer on which to use it, and claim a<br>
remarkable cure.<br>
<p>
It seems to me that ones view of inspiration and ones gullibility are <br>
directly correlated.  I should clarify that I am not attacking methods<br>
of interpretation such as are used within the Bible.  I am attacking<br>
creeping inspiration, in which other inspired writings are used to <br>
bolster ones own unrelated argument.  This particular theological fallacy<br>
has not cropped up on the net recently.<br>
<p>
Perhaps it is easier for a camel to go through the needle's eye than for <br>
a scientist to believe.  It's just natural for a scientist to wonder about<br>
clinical trials, control studies, etc.  As an SDA scientist, I must also<br>
consider that these people who applied the oxalis to their "cancers" were<br>
devout people who may have been healed through prayer.  <br>
<p>
Given my biases, I've tried to be as fair as I can.  No personal offense <br>
is intended.  Now let's hear what you think.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
