<title>Jan_1993: Re: health</title>
<h1>Re: health</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 24 Jan 1993 21:37:02 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#100">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#100">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#100">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#100">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0101.html">Ralf Simonsson: "&gt; Re: health"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0099.html">Steven Timm: "Herbalism"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0093.html">Sherman Cox: "health"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0104.html">Malcolm Butler: "Re: health and the environment"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Sherman Cox asked if the Adventist health message does or should lead to <br>
more of a concern for the environment, since many health problems are<br>
caused by the environment.  It seemed to me that this was the idea that the <br>
statement on "Caring For God's Creation" (posted by me last week) was trying<br>
to convey, albeit in a rather roundabout and clumsy way.<br>
<p>
Some areas that I can think of right off:<br>
<p>
(1)  Vegetarianism is good for the environment because less land is put into<br>
grazing cattle and raising food for animals.  This can also help to alleviate<br>
world hunger.<br>
<p>
(2)  The policy against smoking helps to clean up the indoor and outdoor<br>
air and reduce deaths from secondhand smoke.<br>
<p>
Can people think of others?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
