<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Sherman Cox asked if the Adventist health message does or should lead to </i><br>
<i>&gt; more of a concern for the environment, since many health problems are</i><br>
<i>&gt; caused by the environment.  It seemed to me that this was the idea that the </i><br>
<i>&gt; statement on "Caring For God's Creation" (posted by me last week) was trying</i><br>
<i>&gt; to convey, albeit in a rather roundabout and clumsy way.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Some areas that I can think of right off:</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; (1)  Vegetarianism is good for the environment because less land is put into</i><br>
<i>&gt; grazing cattle and raising food for animals.  This can also help to alleviate</i><br>
<i>&gt; world hunger.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; (2)  The policy against smoking helps to clean up the indoor and outdoor</i><br>
<i>&gt; air and reduce deaths from secondhand smoke.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
I think vegetarianism increases pollution becuase of all the pesticides you have <br>
to spray in the fields. Farming spoils jungles. I think an ordinary carrots is<br>
<p>
as unhealthful today than a beaf.<br>
<p>
I do not think we can do anything, but ask God to take us away from this<br>
misery planet!<br>
<p>
RSi<br>
