<title>Jan_1993: Herbalism</title>
<h1>Herbalism</h1>
Jay Richter (<i>72610.1371@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>25 Jan 93 00:46:41 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#102">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#102">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#102">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#102">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0103.html">Juha Helminen: "sources for OnLine Bible (excellent PC freeware)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0101.html">Ralf Simonsson: "&gt; Re: health"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0115.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Herbalism"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The other day at work a coworker of mine gave me a copy of a herbal book<br>
to look at because we have common interests in healthful living. It was<br>
entitled, "the Natural Pharmacy".  The book was published by Collier<br>
Books which I believe is a good name.  However, as I looked through the<br>
book, the concept of the Egyptian Papyrus (sp ?) came to my mind.  This<br>
book has all different sources included in it such as American Indian<br>
and others which I presently can not remember.  Anyway, I was thinking<br>
to myself that who knows what really works here.  And it made me think<br>
that we as Americans are falling into a pit of vipers if we follow<br>
untested herbal remedies such as these.  I saw no footnotes in the book<br>
substantiating the proposed cures.  This causes in me mixed feelings. <br>
I so much would like to see natural remedies being used, but we need to<br>
have some good research behind these herbal cures.  The pharmacutical<br>
industry probably has tested many of these herbs, but would be<br>
unwilling to reveal their successful results (if any) because they<br>
would be losing potential sales.  Consequently, my proposed solution<br>
would be for some SDA institution such as LLU to establish a program to<br>
test these herbs and publish a book on herbal remedies that has<br>
scientific research behind it.  Maybe a book like this exists already.<br>
 Do you know if that is the case anyone?  Is LLU doing any research on<br>
herbal remedies?  Has anyone seen a book on herbal remedies that has<br>
phamacutical (FDA type) testing behind it?<br>
<p>
						Jay Richter<br>
						Mechanical Engineer<br>
						Rock Island Arsenal<br>
	<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
