<title>Jan_1993: Re: health and the environment</title>
<h1>Re: health and the environment</h1>
Malcolm Butler (<i>malb@boojum.ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 25 Jan 93 17:23:50 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#104">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#104">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#104">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#104">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0105.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Inspiration"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0103.html">Juha Helminen: "sources for OnLine Bible (excellent PC freeware)"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0100.html">Steven Timm: "Re: health"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0101.html">Ralf Simonsson: "&gt; Re: health"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steven Timm writes:<br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Sherman Cox asked if the Adventist health message does or should lead to </i><br>
<i>&gt;more of a concern for the environment, since many health problems are</i><br>
<i>&gt;caused by the environment.  It seemed to me that this was the idea that the </i><br>
<i>&gt;statement on "Caring For God's Creation" (posted by me last week) was trying</i><br>
<i>&gt;to convey, albeit in a rather roundabout and clumsy way.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
It is not necessary to look to the health message to find reasons to car<br>
for the environment.  Right at creation, we are told that we are to<br>
"rule over the fish of the sea and the birds of the air, over the<br>
livestock, over all the earth, and over all the creatures that move<br>
along the ground".  (Gen 1:26, NIV)<br>
<p>
I take this to mean stewardship, not the exploitative interpretation<br>
that has historically been applied by some christians.  e.g, it has<br>
been reasoned that, as the earth will be burned up one day, we don't<br>
need to be too concerned for its long-term survival, so we may as well<br>
use it as we see fit, since it has been given to us.  But it has not<br>
been given to us, though we have control over it:  "The earth is the<br>
Lord's, and everything in it" (Ps 24:1).  And if we need any more<br>
incentive to look after the earth, we need only note that God will<br>
"destroy those that destroy the earth" (Rev 11:18).<br>
<p>
Malcolm Butler<br>
<pre>
-- 
Switched Networks Research Centre,               malb@ee.uts.edu.au
Uni. of Technology, Sydney, Australia            +61 2 330 2344
</pre>
