<title>Jan_1993: Inspiration</title>
<h1>Inspiration</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 25 Jan 93 13:26:26 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#105">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#105">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#105">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#105">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0106.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Oxalis"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0104.html">Malcolm Butler: "Re: health and the environment"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Another difficulty associated with the view of word inspiration of the<br>
scriptures is that very few can actually read the scriptures as they were<br>
originally written.  During the translations process, the best English<br>
equivalent had to be used, which many times clumsiliy expresses what was<br>
so clear in the original tongue.<br>
<p>
If English-speaking Christians belief in literally word-inspiration, they<br>
must accept that all involved in the translation process were prophets of<br>
God or did their their translation under direct guidance of the Holy Spirit.<br>
I don't think many would actually go that far in expressing that belief.<br>
Yet, they still insist on word inspiration rather than thought inspiration.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
