<title>Jan_1993: Inspiration</title>
<h1>Inspiration</h1>
Malachi Robertson (<i>Malachi.Robertson@lambada.oit.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 25 Jan 93 18:31:52 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#107">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#107">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#107">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#107">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0108.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Religion, environment, and health"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0106.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Oxalis"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hello.  It is interesting to see people talking of Alden Thompson's book<br>
on Iinspiration.  I have read the last few messages seeing if people might<br>
mention the publication from the SDA theological Society called Issues in<br>
Revalation and Inspiration (or is it Insp. and Reval.?).  No one seems to<br>
have mentioned it.  It was interesting to read this work of several<br>
authors after having read Thompson's book.  The piece was basically a<br>
critique of Thompson's ideas.  Although I felt at times that the authors<br>
seemed to question Thompson' the man and not his work.  Anyway the<br>
critique caused me to calm down the warm rception that I once had for<br>
Thompson's book.  I believe Thompson has brought up several interesting<br>
questions, but I felt that in some ways his treatment was lacking.  One<br>
thing I felt that he should have discussed was what the Bible says about<br>
itself in regards to inspiration.  I donot just mean the verse from Peter<br>
and the verse from Timothy.  I am refering to something he touched on only<br>
a little when he mentioned Jeremiah's feeling of fire within.  My response<br>
to Thompson's work would be one of motivation to further study this issue<br>
and the "difficulties" of the Bible text.  One way to study it is to look<br>
at what the BBible says of itself and what statements E.G. White has to<br>
say besides thouse mentioned in Thompson's book.  I would also echo Dave<br>
Plaisted's mention of the apologetical works of Christian in the past<br>
which have dealt with apparent Bible difficulties.  I believe that some of<br>
their explanations may be a worthwhile comparison to those offered by<br>
Thompson.  Ian. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
