<title>Jan_1993: Daniel 9:24-27</title>
<h1>Daniel 9:24-27</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 26 Jan 1993 09:20:07 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#110">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#110">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#110">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#110">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0111.html">Warren C Trenchard: "Thoughts on Inspiration"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0109.html">Sherman Cox: "abortion"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0112.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Daniel 9:24-27"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Recently I have been involved in a discussion on the talk.religion.misc<br>
b-board regarding the 70 weeks prophecy of Daniel 9:24-27, and it <br>
seems that I've managed to get myself in over my head.  I'm arguing<br>
for the position that the 70th week followed immediately the other 69,<br>
based on verse 27<br>
"And he shall confirm the covenant with many for one week, but in the <br>
midst of the week he shall cause the sacrifice and the oblations to cease..."<br>
<p>
SDA's have traditionally interpreted this as referring to the crucifixion<br>
in the middle of the 70th week.  I have now been faced with the argument<br>
on the net (which is echoed by many Catholic and Dispensationalist<br>
theologians alike) that he who is confirming the covenant is the same as<br>
the<br>
prince who is to come and destroy the city in verse 26.  They claim the <br>
rules of Hebrew grammar indicate this.<br>
<p>
Now, I know nothing about the rules of Hebrew grammar, nor could I <br>
even tell you if this chapter of Daniel is written in Hebrew or Aramaic.<br>
But any insight or arguments against extending the 70th week far into <br>
the future would be helpful, as well as any arguments against using<br>
a 360-day year to calculate the prophetic years.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
