<title>Jan_1993: Thoughts on Inspiration</title>
<h1>Thoughts on Inspiration</h1>
Warren C Trenchard (<i>70711.3366@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>26 Jan 93 00:59:28 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#111">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#111">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#111">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#111">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0112.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Daniel 9:24-27"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0110.html">Steven Timm: "Daniel 9:24-27"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
One could consider many principles for dealing with the issue of<br>
inspiration.  I would like to offer four that I consider<br>
important, along with a few remarks about each.<br>
<p>
1. The determination of the inspiration of a text is a matter of<br>
faith and not empirical evidence.<br>
<p>
If that text is the Bible, one can advance numerous pieces of<br>
evidence in support of its apparent supernatural origin. <br>
However, for each type of evidence, e.g., fulfillment of prophecy<br>
and accuracy of historical portrayal, one can present counter<br>
evidence, e.g., unfulfilled prophecies (escaping into conditional<br>
prophecy is a copout) and historical contradictions and conflicts<br>
with archaeology.<br>
<p>
One comes to believe the Bible to be inspired by a personal faith<br>
through recognizing its spiritual usefulness and significance and<br>
by accepting its self-testimony.  It is also important to<br>
acknowledge the faith of the community of believers over time. <br>
This is exhibited at various levels, including acceptance by<br>
family and colleagues and proclamation by the church.<br>
<p>
2. There is a difference between accepting a text as inspired and<br>
investigating the characteristics of that inspiration.<br>
<p>
While the former is a matter of faith, the latter is a process of<br>
discovery.  In this context, investigation is not carried on to<br>
determine the inspiration of the text, but to uncover the way<br>
such inspiration works and how it behaves.  It is a process that<br>
should have no restrictions and no predeterminations.<br>
<p>
3. One should consider all the evidence, even the seemingly<br>
disturbing data, and work towards a theory or theology of<br>
inspiration that will account for all of it.<br>
<p>
It is important to read the entire Bible when attempting to<br>
understand how inspiration works.  Along side the marvellous<br>
portrayal of the gospel and much that is historically sound, the<br>
Bible contains some inaccuracies, contradictions, ethically<br>
disturbing advice, unscientific observations, and culturally<br>
conditioned assumptions and injunctions.  Any view of inspiration<br>
that is true to the actual contents of the text must take note of<br>
and account for all of this.<br>
<p>
4. One should be inductive rather than deductive in drawing<br>
conclusions about the characteristics of inspirations.<br>
<p>
In examining the characteristics of inspiration, one should not<br>
decide in advance what is acceptable and unacceptable.  In<br>
dealing with this issue, there is little or no value in<br>
superimposing upon the Bible a theory of inspiration developed<br>
outside the crucible of actual observation of the biblical data. <br>
One cannot afford to develop a theory of inspiration by piously<br>
reflecting on how one thinks that God would or should conduct the<br>
process of inspiring the biblical writers and by trying to fit<br>
the biblical data into such a theory.  Only the reverse will be<br>
productive.  One must let the theory or theology arise from the<br>
observation of the data and a reflection on its characteristics.<br>
<p>
Warren C. Trenchard<br>
Internet: 70711.3366@compuserve.com<br>
CIS: 70711,3366<br>
<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
