<title>Jan_1993: Re: Daniel 9:24-27</title>
<h1>Re: Daniel 9:24-27</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 27 Jan 93 12:43:26 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#112">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#112">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#112">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#112">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0113.html">Steven Timm: ""God Cares" by Mervyn Maxwell"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0111.html">Warren C Trenchard: "Thoughts on Inspiration"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0110.html">Steven Timm: "Daniel 9:24-27"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi Steve,<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Recently I have been involved in a discussion on the talk.religion.misc</i><br>
<i>&gt; b-board regarding the 70 weeks prophecy of Daniel 9:24-27, and it </i><br>
<i>&gt; seems that I've managed to get myself in over my head.  I'm arguing</i><br>
<i>&gt; for the position that the 70th week followed immediately the other 69,</i><br>
<i>&gt; based on verse 27</i><br>
<i>&gt; "And he shall confirm the covenant with many for one week, but in the </i><br>
<i>&gt; midst of the week he shall cause the sacrifice and the oblations to cease..."</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
I have discussed this in the past with various Jews. The problem with the<br>
evangelical interpretation is that it is completey arbitrary with regard<br>
to the interpretation itself. i.e. if it fells like a good fit then it must be.<br>
<p>
All the Jews who have heard the Evan.  interpretation have shot it to pieces<br>
in seconds because of this reason. The SDA interpretation is consitent and<br>
systematic and the Jews have been unable to negate it. (that doesn't mean they<br>
accept it necessarily though) <br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; SDA's have traditionally interpreted this as referring to the crucifixion</i><br>
<i>&gt; in the middle of the 70th week.  I have now been faced with the argument</i><br>
<i>&gt; on the net (which is echoed by many Catholic and Dispensationalist</i><br>
<i>&gt; theologians alike) that he who is confirming the covenant is the same as</i><br>
<i>&gt; the</i><br>
<i>&gt; prince who is to come and destroy the city in verse 26.  They claim the </i><br>
<i>&gt; rules of Hebrew grammar indicate this.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
This is bunkum because it is not the prince but "the people of the prince" who <br>
come and destroy the city in verse 26. The rules of Hebrew grammar have nothing to do with it. The prince does not destroy the city at all.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Now, I know nothing about the rules of Hebrew grammar, nor could I </i><br>
<i>&gt; even tell you if this chapter of Daniel is written in Hebrew or Aramaic.</i><br>
<i>&gt; But any insight or arguments against extending the 70th week far into </i><br>
<i>&gt; the future would be helpful, as well as any arguments against using</i><br>
<i>&gt; a 360-day year to calculate the prophetic years.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
This would destroy the concept of the 70 weeks and that they were given to<br>
the Jewish nation as a time of probation.<br>
<p>
<p>
The following 4 rules must always be obeyed in prophetic interpretation<br>
<p>
1) the interpretation must not contradict or violate any other portion of the scritpures<br>
2) any symbol must only be interpreted as suggested directy by the scripture itself(eg day=year)<br>
3) The symbolic nature of a passage is determined by <br>
		a) direct textual evidence<br>
		b) historical evidence of non literal fulfilment<br>
4) the application of symbolism must be consistent, systematic and coherent.<br>
						<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Well here is one of my postings on this matter to some Jews :<br>
I hope it helps<br>
-----------------------------------------<br>
The Hebrew for "seventy weeks" is shabuim shibim. The word shibim is seventy,<br>
but the word shabuim is understood by Hebrew scholars to mean "a period of<br>
seven years." All devout orthodox commentators translate this word shabuim,<br>
- shmitoth. A Shmitah is "a period of seven years." While the English <br>
translations of the Hebrew Old Testament by Jewish scholars render the<br>
word shabuim shibim as "seventy weeks", it is clear that these weeks are<br>
prophetic rather than weeks of seven literal days." (see Num 14:34; Eze 4:6)<br>
Rabbi Isaac Leeser, who translated the Old Testament into English,<br>
is in accord with this prophetic interpretation of shabuim shibim. He says:<br>
"Ancient Jewish writers thought that the second temple stood four hundred<br>
and twenty years, which, with the seventy years of Babylonian captivity,<br>
make four hundred and ninty years." (Note 47, Lesser's comments on his<br>
Old Testament translation.) The comment of this famous rabbi on these two<br>
Hebrew words is agreed to by Hebrew scholars. These words of Lesser indicate<br>
that Jewish writers believe the year day method to be the correct way to<br>
reckon the seventy weeks, but they failed to take note of the angel's words<br>
that the period "to Messiah the Prince" is to be reckoned "from the going<br>
forth of the commandment to restore and to build Jerusalem." Dan 9:25.<br>
The commandment to restore and to build Jerusalem went forth in 457 BC<br>
and at that time began the seventy weeks.<br>
<p>
F.C. Gilbert's "Messiah in His Sacntuary."<br>
<p>
------------------------------------<br>
Ruben<br>
