<title>Jan_1993: Re: &gt; Re: health</title>
<h1>Re: &gt; Re: health</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 26 Jan 1993 08:21:07 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#114">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#114">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#114">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#114">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0115.html">Woody Baker: "Re: Herbalism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0113.html">Steven Timm: ""God Cares" by Mervyn Maxwell"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0101.html">Ralf Simonsson: "&gt; Re: health"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0132.html">Ralf Simonsson: "&gt; Re: &gt; Re: health"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
RSi writes<br>
<i>&gt;I think vegatarianism......etc.</i><br>
Come on now, just what do you think they feed beef?  More grain and corn is<br>
used to feed animals than to feed humans.  Those crops are heavily sprayed.<br>
My dad lives up in east texas.  There is a chicken farmer that is going]<br>
out of business.  He was running 3 brooder houses, with 18,000 chickens per<br>
brooder house.  He was turning out a crop of fryers for Tyson every 9 weeks.<br>
When he went out of business, he had the waste (18 inches or so in the<br>
bottom of each barn. (These suckers are about 40 feet wide, and 90 feet long,)<br>
tested.  One breeder shed's refuse (dropped feed, and chicken manure) tested<br>
out as being suitable for inclusion in CATTLE FEED, so he sold all of the<br>
waste, feathers, droppings, dropped food and all to a firm that makes feed<br>
for cattle for feedlots.  They mix it into the cattle food.  And you're<br>
going to EAT the cattle!!???  He is currently selling the rest at 10.00 per<br>
pickup load for fertilizer.<br>
<p>
This is an absolutely true story.  My dad bought a bunch of the manure from<br>
him, and got to talking with the man.<br>
<p>
The fact of the matter, is that there is a about a 90 percent waste in<br>
conversion of grains to meat.  That is, it takes 10 lbs of grain to produce<br>
1 lb of beef.  This means that you could grow 10 times the amount of grain<br>
and other food stuffs per acre, than you can beef or other meat.  This does<br>
not take into account the some 36,000 gallons of water it takes to bring<br>
a steer to butchering size.<br>
<p>
The economics don't make sense.<br>
Cheers<br>
Woody<br>
<pre>
-- 
Woody Baker Postscript consultant/Flint knapper  512-837-8317 (Austin, Tx)
<p>
"If you ain't bleedin' you ain't knappin'" ---&gt; go ahead, ask me...
