<title>Jan_1993: Re: Herbalism</title>
<h1>Re: Herbalism</h1>
Woody Baker (<i>woody@knapper.cactus.org</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 26 Jan 1993 08:26:42 CST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#115">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#115">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#115">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#115">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0116.html">Steven Timm: "Re: KJV - historical Adventist's bible"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0114.html">Woody Baker: "Re: &gt; Re: health"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0102.html">Jay Richter: "Herbalism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
There is a standard book, but I don't remember the name of it<br>
something with "Pharmcopiea   " in the title.<br>
<p>
Most herbal remidies are subtle in thier effect, but one that I have<br>
recently run across up in the east texas woods, (used by the country<br>
folk for tooth-ache) is anything but subtle.  Chewing the leaves, bark<br>
or fruits of the Northern Prickly Ash, produces a profound tingling of the<br>
toung and lips, followed by a rather deep anesthesia.  they say the leaves<br>
are best, but when I encountered it, it was in the form of bark.  I have<br>
used it with much success for canker sores etc.  Does a real good job<br>
of numbing mouth tissues, to the point where you can bite your tounge or<br>
burn it without realizing it.  It works well for a burned tounge as well.<br>
We seem to be digressing here.....<br>
Cheers<br>
Woodu<br>
Woody<br>
