I'm reminded of the time when my 4th grade teacher in an Adventist school<br>
said that if we had a stack of Bibles of various translations, we should<br>
always make sure that the King James Version was on top!  Then below <br>
all of the Bibles should come any Ellen White books, then any other books.<br>
<p>
The Bible curriculum in the lower grades gave the definite hint, although <br>
it never said so in so many words, that the translators of the Septuagint<br>
as well as those of the King James Version were inspired.<br>
<p>
I'm sure there is some feeling from those who are used to explaining<br>
the doctrines with the KJV that the doctrines are not as clear in the newer<br>
versions.  But really there isn't much difference between new and old versions.<br>
<p>
Those people who have to work from an Italian version have a harder time <br>
of it than any modern English version.  From what I've been told the <br>
Italian version plays very fast and loose particularly with texts about <br>
the Sabbath.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<p>
