<title>Jan_1993: KJV - historical Adventist's bible</title>
<h1>KJV - historical Adventist's bible</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>28 Jan 1993 09:41:01 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#117">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#117">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#117">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#117">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0118.html">Fred Christiansen: "Rejoice with me for my house has passed final inspection!"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0116.html">Steven Timm: "Re: KJV - historical Adventist's bible"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0116.html">Steven Timm: "Re: KJV - historical Adventist's bible"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have often wondered why certain elements of the church are so opposed<br>
to the use of the newer, more accurate translations of the bible. <br>
<p>
Could it be because the KJV supports some of the distinctive SDA doctrines<br>
well, whereas other translations may not?<br>
<p>
The main examples which come to mind are "2300 days" (KJV) versus "2300<br>
evening-mornings" or "2300 evenings and mornings" (NIV etc.), and also<br>
the passages in Hebrews 9 referring to the ministry of christ in heaven.<br>
Also the word "cleansed" in Daniel in the KJV which is used to link the<br>
verse to the day of atonement in Leviticus turns out to be different inl<br>
other translations. (Sorry I can't be more specific).<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
