<title>Jan_1993: Re: Inspiration</title>
<h1>Re: Inspiration</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 28 Jan 93 11:59:19 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#121">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#121">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#121">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#121">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0122.html">Steven Timm: "Inspiration"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0120.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: health"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0122.html">Steven Timm: "Inspiration"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all,<br>
<p>
<p>
Paul J. Writes<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt;  [....]</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;      Catching up on the net's correspondence, it seems many of us are</i><br>
<i>&gt; trying to identify "church," especially our church, and to suggest ways</i><br>
<i>&gt; out of our quandry.</i><br>
<i>&gt;      Marcus, you suggest that "these 'devisive' groups have sprung up</i><br>
<i>&gt; because the church has failed to move in meeting the needs of the</i><br>
<i>&gt; people."  Why should we consider something a failure if it has indeed</i><br>
<i>&gt; met the needs of SOME people?  Do we Adventists have to so often assume</i><br>
<i>&gt; that one church--our church--should do it all?</i><br>
<i>&gt;      Bill Nickless, why does the church have to be "the true church" to</i><br>
<i>&gt; merit our support?  I support Shadyside Seventh-Day Adventist Church in</i><br>
<i>&gt; Pittsburgh.  I also support St. Andrew's Episcopal Church.  I support</i><br>
<i>&gt; them both, not because they are true, but because they are good.  They</i><br>
<i>&gt; fulfil different needs in my spiritual walk.  I like them.</i><br>
<p>
<p>
It seems to me we may be having a little lapse in understanding of what it <br>
means to be a SDA who is called to proclaim a message of judgement to Babilon<br>
and her daughters and to call the true to "come out of her". I suggest a little<br>
reading of Rev 12 might also help.<br>
<p>
Is this what happens when we begin to belittle the inspiration of our prophets<br>
and put in place our own interpretations ?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;      Another suggested applying a number of principles from "our</i><br>
<i>&gt; prophet."  For instance, we were admonished to remember that "those who</i><br>
<i>&gt; are inclined to regard their individual judgement as supreme are in</i><br>
<i>&gt; grave peril."  I have never met anyone who considered his or her</i><br>
<i>&gt; judgement as supreme.  But--and this brings us back to the topic of</i><br>
<i>&gt; inspiration--it seems one's judgment is supremely unavoidable.</i><br>
<p>
This not only applies to those who consider their judgment as supreme, but to<br>
those who consider it at least on par with that of God's own messengers.<br>
To the extent that we feel qualified to ignore or modify the message according<br>
to our own likings.<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
