<title>Jan_1993: Inspiration</title>
<h1>Inspiration</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 27 Jan 1993 23:13:05 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#122">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#122">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#122">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#122">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0123.html">Steven Timm: "If the KJV was good enough for Ellen G. White, it's good enough for me!"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0121.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Inspiration"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0121.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Inspiration"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I think it's unfortunate that Selected Messages, Vol. 1, by E.G. White,<br>
wasn't published until 1958.  The balanced view of inspiration presented <br>
there is a must for anyone who is seriously studying the question.<br>
To a certain extent the writing in those chapters is in conflict with <br>
what the church had been teaching in the forty intervening years since<br>
the death of Ellen White, and to some extent even during her life.<br>
<p>
In the mind of Ellen White there is no tension at all between a Bible<br>
into which some historical errors have crept and a Bible which is the <br>
whole and entire Word of God.  She urges not to focus on the small details,<br>
but on the coherent whole which points to salvation.  I think we would <br>
be wise to do the same.<br>
<p>
Traditional Adventism has not been the champion of inerrancy that some other<br>
fundamentalist denominations have been.  There are evangelical works that<br>
seriously try to resolve the two stories of Peter's denial of Christ,<br>
where one gospel records one cock crow and another records two.  The<br>
composite ends up with three cock crows and six separate denials!  <br>
<p>
Resolving  paradoxes in the Bible can be a source for  spiritual growth.<br>
But it can also lead, as above, into making the Bible say what it does <br>
not say at all.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
