<title>Jan_1993: Historical Adventism and the environment</title>
<h1>Historical Adventism and the environment</h1>
<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>28 Jan 1993 16:29:50 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#124">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#124">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#124">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#124">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0125.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: KJV - historical Adventist's bible"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0123.html">Steven Timm: "If the KJV was good enough for Ellen G. White, it's good enough for me!"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben writes<br>
<p>
------&gt;<br>
It seems to me some of us would like to stay on this earth for a long time to <br>
come. No thanks, get me out of here and into heaven. This world is not my home,<br>
we are to be pilgrims and wanderers upon the earth, are we not ?<br>
<p>
We forget that the reason for the ecology going down the tubes and poverty<br>
(mainly due to famine and greed) is because of the curse of sin which is<br>
upon the earth which will not dissipate not matter what we do but will increase<br>
until the final day. <br>
<p>
How about instead of putting the symptoms in 1st priority we treat the cause <br>
of the disease first. No we shouldn't ignore these things but as people living<br>
in the last days shouldn't we be hastening the Lord's coming ? Or do we say<br>
"the Lord delayeth His coming all things continue..." ?<br>
&lt;-------<br>
<p>
Considering the weight of inspired texts which point out that in order to<br>
be ready for the close of probation we need to have removed all sin from<br>
our lives, surely this is not a responsible attitude for the remnant to<br>
take. After all, sins of omission are still sins aren't they? Neglecting<br>
to take the proper care of our environment as directed by our Lord in<br>
the Garden of Eden shows disregard for God's commands, as well as a lack<br>
of care for our fellow man. Besides which, a damaged environment clearly<br>
affects our health, and this cannot be ignored in the light of the strong<br>
health and temperance emphasis the SDA church has historically had.<br>
<p>
Considering the fact that sin consists of physical actions performed by <br>
physical beings, the imperfect state of the environment cannot be blamed<br>
on "sin" without blaming it on "sinners". We as a human race are the ones<br>
who have ruined the environment, and we also have the option to make good<br>
choices and look after it. If we ignore this issue, and either omit to<br>
be "environmentally friendly" ourselves, or if we take actions which<br>
actively harm the environment, we are continuing the sinful practices<br>
which have caused the current situation.<br>
<p>
Lesser Christians would agree with Ruben when he points out that some of <br>
these deficiencies in our lives will only be removed when the Lord comes<br>
again, but surely this weak perspective is not promoted by His remnant<br>
people?<br>
<p>
Clearly, the members of God's remnant must accompany their preaching<br>
of the three angels' messages with a suitable attitude to environmental<br>
issues, since this is a necessary step in the process of full <br>
sanctification which we all need before translation, don't we?<br>
<p>
Even perfectionists need to be green!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
