<!-- body="start" -->
On Jan 28, 11:49am, Ruben Gonzalez wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; Subject: Re: KJV - historical Adventist's bible</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Hi all,</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Tony writes :</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;I have often wondered why certain elements of the church are so opposed</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;to the use of the newer, more accurate translations of the bible.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; I would disagree with you here Tony, what evidence is there to support</i><br>
<i>&gt; this claim that the newer translations are more accurate ? In fact I would</i><br>
<i>&gt; argue the opposite considering that almost all of the new translations</i><br>
<i>&gt; come directly from Jesuit scholars and are based on texts which belong</i><br>
<i>&gt; in the same family as the Latin Vulgate.</i><br>
<p>
I think you need to substantiate your statements here.  I do not believe that<br>
"almost all of the new translations come directly from Jesuit scholars...".  I<br>
believe the NIV was put together and reviewed by scholars from many<br>
denominations, mostly protestant in origin.  There have been studies done by I<br>
believe professors at Andrews U. or at the G.C. that have found both the RSV and<br>
the NIV to be the most accurate translations of scripture, when comparing them<br>
to the original hebrew/greek.  If you want sources on this, I read it in a<br>
Review article a few years back.<br>
<p>
I will agree that not all new translations are more accurate than the KJV but<br>
the ones I mentioned above are claimed to be more accurate.  And given the fact<br>
that I have a hard time understanding the english used in the KJV, I find the<br>
NIV to be far more beneficial to my spiritual life than trying to read the KJV<br>
which only frustrates me.  What good is a Bible that frustrates the reader and<br>
hides some of its meaning through middle-ages english?  If it isn't written in a<br>
language used by proper speaking people of today in your native tongue, then you<br>
will miss something.  And of course it has to retain its accuracy to the<br>
original text.  This also doesn't negate the value obtained in trying to go back<br>
to the original and studying it on key issues to obtain a more pure form...but<br>
for everyday reading, I think that some of the newer translations have been<br>
tremendously beneficial for Bible reading and study.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; All those interested in assertaining whether or not there still is any</i><br>
<i>&gt; merit in the KJV compared to the newer translations should read</i><br>
<i>&gt; "Our Authorised Bible Vindicated" (by Andreason ?) some time.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;Could it be because the KJV supports some of the distinctive SDA doctrines</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;well, whereas other translations may not?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; I wonder why this would be so ? :)</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;The main examples which come to mind are "2300 days" (KJV) versus "2300</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;evening-mornings" or "2300 evenings and mornings" (NIV etc.), and also</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;the passages in Hebrews 9 referring to the ministry of christ in heaven.</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;Also the word "cleansed" in Daniel in the KJV which is used to link the</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;verse to the day of atonement in Leviticus turns out to be different inl</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;other translations. (Sorry I can't be more specific).</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Not to mention entire or portions of verses deleted from the text.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Ruben.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;-- End of excerpt from Ruben Gonzalez</i><br>
