Hi all,<br>
<p>
Tony writes :<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Considering the fact that sin consists of physical actions performed by </i><br>
<i>&gt; physical beings, the imperfect state of the environment cannot be blamed</i><br>
<i>&gt; on "sin" without blaming it on "sinners". We as a human race are the ones</i><br>
<i>&gt; who have ruined the environment, and we also have the option to make good</i><br>
<i>&gt; choices and look after it. If we ignore this issue, and either omit to</i><br>
<i>&gt; be "environmentally friendly" ourselves, or if we take actions which</i><br>
<i>&gt; actively harm the environment, we are continuing the sinful practices</i><br>
<i>&gt; which have caused the current situation.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Lesser Christians would agree with Ruben when he points out that some of </i><br>
<i>&gt; these deficiencies in our lives will only be removed when the Lord comes</i><br>
<i>&gt; again, but surely this weak perspective is not promoted by His remnant</i><br>
<i>&gt; people?</i><br>
<p>
Now, now, I no way did I insinuate that SDAs should be environmentally<br>
irresponsible. In reference to my statement I think the context it was made <br>
in should not be overlooked. The context was one of which priority should come<br>
first as a people not whether we should or should not be concerned about the <br>
ecology.<br>
<p>
Of course we should make good choices with regard to taking care of nature,<br>
we are responsible for it. But let me remind you that the point I was discussing<br>
is whether we as a people should be at the *front* of various social movements.<br>
<p>
In fact I find the whole thing a little worrying. The reason is because<br>
we the SDA church should have been at the front of the health message, but<br>
due to our wilful neglect of the message, others have taken up the banners<br>
we should be carrying. To the point that the work that Gods people should<br>
have been at the front of Satan has taken over and his people -- the New Age<br>
Movement is now at the forefront. That's right go into any health food shop<br>
and look around. And you know, a lot of people are coming to the new age <br>
movement through, *our* health message. Healthy living these days is almost <br>
always associated with spiritism and the new age. How very sad for the church <br>
that we have allowed Satan to steal our secret weapon because we couldn't <br>
care less.<br>
<p>
And what's worse is that while we have allowed Satan to steal our weapons,<br>
the movement we should be in front of, we in turn are now trying to steal<br>
his weapon and the movements that his followers (spiritists) have been in front<br>
of for a long time. Really, just ten years ago a greenie = a spiritist.<br>
<p>
Whats happened ? have we switched camps or something ?<br>
<p>
As for the weak perspective and Lesser christians, We know that there will be<br>
increasing floods, and storms and earthquakes, until the very earth<br>
beneath our feet breaks up from beneath us. I can't see what that<br>
has to do with weak perspectives at all. Remeber it is the weak that allow<br>
themselves to be carried by the crowd, and do what is popular or trendy.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; Clearly, the members of God's remnant must accompany their preaching</i><br>
<i>&gt; of the three angels' messages with a suitable attitude to environmental</i><br>
<i>&gt; issues, since this is a necessary step in the process of full </i><br>
<i>&gt; sanctification which we all need before translation, don't we?</i><br>
<p>
I wish the members of God's remnant *did* preach  the three angels' messages<br>
full stop. Its been years since the message was preached, <br>
<p>
Q. What was the last time you heard a historical Adventist sermon on the <br>
three angels message ?<br>
<p>
It seems to me some pastors occupy a larger segement of their time preaching <br>
about the environment than preaching the 3 angels message. lets see<br>
the 3 unpopular messages judgment, Sabbath worship/mark of the beast, <br>
and to come out and be separate from the *popular* churches.<br>
<p>
No, I'm not saying we should be ecologically irresponsible, I never have,<br>
however I do have a little difficulty regarding equating the need to be a <br>
green activist and sanctification. (if I did not missunderstand your comment)<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
