You should be able to go to your public (or even academic) library and<br>
have Maxwell's book (or any other, for that matter) sent to you on<br>
interlibrary loan.  In some cases the library will charge you, in others<br>
not.  If the borrowing library tells us it's for an SDA, we will waive<br>
our ILL charge.  We do have the book, but I'm not sure whether it's in<br>
circulation.  I would note that Maxwell is a church historian, not a<br>
theologian, and his book is seen by many SDA theologians as more of an<br>
apologetic than good theology.  However, as a librarian, I feel that you<br>
should be able to borrow a copy of virtually anything, so give it a try<br>
(if you're interested).<br>
<p>
I plan to reply to some of the suggestions about our OPAC made on the<br>
net after I have a few more answers.<br>
<p>
Are you living in Chicago now?<br>
<p>
Harvey Brenneise (brneise@andrews.edu)<br>
