<!-- body="start" -->
Hello,  my two-bits worth...<br>
<p>
On Jan 28, 12:13pm, Ruben Gonzalez wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; Subject: Re: health</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Hi all,</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Sherman H. Cox, II writes :</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; I was wondering if anyone out there has any thoughts on the Adventist</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; Health message calling us to be at the front of the conservation,</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; anti-polution, andti-poverty movements.  I ask this because a lot of</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt; health problems stem from the envirement we live in.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Well lets see in our list of priorities as the remnant church what should</i><br>
<i>&gt; be our number one priority ?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; 1) conservation</i><br>
<i>&gt; 2) anti-polution</i><br>
<i>&gt; 3) anti-poverty</i><br>
<i>&gt; 4) anti-war</i><br>
<i>&gt; 5) anti-nuclear</i><br>
<i>&gt; 6) what ever you feel anti about</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; 7) proclaiming the judgment message (3 angels) and preparing the world for</i><br>
<i>&gt; the advent and the end of all things. (which includes the end of war, and of</i><br>
<i>&gt; poverty, and polution AND the end of the ecology.</i><br>
<p>
<p>
Maybe its time for a reality check here.<br>
<p>
My observations indicate that the SDA church has NOT put the above issues in the<br>
order of priority as you suggest.  In fact #7 has been the #1 priority for as<br>
long as I have been in the SDA church (all my life).  What is an attempt to get<br>
SDA's to take our blinders off and realize that there is other causes to fight<br>
for is instead being shot down.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; It seems to me some of us would like to stay on this earth for a long time to</i><br>
<i>&gt; come. No thanks, get me out of here and into heaven. This world is not my</i><br>
home,<br>
<i>&gt; we are to be pilgrims and wanderers upon the earth, are we not ?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; We forget that the reason for the ecology going down the tubes and poverty</i><br>
<i>&gt; (mainly due to famine and greed) is because of the curse of sin which is</i><br>
<i>&gt; upon the earth which will not dissipate not matter what we do but will</i><br>
increase<br>
<i>&gt; until the final day.</i><br>
<p>
Very true indeed.  But until we get off this planet, we have to live in this<br>
place and be a witness for others.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; How about instead of putting the symptoms in 1st priority we treat the cause</i><br>
<i>&gt; of the disease first. No we shouldn't ignore these things but as people living</i><br>
<i>&gt; in the last days shouldn't we be hastening the Lord's coming ? Or do we say</i><br>
<i>&gt; "the Lord delayeth His coming all things continue..." ?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; You know inspiration tells us that the Lord would have come a long time ago</i><br>
<i>&gt; and put an end to these things, but we as a people and individually like the</i><br>
<i>&gt; Jews have been unprepared for His coming. The scripture tells us that this is</i><br>
<i>&gt; reason why the Lord has delayed His coming (for over 100 years now) because He</i><br>
<i>&gt; wishes none to be lost. Instead of focusing on the things of this world so</i><br>
much<br>
<i>&gt; why don't we do our utmost to hasten His coming. ?</i><br>
<p>
When Mrs. White talked about Jesus's delay, it was due to His people not being<br>
ready.  Who are His people?  Everyone on this earth.  Sometimes I think we focus<br>
on our selves abit too much in thinking about preparation for Jesus's second<br>
coming.  This is the place to start but not the place to end.<br>
<p>
How can we influence "worldly" people out there into accepting Christ into their<br>
lives if we don't give a hoot about our environment, a growing concern among<br>
many non-SDAs?  If they see us showing no concern, how likely are they to be<br>
interested in learning about our God?  Christ made us stewards of this earth,<br>
according to Genesis.  I don't believe we will be effective in reaching people<br>
(a prerequisite for preparing them for the 2nd Coming) until we can pull our<br>
heads out of the sand and show some awareness and concern for our environment.<br>
<p>
Asked another way, are we going to influence more people by being strong leaders<br>
that others can look up to because of our moral stand on issues or by hiding in<br>
the shadows as we have done in the past (just ask any non-SDA where SDA's stand<br>
on any given environmental issue...pollution, war, conservation, abortion, etc<br>
and you will see my point...they won't know)?<br>
<p>
--Bruce<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; That will bring the ultimate solution to these problems we see around us.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Ruben.</i><br>
<i>&gt;-- End of excerpt from Ruben Gonzalez</i><br>
