<title>Jan_1993: Re: If the KJV was good enough for Ellen G. White, it's good enough for me!</title>
<h1>Re: If the KJV was good enough for Ellen G. White, it's good enough for me!</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 28 Jan 93 17:37:43 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#130">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#130">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#130">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#130">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0131.html">David Plaisted: "Ellen White and scripture versions"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0129.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: health"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0123.html">Steven Timm: "If the KJV was good enough for Ellen G. White, it's good enough for me!"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0134.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: If the KJV was good enough for Ellen G. White, it's good enough for me!"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve Writes:<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Ah, but here's the trap.  The KJV wasn't good enough for Ellen G. White.</i><br>
<i>&gt;  Many times in her writings she quotes from the Revised Version, which</i><br>
<i>&gt; was the only other version available in her time.  </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
ah, but you will also note that she does so very carefully. Also EGW never<br>
said that the KJV was a perfect traslation, just that it was much better<br>
than than the others. But then as a prophet I'm sure she had the discernment<br>
to know which verse was translated the best. You will note also that<br>
the KJV was definitively good enough for EGW as it was the only bible she<br>
used for her personal reading, and the majority of quotes in her writing <br>
where from the KJV.<br>
<p>
Hey, I use other versons (and languages) too sometimes when studying a <br>
particular text to get a more complete picture of the meaning the verse conveys.<br>
However on matters of scriptural authority I rely on the KJV or better still<br>
on the Greek text itself (textus receptus, not that I know Greek :)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; [...]</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Since we have many people on this net who are not blessed (or cursed)</i><br>
<i>&gt; with many different translations of the Bible in their language, it would</i><br>
<i>&gt; be interesting to hear how the various Adventist doctrines translate into</i><br>
<i>&gt; other languages.  I know from personal experience that they translate into</i><br>
<i>&gt; Afrikaans rather well.  Does every Adventist in South America learn that </i><br>
<i>&gt; the two-horned beast of Revelation 13 is the United States, for instance?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
<p>
Well in the Spanish there is no problem with Rev 13 but there is a problem <br>
with Hebrews where it says that Jesus went straight into the Most Holy place<br>
instead of correctly translating is as the holy place (sorry can't remember <br>
the reference). There are no other major problems with the Spanish Reina-Valera <br>
version (it would almost the be the equivalent to the KJV in English) as far <br>
as I know.<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
