<title>Jan_1993: Ellen White and scripture versions</title>
<h1>Ellen White and scripture versions</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 28 Jan 93 13:09:05 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#131">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#131">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#131">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#131">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0132.html">Ralf Simonsson: "&gt; Re: &gt; Re: health"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0130.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: If the KJV was good enough for Ellen G. White, it's good enough for me!"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I think that the reason Ellen White used the revised version was the<br>
more modern language.  The problem with the modern versions (in my<br>
view) is that they couple the modern language with the wrong<br>
Greek manuscripts.  It doesn't show that she supported one Greek<br>
version or the other, just that she favored modern language.  The<br>
New King James attempts to put the KJV in modern language.  Also<br>
it's not clear to me which version she used most frequently;  do<br>
you know?<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
