<title>Jan_1993: Re: health</title>
<h1>Re: health</h1>
Malcolm Butler (<i>malb@boojum.ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 28 Jan 93 17:51:52 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#133">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#133">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#133">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#133">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0134.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: If the KJV was good enough for Ellen G. White, it's good enough for me!"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0132.html">Ralf Simonsson: "&gt; Re: &gt; Re: health"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0120.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: health"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0129.html">Bruce Holm: "Re: health"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben Gonzalez writes:<br>
<i>&gt;Well lets see in our list of priorities as the remnant church what should</i><br>
<i>&gt;be our number one priority ?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;1) conservation</i><br>
<i>&gt;2) anti-polution</i><br>
<i>&gt;3) anti-poverty</i><br>
<i>&gt;4) anti-war</i><br>
<i>&gt;5) anti-nuclear</i><br>
<i>&gt;6) what ever you feel anti about</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;7) proclaiming the judgment message (3 angels) and preparing the world for</i><br>
<i>&gt;the advent and the end of all things. (which includes the end of war, and of </i><br>
<i>&gt;poverty, and polution AND the end of the ecology.)</i><br>
<p>
It is possible proclaim the judgement until we are blue in the face, but<br>
if it makes no perceived difference in our lives here on earth, we are<br>
in trouble.  People are looking for solutions to their problems NOW, not<br>
at the end of time.  Sure, we can promise them an advent, but without<br>
any evidence that belief in the judgement can make an immediate<br>
difference in their lives, you are going to have a hard time convincing<br>
them that you have anything to offer.<br>
<p>
If someone shows a lack of care for the environment, polution, poverty,<br>
war, etc, it tells me that they are not particularly concerned about how<br>
their own actions affect other people.  If someone came and knocked on<br>
my door telling me how wicked I am and that I will be burned up if I<br>
don't change, after driving up in a V8 gas-guzzler, stepping over the<br>
drunk in the gutter, ignoring the homeless kid on the corner, I would<br>
seriously wonder who needs changing.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;It seems to me some of us would like to stay on this earth for a long time to </i><br>
<i>&gt;come. No thanks, get me out of here and into heaven. This world is not my home,</i><br>
<i>&gt;we are to be pilgrims and wanderers upon the earth, are we not ?</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;We forget that the reason for the ecology going down the tubes and poverty</i><br>
<i>&gt;(mainly due to famine and greed) is because of the curse of sin which is</i><br>
<i>&gt;upon the earth which will not dissipate not matter what we do but will increase</i><br>
<i>&gt;until the final day. </i><br>
<p>
It may not be my home, but (at least in parts) it's a great place to<br>
visit.  You are seriously under valuing what God has created.<br>
<p>
The curse of sin arose out of man's actions ("Because thou .. hast<br>
eaten of the tree ..." Gen 3:15).   Today, it is still our actions that<br>
have the biggest destructive impact on our environment.  The parts of<br>
the earth that are least touched by man remain, IMHO, the most exciting<br>
places to visit.<br>
<p>
If sin can only increase, then I am doomed in my personal as well as<br>
communal life.  Cannot God change people and turn them away from sin?<br>
Then how can you say we cannot make a difference to other things.  For<br>
example, if poverty is due to our greed, and if I do not become less<br>
greedy, how have I gained?  Have I simply become greedy and happy,<br>
instead of greedy and unhappy?<br>
<p>
The reasons for the ``social gospel'' are the same as those for changing<br>
any other aspect of our behaviour.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;How about instead of putting the symptoms in 1st priority we treat the cause </i><br>
<i>&gt;of the disease first. No we shouldn't ignore these things but as people living</i><br>
<i>&gt;in the last days shouldn't we be hastening the Lord's coming ? Or do we say</i><br>
<i>&gt;"the Lord delayeth His coming all things continue..." ?</i><br>
<p>
I don't say that the Lord has delayed his coming.  But we have no excuse<br>
for not caring about how we live.  If it was, we could say, it doesn't<br>
matter about my health, God will give me a new body one day Real Soon<br>
Now.  In the meanwhile, I'll just do whatever is most convenient for me.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;You know inspiration tells us that the Lord would have come a long time ago</i><br>
<i>&gt;and put an end to these things, but we as a people and individually like the </i><br>
<i>&gt;Jews have been unprepared for His coming. The scripture tells us that this is </i><br>
<i>&gt;reason why the Lord has delayed His coming (for over 100 years now) because He </i><br>
<p>
Where does the scripture tell us that the Lord has delayed his coming<br>
for over 100 years?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;wishes none to be lost. Instead of focusing on the things of this world so much</i><br>
<i>&gt;why don't we do our utmost to hasten His coming. ?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
We don't necessarily have to go out and preach all things green.  The<br>
most important aspect of the social aspects of the gospel is that it is<br>
spread by DOING things, rather than SAYING things.  This contrasts<br>
rather markedly with the prophetic aspects.  We must not forget that it<br>
is possible to both do and say things simultaneously, so to be socially<br>
aware doesn't mean you have to stop whatever it is you wish to say, as<br>
long as the two do not conflict.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;That will bring the ultimate solution to these problems we see around us.</i><br>
Amen.<br>
<p>
<p>
Malcolm Butler<br>
<pre>
-- 
Switched Networks Research Centre,
University of Technology, Sydney, Australia
</pre>
