<title>Jan_1993: Re: If the KJV was good enough for Ellen G. White, it's good enough for me!</title>
<h1>Re: If the KJV was good enough for Ellen G. White, it's good enough for me!</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 29 Jan 93 12:11:00 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#134">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#134">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#134">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#134">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0135.html">Steven Timm: "Translations--Primacy vs. Recency"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0133.html">Malcolm Butler: "Re: health"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0123.html">Steven Timm: "If the KJV was good enough for Ellen G. White, it's good enough for me!"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all,<br>
<p>
Bruce writes :<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I think you need to substantiate your statements here.  I do not believe that</i><br>
<i>&gt;"almost all of the new translations come directly from Jesuit scholars...".  I</i><br>
<i>&gt; believe the NIV was put together and reviewed by scholars from many</i><br>
<i>&gt; denominations, mostly protestant in origin.  There have been studies done by I</i><br>
<i>&gt; believe professors at Andrews U.or at the G.C.that have found both the RSV and</i><br>
<i>&gt; the NIV to be the most accurate translations of scripture, when comparing them</i><br>
<i>&gt; to the original hebrew/greek.  If you want sources on this, I read it in a</i><br>
<i>&gt; Review article a few years back.</i><br>
<p>
<p>
Well in case you weren't aware the RSV mainly translated <br>
(or should I say the translation was "guided") by two Oxford professors<br>
Wescott and Hort. These two men *hated* the KJV with a passion and blatantly<br>
said so, it is also well known that they were very pro-Catholic which at that <br>
time was very unprotestant. I can get you the evidence if you so desire. <br>
It is also well known that Oxford had been well infiltrated by the Jesuits<br>
by that time which would well explain the leanings towards Romanism that these<br>
men shared. As for the NIV and other modern translations you will find that<br>
the Jesuit scholars contributed a significant proportion of the translation <br>
effort, and as for being reviewed by scholars from many denominations I don't <br>
find this fact very important due to the convenient ecumenical climate. That<br>
only demonstrates that they will select the translation that most fully<br>
serves their purpose of joining hands more fully with Romanism.<br>
<p>
As for the studies done by certain conference men, I don't really know of which<br>
you are refering, if you refer to their reply to the study I mentioned yesterday<br>
you will find that it was most admirably refuted. <br>
<p>
As for comparing to the original Greek (The Hebrew is not an issue) It really<br>
depends on ones bias. The reason I say this is that you will find that <br>
historically there are two distinct families of texts in the orignal languages.<br>
One family that from which the KJV is derived is from the Textus Receptus<br>
otherwise known as the received text. About 90% of all the original texts<br>
are from this family. *All* (excepting NKJV) the modern translations come from<br>
the other family of original texts of which the latin vulgate belongs. We know<br>
(EGW says so apart from other reasons) that the Latin Vulgate is full of errors.<br>
Of this other class less, they comprise less than 10% of all the manuscripts.<br>
The Siniaticus manuscript (which was found on a trash heap outside a monastery,<br>
very appropriatly I think) and the Vaticanicus (which was found amazingly in<br>
the Vatican of all places) are the most recently found and claimed to the the<br>
oldest actual texts, these belong to the Vulgate family. <br>
<p>
Scientifically, and textually the correct version is that which of which there<br>
is the bulk of evidence. However the KJV being derived from the TExtus receptus<br>
is very poorly received by the RCC for obvious reasons, one of which is because<br>
it is the very text that the Waldensians treasured and kept alive and passed <br>
down from generation to generation. It is the manuscript that God preserved<br>
through the dark ages.<br>
<p>
I can give you the entire story on the origins of the Siniaticus and the <br>
Vaticanicus manuscripts and how they originated with Constantine and Origen,<br>
with references if you really desire.<br>
<p>
As for the the New versions being more correctly translated this is only so<br>
if you beleive that the Vulgate family is the correct family of texts.<br>
<p>
Ruben. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
