<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0148.html">Malcolm Butler: "Re: Australia"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;</i><br>
Ruben writes<br>
<i>&gt; I'm sorry if you felt attacked. It was not my intention to attack you or </i><br>
<i>&gt; anybody personally. I am concerned however about a growing trend (here in </i><br>
<i>&gt; Australia at least) where the youth no longer know anything about the </i><br>
<i>&gt; Adventist message or the bible bar the superficials, and seem to think that</i><br>
<i>&gt; being and Adventist means being at the front of all the current social issues.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Something which Jesus in His day did not do at all, instead He avoided them.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
I must admit my exposure to Adventism is in the United States.  And most of<br>
my exposure to Adventism is in the Black Churches of the United States.  I<br>
did not consider where you were writing from.  I have heard about the situation<br>
in Australia from some "independent ministers" here.  It is interesting to learn<br>
that the Australian Adventists preach social issues above the Adventist <br>
distinctive message.   I forgot, for a minute, that we are a world<br>
church.  <br>
<p>
Actually I can remember sermons on the Sabbath, Religious Liberty, personal<br>
Health.  I also can remember references made to the State of the Dead, <br>
Spirit of Prophecy, and other adventist distinctives.  Once again I would say<br>
this is in the Black  churches of the United States.  I cannot remember a <br>
sermon on the environment, but one might conceivable say that the principles<br>
presented would cause one to be concious.<br>
<p>
The main idea is that Christianity is a lifestyle that should affect every<br>
thing you do.  Sometimes one can see an utter disregard for other  people<br>
from those who claim to be christians.  I understand you come from, by your<br>
testimony, a place where people lost an understanding of the message, so it <br>
is understandable<br>
that you would see a red flag when someone comes with the environment.<br>
<p>
We learn from exposure to others<br>
<p>
