<title>Jan_1993: Bible versions</title>
<h1>Bible versions</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 29 Jan 1993 09:57:41 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#142">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#142">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#142">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#142">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0143.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Getting files from the server..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0141.html">Malcolm Butler: "Re: Historical Adventism and the environment"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0145.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Bible versions"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben's defense of the "textus receptus" of the New Testament could <br>
profit by a bit of analysis.  The early English and German translators <br>
of the Bible including Tyndale, Luther, and the translators of the KJV<br>
worked from the Greek New Testament compiled by Erasmus in the early 1500's.<br>
<p>
In the compilation of that work, Erasmus noted that 1 John 5:8 as translated<br>
in the Vulgate had an addition which did not appear in the Greek manuscripts:<br>
"For there are three that bear witness **in heaven, the Father, the Word,<br>
and the Holy Spirit, and these three are one.  And there are three that<br>
bear witness on earth**, the Spirit, the water, and the blood; and these<br>
three are in agreement."<br>
<p>
The part between the asterisks evidently was added quite some time later.<br>
Erasmus did not want to include it, but the Church fathers insisted that<br>
he should.  He said that if they could even find one Greek manuscript<br>
which contained this "comma", as it has come to be known, he would include<br>
it.  A manuscript was promptly "discovered" in Ireland which has since been <br>
found to be a translation of the Latin back into Greek, and that part of the <br>
text was included in the "textus receptus", and in the King James Bible<br>
and in the New King James Bible, and in a footnote in almost every other<br>
translation.<br>
<p>
So you see there has been tampering with the "textus receptus" by the <br>
very same people Ruben accuses of tampering with the other versions.<br>
We should be careful in choosing our points of defending the Word.<br>
<p>
By the way, I don't dispute that there are many errors in the Vulgate<br>
and other Catholic versions based on it.  One of the first and prominent<br>
ones is making Genesis 3:15 refer to Mary and not to Jesus.  At the same <br>
time, we should consider that the final makeup of the New Testament was <br>
not decided until 360 AD by a Catholic church that Adventists claim was<br>
already deep into apostasy. <br>
<p>
Finally, when the Vulgate was released in the 300's AD, many of the same<br>
claims against it were made as are made against the various modern<br>
translations now.  Jerome didn't want to include the Apocrypha but was <br>
forced to do so by the church fathers because there was 300 years of<br>
tradition of having them around.  The familiar versus the more accurate<br>
is a battle that has gone on almost since the beginning.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
