<title>Jan_1993: PERSONAL INFO</title>
<h1>PERSONAL INFO</h1>
ARKUSINSKI ANDY  (<i>/S=ARKUSINSKI_ANDY/O=MSMAIL/PRMD=SMITHS_IND./ADMD=TELEMAIL/C=US/@mailtalk.si.comARKUSINSKI ANDY </i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 30 Jan 93 11:56:38 GMT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#147">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#147">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#147">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#147">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0148.html">Malcolm Butler: "Re: Australia"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0146.html">cheryl berthelsen: "The cure for the evil on this earth"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I enjoy reading the little notes people put in about themselves.  It makes it <br>
more interesting to asociate more than just a name with the messages.  So to be <br>
fair I should tell something about myself.<br>
<p>
I'm currently living in the Grand Rapids, Michigan area. I've been here since <br>
1979, when I took a position with Lear Siegler, now known as Smiths Industries <br>
after a couple of sales.  I work as a systems engineer in the aerospace field, <br>
specifically with navigation and guidance systems for transport aircraft.<br>
<p>
I went to school at Southwestern Union College and Walla Walla College, <br>
receiving a BSE in electrical engineering in 1977.  I've also earned an MBA from <br>
Grand Valley State University.<br>
<p>
My wife's name is Holly.  We have a 10-month old daughter, Abigail Ann.  She's <br>
teaching us how to be parents, and having a difficult time of it, some days.  I <br>
could go on and on, but those of you who are parents know what it is like, and <br>
those of you who aren't would be bored, so I'll stop.<br>
<p>
A year and a half ago the Wyoming (suburb of GR) church asked me to be the <br>
Pathfinder director for the club that was being organized.  This is quite a <br>
challenge for someone who has never even been a Pathfinder, ever.  But we were <br>
an honor club our first year and are having a successful second year.  My <br>
personality just isn't the type for many direct outreach activities, but I find <br>
that I can set up the program and the kids will go out and enjoy doing those <br>
activities that are so difficult for me to do personally.  It really brings home <br>
to me the fact that we are all members of the same body, and though we have <br>
different talents, together we can meet the goal of spreading the gospel to the <br>
world.<br>
<p>
I really enjoy reading the messages, so much so that I found myself interrupting <br>
my work to read them as they came in.  Now I'm on the Digest and it's much <br>
better even though some messages are nearly two weeks old by the time I read <br>
them.  I print the week's Digest on Friday and take it home to read and share <br>
with family and friends over Sabbath.<br>
<p>
Andy Arkusinski<br>
arkusinski_andy@si.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
