<!-- body="start" -->
Sherman Cox writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;The main idea is that Christianity is a lifestyle that should affect every</i><br>
<i>&gt;thing you do.  Sometimes one can see an utter disregard for other  people</i><br>
<i>&gt;from those who claim to be christians.  I understand you come from, by your</i><br>
<i>&gt;testimony, a place where people lost an understanding of the message, so it </i><br>
<i>&gt;is understandable</i><br>
<i>&gt;that you would see a red flag when someone comes with the environment.</i><br>
<p>
I'm not sure if I would say people have lost an understanding of the<br>
message, though one could possibly make a case for this.  I do think,<br>
however, that we are failing to reach the majority of people because we<br>
have not realised that most people don't even believe in God, let alone<br>
the mark of the beast.  Traditionally, our outreach has always been most<br>
successful in attracting other christians.  I was told recently that<br>
this is the case even in non-christian countries such as the pacific<br>
islands: most of our membership comes from people already converted to<br>
other christian denominations, and compared to them we convert<br>
relatively few heathens.  (If anyone with better than third hand<br>
knowledge can correct this, please do so.)<br>
<p>
In such an environment (i.e., atheistic/agnostic), it is very important<br>
that our beliefs should be seen to have a positive impact on our<br>
lifestyle.  We shouldn't need to preach green-ness, but if we only<br>
preach the mark of the beast and the last judgement, people may be<br>
justified in missing the connection.<br>
<p>
Malcolm Butler<br>
<pre>
-- 
Switched Networks Research Centre,
Uni. of Technology, Sydney, Australia
</pre>
