<title>Jan_1993: Death and escape from death</title>
<h1>Death and escape from death</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 30 Jan 93 00:06:28 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#149">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#149">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#149">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#149">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0148.html">Malcolm Butler: "Re: Australia"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dear SDAnetters,<br>
<p>
I've been off the net for a few days and note a huge accumulation of postings<br>
about translations of the Bible and the environment.  You've all been busy!<br>
Not to side track the discussions or anything.  But I have had a particularly<br>
difficult two weeks dealing with some family tragedies.  Before I do though,<br>
I would like to point out that Jesus Christ was concerned about the<br>
environment.  After the feeding of the 5,000, He instructed the disciples to<br>
pick up the uneaten debri and collected it into baskets.  The Bible doesn't<br>
say it was for the purpose of saving it for the hungry.  I interpret this to<br>
mean that He was setting an example about how to respect the earth He created<br>
for us.<br>
<p>
Now on to the topic on my heart--death and grieving.  On XMAS day my sister's<br>
mother-in-law suffered a massive brain stem stroke.  After 3 agonizing weeks<br>
she finally died and they buried her last Friday.  My sister's husband was<br>
very close to his mother, having lost his father when he was 14.  She was<br>
just 70 years old and a very dear grandmother to my niece and nephew.  As<br>
all would guess, this has been a real family tragedy and very difficult for<br>
them to cope with.  Ironically, though, grief sometimes makes people act<br>
very strange and crazy and those grieving inflict pain on other family<br>
members.<br>
<p>
My brother-in-law's mother did not leave a will.  (Why do so many SDA's<br>
fail to leave a last will and testament?  Do they presume that Jesus Christ<br>
will return in their lifetime?)  He was one sister and over the years they<br>
have been quite close.  Their families vacation together every year even<br>
though thelive 1200 miles apart.  But their mother's death and the ensuing<br>
events of funeral and dealing with the estate has caused agonizing pain to<br>
my brother-in-law.  The sister and family arrived from out-of-state and<br>
immediately began rummaging through the deceased's home and earthly belongings.<br>
The kids gathered precious family treasures and claimed them for their own.<br>
My brother-in-law was horrified that they picked through the stuff like<br>
"the spoils of war" and his mother had not even been buried yet.  He begged<br>
his sister to please wait to discuss distribution of the her belongings<br>
until "she's in the ground."  But his sister wouldn't listen.  Major war<br>
broke out with the sister placing claim on everything of sentimental<br>
value stating that "mom would want **ME** to have this".  She refused to<br>
help pay any of the funeral expenses so my sister's family had to borrow<br>
$8,000 to cover the costs.  Immediately after the funeral, the "vulchers"<br>
returned to the home, gathering up everything they could possibly pack<br>
into their car and they left California to return home.  My sister found<br>
a note 3 days later (when their family ventured to the home), written by<br>
the "greedy" sister.  The note said, "Now that I have everything I want,<br>
do whatever you want with the rest."  My sister's family is left with<br>
the enormous task of packing up the deceased's belongings, the sale of<br>
the mobile home, paying off her debts which far exceed what the estate is<br>
worth, and disposing of what is not wanted.<br>
<p>
They had major fights about the funeral arrangements.  My brother-in-law<br>
knew his mother did not want to be cremated.  Yet the sister kept insisting<br>
that "it would be cheaper" and "she wouldn't know the difference anyway."<br>
The emotional support expected from family members was totally missing.  The<br>
sister seemed oblivious to the loss they had both just experienced.  For all<br>
intents and purposes, she was there to stake her claim on what she wanted<br>
and didn't seem to care about paying any respect for the dead.  My sister<br>
was deeply troubled by this and the agonized with the torment her husband<br>
was experiencing.  The loss of his mother was great but the attitude of<br>
his sister was killing him inside he said.<br>
<p>
Now I can't judge this woman but I cannot understand this behavior any more<br>
than my sister or her husband can.  It is SO OUT OF CHARACTER for her and<br>
so very unexpected.  Today, my sister discovered that the "pink slip" to<br>
the deceased's car was among the items taken out of state.  So my brother-<br>
in-law cannot sale the vehicle.  The sister took all of the family photo<br>
albums, all the personal effects of importance, and all items of value.<br>
Because these were removed from the state of where the deceased resided,<br>
my brother-in-law can't do anything about liquidating the estate to pay<br>
off some of the deceased's debts.<br>
<p>
Tonight, my sister called me sobbing her heart out.  She was at "Gram's<br>
trailer" and was supposed to packing up stuff.  But she just couldn't.<br>
<p>
Everything she packed reminded her of Gram's.  The very act of packing<br>
her stuff seemed a violation of Gram's life and privacy.  She couldn't<br>
stand it.  She missed Gram's so much.  (My sister was very close to her<br>
mother-in-law).  The hurt inflicted on her husband by his sister had<br>
become intolerable.  How could the two families ever speak again?  How<br>
could help her husband cope with the loss of both mother and sister?<br>
<p>
I'm asking the people on the net for help.  What can I say to my sister<br>
and the grieving husband?  What could possibly motivate such sibling<br>
cruelty at such a time of great grief?  How can my brother-in-law cope<br>
with these losses?  I can't tell him she didn't mean it.  I can't tell<br>
him to "forgive" or "leave it in God's hands."  I think the worst shame<br>
of all this is that my sister and her husband have been inactive SDAs<br>
for many years and just started attending church at their kids' request.<br>
This "cruel" sister is a very active SDA with conference office connections.<br>
Will my sister's family ever go to church again?  The wounds inflicted by<br>
the SDA sister are very deep and hideous.<br>
<p>
Thanks for your thoughtful replies.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
