<title>Aug_1992: Adventist Education</title>
<h1>Adventist Education</h1>
Tim Swensen (<i>swensen@ecn.purdue.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 18 Aug 92 16:17:42 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#29">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#29">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#29">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#29">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0030.html">Paul Johnston: "rules &amp; culture"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0028.html">Bill Nickless: "Re: measuring SDA school success"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0034.html">Bill Nickless: "Adventist Education"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In the summer of 1990 my brother and I had the opportunity of traveling<br>
to eastern Europe to see what things were like after the fall of the <br>
Berlin Wall.  It was an eye-opening experience in many ways, not the <br>
least of which was the realization it brought to me of how privileged <br>
"Westerners" are, especially Adventist Westerners.  I trust you will not<br>
bemoan the following as simply a vignette of the "be thankful for what<br>
you have" variety.<br>
<p>
All the discussion of Adventist education brings to mind the time Ron<br>
(my brother) and I decided to look up a church in Budapest.  It was <br>
Sabbath morning and time was running short.  I figured it may be tough to<br>
find an Adventist church on such short notice since I didn't know<br>
Hungarian.  Nonetheless, I went to the phone book and started thumbing <br>
through the S section.  No luck.  Then the A's.  Ah hah!  The only listings<br>
involving something to do with "Adventista" jumped out at me.  I checked the<br>
map and found the street listing for what turned out to be the largest<br>
Adventist church in Hungary.<br>
<p>
It didn't appear to be a church from the street entrance, but we figured,<br>
"Who else would be meeting on Saturday morning?"  Sure enough.  One look at<br>
some of the literature posted on the bulletin board  (Voice of Prophecy <br>
or Adventist World Radio, or something like that) and I knew we were at <br>
the right place.<br>
<p>
After the service (of which I didn't understand a word, but still enjoyed),<br>
we talked with a young man (age 20, I would guess) who spoke pretty good<br>
English.  He wanted to train for the ministry but his conference didn't <br>
have the money to send him to any of the Adventist institutions of western<br>
Europe or North America.  He said he was attending a Calvinist seminary in<br>
Hungary since this was affordable.<br>
<p>
Doesn't something seem wrong about a young Adventist eager to train for the<br>
pastorate at ANY Adventist institution but is unable, while scores of well-to-<br>
do Adventists such as myself dissect the myriad perceived faults and <br>
injustices of a parochial school system designed to prepare Christians to <br>
serve Christ more effectively?  (Do I have consensus on this albeit overly<br>
general but hopefully undisputable definition of Adventist education's <br>
mission?) Where is our sense of perspective?  (I speak to myself as well as<br>
to the net.)  For the cost of sending a few young adults to an SDA college<br>
we can hold meetings in Russia where hundreds, if not thousands, of people<br>
make decisions for Christ.  Thus, it would appear that we value Adventist<br>
education highly.  Do we?  Perhaps the crisis many feel is developing in<br>
Adventist education is not one of quality but of purpose, as many of the <br>
posts preceding mine have alluded to.<br>
<p>
I've said enough.  I hope this adds another viewpoint to the already lively<br>
discussion on this topic.<br>
<p>
Tim Swensen<br>
swensen@ecn.purdue.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
