<!-- id="geYZFYS00WB7A2nnp3@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Aug_1992: rules &amp; culture</title>
<h1>rules &amp; culture</h1>
Paul Johnston (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 19 Aug 1992 10:02:12 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#30">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#30">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#30">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#30">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0031.html">Paul Johnston: "Re: measuring SDA school success"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0029.html">Tim Swensen: "Adventist Education"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[These are the words of Paul Johnston, double-spaced due to the fact<br>
that sometimes people forget to end each line with a CR and make messages<br>
which I can't send out over the net unless I edit them.  He refers to <br>
the post of a Dean M. Kelley, which puzzles me since there is no such<br>
person on the net.  SCT]<br>
<p>
I see a connecting thread through much of the correspondence of the past<br>
<p>
few months.  There is a struggle over identity.  What is the real<br>
<p>
Adventist Church?  And what's a real Adventist?  From what I've read, it<br>
<p>
seems like a lot of us are trying to figure out if, or how, we each fit<br>
<p>
in.<br>
 <br>
I'm writing you now without answers to those questions--except to say,<br>
<p>
"It depends..."  But my own questions of identity came a little more<br>
<p>
into focus reading the items from Alice Fay Martin and Dean M. Kelly.  I<br>
<p>
hope some of you can bring your unique perspectives to bear on these<br>
<p>
problems.<br>
<p>
Incidentally, there's probably a link between what I see as an identity<br>
<p>
crisis in North American Adventism and flat growth charts.  Yet, isn't<br>
<p>
identity diluted by diversity?  And isn't diversity an unavoidable<br>
<p>
biproduct of growth?  And doesn't growth depend on distinctiveness?  And<br>
<p>
isn't distinctiveness the source of an organization's identity?  And<br>
<p>
isn't identity diluted by diversity?  And...  you must be gettng my<br>
<p>
drift.<br>
<p>
I guess the difficulty is this:  no denomination can be expected to be<br>
<p>
big enough to contain any individual's unique set of needs,<br>
<p>
indiosyncracies, and beliefs.  But no individual is strong enough to<br>
<p>
stand alone either.  In my case, the SDA Church is certainly far from a<br>
<p>
perfect fit.  (In fact, it's an outfit which too frequently embarrassed<br>
<p>
me.)  But there is a symbiosis where I've gained important spiritual<br>
<p>
nurture and where I've been able to contribute significantly to the<br>
<p>
church body, at least on a local level.  That's kind of an<br>
<p>
issues-oriented answer and kind of a cultural answer and kind of<br>
<p>
lukewarm.  It lacks the "burning in the bosom" which my Mormon friends<br>
<p>
testify to.<br>
<p>
So Alice Fay's central question strikes close to home for me.  I hope<br>
<p>
some of you will come up with a better answer than I have so far.  She<br>
<p>
asks, "How can I know the culture from the important issues...?"  Alice<br>
<p>
Fay--as far as I can tell, we'll never be able to distinguish the<br>
<p>
culture from the important issues.  Culture isn't an isolated commodity.<br>
<p>
 A culture is defined by its people, its issues, politics, art, history,<br>
<p>
economics, religion.  A person is defined by the culture around him or<br>
<p>
her.  So there's an unbreakable tie between a people and a person. <br>
<p>
There's also an unbreakable tie between what you call "culture" and what<br>
<p>
you call "important issues."  If there's something screwy about our<br>
<p>
Adventist culture, there must be something screwy about its<br>
<p>
sources--something in our psyche or hermeneutical style or origins or<br>
<p>
whatever.  The best you and I can do now is decide if it's worth our<br>
<p>
effort to try to contribute to the subculture of Adventism and if we<br>
<p>
like the influence it's having on us.<br>
<p>
There's not much we can do about your friend's observation about our<br>
<p>
rules without her "getting inside" our culture.  Every culture has<br>
<p>
certain defining values.  They look ridiculous and arbitrary to the<br>
<p>
uninitiated.  But they're not entirely arbitrary.  They've evolved,<br>
<p>
partly by design and partly, I think, by accident.  These "rules" shape<br>
<p>
us and tell us who we are until, or unless, we chuck 'em.<br>
<p>
I'm active in the Shadyside SDA Church in Pittsburgh.  It's close to<br>
<p>
where I work at WQED.  I also like to attend St. Andrew's Episcopal<br>
<p>
Church, close to where I live.  Now, Episcopalians have rules too.  I<br>
<p>
mean cultural rules.  There are things you just do.  Some of them seem<br>
<p>
silly to the alien.  There are a lot of what we Adventists tend to call<br>
<p>
empty or meaningless rituals.  But as you participate in--become a part<br>
<p>
of--those rituals, over time, they take on meaning for you.  They are<br>
<p>
empty only as long as you bring nothing to them.  You discover that the<br>
<p>
seemingly meaningless rote of the liturgy is neither meaningless nor<br>
<p>
rote--it's just not as theatrical as we Adventists expect.  Ritual is<br>
<p>
valuable and unavoidable on individual and corporate levels.  But one<br>
<p>
person's meaningful ritual is another's irrelevent rule.<br>
<p>
Obviously, I'm the type Dean M. Kelley warned against when telling us<br>
<p>
elsewhere on the net what Adventists can do to stop growing.  He pointed<br>
<p>
out--and statistics support his case--that growing churches are<br>
<p>
conservative and distinctive.  Fellow networkers, that brings us back to<br>
<p>
questions I have about the identities of my church and myself.  Is<br>
<p>
conservatism something I want to preserve in order to see the<br>
<p>
institution grow?  If we deliberately try to preserve our uniqueness,<br>
<p>
don't we run the risk of being a mere novelty?<br>
<p>
-- Paul Johnston<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
