<!-- id="9208212126.AA17310@lunch" -->
<!-- inreplyto="9208182117.AA29953@ec.ecn.purdue.edu" -->
<title>Aug_1992: Adventist Education</title>
<h1>Adventist Education</h1>
Bill Nickless (<i>nickless@antares.mcs.anl.gov</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 21 Aug 1992 16:26:11 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#34">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#34">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#34">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#34">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0035.html">Ian Brown: "Question of translation"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0033.html">Tony: "Re: Adventist Education"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0029.html">Tim Swensen: "Adventist Education"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Tim Swensen asks (and I apologize if I miss his point) why those of us<br>
fortunate enough to attend our Adventist schools criticize those same schools,<br>
especially when many people in other countries, who dearly wish to attend,<br>
cannot do so due to financial or political barriers.<br>
<p>
I feel that this is a way of avoiding the issue.  A similar argument advanced<br>
by a residence hall dean was, "if you don't like it here (because you don't<br>
feel like you're being treated like adults,) exercise your assumed right as an<br>
adult to leave and go elsewhere."<br>
<p>
Why can't I have both?<br>
<p>
Why must I accept being treated like less than a person in order to receive a<br>
Christian education?  I do not want my Adventist school to turn into a huge<br>
public school.  If I wanted a huge public university setting with the<br>
hedonistic lifestyle that goes along with it I would have gone there.  Are the<br>
defenders of Adventist education so arrogant (sorry, strong word) as to say<br>
that they have the perfect system "because people want to attend from all over<br>
the world" and that there is no room for improvement?<br>
<p>
I believe that our schools can fulfill their mission of training people for<br>
service without being patronizing and controlling.  Further, I believe they<br>
can provide a Christian environment without micromanaging the lives of each of<br>
the students.  This is the end I advocate.  Can't we have it both ways?<br>
<p>
--Bill Nickless<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0035.html">Ian Brown: "Question of translation"</a>
