<title>Aug_1992: (no subject)</title>
<h1>(no subject)</h1>
Alice Fay Martin (<i>armg9488@uxa.cso.uiuc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 5 Aug 1992 11:47:57 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#0">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#0">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#0">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#0">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0001.html">C9105461@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "(no subject)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
This is a reply forwarded from Paul Gates with a few added <br>
comments from myself, denoted by &lt;.....&gt;<br>
.............<br>
<p>
I read your email on the SDA net and wanted to make a couple of <br>
comments.<br>
<p>
Concerning your friend who married outside of her faith, I would <br>
hesitate to say that she is not saved. We really do not have that <br>
prorogative(spelling??). From reading your message I would say that <br>
the Pastor and the people must also accept a part of the blame.<br>
<p>
I have been a pastor for 36 years and I hope I have learned a few <br>
things.I do not know all the "in's and out's of this situation but I can <br>
share with you how I would have handled the situation.<br>
<p>
It would appear that the pastor did counsel with the young lady and <br>
advise her not to marry outside of the faith and explain to her all the <br>
reasons for that counseling.  <br>
<p>
 &lt;&lt;..... Unfortunately, there was no counseling from the pastor.  From <br>
what I understand they did not request counseling. There was a <br>
request to use the church building for the service but it was basically <br>
ignored by the pastor (no reply) so they had the service in a Moslem <br>
prayer hall.  To complete though, I think there were a number of <br>
church members who did take the time to express thier concern with <br>
her decision, but clearly declined to attend the wedding......afm &gt;&gt;<br>
<p>
If she still went ahead and married the young man. I would have <br>
accepted her decision and let her know that I did. Our social <br>
committee would have had a bridal shower for the young girl. I <br>
would have made it a point if possible to make friends with the <br>
young man and discover what his interests are. If he played golf I <br>
would take him out golfing with me and say nothing about the <br>
situation -- just have a good time with him and get  better <br>
acquainted with him. My wife and I would socialize with them <br>
outside of church time. Since I am an Amateur radio operator I <br>
would discovered if the couple would like to come over to the house <br>
and let them see or hear I should say some of the contacts that I <br>
could make with other stations in USA as well as overseas. I would <br>
let them both know that the church felt like they (the church) loved <br>
them and were their extended family! I would try to involve them in <br>
church activities whenever possible.   &lt;&lt;... We did have a nice shower <br>
for her...&gt;&gt;<br>
<p>
By doing the above you are not condoning the "union" and the girl <br>
knows that but she would also know that the Pastor and the church <br>
still loved both and were their friends. They made the decision to get <br>
married in spite of the counseling. So let's pick up from here and go <br>
on. I have plenty of couples in my church that wed non-believers in <br>
the past. Sometimes this happens because there are no available <br>
Adventists to marry. The non-SDA spouses are very close to the <br>
members of the church and in a few cases the spouses have given up <br>
their church affilation and joined the Adventist church. I have 2 <br>
prospective spouses right now that may be baptized by the end of <br>
the year. BTW when I did the counseling I would have counseled <br>
both of them and I would let the young man know what it meant to <br>
marry an SDA. <br>
<p>
This morning I went golfing with the Episcopalian, &amp; Lutheran <br>
Pastors. The Catholic Priest was supposed to go with us but he had a <br>
funeral. We all had a good time playing 9 holes and then went to <br>
McDonald's for lunch. While we were eating both pastors said to me, " <br>
You know Paul, sometime I would like to know what Adventist really <br>
believe we do not know anything about Adventism and have always <br>
wondered. We know you all go to church on Saturday but that is the <br>
extent of our knowledge." I belong to the local ministerial association <br>
with them. We all thought today that it would be a good idea to share <br>
with one another at one of our ministerial meetings what we as <br>
christians believe.<br>
<p>
You can never tell what will happen or what God has in mind even <br>
when we go against His plan as in the case with your friend.<br>
<p>
Paul Gates<br>
<p>
&lt;&lt;...  Thanx for the reply...  The more I look at this situation I think I <br>
am just sad to observe it.  This lady is a wonderful person.  She <br>
directed a play with a "young adult" cast not more than 4 months ago <br>
and enjoyed being a greeter on Sat. mornings, and yet in full <br>
knowledge of the risks and possible sacrifices she was taking, went <br>
ahead.... and now she appears reluctant to participate.  Maybe it will <br>
just take time and yes continued love from the church.  Maybe I just <br>
lack faith in them and myself to do so..... &gt;&gt;<br>
<p>
&lt;&lt;...Just for interest sake... this was also a marriage of two different <br>
races.  I haven't a problem with this but fear it may add even more <br>
differences and complexities in the future....&gt;&gt;<br>
<p>
&lt;&lt; Alice Martin   armg9488@uxa.cso.uiuc.edu    &gt;&gt;<br>
