<!-- body="start" -->
Concerning the marriage of adventists to non SDA's Paul gates wrote that we<br>
should still socialise and be friendly with them. <br>
<p>
&lt;By doing the above you are not condoning the "union" and the girl <br>
&lt;knows that but she would also know that the Pastor and the church <br>
&lt;still loved both and were their friends. They made the decision to get <br>
&lt;married in spite of the counseling. So let's pick up from here and go <br>
&lt;on.<br>
<p>
I think that this extremely important.  We don't have to agree with their<br>
decision but by being critical and often downwright rude we aren't giving that<br>
person (or perhaps more importantly their spouse) a very good impression of us<br>
and our church.  The church is not some exclusive social club.  We are very<br>
happy to welcome visitors into our churches irrespective of their religion. <br>
Why shouldn't we afford the same degree of friendship to our own members?<br>
<p>
Often people who marry outside there own religion will experience this sort of<br>
attitude where it's like they are no longer welcome at church.  If we maintain<br>
our support and friendship at least they may still be SDA's even if their<br>
spouses never do. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
