<title>Aug_1992: Things to do with campus groups</title>
<h1>Things to do with campus groups</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun,  9 Aug 1992 13:12:50 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#2">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#2">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#2">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#2">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0003.html">Steven Timm: "Subculture,Superculture, or Counterculture?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0001.html">C9105461@cc.newcastle.edu.au: "(no subject)"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I saw Dave Thomas' post a while ago and didn't have time to respond--<br>
things have been quite hectic as I am in the midst of a move with <br>
half of my stuff in Pittsburgh and the other half in Chicago  (I'm<br>
heading towards Pittsburgh) and there is still a lot of work to be done<br>
in Chicago.<br>
<p>
At Carnegie Mellon we tried a few things.  There are three SDA students<br>
at CMU that I know about right now, and there are times that I've been the <br>
only one.  <br>
<p>
Principle 1:  If you offer free food, someone will always show up.<br>
Students can't resist.<br>
<p>
Principle 2:  Students want discussion that's relevant to them.  Even <br>
though they may be yuppie wanna-be's, they aren't interested in going<br>
to listen to a bunch of doctors moaning about how hard it is to find <br>
good tires for their Volvo.  Students deal with real-life problems.<br>
<p>
Principle 3:  You need to keep it cheap.  Most students are poor<br>
and may have problems going out to eat somewhere, or other expensive things.<br>
They may also be ashamed to admit it.<br>
<p>
Principle 4:  If you are part of a group which includes students and <br>
other young professionals, and you are planning an activity to which the <br>
whole group is not invited, have enough tact not to discuss your activity<br>
in front of those who are not invited.  In many groups an "inner circle"<br>
is obvious and obnoxious.<br>
<p>
Principle 5:  Go through the exercise of making a list of every <br>
SDA college student in your town.  You will find there are lots more <br>
than you think.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
