<title>Aug_1992: Subculture,Superculture, or Counterculture?</title>
<h1>Subculture,Superculture, or Counterculture?</h1>
Bill Nickless (<i>nickless@antares.mcs.anl.gov</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 11 Aug 92 00:08:07 CDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#4">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#4">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#4">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#4">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0005.html">Bill Nickless: "Subculture,Superculture, or Counterculture?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0003.html">Steven Timm: "Subculture,Superculture, or Counterculture?"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0003.html">Steven Timm: "Subculture,Superculture, or Counterculture?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0005.html">Bill Nickless: "Subculture,Superculture, or Counterculture?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; However, since nobody has told the people at the SDA colleges that the</i><br>
<i>&gt; subculture is dead yet, it still persists in these historical communities.</i><br>
<p>
The subculture is far from dead.  There still exist plenty of churches outside<br>
the saltworks such as Berrien Springs and Loma Linda that are full of what you<br>
would consider a dead subculture.<br>
<p>
The Adventist educational system derives its purpose (dare I say legitimacy?)<br>
from providing a traditional Adventist educational environment.  To allow<br>
for--let alone encourage--deviation from the traditional Adventist orthodoxy<br>
is to undermine the structure on which the system is built.<br>
<p>
Simple principle: people who expect the colleges and academies to indoctrinate<br>
and reform the students are much more vocal and involved than people who<br>
expect the colleges and academies to simply provide a wholesome atmosphere and<br>
Adventist doctrinal teaching.  When was the last time you heard of a parent<br>
writing to a college dean saying "how dare you keep my daughter locked up in<br>
the dormitory, violating her rights as a person, when she's doing well in<br>
school and has demonstrated over and over to us her trustworthiness?"<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Should we put our lifestyle forth as a sort of spiritual Epcot center?</i><br>
<p>
I think there is something to that.  More later, if anyone is interested.<br>
<p>
--Bill<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
