<!-- subject="SDA subculture" -->
<!-- id="9208112303.AA04707@csd4.csd.uwm.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Aug_1992: SDA subculture</title>
<h1>SDA subculture</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 11 Aug 92 18:03:07 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#7">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#7">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#7">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#7">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0008.html">McCluskey G: "measuring SDA school success"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0006.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Subculture,Superculture, or Counterculture?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve would like to declare the subculture dead and in many ways it is.<br>
Many have realized that the goal of turning out thousands of well-trained<br>
workers for the church is not happening.  SDA colleges ARE turning out<br>
well-trained workers for society, productive individuals who are responsible,<br>
law-abiding citizens.  The "SDA factory" which intended to turn out many<br>
identically-thinking SDAs whose primary loyalty in life is the SDA church<br>
malfunctioned a long time ago.  Young people were encouraged to think and<br>
decide for themselves and then saddled with rules and regulations that<br>
strip them all dignity implying they really can't think and decide for<br>
themselves.  Many now know the truth of the matter.  The primary purpose<br>
of SDA educational system is train for church-related jobs.  Many majors<br>
that do not have a role in the institution have never been offered at<br>
SDA colleges.  (Is a J.D. offered anywhere?  How about a Ph.D. in Psychology?<br>
A Ph.D. in Nuclear Physics?)  Actually doctorates have been essentially in<br>
the Professions (M.D., D.D.S) or education (Ed.D.).  There has never been<br>
an active thrust to provide for all fields because the church mainly needed<br>
teachers for the elemetary and secondary school systems and medical personnel<br>
for the health system and missionary appointments.  The SDA educational<br>
system of higher education was to provide training for "SDA church jobs."<br>
This changed when many young people in the 1960s started looking at other<br>
career options and SDA colleges gradually changed to offer "Christian<br>
education" as opposed to "Heathen edcuation at public colleges".  Somebody<br>
forgot why the system was started in the first place!  I find it very<br>
interesting that at least 50% of SDA medical school graduates before 1960<br>
served as missionaries while maybe 1/100 of 1990s graduates will even<br>
think about doing so.  When the SDA church lost is "Medical Missionary"<br>
focus, the SDA educational system lost its reason to exist.  So it changed<br>
into a place where a young person could be indoctrinated.  I remember my<br>
parents lamenting that so and so's child had rebelled and was going to<br>
attend state college.  In other words, not wanting to go to SDA college<br>
was equivalent to apostacy--a refusal be indoctrinated.  This transition<br>
is obvious when you talk with anyone who attended SDA college before 1950-60.<br>
They aren't bitter about ridiculous rules and regulations.  My own parents<br>
always felt it was a "privilege" to attend Union College and what a job<br>
in the church meant to them.  It meant security.  It meant working with<br>
believers.  It was to be "heaven on earth".  Ask anyone who attended in<br>
the 1960-70s and you will find many bitter young people.  Those who suffered<br>
gross injustices.  Those who rebelled at the heavy-handed military-style<br>
discipline.  Those who were kicked out of college for seemingly minor<br>
infractions.  (I was kicked out of the dorm at La Sierra one semester about<br>
finals time.  I was never told WHAT I had done and was given no chance to<br>
either defend myself on anonymous charges or understand why I was being<br>
treated so.  GUILTY without chance of a trial is universal among SDA<br>
institutions.  Even now, 20 later, I do not know what I as accused of.  I<br>
do know that my two roommates, daughters of rich influential doctors at<br>
Loma Linda, didn't want a 3rd roommate and had made my life miserable for<br>
months before that.  After a plea to the President of the College, I was<br>
allowed to take final exams as long as I commuted from home with a car<br>
I did not have.  That was the most miserable semester in my life!)<br>
<p>
Almost all SDA college gradautes are functioning members of society.  I<br>
think the number in prison is minute.  Just because they didn't stay in<br>
the church doesn't mean the system has failed.  It means that many SDA<br>
now see SDA college for what it really is--NOT a place to train for a<br>
church-related job!  NOT a place to indoctrinate young people!  It IS<br>
a place where SDA young people can study together and prepare for careers,<br>
and become functional members of society.  If that happens with the last<br>
(least) amount of grief, then the systems is successful.  The success of<br>
an educational institution is measured by the number of graduates who are<br>
successful in careers and life!<br>
<p>
cheryl<br>
cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
