<title>Aug_1992: Individuals are responsible</title>
<h1>Individuals are responsible</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 14 Aug 1992 10:47 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#20">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#20">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#20">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#20">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0021.html">Russell Grau: "Individuals are responsible"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0019.html">Steve Hix: "Re: measuring SDA school success"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; It seems to me that as long as the place called "out there" is defined</i><br>
<i>&gt; in the minds of SDA students, then SDA schools have not done their job. </i><br>
<i>&gt; Once</i><br>
<i>&gt; a person leaves an SDA school, he or she should be ready to approach the </i><br>
<i>&gt; world, not as an enemy or a stranger, but ready to serve.  Of course, </i><br>
<i>&gt; some people never learn this task, SDA school or no.</i><br>
<p>
I think that's the point...it all comes down to the individual.<br>
<p>
As for the "out there" thing, I would venture to say that this<br>
is historically important in Adventism. Hence the main reason students<br>
have this place in their minds is through the attitudes of their parents<br>
and other members of their church community. If Adventist schools are<br>
perpetuating this attitude, then it is because the teachers also relate<br>
to society this way.<br>
<p>
How can any of us expect the system to change, when it is so self-<br>
perpetuating? Mostly those of us who disagree with the separationist<br>
stance do not teach within the SDA school system. Many of us never<br>
will, leaving the schools with a majority of teachers/administrators<br>
who continue to convey the "us and them" mentality.<br>
<p>
I definitely feel that if anything the schools reflect a slightly <br>
liberal side of the church populace in general. It seems unfair to<br>
criticize the people working in the institutions of the church when<br>
they are no worse than the general church attender. <br>
<p>
If a person feels they "can't relate" to people outside their church <br>
community, I hardly think this can be blamed on their school. There are <br>
plenty of agnostics in state schools that can't relate socially.<br>
<p>
Tony Dyson<br>
University of Newcastle<br>
Australia<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
