<title>Aug_1992: Individuals are responsible</title>
<h1>Individuals are responsible</h1>
Russell Grau (<i>reg@ctsx.celtech.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 13 Aug 92 09:23 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#21">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#21">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#21">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#21">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0022.html">Russell Grau: "Individuals are responsible"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0020.html">Tony: "Individuals are responsible"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Re:Adventist Education Failures....<br>
<p>
Tony Dyson writes:<br>
<i>&gt;I've been following the discussion regarding Adventist education and</i><br>
<i>&gt;institutions with interest, and one thing which has come across very</i><br>
<i>&gt;strongly is this conclusion that SDA schools are not "working" at all.</i><br>
<p>
I would find this hard to believe.  But, on the other hand, what we are seeing<br>
is simply an extension of what the church as a body desires.  It is hard to<br>
blame everything on the governing council of the church, the adminstrators<br>
of the colleges, etc, when most often people are unwilling to take a stand on<br>
what they see as the necessary vision for Adventist education.<br>
<p>
Further, as the church has grown, have we not all seen the secularization of<br>
the church itself?  As a teenager in a non-Adventist home, I can remember<br>
many times visiting Adventist homes in the 70's where TV was not to be found.<br>
Today, it is rare that you don't see one in operation and also tons of VCR <br>
tapes (not a flame - I have a TV and a VCR.  Just a contrast in the times).<br>
<p>
Why should this not also occur with our institutions?  Through the years it<br>
can be said that we have been courting the media.  In order to do this you<br>
have to do something spectacular (transplant a monkey heart to a little girl)<br>
or else you have to change what people view as not important in their sight<br>
(possibly our sense of missions?  I don't know, just wondering aloud :-)<br>
<p>
As a teenager, I longed for SDA high schools.  I never could attend.  Then, as<br>
an young adult, I could only afford a single year at SW Adventist College.<br>
<p>
During that year, 1978, I guess I lost my innocence with regard to the schools.<br>
I also matured a lot during this time as I was forced to come in from the<br>
"real world" into the sub-culture.<br>
<p>
I don't know about the others on this list, but, I ended up graduating from <br>
a state-supported institution.  It was ALWAYS the rule that the professors<br>
spoke about what happened in the "real world".  And, how the university atmos-<br>
phere did not even compare.<br>
<p>
While in the sub-culture of Adventist colleges you have certain values and<br>
expectations, I found that the only difference in public college was that <br>
you had more "freedom" of expression.  You know, things like short dresses,<br>
long hair, stay up all night if you wanted to, not have chapel, etc, etc.<br>
<p>
While we can and should cheer the "death" of the sub-culture, let us be wary<br>
that we do not replace it with another culture that is unto death.  A sense <br>
of mission is the cornerstone of our educational system.  If we have lost that,<br>
then we really have nothing more than what another writer intimated, a<br>
second-rate educational system that will and cannot meet the expectations of<br>
a secular world and church.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;The students</i><br>
<i>&gt;themselves are a part of the system, and they must take the responsibility</i><br>
<i>&gt;for their own decisions.</i><br>
<p>
I agree.  The Valuegenesis study showed us that the students are more than <br>
willing to take responsibility if we let them.  Problem is, too many of our<br>
students have no sense of anything. (boy am I going to get it over that one :0)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Let the discussion continue...</i><br>
Amen.<br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Tony Dyson</i><br>
<i>&gt;University of Newcastle</i><br>
<i>&gt;Australia</i><br>
<p>
