<title>Aug_1992: Fails miserably?</title>
<h1>Fails miserably?</h1>
Bill Nickless (<i>nickless@antares.mcs.anl.gov</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 14 Aug 92 07:15:28 CDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#24">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#24">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#24">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#24">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0025.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Re: measuring SDA school success"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0023.html">Stan Macasieb: "Re: measuring SDA school success"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0013.html">Tony: "Fails miserably?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I don't think our (Adventist) schools are "failing miserably."  I really<br>
don't.  The opportunity to study in a small-department environment is quite<br>
valuable and positive.  I got an undergraduate education that allows me to<br>
function at a level competitive with the some advanced degreed people here at<br>
the lab.  That is directly attributable to the availability of one-on-one<br>
caring faculty.<br>
<p>
My concerns focus more on the insularity and indoctrination/control that I<br>
experienced both at Andrews and at the academy.  This goes back to needing a<br>
metric other than enrollment to measure effectiveness.  The requirement for<br>
freshmen to stay in the dorms from 7:30 to 9:30 weeknights during their first<br>
quarter was justified in terms of keeping enrollment up (in a personal<br>
conversation with the dean when I was a junior.)<br>
<p>
--Bill<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
