<title>Aug_1992: Dress codes</title>
<h1>Dress codes</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>COTRSSM@sea04vm.navsea.navy.mil</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 16 Aug 92 22:02:04 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#26">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#26">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#26">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#26">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0027.html">Russell Grau: "Re: measuring SDA school success"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0025.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Re: measuring SDA school success"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0040.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Dress codes"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On Fri, 14 Aug 1992 11:38:53 -0400 (EDT) you said:<br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; ............. stuff deleted .................</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;SO...WHY do SDA schools continue to focus on ridiculous standards such as</i><br>
<i>&gt;jewelry, make-up, and dress codes?  Why are "designer jeans" still prohibited?</i><br>
<i>&gt;Why must the artificial standards of the previous generation still pervade</i><br>
<i>&gt;the SDA educational system?</i><br>
<p>
  I must admit to not knowing a thing about SDA school codes but for<br>
what it is worth;<br>
<p>
  As long as the 'code' is vague enough to allow individual variety, but<br>
specific enough to make it clear what is expected, a dress code is<br>
alright.  In fact, using the one in the Bible fits most occasions.<br>
Modest dress and not all painted up or bedecked with jewels.  IMO,<br>
things like 'designer jeans' (that are usually painted on), 5 earrings<br>
in each ear (but none that match), and a 1/4" of pancake mix (to hide a<br>
naturally pretty face) are not in keeping with God's ideas.<br>
<p>
  Modesty is never out-of-date.<br>
<p>
Scott       | No success can compensate for failure in the home. David O. McKay<br>
Mattes      | President 1951-70, Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints<br>
