<title>Aug_1992: Question of translation</title>
<h1>Question of translation</h1>
Ian Brown (<i>Malachi.Robertson@lambada.oit.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 21 Aug 92 12:14:30 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#35">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#35">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#35">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#35">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0036.html">Ian Brown: "Question of translation"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0034.html">Bill Nickless: "Adventist Education"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I was wondering if any of my Adventist brethren knew Hebrew and could give<br>
me a literal rendering of Daniel 11:14.  I ask this as it has implications<br>
on how to view this verse in prophecy.  My NRSV translates the last part<br>
of the verse as "The lawless among your own people shall lift themselves<br>
up in order to fulfill the vision, but they shall fail."  The way this is<br>
translated makes it seem that the lawless are a subset of "your own<br>
people".  Does the actual Hebrew imply this?  Or is it possible given the<br>
Hebrew to view the lawless as just coming in among the people and not<br>
necessarily being a part of them?<br>
<p>
Thanks for your help.<br>
<p>
"Malachi Robertson" better known as Ian Robertson Brown<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
