<title>Aug_1992: Re: Message from Internet</title>
<h1>Re: Message from Internet</h1>
Paul Gates (<i>70516.420@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>21 Aug 92 21:46:46 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#37">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#37">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#37">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#37">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0038.html">Tim Swensen: "Adventist Education"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0036.html">Ian Brown: "Question of translation"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Russell Grau:<br>
<p>
Hi Russell, Dress codes etc are not a problem of our generation only! My<br>
motherinlaw used to tell me about the hassle in her day!!<br>
<p>
Some christians, so called, focus so much on outward appearance that it<br>
frustrates other people. Then also the reasoning behind some codes or<br>
rules just does not make sense. Back in the 40s I was instructed in grade<br>
school and academy that movies were a no-no because of the evil influence<br>
of the people in attendance in theaters. That was no problem for me<br>
because I could go to a movie by myself, my parents or take my girl<br>
friend and we did not associate with the others in the theater. I might<br>
add and perhaps I have mentioned this before -- My dad was not an<br>
adventist. My dad had problems with drinking etc. My mother felt that<br>
going to movies on Sat. night was something we could do with my dad and<br>
keep him sober and away from the bars, women etc. My mother often told me<br>
that doing this was against the teachings of the Adventist church but at<br>
the same time she wanted to hold our family together.<br>
<p>
As I got older ........  Then there was the thing against going bowling<br>
because in some bowling  alleys they served beer. My friends and I could<br>
go bowling and leave and we didn't drink the beer and we did not go to<br>
movies.  I figured it was better than staying home on Saturday night and<br>
watching TV.<br>
<p>
One more case in point: When I moved to Grand Ledge, MI my son Clayton<br>
thought he might take his senior year of academy at Grand Ledge<br>
Adventist Academy and live home as oppossed to living in the dorm at<br>
Adelphian. As early in his life that Clayton could grow a mustache, he had<br>
one. When he went to pre-register at GLAA, he was told that he would have<br>
to shave his mustache off as it was not in keeping with the dress code of<br>
the school! Now mind you, he was willing to shave it off as it was no big<br>
deal. However, he could not get all the required subjects that he needed<br>
for his senior year so he went back to Adelphian for his senior year and<br>
kept his mustache which he wears today at age 35!<br>
<p>
It is things like the above that frustrates some of us. It seem like in<br>
the Adventist church that after something goes out of style that it is ok<br>
with Adventists. Beards are a good case in point.<br>
<p>
Idealistically, I believe that it is not my place to pin point everything<br>
that a Christian can or cannot do as it is in the minds of some people and<br>
preach it on Sabbath. I believe it is my mandate to point people to Christ<br>
and the gospel and allow the Holy Spirit to work in the life of an<br>
individual.<br>
<p>
.........Paul<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
