<title>Aug_1992: Adventist Education</title>
<h1>Adventist Education</h1>
Tim Swensen (<i>swensen@ecn.purdue.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 21 Aug 92 17:46:39 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#38">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#38">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#38">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#38">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0039.html">Paul Gates: "Re: measuring SDA school success"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0037.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Message from Internet"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Bill Nickless makes a good point in saying that we should be able to<br>
constructively criticize the Adventist educational system without being told<br>
to "live with it or leave it."  In this I wholeheartedly agree.  My story of<br>
the experience I had in Hungary was meant to supply some balance to what I felt<br>
to be a large number of fairly negative posts.  It was not meant to squelch the<br>
discussion.<br>
<p>
Indeed, I remember chafing under the sometimes weighty burden of rules I lived<br>
with in Adventist schools.  Being told that they are good for you is not<br>
terribly appealing at age 18!  My Mom and I chuckle at some of the antics her<br>
generation went through to go on an off-campus date.<br>
<p>
I feel it would be inaccurate to characterize Adventist schools as failing in<br>
their mission.  At the same time, it must be admitted that the goal of <br>
training students to make progressively more important decisions is a lofty <br>
one -- one which in many cases is unattained.<br>
<p>
So I ask the net, How do we as church leaders teach the younger generation <br>
to take more and more responsibility for their lives?  How do we teach them<br>
to ask the questions and gather the facts (from Scripture and human experience)<br>
that will enable them to make healthy choices?  And, crucially, how do we<br>
react when students choose to walk down ultimately destructive paths.  <br>
<p>
Since I am the teen Sabbath school class leader at our local church, I would <br>
be interested in your responses.  I am gleaning some important tidbits <br>
from Roger Dudley's book "Why Teenagers Reject Religion," but always welcome<br>
more.<br>
<p>
<p>
Tim Swensen<br>
swensen@ecn.purdue.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
