<title>Aug_1992: Drug money</title>
<h1>Drug money</h1>
Adam David (<i>adamd@rhi.hi.is</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 22 Aug 92 7:04:07 GMT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#41">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#41">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#41">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#41">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0042.html">McCluskey G: "Re: drug money"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0040.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Dress codes"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
About a month ago, Fred Christiansen asked whether drug money would be<br>
acceptable if offered for funding. I don't remember anyone answering this,<br>
perhaps because it was intended to be obvious that such could never be.<br>
There are some difficult issues involved, but if no strings were attached<br>
the only hinderance would be some federal edict that allows seizure of<br>
all money and property obtained by or used for the purpose of trafficking.<br>
<p>
Let's imagine for a moment, some drug dealer comes to Christ and starts<br>
a new life. Let's say he has a pretty big fortune stashed away. Is it<br>
wrong for him to start giving (anonymous) donations to support Christian<br>
activity? Is it wrong for him to help finance a drug rehabilitation program,<br>
or any other social reform? Surely these monies would be better spent building<br>
up society, than in financing a bogus (IMHO) "war against drugs" which is<br>
stirring up quite a hornets nest.<br>
<p>
If money is tainted because of the route it has taken, then all money is<br>
inherently bad and should be shunned. On the other hand, money is needed<br>
for trading with material society in the furtherance of worthy goals.<br>
<p>
I am not advocating drug-running or gun-running as acceptable fundraisers,<br>
but the governments of the world have made these activities far more<br>
profitable than they deserve to be.<br>
<p>
<pre>
--
Adam David. (adamd@rhi.hi.is)
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
