<title>Aug_1992: Answer to trivia question</title>
<h1>Answer to trivia question</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 25 Aug 1992 10:43:11 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#43">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#43">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#43">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#43">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0044.html">Steven Timm: "Family Values in the SDA church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0042.html">McCluskey G: "Re: drug money"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Every time I archive the messages from a previous month, I always find<br>
some things that were never finished.  I posed the trivia question<br>
"What hymn in the old SDA church hymnal has a tune written by <br>
Stephen Foster, but not attributed to him?"<br>
<p>
The hymn is number 430, "Long For My Saviour I've Been Waiting"<br>
and is sung to the tune of Foster's song "Nellie Was A Lady".<br>
<p>
This was only one of several early Advent hymns set to the music of <br>
Stephen Foster.  Another common one was sung to the tune of "Old Folks<br>
At Home."<br>
<p>
Since I'm in Pittsburgh now, the birthplace of Stephen Foster,<br>
I think about things like this.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
