<title>Aug_1992: Family Values in the SDA church</title>
<h1>Family Values in the SDA church</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 25 Aug 1992 10:59:41 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#44">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#44">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#44">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#44">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0045.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: drug money"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0043.html">Steven Timm: "Answer to trivia question"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
As I watched the political conventions, I was surprised how much the <br>
term "family values" came up.  Since our church's general conference<br>
much resembles a political convention,  in fact it was bigger than the <br>
Democratic National Convention, I'm wondering if there are any good<br>
ideas or any mistakes that we can learn from.<br>
<p>
The Republican party has given lip service to the "conservative family<br>
values" issue for the last twelve years but has proved largely unable <br>
to deliver, except by appointing conservative judges.   Proposals for<br>
aid for private schools, school prayer, and constitutional bans on<br>
abortion have gone essentially nowhere.<br>
<p>
What is the state of our church today?  Time was that a divorce meant<br>
automatic departure from the ministry.   Not anymore.    Today divorced<br>
and remarried ministers abound and flourish.   Perhaps the church is<br>
also moving away from the idea that ministers must be married with a<br>
family to  serve most effectively, and single ministers also have a<br>
calling.    <br>
<p>
Nevertheless the ideal of a pastor who is mature enough to look<br>
distinguished and have 20 years experience, yet with kids young enough<br>
to put in church school, is still with us.    The pastor with the wife<br>
who devotes her time to helping him rather than pursuing a profession is<br>
still thought to be desirable.  (In Pittsburgh, where we  are fortunate<br>
enough to have two pastoral families like this, I can assure you it is<br>
very nice indeed.)<br>
There is still a profile of the "climber"  the one who you can tell will <br>
be a conference president in short order.  And beside every one of these<br>
people, there is a wonderful wife.<br>
<p>
Are these stereotypes necessarily bad?  Are churches benefitted because<br>
they set these high standards for their ministers?   The churches I know<br>
who have insisted on quality haven't regretted it.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
