<title>Aug_1992: The minister's wife - what's her name again?</title>
<h1>The minister's wife - what's her name again?</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 26 Aug 1992 09:34 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#46">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#46">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#46">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#46">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0047.html">Dan Blake: "Who's in charge?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0045.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: drug money"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0052.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: The minister's wife - what's her name again?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve writes<br>
<p>
-----&gt;<br>
and remarried ministers abound and flourish.   Perhaps the church is<br>
also moving away from the idea that ministers must be married with a<br>
family to  serve most effectively, and single ministers also have a<br>
calling.<br>
&lt;-----<br>
<p>
I sure hope so...there is a lot more Biblical support for a single<br>
minister than there is for a married one with a family. In fact, <br>
Paul's statements regarding a minister and marriage are quite the<br>
reverse in that he maintains that singles are more effective.<br>
<p>
Now I'm not saying that Biblical precedents are always directly<br>
applicable - I don't believe that at all. But why has the SDA church<br>
been so reticent to ordain single guys??<br>
<p>
<p>
-----&gt;<br>
to put in church school, is still with us.    The pastor with the wife<br>
who devotes her time to helping him rather than pursuing a profession is<br>
still thought to be desirable.  (In Pittsburgh, where we  are fortunate<br>
enough to have two pastoral families like this, I can assure you it is<br>
very nice indeed.)<br>
There is still a profile of the "climber"  the one who you can tell will <br>
be a conference president in short order.  And beside every one of these<br>
people, there is a wonderful wife.<br>
<p>
Are these stereotypes necessarily bad?  Are churches benefitted because<br>
they set these high standards for their ministers?   The churches I know<br>
who have insisted on quality haven't regretted it.<br>
&lt;-----<br>
<p>
These stereotypes are necessarily bad because of what they do to the <br>
woman. Unless she can arrange things in her mind such that his calling<br>
is "their calling" and his work is "their work", and that people view<br>
them as the pastoral team rather than the pastor and his lovely wife,<br>
she is hardly going to find personal fulfilment as a woman in the late<br>
twentieth century.<br>
<p>
Some women can arrange things this way, others can't but live with it<br>
anyway. Still others have trouble with it all of their married life.<br>
<p>
soapbox on<br>
My mother pulled out of her teaching degree early when she married my<br>
father, a ministerial student at her college. After all, a minister's wife<br>
doesn't need a degree, since she is destined for a life of being a<br>
minister's wife. That was in 1966, and in 1987 Mum went back to College<br>
part time to complete her studies. <br>
<p>
This has meant a lot to her, and now she is able to work part time<br>
using the skills and abilities she has. It has improved her self-image<br>
and consequently both my parents are happier.<br>
<p>
During the intervening years she has had to live with patronizing church<br>
members, some of whom never stop relating to her as the "minister's wife"<br>
even after years in a church, when she has more than shown herself to be<br>
an individual with her own personality, abilities and needs.<br>
<p>
To me, treating a woman like the extension of a man is a remnant of a<br>
byegone era which also encompassed slavery and ignorance. The Christian<br>
church at large and the SDA church in particular should be at the forefront<br>
of changing this state of affairs, not hanging on to all the old traditions<br>
wherever it happens to be convenient.<br>
<p>
Perhaps those churches who wish to "insist on quality" in this particular<br>
way (ie two for the price of one) should start with themselves. Perhaps<br>
the congregations Steve referred to did just that.<br>
<p>
soapbox off<br>
<p>
I agree that ministers need to be special since they have to care for the<br>
needs of the church. But let's not hold standards for them that we wouldn't<br>
expect of ourselves.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
