<!-- body="start" -->
[Paul writes]<br>
<i>&gt; As I got older ........  Then there was the thing against going bowling</i><br>
<i>&gt; because in some bowling  alleys they served beer. My friends and I could</i><br>
<i>&gt; go bowling and leave and we didn't drink the beer...</i><br>
<p>
and we didn't submit to authority, and we didn't obey.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; I figured it [what Paul did] was better than [what he was permitted</i><br>
<i>&gt; to do]...</i><br>
<p>
And when the woman saw that the tree was good for food, and that it<br>
was pleasant to the eyes, and a tree to be desired to make one wise,<br>
she took of the fruit thereof, and did eat, and gave also unto her<br>
husband with her; and he did eat.  (Gen. 3:6)<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; [My son] was willing to shave [his mustache] off as it was no big</i><br>
<i>&gt; deal.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; It is things like the above that frustrates some of us.</i><br>
<p>
Sounds as if your son had the right idea; why are you<br>
frustrated by such inconsequential matters?  Is your<br>
personal sovereignty is being rubbed the wrong way?<br>
<p>
I am confused by much of this talk about generations of believers<br>
figuring out how to beat the system while giving lip service to<br>
those in authority.<br>
<p>
Dan Blake<br>
dblake@hprnd.rose.hp.com<br>
