<title>Aug_1992: Adventist Education</title>
<h1>Adventist Education</h1>
Ian Brown (<i>Malachi.Robertson@lambada.oit.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 25 Aug 92 17:53:32 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#48">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#48">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#48">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#48">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0049.html">Ian Brown: "RE: Question of translation"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0047.html">Dan Blake: "Who's in charge?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0033.html">Tony: "Re: Adventist Education"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I belive part of the education of young adults for them to take more<br>
responsiblity and think about their choices involves discussing with them<br>
consequences possible actions might have.  Give them some reasons for why<br>
it is better to take one choice over another.  I think it also involve the<br>
educators providing examples.  They ought to show that they think about<br>
the consequences and are willing to admit that when they make a mistake<br>
they might not have thought things through.<br>
<p>
"Malachi Robertson" better know as Ian Robertson Brown<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
