</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
As an administrator in the Adventist educational system, I have<br>
naturally followed the discussion of campus rules with some interest!<br>
Let me add two points to the discussion.<br>
<p>
First, remember that most of the pressure for strict conservative<br>
standards on SDA campuses comes from the "field", i.e. church members,<br>
either directly or through conference or other church officials. School<br>
administrators don't make up endless rules because they have nothing<br>
better to do, I can assure you! It has been my experience that the very<br>
conservative people are more vocal about their "standards" than other<br>
members, for example those who would rather emphasize individual<br>
development and freedom. The remedy is more communication to school<br>
administrators from people with different views. For example, have you<br>
ever written or spoken to an SDA college president or VP for student<br>
affairs about the importance of learning to make individual choices,<br>
etc? They need to know that members have those views as well as concerns<br>
about jewelry and clothing.<br>
<p>
Second, I think we (on SDA campuses) make a mistake in defending our<br>
campus standards on strictly moral grounds. Every campus I know about<br>
has some rules or traditions that are there simply as part of the<br>
character of the institution. A school certainly has a right to try to<br>
set a tone for its campus and I think students can understand that. I<br>
don't mean to imply that no moral issues are involved, only that we make<br>
a mistake when we try to define for each individual exactly where the<br>
moral boundary is. I would much prefer, personally, to have a student on<br>
campus who is dedicated to a career of service - and who happens to wear<br>
earrings occasionally - than one who sees nothing beyond a large personal<br>
income - and conforms to all visible standards.<br>
<p>
--------------------------------------------------------------<br>
J. Mailen Kootsey		kootsey@cs.andrews.edu<br>
College of Arts &amp; Sciences	(616)471-3411, 6156<br>
Andrews University		(616-473-4436 FAX<br>
Berrien Springs, MI 49104<br>
