<title>Aug_1992: Re: The minister's wife - what's her name again?</title>
<h1>Re: The minister's wife - what's her name again?</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 26 Aug 92 11:44:27 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#52">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#52">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#52">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#52">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0053.html">Steven Timm: "Re: rules &amp; culture"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0051.html">Mailen Kootsey: "SDA education"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0046.html">Tony: "The minister's wife - what's her name again?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0056.html">Tony: "Re: The minister's wife - what's her name again?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
This one hit my hot button.  Those who know me know that I don't get hot<br>
under the collar, but that I can expound at great length with intensity:<br>
<p>
[PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; I sure hope so...there is a lot more Biblical support for a single</i><br>
<i>&gt; minister than there is for a married one with a family. In fact, </i><br>
<i>&gt; Paul's statements regarding a minister and marriage are quite the</i><br>
<i>&gt; reverse in that he maintains that singles are more effective.</i><br>
<p>
Paul was a member of the Sanhedrin.  There is a fair amount of evidence<br>
that members had to be married.  However, his writings do not lead<br>
directly to that conclusion, IMO.  Interesting ...<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; But why has the SDA church been so reticent to ordain single guys??</i><br>
<p>
I'm not sure it's a compelling reason, but my pastor father reckons it's<br>
to protect them.  Many times men are unaware of the wiles of treacherous<br>
women.  A wise wife can alert a husband to what she senses.  Then, there's<br>
the propriety of visiting single women (or even married women when alone);<br>
it is wise to avoid occasions that can result in a bad name (cf. principles<br>
in 2 Sam 12:14 and 1 Tim 5:14).<br>
<p>
I say "maybe not compelling" because there are alternatives (EGW has a<br>
multitude of comments on how to minister to women; the "gold" is only found<br>
by those who "dig", so I leave it as an exercise for the thoughtful reader).<br>
<p>
[Originally written by Steve Timm:]<br>
<i>&gt; The pastor with the wife</i><br>
<i>&gt; who devotes her time to helping him rather than pursuing a profession is</i><br>
<i>&gt; still thought to be desirable.</i><br>
<p>
When Christ is our Lord, we seek His will on these things.  The question<br>
is not whether people think it is desireable, but whether the Lord does.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; There is still a profile of the "climber" the one who you can tell will </i><br>
<i>&gt; be a conference president in short order.</i><br>
<p>
This often imitates corporate models of behavior; Christ's model is radically<br>
different (Mark 9:35).  Jockeying, politicking for position (ever larger<br>
churches) is grievous to the Lord, I believe.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Are these stereotypes necessarily bad?  Are churches benefitted because</i><br>
<i>&gt; they set these high standards for their ministers?   The churches I know</i><br>
<i>&gt; who have insisted on quality haven't regretted it.</i><br>
<p>
Scripture is clear that spiritual leaders are to be held to higher<br>
standards of accountability.<br>
<p>
[Back to PHTH1:]<br>
<i>&gt; These stereotypes are necessarily bad because of what they do to the </i><br>
<i>&gt; woman. Unless she can arrange things in her mind such that his calling</i><br>
<i>&gt; is "their calling" and his work is "their work", and that people view</i><br>
<i>&gt; them as the pastoral team rather than the pastor and his lovely wife,</i><br>
<i>&gt; she is hardly going to find personal fulfilment as a woman in the late</i><br>
<i>&gt; twentieth century.</i><br>
<p>
EGW is quite clear that the call to ministry is for both husband and wife.<br>
(Some denominations even do it that way, e.g., Salvation Army ordains both.)<br>
You all may recall Dave Buxton's posting re tithe.  EGW is clear that<br>
a wife who ministers with her husband is also to be paid.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Some women can arrange things this way, others can't but live with it</i><br>
<i>&gt; anyway. Still others have trouble with it all of their married life.</i><br>
<p>
The problem is that we Christians have believed the lies that Satan propounds.<br>
The notion that a wife must work as does a husband (outside the home) to be<br>
somebody is totally and completely an invention of this world.  And the<br>
societal pressures are incredibly humongous ... which the church has done<br>
precious little to counteract (Rom 12:2).<br>
<p>
The model that Scripture (and EGW) really proposes for women and their ministry<br>
is so radically different from both the world's view and from what<br>
we seem to think Scripture says, it'll knock your socks off (1 Cor 2:9 is<br>
also broadly applicable to everthing God has in store for us, even on earth).<br>
My wife has been doing extensive reading on this matter.<br>
<p>
If you're thinking "pregnant, barefoot, and in the kitchen" you have a<br>
megasurprise coming.  Dig into it, folks!<br>
<p>
Think of this:  I get paid good money to program computers.  My programs<br>
have a shelf life of a few years before they're put out to pasture.  But<br>
when my wife and I (esp her, homeschooling mom) work to develop Godly<br>
character in our children, the results last forever.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; During the intervening years she has had to live with patronizing church</i><br>
<i>&gt; members, some of whom never stop relating to her as the "minister's wife"</i><br>
<i>&gt; even after years in a church, when she has more than shown herself to be</i><br>
<i>&gt; an individual with her own personality, abilities and needs.</i><br>
<p>
There is not a shred of Scriptural or EGW support for having a wife be<br>
in her husband's shadow.  Check out Proverbs 31.  This old stuff of<br>
"Mrs. Fred Christiansen" is totally societal in nature.  We don't really<br>
know what Scripture has to say and society is beating us up (with<br>
Satan's lies).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; SDA church in particular should be at the forefront of changing this</i><br>
<i>&gt; state of affairs, not hanging on to all the old traditions</i><br>
<i>&gt; wherever it happens to be convenient.</i><br>
<p>
Again, the goal must be to change things to God's ways, not society's<br>
(which is at enmity with God).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; But let's not hold standards for them that we wouldn't</i><br>
<i>&gt; expect of ourselves.</i><br>
<p>
Check the requirements for pastors, elders and deacons.<br>
<p>
OK, end of exposition.  May the peace of God rule in our hearts<br>
(Colossians 3:15; memorize the whole chapter, folks, it's good stuff).<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  On Attitude &amp; the Immune System:  A sound heart is the life of the flesh:
    but envy the rottenness of the bones.  Prov 14:30
</pre>
