<title>Aug_1992: Re: rules &amp; culture</title>
<h1>Re: rules &amp; culture</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 26 Aug 1992 21:45:28 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#53">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#53">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#53">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#53">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0054.html">Tony: "Re: Who's in charge?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0052.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: The minister's wife - what's her name again?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Paul Johnston answered the question "how can we tell the rules of the culture<br>
from what's really important" with "you can't."<br>
<p>
I'd like to propose that a different mechanism operates here.  The reason <br>
we have trouble distinguishing between the rules of the culture and the <br>
moral absolutes is that for most of our lives we have dealt with church<br>
leaders and church school administrators who claim absolute authority,<br>
argue from a position of absolute authority, and put the whole power of<br>
the church<br>
and your eternal salvation squarely on whether you wear jeans on Sabbath<br>
or not.  This view reflects a gross distortion of what scriptural<br>
authority<br>
ought to be, and unfortunately it is widely held not only by most<br>
Christians but by the fiercest enemies of Christianity  (some of whom<br>
are also Christians). <br>
<p>
The so-called conservatism of today chooses passages from inspired writings, <br>
claims verbal inspiration for them which the writings do not claim for<br>
themselves, and proceeds to declare its interpretation of those writings<br>
as the word of the LORD.  This style of interpretation is found in the<br>
various right-wing magazines named after adult undergarments, but<br>
unfortunately<br>
it is also found in the various attacks that the bureaucrats put out <br>
on these organizations, often with a much reduced level of content and<br>
even more out of context.  Even liberals and antagonists of the church<br>
fall into the trap of attacking this caricature of authority.<br>
<p>
Christ was recognized as one who taught with authority, not because of all <br>
the scripture he quoted (though he was fond of quoting it).  Rather his<br>
teachings were recognized to have authority because they made sense.  <br>
The validation of the Bible and the validation of the writings of Ellen G. <br>
White should come from the same source.  Both sets claim inspiration.<br>
Rather than *assuming* that inspiration, we should point to the results<br>
of a fulfilled Christian life as *proof* of that inspiration.  (As<br>
always, I point out that here I differ from most expositions of SDA<br>
doctrine.  SDA doctrine assumes the inspiration of the Bible as its<br>
starting point.)  We shortchange ourselves by postulating that which can<br>
be proved.<br>
<p>
The logjam of tying everything from Sabbathkeeping to hemlines to<br>
salvation was broken in the early 70's when people started preaching<br>
more salvation by faith.  But once the motive of fear of death and<br>
hell-fire was removed, many people saw no reason to do almost anything.  <br>
<p>
I propose a simple test:  "Any doctrine we believe and any actions which<br>
flow from that doctrine should enable us to better love God and love our<br>
neighbor as ourselves."  If such a quantity as lovipotential could be<br>
measured with a love-meter, and then ones' life would be altered in such<br>
a way as to maximize lovipotential, I am convinced that it must happen<br>
through the SDA way of life.<br>
<p>
Maintaining conservative standards for the sake of conservatism will<br>
eventually lead to thousands of churches with one member each. <br>
Obedience to the law of God will enable our church to become a loving<br>
machine with incredible lovipotential. <br>
(I know lovipotential isn't really a word.  If someone has a better word<br>
please let me know).<br>
<p>
It's notable but not really surprising that when I started the thread of <br>
subculture, superculture, and counterculture, almost everyone chose to <br>
focus on the subculture aspects.  The majority of this list does not live<br>
in proximity to the subculture.  Why is it that the subculture and its<br>
rules occupy such a disproportionate amount of discussion space?  It's<br>
decline and fall, after all, is a sign of the end times and something<br>
that is bound to happen, so oughtn't we to rejoice at its demise?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
