<title>Aug_1992: Re: Who's in charge?</title>
<h1>Re: Who's in charge?</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 27 Aug 1992 11:43 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#54">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#54">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#54">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#54">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0055.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Who's in charge?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0053.html">Steven Timm: "Re: rules &amp; culture"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0058.html">Bill Nickless: "Who's in charge?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0055.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Who's in charge?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dan writes:<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
I am confused by much of this talk about generations of believers<br>
figuring out how to beat the system while giving lip service to<br>
those in authority.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
The point here is that people shouldn't have to "beat the system".<br>
<p>
The whole idea that the church structure and educational institutions<br>
are there to exert control is the real problem. The church administration<br>
is there to serve the church, not to control it.<br>
<p>
To put this in balance, I would also say that an important role of church<br>
leaders is to provide direction for the evangelistic efforts of the<br>
worldwide church. This is supposed to make evangelism more effective than<br>
if every congregation was forced to do it independently with only their<br>
own resources to draw on.<br>
<p>
Sure, authority is needed in any school. I'm not advocating the totally<br>
lassez faire approach to education. But as long as this debate encompasses<br>
wider issues such as dress, forms of entertainment and so on, I think<br>
it is important to stay away from the idea that church administrators have<br>
"authority" in the sense that they set the standards for everyone, and that<br>
making your own decisions is bucking the system etc. etc.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
