<!-- body="start" -->
Hi, folks<br>
<p>
As long as we are talking subculture, I urge you to wake up and smell<br>
the coffee.  No, I mean, wake up and smell the tobacco smoke.  Or should<br>
I say wake up and smell the alcohol on the breath of our young people.<br>
I didn't want to believe the statistics until I saw it with my own eyes.<br>
But now I have seen it.  Teenagers not afraid to smoke cigarettes in the<br>
open on a church-sponsored outing.  <br>
<p>
In today's Adventist schools, the battle lines are drawn in exactly the same<br>
places as they are in any public school.  The real temptations our kids are <br>
facing are premarital sex, suicide, and substance abuse.  In some<br>
schools the faculty are still fighting the skirmishes against violations<br>
of the minor <br>
rules, but the expressions of rebellion are major and they are real.<br>
<p>
The statistics say that those SDA kids who do start drinking are 5 times<br>
more likely to become alcoholic than the general population.  I think<br>
this has largely to do with the setting up of what seems to them like so<br>
many arbitrary rules.  The solution is to be found in acting from reason<br>
and not from passion, in building a relationship of trust between<br>
rule-maker and rule-breaker.  Respect must be earned before it can be<br>
demanded.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
