<title>Aug_1992: Re: The minister's wife - what's her name again?</title>
<h1>Re: The minister's wife - what's her name again?</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 27 Aug 1992 12:56 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#56">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#56">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#56">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#56">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0057.html">Bob Moynihan: "re: Rules and Culture"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0055.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Who's in charge?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0046.html">Tony: "The minister's wife - what's her name again?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0065.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: The minister's wife - what's her name again?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Fred:<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
This one hit my hot button.  Those who know me know that I don't get hot<br>
under the collar, but that I can expound at great length with intensity:<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
Are you hot because I upset you or because you have feelings on this<br>
topic?? This sentence got me worried initially, but I found myself<br>
agreeing with most of your reply, so I was just wondering whether<br>
there was anything about my post you objected to.<br>
<p>
I'd just like to continue discussion on a couple of points.<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
EGW is quite clear that the call to ministry is for both husband and wife.<br>
(Some denominations even do it that way, e.g., Salvation Army ordains both.)<br>
You all may recall Dave Buxton's posting re tithe.  EGW is clear that<br>
a wife who ministers with her husband is also to be paid.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
I know a lot of single guys who felt called to the ministry, went to study<br>
theology at college, met a nice girl... Do you think that he shouldn't<br>
marry her unless she feels called to ministry with him? Or that she should<br>
consider herself called because he considers himself called?<br>
<p>
How about a single girl who feels called to ministry? Should she look for<br>
a guy who himself feels called? Or should her partner consider himself<br>
called along with her?<br>
<p>
The other thing is, EGW was writing to a society quite different to our<br>
own. Now I know you say society is opposed to God's wishes...but we<br>
can't remove ourselves from society. Perhaps if women were considered<br>
more as individuals back then, her message may have been different. I<br>
agree that not all progress is progress, but I think that the sooner<br>
women are viewed as individuals in their own right the better. (This is<br>
improving, but not perfect yet.)<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
The notion that a wife must work as does a husband (outside the home) to be<br>
somebody is totally and completely an invention of this world.  And the<br>
societal pressures are incredibly humongous ... which the church has done<br>
precious little to counteract (Rom 12:2).<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
OK, but you won't find too many guys with this view who would be prepared<br>
to turn the tables and stay home themselves while their wife follows the<br>
career path. The presence of children in the family changes the equation<br>
quite a lot, but consider for a minute a couple married with no kids.<br>
<p>
In this case, I would say that the "as does a husband" phrase from the<br>
above quote is the invention. In my opinion there are many ways to serve<br>
God outside the ministry of the church, and so a person can feel led to<br>
take up a certain occupation regardless of their gender. Were I to <br>
change careers and become a minister, I would encourage my wife to <br>
continue the development of her scientific career. She is good at what<br>
she does, she makes a contribution in her field, and is a Christian<br>
witness in an otherwise largely non-Christian environment. All these<br>
things are good, for her, her colleagues, us, and the church at<br>
large.<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
Again, the goal must be to change things to God's ways, not society's<br>
(which is at enmity with God).<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
The difficulty is identifying God's ways. The way God is represented in<br>
the world has always been largely dependent on the society of the time.<br>
The chronological development in the Bible of the way God portrays himself<br>
indicates that He is behind the different models of himself, rather than<br>
the models being cooked up by mankind.<br>
<p>
Ecclesiastical authority has always been a problem for me, since so many<br>
mistakes have been made in the name of doing things "God's way". I'm not<br>
making a comment about SDA leaders or anyone in particular, but too many<br>
times in the past people have used the God's way argument to get *their*<br>
way.<br>
<p>
I think I probably agree with you, but I get confused by the number of<br>
different people who all want to do things "God's way", who all have<br>
different things in mind, and most of whom believe that God only has<br>
one way!!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<p>
P.S. I'd really like to meet some of you guys on the net! Let me know<br>
     if you're ever planning to visit Australia and I'll have to invite<br>
     you around for a gluten steak! Cheerio...<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
