<title>Aug_1992: re: Rules and Culture</title>
<h1>re: Rules and Culture</h1>
Bob Moynihan (<i>moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 27 Aug 92 10:24:51 EDT </i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#57">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#57">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#57">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#57">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0058.html">Bill Nickless: "Who's in charge?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0056.html">Tony: "Re: The minister's wife - what's her name again?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0070.html">Paul Gates: "Re: re: Rules and Culture"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Our esteemed moderator writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; ...The reason  we have trouble distinguishing between the rules of </i><br>
<i>&gt; the culture and the moral absolutes is that for most of our lives </i><br>
<i>&gt; we have dealt with church leaders and church school administrators </i><br>
<i>&gt; who claim absolute authority, argue from a position of absolute </i><br>
<i>&gt; authority, and put the whole power of the church and your eternal </i><br>
<i>&gt; salvation squarely on whether you wear jeans on Sabbath or not.  </i><br>
<i>&gt; This view reflects a gross distortion of what scriptural authority</i><br>
<i>&gt; ought to be... </i><br>
<p>
Funny thing this:  These are some of the same antics that caused me to<br>
walk away from the Catholic Church.  (Substitute the Pope and the <br>
Catholic Church hierarchy for the Adventist leaders and adminstrators <br>
above.)  There is no human being on this planet that has any right to<br>
tell me what is moral and what is not, what I can or cannot do.  The<br>
simple fact that someone holds some administrative post in the Adventist<br>
Church doesn't grant them that right, nor does the collective weight of<br>
some church board.  That is the task of Scripture.  The Church can use<br>
Scripture to support it's advised standards of behavior, but cannot<br>
force me to adhere to them if I feel their logic is tenuous.  I follow<br>
precepts of the church that from personal study I can see solid Scriptural<br>
support for.  However, if church leaders expect me to follow a rule that <br>
is based on little more than an ad baculum argument, they are sadly<br>
mistaken. <br>
<p>
My attitude on "things" is simply this:  If it gets in the way of you and <br>
the Lord, get rid of it.  As I type this, I wear a wedding ring.  Yup, evil<br>
jewelry. &lt;collective gasp&gt;  Is it an act of defiance?  No, it's a way of<br>
showing others that I am married.  That way, I can carry on an intelligent<br>
and friendly conversation with a woman without her thinking that I'm on <br>
the make.  Or if a woman should think me attractive, it tells her that I'm<br>
'taken'. <br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Christ was recognized as one who taught with authority, not because of all </i><br>
<i>&gt; the scripture he quoted (though he was fond of quoting it).  Rather his</i><br>
<i>&gt; teachings were recognized to have authority because they made sense.  </i><br>
<p>
I used to drink alcohol occasionally.  I don't any more.  Not because the<br>
church says it's wrong, (reviewing Scripture clearly warns against getting<br>
intoxicated, but does not say anything about not taking a single drink,)<br>
but because it's just plain not good for me.  Spring water, fruit juices,<br>
and milk are, so I drink them instead.  This health message the Adventist<br>
church taught me, but didn't ram down my throat.  It "made sense."  <br>
<p>
Ah well, I've gone on long enough...<br>
<p>
Bob Moynihan                               Bush/Quayle '92: Just say noe.<br>
moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com                   Go Ipswich Town! <br>
<p>
  Disclaimer: I speak only for myself.  Not for HP, not the SDA Church.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
