<title>Aug_1992: Who's in charge?</title>
<h1>Who's in charge?</h1>
Bill Nickless (<i>nickless@antares.mcs.anl.gov</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 27 Aug 1992 10:30:11 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#58">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#58">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#58">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#58">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0059.html">Daniel D Deavours: "Re: Who's in Charge?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0057.html">Bob Moynihan: "re: Rules and Culture"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0047.html">Dan Blake: "Who's in charge?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0054.html">Tony: "Re: Who's in charge?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; I am confused by much of this talk about generations of believers</i><br>
<i>&gt; figuring out how to beat the system while giving lip service to</i><br>
<i>&gt; those in authority.</i><br>
<p>
Let's talk about beating the system.<br>
<p>
There exists (last I knew) a rule at Andrews University that by default, any<br>
undergraduate student less than 22 years of age must live in the dormitory and<br>
purchase a meal plan from the cafeteria.  The only acceptable exceptions to<br>
this policy are derived from having a family member (older than 25) to live<br>
with.  A further requirement is that the family member's hospitality is<br>
uncompensated.  (Technically, you can't rent a room from your cousin.)<br>
<p>
I know of parents who have literally purchased a house in Berrien Springs,<br>
Michigan, so that their children could live outside of the dormitory.<br>
<p>
Interestingly, this restriction does not hold during the summer term.<br>
<p>
Oh--I forgot.  If you get married at age 18, you obviously don't need to live<br>
in the dorm anymore.  But if you do wish to wait for marriage until after<br>
graduation, you are required to live in the dormitory and purchase a meal<br>
plan, or until you reach age 22.  (Why 22?  They did a study and determined<br>
that by some statistical measure graduate students were of that age.)<br>
<p>
Once again I stress that fundamentally our school systems do not believe that<br>
unmarried young people are capable of living their own lives, free from<br>
oversight and control.  Until that happens these conflicts will continue.<br>
<p>
--Bill Nickless<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
