<title>Aug_1992: Re: Who's in charge?</title>
<h1>Re: Who's in charge?</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 28 Aug 1992 09:25 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#60">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#60">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#60">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#60">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0061.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Religious liberty on University campuses"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0059.html">Daniel D Deavours: "Re: Who's in Charge?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0058.html">Bill Nickless: "Who's in charge?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0078.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Who's in charge?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Bill discusses the fact that at Andrews University single students are<br>
not permitted to live outside the dormitory etc. until age 22, and goes<br>
on to write:<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
Once again I stress that fundamentally our school systems do not believe that<br>
unmarried young people are capable of living their own lives, free from<br>
oversight and control.  Until that happens these conflicts will continue.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
At Avondale College where I recently attended there was some unwritten<br>
rule that you had to be 25 to live "outdoor", unless you were living with<br>
more-or-less immediate family.<br>
<p>
I thought this was because of the things you refer to, so when I was feeling<br>
the pinch financially at age 21 I wrote and asked permission to live with<br>
my grandparents. My stated reasons were largely that I felt I could study<br>
more efficiently and spend less time raising money as an outdoor. I was<br>
turned down.<br>
<p>
After receiving some unofficial advice from one of the college administrators<br>
I reapplied, this time stating that the reason I wished to go outdoor was<br>
to be with my grandparents. I said that due to the fact that my parents<br>
were missionaries overseas when I was a child I had never had a chance to<br>
really get to know them, and besides which Grandpa was getting old and<br>
silly and Nana needed me around the house. This time my application was<br>
approved.<br>
<p>
As it turned out, I managed to discover that the rule about not living<br>
outdoor is based almost 100% on *financial* considerations ie we can't<br>
afford to run the dorm and the caf if more than x% of our students are<br>
not using them. So I had to provide a reason to go outdoor which no-one<br>
else could use as a precedent for their own application.<br>
<p>
Interesting, huh?! Perhaps Andrews is the same...perhaps not.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
