<title>Aug_1992: Religious liberty on University campuses</title>
<h1>Religious liberty on University campuses</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 27 Aug 92 22:10:29 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#61">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#61">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#61">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#61">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0062.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Religious liberty on University campuses"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0060.html">Tony: "Re: Who's in charge?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0062.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Religious liberty on University campuses"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I'd like those who are attending public institutions of higher education to<br>
respond.  I'm preparing for my first year as an assitant professor and was<br>
surprised to receive a form letter from the Assistant Chancellor about<br>
a Wisconsin law.  According to his memo, Wisconsin law requires that the<br>
university provide "reasonable accommodation of a student's sincerely<br>
held religious beliefs with regard to all examinations and other academic<br>
requirements."  (Chapter 36.43 of Wisconsin Law).  Along with the memo was<br>
a list of various religious holy days which may preclude students from<br>
attending class or examinations by religious affiliation.  Here are the<br>
dates we as faculty were to alerted to which might conflict with student<br>
religious obversances:<br>
<p>
	September 28-29, 1992	ROSH HASHANAH (Jewish)<br>
	October 7		YOM KIPPUR (Jewish)<br>
	October 11-20		SUKKOT (Jewish)<br>
	October 20		Birth of the BAB (Baha'i)<br>
	November 12		Birth of the BAHAULLAH (Baha'i)<br>
	November 28		Ascension of ABDUL-BAHA (Baha'i)<br>
	December 20-27		HANUKKAH (Jewish)<br>
	December 25		CHRISTMAS (Christian)<br>
	February 6, 1993	TU B'SHEVAT (Jewish)<br>
	Feb 24-March 24		RAMADAN (Muslim)<br>
	March 7			PURIM (Jewish)<br>
	March 21		NEW YEAR (Baha'i)<br>
	March 25		EID AL FITR (Feast of Breaking Fast at the<br>
					end of Ramadan) (Muslim)<br>
	April 6-13		PASSOVER (Jewish)<br>
	April 9			GOOD FRIDAY (Christian)<br>
	April 11		EASTER (Christian)<br>
	April 21		RIDZAN (Baha'i)<br>
	May 23			Declaration of the BAB (Baha'i)<br>
	May 26-27		SHAVUOTH (Jewish)<br>
	June 1			EID AL ADHA/Feast of Sacrifice (Muslim)<br>
<p>
It was noted that many of these holy days "make it impossible for students<br>
to attend the University or do any type of school work."  Others were<br>
annotated that "Although work on this day is permitted, observance would<br>
make one unavailable to attend the University in the evening or morning, or<br>
during religious services, or to prepare any assignments during this time."<br>
"All Jewish holidays begin the evening before the calendar day."  "Shabbat<br>
is observed every Saturday, and no manner of University work or attendance<br>
would be allowed."<br>
<p>
Most obvious to SDAs is not mention that SDAs would not be available to<br>
attend University classes or do University assignments.  More importantly,<br>
not a single note of Sunday observance for ANY RELIGION<br>
<p>
Now my questions.  Do other state universities have such a policy or law?<br>
What degree of accomodation you required to make for student religious<br>
observance?  Are faculty and staff given the same liberties as students?<br>
<p>
Why do you think Sunday observance is totally missing from the list?  Is<br>
it because so few churches really keep Sunday according to the 4th commandment?<br>
(In other words, Sunday observance by abstaining from work or university<br>
studying is not professed by most denominations).<br>
<p>
BTW.  You won't find me giving an exam or having an assignment due on<br>
December 25!<br>
<p>
This is quite a list!  Just about every week in the academic year has some<br>
religious holiday.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
