<!-- body="start" -->
At Carnegie Mellon there is a similar policy, although I have never had <br>
a student claim the Bahai holidays as yet.  But there is a large Jewish <br>
community and every year around Passover and High Holy Days a lot of <br>
students disappear.  I had never heard of the Jewish holiday of Shavuoth<br>
until there was quite a hullaballoo last year because CMU's graduation<br>
was scheduled on that day.  The graduation service was not moved<br>
but special arrangements were made for those who could not participate.<br>
<p>
Sometimes I wonder if we are willing to give in our SDA institutions the <br>
same religious freedom that we demand on secular campuses.  The problems<br>
of examinations scheduled on Sunday were frequently encountered by non-SDA<br>
students at Andrews.  Some teachers were accomodating, others were not.<br>
Can we reasonably expect to obtain freedoms which we do not give to others?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
