<title>Aug_1992: Re: Who's in charge?</title>
<h1>Re: Who's in charge?</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 27 Aug 92 10:35:33 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#63">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#63">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#63">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#63">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0064.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Who's in charge?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0062.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Religious liberty on University campuses"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0054.html">Tony: "Re: Who's in charge?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0060.html">Tony: "Re: Who's in charge?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; The whole idea that the church structure and educational institutions</i><br>
<i>&gt; are there to exert control is the real problem. The church administration</i><br>
<i>&gt; is there to serve the church, not to control it.</i><br>
<p>
Unfortunately, people often look to institutions and leaders for guidance<br>
as a substitute for looking to Scripture (2 Tim 3:16) and the Holy Spirit<br>
(John 16:13) (not that you never seek counsel from Godly people (Prov 13:20;<br>
Prov 11:14), but that you go to the Source foremost).  For example, at the<br>
last GC, a request from some Europeans was for a set of do's and don't's for<br>
Sabbath activities (cf. the proceedings in the Review) (many Americans have<br>
trouble with what Europeans do on Sabbath, you see.  Having spent time in<br>
Europe, I sorta see, but want to be mindful of Matt 7:3-5.).  I think this<br>
is an example of what contributes in a demand-pull fashion towards the<br>
establishment of hierarchic structures larger than Scripture's model<br>
(which my reading suggests as God-&gt;patriarch-&gt;household and<br>
prophet/priest-&gt;father-&gt;family for authority, leadership, and instruction).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; To put this in balance, I would also say that an important role of church</i><br>
<i>&gt; leaders is to provide direction for the evangelistic efforts of the</i><br>
<i>&gt; worldwide church. This is supposed to make evangelism more effective than</i><br>
<i>&gt; if every congregation was forced to do it independently with only their</i><br>
<i>&gt; own resources to draw on.</i><br>
<p>
Good point.  An additional observation:<br>
<p>
 From my wife's and my readings recently in Scripture and EGW testimonies and<br>
counsels, we've learned a few things:  Pastors are to work more as evangelists,<br>
visiting house to house and holding meetings.  Men work primarily with men,<br>
women with women, husband-wife teams with families.  Elders ("bishops" in<br>
Scripture) and deacons (and their spouses) are to take on the major part<br>
of ministering to the spiritual and physical needs of the congregation,<br>
visiting members, counseling, praying with, taking food to, doing repairs<br>
around the house for widows, etc.<br>
<p>
Kinda different from current practice, eh?<br>
<pre>
-- 
