<title>Aug_1992: Re: Who's in charge?</title>
<h1>Re: Who's in charge?</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 27 Aug 92 11:37:20 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#64">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#64">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#64">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#64">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0065.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: The minister's wife - what's her name again?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0063.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Who's in charge?"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0055.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Who's in charge?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0063.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Who's in charge?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Steven Timm writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; In some schools the faculty are still fighting the skirmishes against</i><br>
<i>&gt; violations of the minor rules, but the expressions of rebellion are</i><br>
<i>&gt; major and they are real.</i><br>
<p>
What produces rebellion?  Schools are not they only problem area; I can<br>
see a number of other failure points:<br>
<p>
Parents who fail to teach their children how to develop a personal<br>
  relationship with the Lord, including a personal devotional life (Deut 6:7).<br>
Parents who lack self-control, are un-Christ-like (Phil 2:5; 1 Pet 4:1), thus<br>
  communicating a lousy image of Father-God.<br>
Parents in whom the fruits of the Spirit are sadly and chronically lacking,<br>
  whose lives are a spiritual wasteland, lacking spiritual growth.<br>
Parents who just bark out orders and do not teach principles (too often,<br>
  because that's how they were brought up).<br>
Parents who abdicate their spiritual responsibilities, assuming that the<br>
  church and the church school (institutions) will take up the slack.<br>
Parents who feel their children can do no wrong (Prov 24:24).<br>
Parents who assert that their children are always wrong, even indirectly;<br>
  who do not confess their own failings (Eph 6:4, Col 3:21; James 5:16).<br>
Parents who fail to see that the great controversy occurs on an individual<br>
  level, who figure they can just muddle long, who do not see Satan out<br>
  to destroy their children (Isa 49:25).<br>
Parents who "sacrifice" their children on the altar of convenience,<br>
  a certain standard of living, personal aggrandizement, self-serving, etc.<br>
Parents who think you can be Christian and still of the world (2 Cor 6:17,<br>
  Josh 3:5; 1 Pet 2:9).<br>
Parents whose lives are not a demonstration of a victorious Christian life<br>
  ("rather see a sermon than hear one any day", "if it's not working for<br>
  you, it ain't real").<br>
<p>
Churches that teach doctrine ("what") but not spiritual disciplines ("how").<br>
Blind guides.<br>
<p>
Not exhaustive.  But I want to make the point that parents are very<br>
important (altho God is not limited; see Ps 27:10).  I have a theory<br>
and that is that the old statistics of how more kids stay SDA if they<br>
go to church schools .. has a lot less to do with church schools and<br>
a lot more to do with parents and how the children were raised.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I think</i><br>
<i>&gt; this has largely to do with the setting up of what seems to them like so</i><br>
<i>&gt; many arbitrary rules.  The solution is to be found in acting from reason</i><br>
<i>&gt; and not from passion, in building a relationship of trust between</i><br>
<i>&gt; rule-maker and rule-breaker.  Respect must be earned before it can be</i><br>
<i>&gt; demanded.</i><br>
<p>
And let that reason be in submission to the Spirit (Prov 3:7; Prov 14:12).<br>
<p>
p.s.  I trust gentle readers are reading the verses I reference.<br>
	Gotta drill to find the oil. 8-)<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
