<title>Aug_1992: Re: The minister's wife - what's her name again?</title>
<h1>Re: The minister's wife - what's her name again?</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 27 Aug 92 12:31:23 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#65">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#65">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#65">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#65">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0066.html">Stan Macasieb: "Re: Religious liberty on University campuses"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0064.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Who's in charge?"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0056.html">Tony: "Re: The minister's wife - what's her name again?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; Are you hot because I upset you or because you have feelings on this topic??</i><br>
<p>
Not hot as in "hot under the collar", but "hot button" as in "motivated me<br>
strongly to respond".<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I know a lot of single guys who felt called to the ministry, went to study</i><br>
<i>&gt; theology at college, met a nice girl... [1] Do you think that he shouldn't</i><br>
<i>&gt; marry her unless she feels called to ministry with him? [2] Or that she</i><br>
<i>&gt; should consider herself called because he considers himself called?</i><br>
<p>
[1] Several pastoral dropouts/divorces with whom I am personally acquainted<br>
    (as well as several indirectly) dropped out/divorced because of tensions<br>
    as the wife discovered she did not like being a pastor's wife.  Granted,<br>
    some pressures resulted from expectations (husband's, congregation's,<br>
    in-law's) which are probably not God's, but some do just come with the<br>
    territory.  My readings suggest that God has grand vistas of opportunity<br>
    for ministry by a husband-wife pastoral team (moderated, of course,<br>
    by ages of the children, if any).  I don't quite have the temerity to<br>
    suggest that all should be this way, but I believe God would be<br>
    delighted to have more than there are.<br>
<p>
    p.s.  I think there's something fundamentally flawed with the system<br>
    when so many mothers *have* to work in order to send the kids the<br>
    church school.  God has solutions if we'll seek for them.<br>
<p>
[2] Mary was called directly to what God hand in mind; Joseph's came<br>
    afterward.  However, we don't know how it was for Zipporah.  Anyway,<br>
    marriage is always a big (and supposed to be permanent) step.<br>
    The young woman should be very certain of God's leading.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; How about a single girl who feels called to ministry? Should she look for</i><br>
<i>&gt; a guy who himself feels called? Or should her partner consider himself</i><br>
<i>&gt; called along with her?</i><br>
<p>
I can't answer this one because I'm unclear as to where God is on women<br>
pastor-shepherds.  If, in fact, God is OK on women pastors, then I think<br>
we need to be careful on how it transpires.  God's name is being dishonored<br>
by the feminist political tactics being used by those agitating and pressuring;<br>
if they win, it gives credence to the "arm of man".  Far better for God's<br>
cause if we heed's Gamaliel's advice (Acts 5:38,39).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; In my opinion there are many ways to serve</i><br>
<i>&gt; God outside the ministry of the church, and so a person can feel led to</i><br>
<i>&gt; take up a certain occupation regardless of their gender.</i><br>
<p>
In general, certainly.  But what is God's best for pastors, both individually<br>
and collectively?  For those contemplating pastoral ministry, that is worth<br>
studying.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The difficulty is identifying God's ways.</i><br>
<p>
We seem to have difficulty, aye!  But God has a method:  Deut 4:9,29, 5:29,<br>
6:5, 10:12, 30:6,10; Josh 22:5; 1 Sam 12:20; 1 Kings 2:4, 8:58; 1 Chr 28:9;<br>
2 Chr 6:14, 7:14, 15:12,15, 16:9; Ps 62:8, 119:10,34; Prov 3:5;<br>
Jer 24:7, 29:13; Ez 18:31; Joel 2:12.  Also, study the lives of the patriarchs.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
