<title>Aug_1992: Re: Religious liberty on University campuses</title>
<h1>Re: Religious liberty on University campuses</h1>
Stan Macasieb (<i>Stan_Macasieb@isu.comm.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 28 Aug 1992 09:57:42 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#66">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#66">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#66">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#66">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0067.html">Lisa Parry: "Re: The minister's wife"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0065.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: The minister's wife - what's her name again?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0061.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Religious liberty on University campuses"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0069.html">Adam David: "Re: Religious liberty on University campuses"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;Date: Thu, 27 Aug 92 22:10:29 -0500</i><br>
<i>&gt;From: cheryl berthelsen &lt;cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu&gt;</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Now my questions.  Do other state universities have such a policy or law?</i><br>
<i>&gt;What degree of accomodation you required to make for student religious</i><br>
<i>&gt;observance?  Are faculty and staff given the same liberties as students?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Why do you think Sunday observance is totally missing from the list?  Is</i><br>
<i>&gt;it because so few churches really keep Sunday according to the 4th commandment?</i><br>
<i>&gt;(In other words, Sunday observance by abstaining from work or university</i><br>
<i>&gt;studying is not professed by most denominations).</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
Not ever having been a member of the staff, I can see how goofy it<br>
all looks. As an SDA on a public school campus a few years ago<br>
(I can't believe I'm saying that!) at Champaign, the U of I has<br>
such a policy, esp for exams. Having not exercised the policy<br>
myself, I know of a few SDAs who did use religious observance<br>
as a reason to back out of a Saturday exam, and the profs allowed<br>
it. It's a judgment call for the prof to make, so you'll have<br>
to be as reasonable as possible.<br>
<p>
As far as Sunday goes, no school in their right mind would officially<br>
hold a class on Sunday. Nothing stops them from holding it at all on<br>
a Sunday, but it just isn't done officially. <br>
<p>
The way the school sees it, giving Sunday off is to give everyone<br>
a mandated break from work and classes. What you do w/ that day<br>
is your problem as far as the school is concerned. It seems to have<br>
nothing to do with religious observance, but its roots are clearly<br>
religious, to make sure those students are at 11 am service, sober<br>
or otherwise.<br>
<p>
Besides, the school makes sure exams don't fall on Dec 25 by giving <br>
us all winter break. Aren't these guys clever? :)<br>
<p>
--Stan Macasieb (stanm@comm.mot.com)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
