[Steven Timm writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; Sometimes I wonder if we are willing to give in our SDA institutions the </i><br>
<i>&gt; same religious freedom that we demand on secular campuses.  The problems</i><br>
<i>&gt; of examinations scheduled on Sunday were frequently encountered by non-SDA</i><br>
<i>&gt; students at Andrews.  Some teachers were accomodating, others were not.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Can we reasonably expect to obtain freedoms which we do not give to others?</i><br>
<p>
Very good point.  Two observations:<br>
1) About 11 years ago, the church school of the church I was attending had<br>
   several students who were World-wide Church of God.  They kept several<br>
   religious holidays which Christians have not historically kept.  The<br>
   teacher and the church were slightly taken aback but then upon reflection<br>
   accomodated.  (Unfortunately, that church was not always that reasonable.)<br>
2) Most of the construction subcontractors I am currently working with are<br>
   Mormon.  I have requested that they not work on my house on my Sabbath,<br>
   and that I do not expect them to work on their "Sabbath".  It's a two-way<br>
   street.<br>
