<!-- body="start" -->
Cheryl wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; Most obvious to SDAs is not mention that SDAs would not be available to</i><br>
<i>&gt; attend University classes or do University assignments.  More importantly,</i><br>
<i>&gt; not a single note of Sunday observance for ANY RELIGION</i><br>
<p>
There were only 4 religions on the list: Jewish, Christian, Moslem, Bahai.<br>
It is therefore not in the least surprising that sabbath-observing christians<br>
are not mentioned, the list is obviously dealing with mainstream interpretations<br>
of these 4 religions.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Why do you think Sunday observance is totally missing from the list?  Is</i><br>
<i>&gt; it because so few churches really keep Sunday according to the 4th commandment?</i><br>
<i>&gt; (In other words, Sunday observance by abstaining from work or university</i><br>
<i>&gt; studying is not professed by most denominations).</i><br>
<p>
My first thought was that Sunday is so obviously a day off in Christian nations<br>
that there was no need to spell it out. Believers can use the day off to<br>
follow their spiritual endeavours, and others can just take it easy and<br>
recover from the weekend.<br>
<p>
My second thought was that this was probably not the case. More probably<br>
there was no mention of Sunday observance because anybody can go to church<br>
if they want to, and just make time on Sunday if anything else needs doing.<br>
<p>
Also, I don't remember seeing Friday being mentioned as a special day for<br>
moslems. Maybe I got this wrong, but I thought this was their holy day (?).<br>
<p>
<pre>
--
Adam David. (adamd@rhi.hi.is)
</pre>
