<title>Aug_1992: Re: The minister's wife</title>
<h1>Re: The minister's wife</h1>
Dan Blake (<i>dblake@hprnd.rose.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 28 Aug 92 21:32:00 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#71">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#71">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#71">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#71">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0072.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Re: The minister's wife"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0070.html">Paul Gates: "Re: re: Rules and Culture"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0085.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: The minister's wife"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Fred writes]<br>
<i>&gt; Scripture is clear that spiritual leaders are to be held to higher</i><br>
<i>&gt; standards of accountability.</i><br>
<p>
AMEN!  See 1 &amp; 2 Timothy and Titus.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; There is not a shred of Scriptural or EGW support for having a wife be</i><br>
<i>&gt; in her husband's shadow.  Check out Proverbs 31.  This old stuff of</i><br>
<i>&gt; "Mrs. Fred Christiansen" is totally societal in nature.  We don't really</i><br>
<i>&gt; know what Scripture has to say and society is beating us up (with</i><br>
<i>&gt; Satan's lies).</i><br>
<p>
Some pages must have fallen from your Bible, Fred.  Here, let me<br>
share with you.<br>
<p>
How about Psalm 17:7-9.<br>
  7 Shew thy marvellous lovingkindness, O thou that savest by<br>
thy right hand them which put their trust in thee from those<br>
that rise up against them.<br>
  8 Keep me as the apple of the eye, hide me under the shadow of<br>
thy wings,<br>
  9 From the wicked that oppress me, from my deadly enemies, who<br>
compass me about.<br>
<p>
Or maybe Psalm 63:7-8.<br>
  7 Because thou hast been my help, therefore in the shadow of<br>
thy wings will I rejoice.<br>
  8 My soul followeth hard after thee: thy right hand upholdeth me.<br>
<p>
Now, I know that in context, these verses speak about the relation-<br>
ship between man and God, but under the light of the first twelve<br>
verses of 1st Corinthians, I think they can be applied to the<br>
husband-wife relationship.  If you don't agree, let me give you<br>
one more Scripture.<br>
<p>
Song of Solomon 2:3-4.<br>
  3 As the apple tree among the trees of the wood, so is my<br>
beloved among the sons. I sat down under his shadow with great<br>
delight, and his fruit was sweet to my taste.<br>
  4 He brought me to the banqueting house, and his banner over<br>
me was love.<br>
<p>
Notice that this is NOT the shadow of death, travail, or judgment,<br>
as some who have not learned the peace of submission view it.<br>
Rather, it is the shadow of protection, peace, rejoicing, delight,<br>
and LOVE.  My mother-in-law, a widow for more than fifteen years,<br>
continues to conduct her business as Mrs. John F. Kling.  She<br>
views it as part of God's protection of her.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; OK, end of exposition.  May the peace of God rule in our hearts</i><br>
<i>&gt; (Colossians 3:15; memorize the whole chapter, folks, it's good stuff).</i><br>
<p>
Amen, amen.  How about verses 18-19?<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; Fred Christiansen</i><br>
<p>
Dan Blake<br>
dblake@hprnd.rose.hp.com<br>
