<title>Aug_1992: Re: Religious liberty on University campuses</title>
<h1>Re: Religious liberty on University campuses</h1>
Drew Corrigan (<i>drew@dubhe.anu.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 31 Aug 92 15:59:21 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#74">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#74">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#74">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#74">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0075.html">Steven Timm: "list demographics"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0073.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Rules and Culture"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0061.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Religious liberty on University campuses"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0079.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Religious liberty on University campuses"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Fred Christiansen writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;1) About 11 years ago, the church school of the church I was attending had</i><br>
<i>&gt;   several students who were World-wide Church of God.  They kept several</i><br>
<i>&gt;   religious holidays which Christians have not historically kept.  The</i><br>
<i>&gt;   teacher and the church were slightly taken aback but then upon reflection</i><br>
<i>&gt;   accomodated.</i><br>
<p>
As a member of the WCoG I would question your comment that we observe <br>
religious holidays which Christians have not historically kept. I quote<br>
from our official Statement of Beliefs:<br>
<p>
THE FESTIVALS<br>
  The observance of the festivals and holy days enjoined on ancient<br>
  Israel was affirmed by the example of Jesus Christ and the apostles.<br>
  They are holy convocations, memorials of God's great acts of<br>
  salvation in history, symbols of the power of God, and types of the<br>
  anticipated future fulfillment of God's plan of salvation.  For the<br>
  Christian, the festivals and holy days are annual celebrations of<br>
  God's power, love, and saving grace.<br>
  (Leviticus 23:1-2, John 4:45, 5:1, 7:37, 12:12, Acts 20:16,<br>
  I Corinthians 5:7-8)<br>
 <br>
Historically, the early Church did observe these Festivals (Passover, the<br>
Days of Unleavened Bread, Pentecost, Atonement, and Tabernacles) - the<br>
references in Acts and elsewhere make this clear. Further, there is evidence<br>
that other Christians down through history observed these too, though they<br>
were often shunned and persecuted as Judaizers.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  (Unfortunately, that church was not always that reasonable.)</i><br>
<p>
We try to be reasonable :-)! We hold these annual festivals with the same<br>
regard as the weekly Sabbath. Further, we do not observe religious festivals <br>
of non-Biblical origin (eg. Easter, Christmas). Perhaps a misunderstanding<br>
arose and this was perceived as unreasonableness on our part?<br>
<p>
Regards,<br>
<p>
Drew Corrigan.<br>
<p>
PS. My Bible does have Colossians 2:16-18, Galatians, etc, just in case<br>
    you're wondering :-)!<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
