<title>Aug_1992: social customs and rings</title>
<h1>social customs and rings</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 31 Aug 92 13:54:15 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#77">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#77">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#77">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#77">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0078.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Who's in charge?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0076.html">Russell Grau: "list demographics"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I would like to make a light hearted comment about wedding rings.  My<br>
experience is that most single men can't remember which finger it is<br>
supposed to be on anyway.  Plus there are often other rings on nearby<br>
fingers to confuse the picture.  In addition, you have to reflect<br>
everything through the vertical axis and remember ``Let's see - her<br>
left hand is on my right now''.  Of course, all the while you are<br>
supposed to be carrying on a conversation and objects can get in the<br>
way of the critical finger -- what was that you said, again -- and<br>
it's not polite to stare at her hand.  Then, I think that in Europe<br>
the ring finger is not the same as here, but I have trouble<br>
remembering which one it is anyway.  Is it really forbidden to wear<br>
another ring on the wedding ring finger?  So I think that the value of<br>
wedding rings for showing your marital status is highly overrated.<br>
<p>
What I do at work is to have a picture of my wife and children on my<br>
desk, to show I am married.  It's also helpful to mention your wife<br>
and children in conversation if you think someone may be getting the<br>
wrong idea.  That goes for both men and women.  When I met my wife,<br>
one of my first questions was, Are you married?  That's a good way to<br>
get someone's attention, by the way!<br>
<p>
I think that one unfortunate result of wearing wedding rings is that<br>
it introduces too great a distinction between the married and single<br>
status.  In Christ, there is no male or female etc. -- no married or<br>
single, either.  For those who are single and would like to be<br>
married, the ring is a constant reminder of their status, and an<br>
unwelcome one, I think (at least, if they can remember which finger it<br>
is on ... ).  I think one reason some ladies wear rings is that they<br>
wish they had a wedding ring and it's as close as they can get.<br>
<p>
We went to Europe as a married couple with children, not wearing<br>
wedding rings, and stayed in hotels and never had trouble.  I<br>
sometimes wonder if a wedding ring is still as necessary in Europe as<br>
it was in Ellen White's day.  Of course, maybe the people just assumed<br>
we were crazy Americans.<br>
<p>
One good result of not wearing a wedding ring or (other?) jewelry is<br>
that some people may be impressed.  I read at least one mission story<br>
where a man noticed how simply and naturally a lady was dressed and<br>
began to wonder what was different about her.  Through this experience<br>
he became introduced to the Lord and the Seventh-day Adventist Church.<br>
On our recent trip to Europe we witnessed to a considerable extent to<br>
two people, both of whom asked why we were vegetarians.  I think the<br>
same thing can happen when our style of dress is simple and natural.<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
