<title>Aug_1992: Re: Who's in charge?</title>
<h1>Re: Who's in charge?</h1>
Paul Gates (<i>70516.420@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>31 Aug 92 13:45:26 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#78">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#78">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#78">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#78">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0079.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Religious liberty on University campuses"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0077.html">David Plaisted: "social customs and rings"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0058.html">Bill Nickless: "Who's in charge?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0083.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Who's in charge?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
To the network:<br>
<p>
I believe that rebels are created as a result of multitudes of rules<br>
without proper foundation.  A good example is the story of the Prodigal<br>
son in Luke 15. The one son rebelled against it. The other son could not<br>
see or understand what was happening when his brother returned because he<br>
had kept all the "rules."<br>
<p>
Dwight Nelson, senior pastor at Andrews University has an excellent<br>
sermon/talk on this very subject. <br>
<p>
<p>
................Paul<br>
