<title>Aug_1992: Re: Religious liberty on University campuses</title>
<h1>Re: Religious liberty on University campuses</h1>
Paul Gates (<i>70516.420@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>31 Aug 92 13:45:21 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#84">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#84">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#84">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#84">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0085.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: The minister's wife"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0083.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Who's in charge?"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0061.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Religious liberty on University campuses"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Network:<br>
<p>
Steve, you are right we need to accomadate Sunday worshippers when even<br>
we can.<br>
<p>
I have gone to "bat" for Sunday ministers when the local high school was<br>
having some activity on Sunday mornings. The problem was solved with the<br>
principal of the school and the Sunday ministers were very appreciative of<br>
my efforts. The reason I did it and not one of them was that I was the<br>
president of the  ministerial assoc.<br>
<p>
Sometimes we miss the real issue in the Sabbath/Sunday controversy. When<br>
this issue comes up our attention is immediately turned to the<br>
Sunday-keeping Christians versus the Sabbath-keeping (Saturday)<br>
Christians. This is not the issue. <br>
<p>
Many Sunday keeping Christians are resting fully in Christ for their<br>
salvation; they are keeping Sunday for the right reason. Likewise there<br>
are many Saturday keeping Christians who believe that their<br>
Sabbath-keeping will save them; they are keeping the Sabbath for the<br>
wrong reason.<br>
<p>
The real issue in the Sabbath/Sunday controversy is the age long<br>
controversy between salvation by works versus salvation by faith.<br>
This controversy will reach its climax in these last days.<br>
<p>
When Adam and Eve turned from God dependence to self dependence, at the<br>
fall, they had to eat their bread "by the sweat of their face." (Gen.<br>
3:19). As a result of this, a man-made rest day had to be established,<br>
and Sunday became that day. But unlike God's Sabbath, man's rest day does<br>
not point to a perfect finished work. Today Sunday is the international<br>
day of rest from man's work. Since all mankind was also created a<br>
spiritual being, his departure from God's dependence to self dependence<br>
also meant a departure from God worship to self worship: Rom. 1:18-32;<br>
Isa. 53:6; Phil 2:21. <br>
<p>
The bottom line is:  salvation by faith in God's grace.( Eph 2:8,9; Titus<br>
3:5). At the heart of every man-made religion is salvation by works. Rom.<br>
9:30-32; 10:1-3; Gal. 3:1-3,10. Those who submit to salvation by grace<br>
enter into God's rest, symbolized in the bible by the Sabbath.<br>
<p>
Those who insist on saving themselves by works enter man's rest which will<br>
be symbolized in the last days by Sunday keeping. These two alternate<br>
ways of salvation have been in conflict ever since Cain killed Abel. This<br>
conflict will culminate in the war of Armageddon when those who have<br>
willfully and ultimately rejected the gospel of grace will persecute<br>
those who are resting entirely in God's redemption in Christ.<br>
<p>
My basic concern is with and for 7th-day Adventists who still are<br>
clinging on to salvation by works. My concern is that according to<br>
scripture they do not have a prayer beyond this world. And it really is a<br>
pity because they do not have the assurance of salvation as John talks<br>
about it in 1 John 5:13 and onward. Those of us who are Adventists here on<br>
the net need to pray and work for these mis-guided church members.<br>
<p>
...........more later,....................Paul<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
