<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Some pages must have fallen from your Bible, Fred.  Here, let me</i><br>
<i>&gt; share with you.  [Psalm 17:7-9; Psalm 63:7-8; Song of Solomon 2:3-4]</i><br>
<i>&gt; Now, I know that in context, these verses speak about the relation-</i><br>
<i>&gt; ship between man and God, but under the light of the first twelve</i><br>
       ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^<br>
<i>&gt; verses of 1st Corinthians, I think they can be applied to the</i><br>
<i>&gt; husband-wife relationship.</i><br>
  ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^<br>
Agreed!  The shadow/wings metaphor is delightful.  Cf. Matt 23:37, Luke 13:34,<br>
Ruth 3.  It is also a challenge:  "When a mother (hen) says Cluck! Cluck!<br>
Who comes running?  All her baby chicks come running!" goes the song.<br>
Now, let's ask ourselves:  When Christ calls us, do we come running, ready<br>
to do whatever He asks of us?<br>
<p>
The "shadow" I was referring to was the shadow of anonymity, wherein the<br>
personality of the wife is buried as an almost non-entity.  I believe I have<br>
the support of Scripture (Proverbs 31) for a wife who is a distinct person,<br>
yet in no way willful, rebellious, or of an independent spirit (1 Pet 3:4).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Rather, it is the shadow of protection, peace, rejoicing, delight,</i><br>
<i>&gt; and LOVE.  My mother-in-law, a widow for more than fifteen years,</i><br>
<i>&gt; continues to conduct her business as Mrs. John F. Kling.  She</i><br>
<i>&gt; views it as part of God's protection of her.</i><br>
<p>
Yes, a husband is to be an "umbrella of loving protection" for his wife and<br>
family.  And a wife is to put herself under that umbrella (Eph 5, Col 3),<br>
be under his authority (1 Pet 3:6), know how to appeal, and when to go over<br>
his head (Ps 50:15).  The husband's love is to be as Christ's, even laying<br>
down his life for her protection.<br>
<p>
As to your mother-in-law:  There's a measure of conviction for me there.<br>
I'm willing to back down from my 1st para above re the use of husband's name.<br>
I think we're in synch on the rest after my expanded comments herein.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  On Attitude &amp; the Immune System:  A sound heart is the life of the flesh:
    but envy the rottenness of the bones.  Prov 14:30
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
