<title>Oct_1992: Re: Discussion on perfection</title>
<h1>Re: Discussion on perfection</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>06 Oct 1992 15:03:43 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#22">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#22">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#22">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#22">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0023.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Re: Praying for gift of tongues"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0021.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Praying for the gift of tongues"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Mime-Version: 1.0<br>
<p>
Before ceasing to post on this topic, I would just like to say what<br>
I have gained from the discussion.<br>
<p>
I had never really investigated the issue of Christian perfection at<br>
all before. I suppose the issues which are closest to me are ones to<br>
do with the relationship of religion and science, and things to do with<br>
music. The views represented by Ruben have only ever been given to me<br>
by people who don't believe things are that way.<br>
<p>
Initially I was surprised by the number of texts Ruben managed to produce<br>
which seemed to back up his view. This motivated me to start to investigate<br>
the issue for myself. I found myself in an awkward position where, on the<br>
one hand, I could not back up my own understanding in the face of the<br>
evidence Ruben presented. On the other hand, I found the views he was<br>
promoting untenable in that I felt they contradicted the core of Jesus'<br>
gospel.<br>
<p>
At present I am in the process of trying to resolve the situation for<br>
myself. I have purchased some books, both EGW books I didn't have and<br>
some others, and am reading them when I can. I have also spoken to my<br>
church pastor regarding the issue, and a couple of other people. Things<br>
are starting to come together, albeit slowly.<br>
<p>
I never intended to get caught up in a discussion/argument/whatever on the<br>
net, partly because I don't know how many other people would benefit from<br>
it (someone said this was all deja vu on the net), and partly because I don't<br>
have a well-considered opinion on the topic. I do, however, have a well-<br>
considered opinion on the way of approach that says "here is the one and<br>
only way to view this doctrinal issue", and it was this that eventually<br>
motivated me to post some replies.<br>
<p>
I would be interested to know what the overall "feeling" was last time<br>
this issue was discussed. Was there one view which seemed to be held by<br>
most people, or was it impossible to tell?<br>
<p>
Cheryl may be right about people "not budging an inch" as a result of<br>
doctrinal discussions. For myself, I know that I have been motivated to<br>
study and pray more than I have for quite some time, so I feel that<br>
I have gained from the experience!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
