<i>&gt; SDAnet has heard before of my experience in South Africa when I prayed for </i><br>
<i>&gt; the gift of tongues to learn Afrikaans, and succeeded in learning the</i><br>
<i>&gt; language quickly, albeit not without study.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Is this another appropriate place to pray for the gift of tongues?  Or</i><br>
<i>&gt; should I, and the congregation at large, be content with the spiritual</i><br>
<i>&gt; gifts we have already been given?</i><br>
<p>
Some *are* given the gift of tongues already...but I doubt if it would<br>
be unreasonable to ask for it.  I remember a summer spent colporteuring<br>
around Salinas, CA when the Spanish that I had studied in academy and<br>
college just seemed to click.  (Odd that it didn't work so well when I<br>
finished work that summer and went back to school.)<br>
<p>
I've been blessed by attending our hispanic congregation's services<br>
(although it gets harder as I get "volunteered" to teach more at our<br>
english-language congregation), although I read much better than I<br>
understand spoken Spanish.  Well, I can follow some better than others.<br>
Good thing for me that there aren't any Cubans in the group.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Do people really feel that tongues, miracles, and prophecy will be </i><br>
<i>&gt; part of the latter rain, or are we holding up our umbrellas for </i><br>
<i>&gt; protection against it?</i><br>
<p>
I think that some may feel that spiritual gifts manifest suddenly with<br>
no effort (other than developing one's relationship with God).  While<br>
that may happen, I'm sure myself that some require more or less real<br>
effort on our part, but are gifts nonetheless.<br>
