<title>Oct_1992: Re: Adam and Eve</title>
<h1>Re: Adam and Eve</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 1 Oct 92 11:46:00 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#1">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#1">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#1">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#1">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0002.html">Ian Brown: "I John"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0000.html">Daniel R. Bidwell: "Re: With this message we break the record"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all,<br>
<p>
Tony's reply <br>
<p>
<i>&gt;This concept of being sinful without sinning...it has interesting implications</i><br>
<i>&gt;in the "translation faith" discussion as well.</i><br>
<p>
regarding the question post to SDAnet : <br>
<p>
?----&gt;<br>
<i>&gt;Question:</i><br>
<i>&gt;  Does anybody know if Adam and/or Eve ever sinned on a "lesser" scale before &gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;they ate from the forbidden fruit.  </i><br>
<i>&gt;&lt;----</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
it very true. However I must disagree with Tony's opinion.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Let's see, sin is an inner state of being which is outwardly manifested as</i><br>
<i>&gt;actions known as sins. Eve and Adam eating the forbidden fruit was an</i><br>
<i>&gt;action which demonstrated their choice to distrust God's words to them</i><br>
<i>&gt;and hence to disobey him.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
If the above statement is true then God created imperfect, or sinful <br>
people with a sinful inner state. And God just arbitrarily selects an<br>
external act on which to condemn Adam.<br>
<p>
<p>
There is no such thing as a lesser sin, all sin is sin and receives the<br>
same reward, death.<br>
<p>
According to the scriptures Sin is not a state of being. And like the Jews<br>
in Jesus time, the opinion of the Rabbis does not really count for much.<br>
<p>
<p>
1 John 3:4 Whosoever committeth sin transgresseth also the law: for sin is the<br>
           transgression of the law. (KJV)<br>
<p>
James 4:17 Therefore to him that knoweth to do good, and doeth it not, to him<br>
           it is sin. (KJV)<br>
<p>
<p>
Sin  by the definition of the scriptures alone (sola scritura) is an act.<br>
An act of choice. This act can either be phyical or mental yet it is still <br>
an act.<br>
<p>
There is no other definition in the bible apart from sin as choice.<br>
<p>
If we really want to understand what sin is, then lets get a really good<br>
theological handle on it by turning to James 1:15  which says.<br>
<p>
"Then when lust has conceived, it gives birth to sin; and when sin is<br>
accomplished, it brings forth death." <br>
<p>
 <br>
ONLY after the LUST conceives it is SIN not before and such we are not <br>
guilty until that time. LUST in itself is not sin unless it is cherished<br>
(which is what is meant by conceiving).<br>
<p>
To directly answer the first question. I would say no they did not sin<br>
before eating of the forbidden fruit. If they had then separation from<br>
God would have occured at that point because <br>
<p>
"...your iniquities have separated between you and your God, and your sins<br>
have hid His face from you, that He will not hear." Isa 59:2<br>
<p>
Yet we read in Genesis that it is only after eating of the fruit that they<br>
were separated from God. <br>
<p>
Sin is the act of rebelling against God and His commandments, the bible<br>
talks about sin as being a mystery, the mystery of iniquity. It is impossible<br>
for us to know exactly when the point of conception occurs yet after it has <br>
happened we know it has. The same with the conception of sin, it is in <br>
likemanner a mystery.<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<p>
 <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
