</DOCHDR>
<!-- received="Mon Jan 01 01:01:01 1990 PST" -->
<!-- sent="01 Oct 1992 11:18:07 -0400 (EDT)" -->
<!-- name="Pam Harris" -->
<!-- email="HARRISP@UTKVX.UTCC.UTK.EDU" -->
<!-- subject="FAMILY VALUES" -->
<!-- id="01GPFKKI0TW88Y6LM2@utkvx.utk.edu" -->
<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Oct_1992: FAMILY VALUES</title>
<h1>FAMILY VALUES</h1>
Pam Harris (<i>HARRISP@UTKVX.UTCC.UTK.EDU</i>)<br>
<i>01 Oct 1992 11:18:07 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#5">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#5">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#5">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#5">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0006.html">Bob Moynihan: "re: Family Values"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0004.html">Steven Timm: "Family Values"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ironically, Jesus focused his attention on those people whose families<br>
were not perfect or perfectly pure: the woman at the well (5 husbands),<br>
the widow, the woman caught in adultry, those demon possessed, etc. He<br>
seemed to focus on the outcasts, those who in society who were not<br>
considered the "perfect family." He came to set the captives free. We<br>
do not read about him giving family enrichment seminars to synagogue<br>
families. For too long our church has alienated those members and non-<br>
members who were not traditional family units. But our church family<br>
should become the family for those who are singles, divorced, single<br>
parents, etc. We should be the place where they feel at home, not where<br>
they feel criticized and disenfranchised. We have always encouraged<br>
the traditional family unit through our education system and its focus<br>
in religion classes on THE ADVENTIST HOME and marriage issues in the<br>
Youth Guidance class at the academy level. If you are an acute observor<br>
of graphic and visuals in our church's publications, you will see the<br>
role model of the foursome family in all our publications, textbooks,<br>
etc.: Mom, Dad, big brother, little sister. <br>
<p>
Our church, however, fails many times in providing social occasions<br>
for church group activities. Remember the olden days of the Saturday]<br>
night church social when everyone came (all ages) and had a great<br>
time? <br>
<p>
There is an excellent book on making these events happen in the church<br>
family which are fun, inclusive, and connect different ages and social<br>
groups. It's by Marlene LaFever. I'll send the title when I think of it.<br>
<p>
Perhaps this is why many other denominations build gymnasiums, bowling<br>
alleys, and plan a myriad of activities and help groups centered at <br>
their churches. <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
