<title>Oct_1992: re: Family Values</title>
<h1>re: Family Values</h1>
Bob Moynihan (<i>moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 1 Oct 92 13:35:10 EDT </i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#6">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#6">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#6">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#6">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0007.html">Tony: "re: Family Values"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0005.html">Pam Harris: "FAMILY VALUES"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0004.html">Steven Timm: "Family Values"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0011.html">Daniel D Deavours: "re: Family Values"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve Timm writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; How can we increase the importance of the family in the SDA church without</i><br>
<i>&gt; condemning or alienating the people who are fast becoming the majority</i><br>
<i>&gt; in our church, namely singles be they those who never married, are divorced,</i><br>
<i>&gt; or are single parents for whatever reason?</i><br>
<p>
I'm not sure if increasing the importance of the family is the <br>
proper focus.  Personally, I think there should be more emphasis <br>
on personal responsibility for one's actions, and the seriousness <br>
of marriage.  We have divorces because one or both members of a <br>
couple do not take their marriage vows seriously.  consequently, <br>
one or both have affairs, and the marriage breaks up.  Or they<br>
get into arguments and instead of working to resolve their <br>
differences, become hateful or just plain decide to trash the <br>
marriage because it's too much work.<br>
<p>
Each prospective marriage partner must ask themself these questions:<br>
Am I prepared to commit the rest of my life to this person, no <br>
matter what the future may bring?  Am I prepared to be faithful to <br>
this person, forsaking all others, for the rest of my life?  Am I <br>
prepared to make whatever effort is required to make this marriage<br>
be a successful one?   If -both- people can't answer all three <br>
questions in the affirmative, they should not get married.  If all<br>
marriages were made up of people that -did- answer "yes", and <br>
subsequently lived up to their vows, no one would be talking about <br>
'family values', because our families would be rock solid.<br>
<p>
When we marry, we make a personal commitment to our spouses and to <br>
God.  If we each lived up to those personal commitments, broken <br>
families would disappear.<br>
<p>
===================================================================<br>
Bob Moynihan                         Bush/Quayle '92: Just say noe.<br>
moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com             Go Ipswich Town!<br>
===================================================================<br>
  Disclaimer: I speak only for myself, not for Hewlett-Packard Co.<br>
===================================================================                                         <br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
