<!-- received="Mon Jan 01 01:01:01 1990 PST" -->
<!-- sent="02 Oct 1992 01:31:51 +1000" -->
<!-- name="Tony" -->
<!-- email="PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au" -->
<!-- subject="re: Family Values" -->
<!-- id="01GPGEPQ4H7694E82R@cc.newcastle.edu.au" -->
<!-- inreplyto="Family Values" -->
<title>Oct_1992: re: Family Values</title>
<h1>re: Family Values</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>02 Oct 1992 01:31:51 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#7">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#7">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#7">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#7">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0008.html">Steven Timm: "Administrivia"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0006.html">Bob Moynihan: "re: Family Values"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0004.html">Steven Timm: "Family Values"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0013.html">cheryl berthelsen: "re: Family Values"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Mime-Version: 1.0<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
If the above statement is true then God created imperfect, or sinful <br>
people with a sinful inner state. And God just arbitrarily selects an<br>
external act on which to condemn Adam.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
No, God created beings with the ability and the responsibility to choose<br>
their inner state. If they chose to rebel, that was not something imposed<br>
upon them by their creator.<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
There is no such thing as a lesser sin, all sin is sin and receives the<br>
same reward, death.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
Agreed.<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
According to the scriptures Sin is not a state of being. And like the Jews<br>
in Jesus time, the opinion of the Rabbis does not really count for much.<br>
<p>
<p>
1 John 3:4 Whosoever committeth sin transgresseth also the law: for sin is the<br>
           transgression of the law. (KJV)<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
The RSV says "Everyone who commits sin is guilty of lawlessness; sin is <br>
lawlessness"<br>
<p>
As for the rabbis, I agree that their opinions and interpretations need<br>
careful examination. That's one reason why I haven't actually *said* much<br>
in my posts on translation faith. I refer all interested to various written<br>
work because these men, just like Ruben, quote extensively from scripture<br>
and give an interpretation. We certainly need to discern which interpretations<br>
are consistent with the message of the Bible.<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
James 4:17 Therefore to him that knoweth to do good, and doeth it not, to him<br>
           it is sin. (KJV)<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
The RSV says "Whoever knows what is right to do and fails to do it, for him<br>
it is sin." This is interesting, because it seems to indicate that a person<br>
who did not know what was right may not be held accountable for doing the<br>
wrong thing. What is sin for me may not be sin for someone else. This is<br>
consistent with the view that sin is a state of lawlessness or rebellion<br>
against God, because if sin was defined as a set of actions then surely<br>
the same set of actions would be applied to everybody.<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
If we really want to understand what sin is, then lets get a really good<br>
theological handle on it by turning to James 1:15  which says.<br>
<p>
"Then when lust has conceived, it gives birth to sin; and when sin is<br>
accomplished, it brings forth death." <br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
Quoting from the RSV again, "...each person is tempted when he is lured<br>
and enticed by his own desire. Then desire when it has conceived gives<br>
birth to sin; and sin when it is full-grown brings forth death."<br>
<p>
Once again this is consistent with the definition of sin as a state<br>
of rebellion. In this case, the birth of sin occurs inside the person,<br>
and the full-grown sin is manifested in rebellious, unloving actions.<br>
<p>
Although I despise the proof-text technique, I will finish with a couple<br>
of statements made by Jesus.<br>
<p>
"You have heard that it was said, 'You shall not commit adultery.' But<br>
 I say to you that every one who looks at a woman lustfully has already<br>
 committed adultery with her in his heart.'..."  Matthew 4:27, part of the<br>
sermon on the mount.<br>
<p>
Speaking to his disciples about the pharisees preoccupation with ceremonial<br>
rites, "But what comes out of the mouth proceeds from the heart, and this<br>
defiles a man. For out of the heart come evil thoughts, murder, adultery,<br>
fornication, theft, false witness, slander. These are what defile a man;<br>
but to eat with unwashed hands does not defile a man." Matthew 15:18-20<br>
<p>
One thing I have learned as a scientist is that the interpretation you make<br>
of a given set of data is often a result of what you read into it. A simple<br>
example can be found in the origins debate. Some scientist marvels over the<br>
finely balanced ecosystem he is investigating, and points out the footprints<br>
of natural selection and evolution at every turn. A Christian looks at <br>
exactly the same thing and sees wonderful evidence for a designer, Creator<br>
God.<br>
<p>
If I read the Bible as a person who believes in the fallen, sinful nature<br>
of Christ, and that sin is defined as actions, then I will see lots of texts<br>
which support my point of view. If I read it as a person who believes that<br>
sin is a state of being, that Christ was born sinless and through the power<br>
of God stayed sinless, then I will still see lots of texts which support my<br>
view. Many of them will be the same texts. <br>
<p>
This is why it is so important to give both perspectives a fair hearing. I<br>
myself am in the process of that right now. My motivation for writing this<br>
post has largely been to point out that you can't just quote a whole lot<br>
of texts, interpret them the way you want, and say that the debate is over.<br>
<p>
Let's face it, the SDA church has done an about turn on this issue more <br>
than once. Obviously it is a difficult topic, and both views can be and<br>
often are taken to an extreme.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
