<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all,<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; As for the rabbis, I agree that their opinions and interpretations need</i><br>
<i>&gt; careful examination. That's one reason why I haven't actually *said* much</i><br>
<i>&gt; in my posts on translation faith. I refer all interested to various written</i><br>
<i>&gt; work because these men, just like Ruben, quote extensively from scripture</i><br>
<i>&gt; and give an interpretation. We certainly need to discern which interpretations</i><br>
<i>&gt; are consistent with the message of the Bible.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Very true, but the writings of men never compare with a clear <br>
"Thus saith the Lord."<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; ----&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; James 4:17 Therefore to him that knoweth to do good, and doeth it not, to him</i><br>
<i>&gt;            it is sin. (KJV)</i><br>
<i>&gt; &lt;----</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; The RSV says "Whoever knows what is right to do and fails to do it, for him</i><br>
<i>&gt; it is sin." This is interesting, because it seems to indicate that a person</i><br>
<i>&gt; who did not know what was right may not be held accountable for doing the</i><br>
<i>&gt; wrong thing. What is sin for me may not be sin for someone else. This is</i><br>
<i>&gt; consistent with the view that sin is a state of lawlessness or rebellion</i><br>
<i>&gt; against God, because if sin was defined as a set of actions then surely</i><br>
<i>&gt; the same set of actions would be applied to everybody.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
yep, agreed, Sin is the ACT of choosing to rebel against (disobey) God,<br>
( however there are two separate things, evil and sin, all sin is evil<br>
not all evil is sin, e.g. a cat killing a bird ) <br>
<p>
get a hold of this :<br>
<p>
What then happens if I do not know, can I claim ignorance ? <br>
Is my sin proportionate to my knowledge ?<br>
<p>
   "If I had not come and spoken unto them, they had not had sin: but<br>
    now they have no cloke for their sin." John 15:22 <br>
   "If I had not done among them the works which none other man did,<br>
    they had not had sin: but now have they both seen and hated both me<br>
    and my Father." John 15:24  <br>
   "Jesus said unto them, If ye were blind, ye should have no sin: but<br>
    now ye say, We see; therefore your sin remaineth." John 9:41<br>
   "Woe unto thee, Chorazin! woe unto thee, Bethsaida! for if the<br>
    mighty works, which were done in you, had been done in Tyre and<br>
    Sidon, they would have repented long ago in sackcloth and ashes.<br>
    But I say unto you, It shall be more tolerable for Tyre and Sidon<br>
    at the day of judgment, than for you.<br>
    And thou, Capernaum, which art exalted unto heaven, shalt be<br>
    brought down to hell: for if the mighty works, which have been done<br>
    in thee, had been done in Sodom, it would have remained until this<br>
    day. But I say unto you, That it shall be more tolerable for the land of<br>
    Sodom in the day of judgment, than for thee.<br>
    At that time Jesus answered and said, I thank thee, O Father, Lord<br>
    of heaven and earth, because thou hast hid these things from the<br>
    wise and prudent, and hast revealed them unto babes. "Matt 11:21-25 <br>
      [willful ignorance however is not excused]<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; Although I despise the proof-text technique, I will finish with a couple</i><br>
<i>&gt; of statements made by Jesus.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;    [stuff deleted to save Bandwidth ]</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; If I read the Bible as a person who believes in the fallen, sinful nature</i><br>
<i>&gt; of Christ, and that sin is defined as actions, then I will see lots of texts</i><br>
<i>&gt; which support my point of view. If I read it as a person who believes that</i><br>
<i>&gt; sin is a state of being, that Christ was born sinless and through the power</i><br>
<i>&gt; of God stayed sinless, then I will still see lots of texts which support my</i><br>
<i>&gt; view. Many of them will be the same texts. </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; This is why it is so important to give both perspectives a fair hearing. I</i><br>
<i>&gt; myself am in the process of that right now. My motivation for writing this</i><br>
<i>&gt; post has largely been to point out that you can't just quote a whole lot</i><br>
<i>&gt; of texts, interpret them the way you want, and say that the debate is over.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
hey, who said the discussion was over. For some it may just be beginning.<br>
It is through discussion that we learn, I'm all for it. <br>
<p>
One thing though is that all discussion should be solidly based on the<br>
scriptures, and if that means profound biblical analysis then let it be. <br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Let's face it, the SDA church has done an about turn on this issue more </i><br>
<i>&gt; than once. Obviously it is a difficult topic, and both views can be and</i><br>
<i>&gt; often are taken to an extreme.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
<p>
I won't necessarily agree with you here, some sections of the church may have<br>
done an about turn on this issue, but the generalisation would not be true.<br>
<p>
<p>
Regards,<br>
Ruben.<br>
