<title>Oct_1992: re: Family Values</title>
<h1>re: Family Values</h1>
Daniel D Deavours (<i>ddd42961@uxa.cso.uiuc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 1 Oct 92 20:13:08 CDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#11">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#11">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#11">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#11">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0012.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: ASRS"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0010.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "re : Sin"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0006.html">Bob Moynihan: "re: Family Values"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0007.html">Tony: "re: Family Values"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Bob Moynihan writes:<br>
[Lots of good comments]<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; If all</i><br>
<i>&gt; marriages were made up of people that -did- answer "yes", and </i><br>
<i>&gt; subsequently lived up to their vows, no one would be talking about </i><br>
<i>&gt; 'family values', because our families would be rock solid.</i><br>
<p>
	I'm not so sure it's so cut and dry.  I know of a family that<br>
has gone through very difficult times.  They were true to their vows, and<br>
are still together.  However, it is NOT a rock solid family.  It is not<br>
always happy or stable, but it is always there.  (Perhaps I'm not sure<br>
what you say "rock solid" means.)<br>
	In other cultures, for example, Islamic and Indian, it is a VERY<br>
disgraceful thing to get a divorce.  Social pressures enforce their vows.<br>
They are committed, and work out solutions to their differences, although<br>
it is often not ideal.<br>
	My point is that committment is not the key.  Some people do<br>
want to have successful marriages, but sincerely don't know how to.<br>
I think that is where the "family values" come into play.  People need<br>
to know how to deal with anger, differences, growing old, mid-life<br>
crisis, medical problems, money, work, etc.  I think the church has a<br>
role here in teaching some of these things.<br>
<p>
Dan Deavours<br>
zeos@uiuc.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
