<title>Oct_1992: re: Family Values</title>
<h1>re: Family Values</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 2 Oct 92 12:23:40 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#13">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#13">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#13">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#13">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0014.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Re:  re : Sin"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0012.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: ASRS"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0004.html">Steven Timm: "Family Values"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have to agree with Dan when he states that just because a family is<br>
together doesn't mean that it is a rock solid family.  The Dysfunctional<br>
Family is very common in the US and in most church denominations.  Many<br>
children live with both parents together but the home is not loving, not<br>
nurturing, and not happy.  Many times this is because of personaility<br>
problems of the parents.  I'm not taking about not able to get along.  I'm<br>
talking about defects in the personality, lifetime problems that have<br>
left pathology, and childhood tragedies that have scarred their ability<br>
to be happy, to love, and to be unselfish as a marriage partner or parent.<br>
Unfortunately, these difficulties also affect their perceptions of God,<br>
the church, and the world.<br>
<p>
The key to building rock solid families is to heal the individual.  Rather<br>
than focusing on purging lives of sin, keeping couples commited to each<br>
other, and making the home happy, the church needs to focus on individual<br>
needs.  The need to be able to give and receive love.  The need for healing<br>
and being able to forgive.  The need for somebody to care.  Too many times<br>
the church becomes involved only at the eleventh hour when the marriage<br>
is at the edge of divorce.  Many couples are hurting but carry a facade<br>
that all is well.  Paul instructed us to confess our weaknesses to one<br>
another (not our sins).  Once people in the church realize that even<br>
the "pillars" in the community have problems, we can become more open<br>
about our pain and where we need help.  Then the church will realize<br>
what is really needed to help our families.<br>
<p>
We don't need more marriage encounter programs.  We don't need more<br>
brow beating about lack of commitment or spirituality.  We need a church<br>
that cares about the individual whether they be single, married, divorced,<br>
old, young, middle age.  The healing that Christ brought in His ministry<br>
to the individual is what the world needs.  He focused on the person and<br>
that person's problems.  A marriage can never be rock solid when the<br>
individuals in that marriage are not solid themselves.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
