<title>Oct_1992: Healing the family</title>
<h1>Healing the family</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri,  2 Oct 1992 16:04:06 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#15">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#15">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#15">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#15">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0016.html">Stan Macasieb: "Re: Healing the family"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0014.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Re:  re : Sin"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0016.html">Stan Macasieb: "Re: Healing the family"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Cheryl mentioned that she thought that individuals needed to be healed first<br>
before relationships could be healed.  I'd like to put a twist on that,<br>
if I may.<br>
<p>
I propose that healing relationships is the way that individuals are healed,<br>
because family relationships form a significant part of one's identity.<br>
The image of God is reflected in relationships, and if relationships are<br>
misguided the individual will have a distorted view of God and of<br>
himself.<br>
<p>
There are various books written with techniques of how to restore people<br>
who have fallen into offense (a technical term in the Greek signifying<br>
a broken relationship).  It would be interesting to share some of them <br>
and I will try to do that.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
