<title>Oct_1992: I John</title>
<h1>I John</h1>
Ian Brown (<i>Malachi.Robertson@lambada.oit.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 3 Oct 92 23:46:06 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#17">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#17">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#17">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#17">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0018.html">David Plaisted: "discussion on perfection"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0016.html">Stan Macasieb: "Re: Healing the family"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have two articles on I John.  One of them (the older) I haven't really<br>
read in detail.  As such I don't know how these two views fit together. <br>
The first article is Sakae Kubo's "I John 3:9: Absolute or Habitual?"<br>
found in Andrews University Seminary Studies Vol. VII, no. 1 January 1969.<br>
The second article is Steven Vitrano's "The Doctrine of Sin in I John"<br>
found in Andrews University Seminary Studies Vol. 25, no. 1 Spring 1987. <br>
In the latter article Mr. Vitrano puts forth evidence that John speaks of<br>
to different groups:  the children of God and the children of the devil. <br>
He moves on to argue that the verse saying "Every one who commits sin is<br>
guilty of lawlessness; sin is lawlessness." taken in the context of v. 6<br>
(no one who abides in him sins) and v. 9 (no one born of God commits sin)<br>
refers to kind of sin (sin under a particular attitude towards it) that is<br>
commited by the children of the devil.  Also, he notes a parallel<br>
construction with v. 3 "And every one who thus<br>
hopes in him purifies himself as he is pure."  Again he points to the<br>
distinct groups being spoken of by John.  With the point about I John 3:4<br>
about lawlessness, he expands on evidence of agreement with Paul (Rom.<br>
6:3, 5-7, 12-14, 19; also Rom. 8:1-8).<br>
<p>
Next the author goes on to discuss the sin of God's children.  He goes to<br>
I John 1:9: "If we confess our sins, he is faithful and just, and will<br>
forgive our sins and cleanse us from all unrighteousness."  The same Greek<br>
word for unrighteousness is used in 5:17 where John says "All wrongdoing<br>
[unrighteousness] is sin."  Again another kind of sin appears (here there<br>
is a different attitude towards it).  <br>
<p>
Next he discusses I John 5:16: "If any one sees his brother committing<br>
what is not a mortal sin, he will ask, and God will give him life for<br>
those whose sin is not mortal.  There is sin which is mortal; I do not say<br>
that one is to pray for that."  He argues that the distinction here is<br>
that the one individual has an advocate in Jesus as such their sin is not<br>
mortal.  Here he points to verses in Hebrews (2:17-18; 7:25; 9:24).  Then<br>
he considers objections.  He ends the article with a chart of the two<br>
groups in English and Greek and then quotes I John 5:18-21.<br>
<p>
On the surface I thought it was pretty good; however, maybe I missed<br>
something.<br>
<p>
Ian.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0018.html">David Plaisted: "discussion on perfection"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0016.html">Stan Macasieb: "Re: Healing the family"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
