<!-- body="start" -->
Thanks, Dave P. for your comments on the discussion.  My feelings on the <br>
discussion:  It is better to discuss than to hurl brickbats from a distance.<br>
I think most people in the SDA church don't know the difference between<br>
the various views that have been expressed.  There are at least three sides<br>
here, possibly more.  Probably, many don't care and Cheryl has rightly <br>
raised the question of whether they should.  I don't think anyone <br>
actually understood the implications of the question I posed at the beginning<br>
of the translation faith thread, or if they did, they didn't post.<br>
<p>
The protagonists on the two extremes of the issue are almost unable to<br>
communicate with each other anymore.  In some circles any suggestion<br>
that "The Law of the Lord is perfect." (Psalm 19:7) is viewed as hopeless<br>
perfectionism.   The two sides use different definitions of "nature"<br>
if they use definitions at all.  One of the main goals of SDAnet<br>
is to keep lines of communication open, and this is an important issue<br>
to do this on.  Having said that, you notice that I have stopped sending<br>
out any of my posts on the issue.  Among the other things more important<br>
are the role of the Holy Spirit in the church.  More in my next post.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
