<title>Oct_1992: Re: Praying for gift of tongues</title>
<h1>Re: Praying for gift of tongues</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 6 Oct 92 09:15:06 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#23">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#23">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#23">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#23">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0024.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: Discussion on perfection"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0022.html">Tony: "Re: Discussion on perfection"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0025.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Praying for gift of tongues"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I offered a qualified **YES** to your question, Steve.  I think the underlying<br>
issue is whether learning Spanish fits into the scheme of things in the<br>
overall plan for your life.  For example, is this a "come over to Macedonia<br>
and help yes" situation?  Is it a situation where you have a specific skill<br>
or leadership that this company of worshipper needs?  Do you feel you have<br>
a specific "calling" to worship and minister to the hispanics?  Or is it<br>
a case of "I'm tired of the lukewarm bath I received when I worship with the<br>
English-speaking congregations?"   It is more fulfilling to us to worship<br>
and serve with enthusiastic new converts.  But does the Lord always want us<br>
to serve where it is "easier", "more comfortable", or "more personally<br>
fulfilling"?  I suggest that there are times for both.  Paul found himself<br>
frustrated with some congregations and totally blessed with others.  But did<br>
that mean that he was to preach where he personally was more blessed abd<br>
(and) neglect those where he felt unfulfilled?<br>
<p>
I guess what I'm saying is the underlying reason a person wants something<br>
from the Lord will indicate whether one should pray for a special gift to<br>
fulfill that purpose.  If one does not receive the gift it could mean one<br>
of two things:  either it was not the Lord's will for that person (would<br>
not benefit the person asking or could be a hindrance to the person) or<br>
the person was not spiritually prepared to receive the outpouring of the<br>
Holy Spirit.<br>
<p>
That's me two cents.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
