[cheryl berthelsen writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; For example, is this a "come over to Macedonia</i><br>
<i>&gt; and help yes" situation?  Is it a situation where you have a specific skill</i><br>
<i>&gt; or leadership that this company of worshipper needs?</i><br>
<p>
Just another tho't here:  Even if Steve was not involved in direct<br>
ministry or leadership, simply being able to converse with them in their<br>
native language will help them feel more at home in that congregation.<br>
<p>
Permit me to share an anecdote:  The group of deaf SDA's in the Portland, OR,<br>
and Vancouver, WA, area met for quite a few years in the B church and then<br>
for quite a few years in the ST church (names shortened to protect the<br>
guilty 8-).  During those years, not one hearing member took the time to<br>
learn even a rudimentary level of sign language (or so I was told by the<br>
deaf group).  And if, perchance, the two groups were to have services<br>
together, the deaf group had to sit "in the back of the bus".  How welcome<br>
do you suppose they felt in those churches?  Then, when hearing members<br>
of the GP church learned sign language and involved the deaf in their<br>
campouts, potlucks, etc., and invited them to sit at the *front* of the<br>
church, and just generally made them feel at home ... what a difference!<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  On Attitude &amp; the Immune System:  A sound heart is the life of the flesh:
    but envy the rottenness of the bones.  Prov 14:30
</pre>
