<title>Oct_1992: Family Values:  School choice</title>
<h1>Family Values:  School choice</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed,  7 Oct 1992 09:10:49 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#29">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#29">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#29">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#29">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0030.html">Dave Thomas: "On perfection"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0028.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re:  Discussion on perfection"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
We have discussed school choice here before.  (For those outside the USA,<br>
it's somewhat of an issue in our current presidential campaign.  Pres. Bush<br>
proposes issuing a voucher of $1000 to most school-age children, to be <br>
spent on education in the school of their choice, be it public, private,<br>
or religious.)  The Liberty magazine editorial staff generally opposes such<br>
plans as violation of the separation of church and state.  I can remember<br>
organized church opposition to such a plan when it was proposed in the state<br>
of Michigan.  Roy Adams, assoc. editor of the Review, caused no little <br>
firestorm by suggesting that such choice might be appropriate.<br>
<p>
I revisit this issue because a troublesome  thought occurred to me.<br>
How is the above-described school choice for grade school students any <br>
different than the federal grants which most college students get to use<br>
at the college of their choice?  Can we consistently benefit from one<br>
and oppose the other?<br>
<p>
It might be interesting to hear from other countries where government funding<br>
of SDA schools on lower levels is already happening.  A desire to maintain<br>
government funding kept our schools in South Africa segregated longer than <br>
they otherwise would have been, for instance.  How is it in Australia?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
