<title>Oct_1992: On perfection</title>
<h1>On perfection</h1>
Dave Thomas (<i>umsfdtho@deimos.oscs.montana.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 6 Oct 92 18:46:22 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#30">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#30">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#30">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#30">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0031.html">Sue Oemcke: "Re: Family Values: School choice"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0029.html">Steven Timm: "Family Values:  School choice"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I've stopped trying to be perfect.  Instead, I'm working on<br>
being nice, compassionate, patient, reliable.  I can't speak<br>
for anyone else, but I like me a lot more this way.  Trying<br>
to be perfect made me feel crabby, impatient, guilty, etc.<br>
<p>
To those tortured souls still trying to purge themselves of<br>
bad thoughts, bad feelings, bad habits,  I offer the following<br>
<p>
1.	Jesus died for us while we were yet sinners.<br>
2.	The controversy is between Christ and Satan, not<br>
	between me and my weaknesses.<br>
3.	The agenda for your reformation is not yours to set.<br>
	That is the responsibility of the Holy Spirit.<br>
4.	We are all going to heaven hanging on to Christ's<br>
	coat tails.  Grab on and be glad!<br>
<p>
Dave Thomas<br>
Montana State University<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
