<!-- body="start" -->
	 We have discussed school choice here before.  (For those outside the U<br>
	SA,<br>
	 it's somewhat of an issue in our current presidential campaign.  Pres.<br>
	 Bush<br>
	 proposes issuing a voucher of $1000 to most school-age children, to be<br>
	 <br>
	 spent on education in the school of their choice, be it public, privat<br>
	e,<br>
	 or religious.)  The Liberty magazine editorial staff generally opposes<br>
	 such<br>
	 plans as violation of the separation of church and state.  I can remem<br>
	ber<br>
	 organized church opposition to such a plan when it was proposed in the<br>
	 state<br>
	 of Michigan.  Roy Adams, assoc. editor of the Review, caused no little<br>
	 <br>
	 firestorm by suggesting that such choice might be appropriate.<br>
<p>
	 I revisit this issue because a troublesome  thought occurred to me.<br>
	 How is the above-described school choice for grade school students any<br>
	 <br>
	 different than the federal grants which most college students get to u<br>
	se<br>
	 at the college of their choice?  Can we consistently benefit from one<br>
	 and oppose the other?<br>
<p>
	 It might be interesting to hear from other countries where government <br>
	funding<br>
	 of SDA schools on lower levels is already happening.  A desire to main<br>
	tain<br>
	 government funding kept our schools in South Africa segregated longer <br>
	than <br>
	 they otherwise would have been, for instance.  How is it in Australia?<br>
<p>
	 Steve Timm<br>
<p>
Here in Australia our schools do accept government funding. The<br>
funding does not pay wages, but does help a lot with running costs.<br>
<p>
	Sue<br>
