<i>&gt; From: Sue Oemcke &lt;sao@cs.flinders.edu.au&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Here in Australia our schools do accept government funding. The</i><br>
<i>&gt; funding does not pay wages, but does help a lot with running costs.</i><br>
<p>
Our local public-school district offered a program last year to<br>
"aid" home-school families.<br>
<p>
Roughly 90% of the qualifying families turned down the offer because<br>
of various strings attached, such as required textbooks and course<br>
offerings.  The money would have been useful, but the baggage that<br>
weighed it down sort of ruined things.<br>
<p>
We pay our taxes to pay for the schools we don't use, and pay some<br>
more to support our local church's elementary school that we don't<br>
currently use, and we pay more for materials and so on to home<br>
school our own.<br>
<p>
Somewhere, *somebody* had better benefit from all this.  :}<br>
<p>
Vouchers sound interesting until you see the strings that invariably<br>
seem to trail in their wake.<br>
<p>
Nobody said it was going to be easy...<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
