<title>Oct_1992: Strings Attached (School Choice)</title>
<h1>Strings Attached (School Choice)</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed,  7 Oct 1992 20:46:22 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#33">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#33">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#33">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#33">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0034.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Giving"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0032.html">Steve Hix: "Re: Family Values: School choice"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve Hix mentioned that often if not always voucher money comes with <br>
strings attached.  This is also true of Federal student aid for colleges.<br>
By having federal grants awarded to students studying at a college, that<br>
college is required to meet a long set of nondiscrimination laws.<br>
So far, though, hardly anyone has complained.  The exception is Colin<br>
Standish, former president of Columbia Union College, in his book<br>
Defenders Of the Faith, who claims that making our colleges essentially<br>
tuition-driven and making most students depend on federal aid was quite<br>
a mistake.<br>
<p>
So I repeat my question.  Why is it that college "vouchers" are generally <br>
considered acceptable and elementary and high school vouchers are not?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
