<title>Oct_1992: Re: School choice</title>
<h1>Re: School choice</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>09 Oct 1992 08:36:50 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#35">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#35">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#35">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#35">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0036.html">Computer Science student: "correspondence"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0034.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Giving"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Mime-Version: 1.0<br>
<p>
It's amazing what people will do when it's a necessity rather than an option.<br>
Our tertiary institutions would probably not survive financially if it was<br>
not for government assistance, even if that only comes in the form of allowancesfor students.<br>
<p>
To me, there is no problem accepting government assistance for anything so long<br>
as the strings attached do not force you to do something you don't want to do.<br>
Once this starts to happen, then you can stop accepting the money, and in the<br>
meantime you've benefited.<br>
<p>
The most interesting case at the moment is in New Zealand, where the entire<br>
church administration is in financial trouble. Our two biggest secondary<br>
schools over there are seriously threatened with closure, and to survive<br>
they are having to amalgamate with the state school system. This quote comes<br>
from "Record", our South Pacific Division magazine.<br>
<p>
     Integration of New Zealand Adventist schools with the government<br>
     school system appears a reality. By 1993 Auckland Adventist High<br>
     School and Hawkes Bay Adventist Primary School will be integrated.<br>
     A "Statement of Special Character" is being prepared ensuring the<br>
     schools will not lose their Adventist orientation while receiving<br>
     government financial assistance.<br>
           "Record", October 3, 1992, p4<br>
<p>
This scenario is even more frightening than simply accepting government<br>
money. Those who constructed this scheme must have worked out things like<br>
who will hire and fire, who will be on the school board and so on. All the<br>
same, it is obviously a desperate measure. But as long as the schools retain<br>
their mission and their "Adventist orientation" I suppose it does provide<br>
people with an Adventist education they wouldn't otherwise get.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
