<title>Oct_1992: Family values:  Teaching our children well</title>
<h1>Family values:  Teaching our children well</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri,  9 Oct 1992 09:41:25 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#38">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#38">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#38">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#38">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0039.html">Dan Blake: "Who is Michael the archangel?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0037.html">Dave Thomas: "Conferencing"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0040.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Family values:  Teaching our children well"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In recent years, a new excuse against Christian education has grown in<br>
popularity.  It rises out of a so-called philosophy of parenting which says:<br>
"I'll tell my kids about Jesus and let them go to Sabbath School if they<br>
want, then they can make their own decisions."<br>
<p>
The problem with this philosophy is that it presumes that a neutral<br>
presentation of both sides is enough to make someone love the truth.<br>
In fact, while sometimes this may be enough, other times we can have<br>
problems with this approach.  <br>
<p>
Whatever happened to the model of immersion in the truth, beginning at<br>
home with the parents before school ever starts, and continuing through<br>
family worship all the way through schooling?  Added to this the<br>
reinforcement of Bible classes and a God-centered education in a church<br>
school as well as Sabbath School.  This (if it is executed right, which<br>
it isn't always)<br>
can be the difference between making someone know the truth and love the truth.<br>
<p>
Note that I am not advocating using subterfuge or flawed logic to defend<br>
doctrine, nor am I advocating denying the child any decision-making<br>
power.<br>
But I have seen again and again how superior the approach "come on,<br>
let's go to church" is to "do you want to go to church?"<br>
<p>
How many times do we presume that young people don't want to come to<br>
programs when in fact they are eager to see something happen, and all<br>
that's needed is a little bit of impetus?  How many times do we see<br>
young people drift away<br>
from the church who are not hostile, but neither are they challenged?<br>
I realize all this is easy for me as a non-parent to say.  Does any<br>
parent have a counter-view on this?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
