<title>Oct_1992: Re: Family values:  Teaching our children well</title>
<h1>Re: Family values:  Teaching our children well</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 9 Oct 92 10:21:26 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#40">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#40">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#40">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#40">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0041.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Family values: Teaching our children well"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0039.html">Dan Blake: "Who is Michael the archangel?"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0038.html">Steven Timm: "Family values:  Teaching our children well"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0041.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Family values: Teaching our children well"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Steven Timm writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; In recent years, a new excuse against Christian education has grown in</i><br>
<i>&gt; popularity.  It rises out of a so-called philosophy of parenting which says:</i><br>
<i>&gt; "I'll tell my kids about Jesus and let them go to Sabbath School if they</i><br>
<i>&gt; want, then they can make their own decisions."</i><br>
<p>
This attitude seems predicated upon the notion that kids will basically<br>
turn out OK on their own (similar to secular humanist tho't; similar also<br>
to Jean-Jacques Rousseau and Voltaire in such works as "Emile" and "Candide",<br>
if I recall my French Lit survey class).  However, Scripture tells us that<br>
there is a great controversy going on, with Satan out to destroy your<br>
children, whether physically or spiritually (1Pet 5:8, Is 49:25, et al).<br>
Hence, left to themselves, except some other person prays a hedge of<br>
thorns about them (so to speak; see Hosea), their choices will tend greatly<br>
towards spiritual declension if not disengagement.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Whatever happened to the model of immersion in the truth, beginning at</i><br>
<i>&gt; home with the parents before school ever starts, and continuing through</i><br>
<i>&gt; family worship all the way through schooling?  Added to this the</i><br>
<i>&gt; reinforcement of Bible classes and a God-centered education in a church</i><br>
<i>&gt; school as well as Sabbath School.  This (if it is executed right, which</i><br>
<i>&gt; it isn't always) can be the difference between making someone know the</i><br>
<i>&gt; truth and [them] lov[ing] the truth.</i><br>
<p>
Deut ch 5,6,7 contain a number of relevant texts.  As to why parents<br>
aren't doing the above?  I would suggest their own lack of a deepening<br>
spirituality which, as a consequence, has left them open to being<br>
deceived (2 Thess 2:11 and its context; Gal 6:7).  I have observed<br>
how my own failings can affect the spiritual tone of the whole family.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; [...] not hostile, but neither are they challenged?</i><br>
<p>
Philip Samaan, a few years ago, faced a rowdy youth group at a campmeeting.<br>
How the group turned around was the topic of a presentation that he made<br>
at Redwood Campmeeting a few years ago.  I was not there, but was told about<br>
it:  Relational Bible study (I think Samaan has a book out on this).<br>
<p>
I would also make a plug for Bill Gothard's Basic Youth Conflicts seminars<br>
as they directly address these issues.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  On Attitude &amp; the Immune System:  A sound heart is the life of the flesh:
    but envy the rottenness of the bones.  Prov 14:30
</pre>
