In Fred's reply he suggested the material of Bill Gothard's Institute<br>
In Basic Youth Conflicts. I am surprised for several reasons.<br>
<p>
1)  I thought that this group was essentially out of business now, the <br>
damage having been caused when Bill's own son rebelled against him.  Are <br>
they still actually giving seminars?<br>
<p>
2)  The view of "chain of command" as he presents it is in my opinion<br>
not Biblically based, but rather designed to enforce in the minds of parents<br>
with problems that they must be right after all.  In other words, he <br>
makes his money by telling troubled parents what they want to hear.<br>
<p>
3)  He damaged his credibility seriously by making a number of false<br>
accusations against Christian recording artists.<br>
<p>
Gothard is part of the Christian parapsychology which arose in the 70's<br>
and early 80's, baptizing worldly concepts and clinging to them when the <br>
world of psychology had long since abandoned them because research had<br>
shown them to be false.  <br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
G<br>
