<title>Oct_1992: Michael the archangel</title>
<h1>Michael the archangel</h1>
Ian Brown (<i>Malachi.Robertson@lambada.oit.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 11 Oct 92 13:09:57 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#42">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#42">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#42">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#42">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0043.html">Steven Timm: "Family Values:  Religion in public life"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0041.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Family values: Teaching our children well"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0052.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Michael the archangel"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
First let's look at what archangel means.  It appears twice in the New<br>
Testament.  Once in relation to the voice heard at the second coming and<br>
the other time in relation to Michael fighting Satan over Moses body.<br>
It is composed from the verb ARKHO and the noun AGGELOS.  Literally it<br>
means chief messenger or first of the messengers where the ARKH- has the<br>
implication of rulership.  Michael comes from the Hebrew and I gather asks<br>
the question "Who [is] like God?"  Typically Adventists have considered<br>
Micheal to a be a reference to Jesus.  Just judging from the usage and<br>
meaning of archangel and from Micheal being called prince (in a similar<br>
meaning to that of ARKH-) and the only angel to be called such (as far as<br>
I know), I would agree with this opinion.  Again, if it hasn't been made<br>
clear from the above the Bible portrays one archangel and calls him Michael.<br>
Also, I should note that in Revelation we see Michael and his angels<br>
versus Satan and his angels.  I see this as significant.  Anyway...<br>
<p>
Ian.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
