<title>Oct_1992: Family Values:  Religion in public life</title>
<h1>Family Values:  Religion in public life</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 11 Oct 1992 14:12:57 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#43">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#43">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#43">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#43">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0044.html">Steven Timm: "Holy Spirit and Holy Flesh"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0042.html">Ian Brown: "Michael the archangel"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0059.html">Trevor: "Re: Family Values: Religion in public life"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have just been on the losing end of a battle which is causing me to <br>
rethink ideas of separation of church and state, and the wider issues<br>
of if separation is really the best way to go.<br>
<p>
The non-denominational Gospel Choir at Carnegie Mellon, of which I once <br>
was a member, was called before the Student Senate for review of their <br>
funding status.  It seems that in its bylaws the Student Senate prohibits<br>
funding of religious organizations.  <br>
<p>
At first the complaints centered around some supposed complaints by an<br>
anonymous former member of the group that "everyone was trying to<br>
convert her" but through the course of the debate it became clear that<br>
some people who were leading the charge were upset that religious songs<br>
were being sung on campus at all.  <br>
<p>
In the end, it was decided to broaden the definition of religious group to <br>
include the gospel choir, and to deny them funding.  <br>
<p>
I could give more details, but my point is that this experience has shown me <br>
that the PC-left is not my friend.  These types are all over university<br>
campuses.  They preach diversity and freedom of speech and religion, but<br>
when the rubber meets the road they have no respect for either.  The strong<br>
influence of the feminist movement and the pro-choice movement have lead<br>
to the strong undercurrent that religion is not Politically Correct.  <br>
And when religious expression is curtailed, anti-religious expression<br>
is by default promoted.  There is no reason to assume that any of the <br>
three presidential candidates will be a defender of religious liberty.<br>
<p>
In the 1960's, Adventists were fond of saying that JFK was going to bring<br>
in the pope and cause the time of trouble.  (Although JFK's record on <br>
church-state issues was probably better than any president who has<br>
followed him.)  In 1976, there was alarm that Carter and his flock of<br>
Southern Baptists would change everything.  In the early 1980's there<br>
was paranoia<br>
that Reagan, who had promised so much to the Moral Majority, would soon <br>
bring on the Time of Trouble.  There would have been more if not for the fact<br>
that Reagan's ideology conformed well to most of mid-America conservative<br>
Adventism who worry most about these things.<br>
<p>
People who say SDA's shouldn't be concerned with partisan politics are <br>
ignoring some factors.  In S. Africa in 1988, SDA's (very nonpolitical there)<br>
mostly sat out the election.  In the small district near our college,<br>
Denis Worall, a would-be leader of the opposition, lost by fewer than <br>
500 votes, against one of the apartheid government's chief ministers.<br>
The SDA vote could have been a key force in changing S. Africa.<br>
<p>
In America, especially in a close election, it can be too, and we need<br>
to be informed.  I have made the assertion that none of the three<br>
candidates is <br>
necessarily a friend to religious liberty.  But I don't have much to<br>
back that up.  If people have information on the religious liberty<br>
stands of the <br>
candidates, or other issues which are of interest to SDA's, please let<br>
us know.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
