<!-- inreplyto="" -->
<title>Oct_1992: Holy Spirit and Holy Flesh</title>
<h1>Holy Spirit and Holy Flesh</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 11 Oct 1992 14:26:32 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#44">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#44">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#44">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#44">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0045.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Holy Spirit and Holy Flesh"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0043.html">Steven Timm: "Family Values:  Religion in public life"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0045.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Holy Spirit and Holy Flesh"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
When SDA's attempt to analyze the modern phenomena which are commonly <br>
associated by Pentecostal churches as signs of the Holy Spirit, <br>
we have to look back through the filter of history to one specific <br>
incident which comprises most of Ellen White's writing on the topic,<br>
this being the Holy Flesh movement of 1900 in Indiana.<br>
<p>
We spoke quite a bit about the theology of this movement last month<br>
in the "Translation Faith" discussion.  The theology is not heard much <br>
anymore, although the attempted offshoot in Pennsylvania just recently<br>
was spouting some of it.  However, the methods of this movement are <br>
still very much used by Pentecostal churches today (as far as I know.)<br>
<p>
They made much use of instruments, including drums, in their services, <br>
particularly near the end of the service.  They called the experience<br>
"crossing the Jordan", because a person would pass out under the intense<br>
emotional pressure, then the drums would beat and the music would play<br>
until they came to sometime later.  <br>
<p>
Although the theological meaning attached to it is quite different,<br>
the phenomenon seems to be quite similar to todays's "getting slain<br>
in the Spirit."  I have never watched such a procedure, nor do I <br>
particularly wish to,.  I've not heard of such an incident happening<br>
in any Adventist churches (except once at the Seminary chapel when a <br>
visiting Baptist choir came to visit and brought their preacher along with.)<br>
Unfortunately Allen Roy has left the net so we have no Celebration Church<br>
correspondent to tell us whether or not it is happening there.<br>
<p>
I have no evidence that such a procedure is Biblical.  But has anyone ever<br>
seen it happen, or can anyone give us more light on this topic and the<br>
related phenomena?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
