<title>Oct_1992: Bill Gothard, etc.</title>
<h1>Bill Gothard, etc.</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 11 Oct 92 14:25:51 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#51">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#51">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#51">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#51">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0052.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Michael the archangel"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0050.html">Raylene: "Just a quick enquiry re Standish"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I attended the Bill Gothard's conference in Long Beach, California about<br>
10 years ago.  I found his focus on scripture study and personal prayer<br>
very helpful.  However, I personally had a difficult time with the idea<br>
that until I married and had a husband to be my "umbrella of protection",<br>
I should live with my parents with my father fulfilling this role.  This<br>
was his teaching for all single adult women.  The other thing that bothered<br>
me about his approach to spiritual things was that it seemed like "cookbook<br>
spirituality" to me.  He had a "recipe" for everything.  Just follow these<br>
n steps everything will be fine.  He had steps for everything.  If you're<br>
depressed, you probably need to confess a wrong you did years ago as a teen.<br>
If you have conflict with family, you need to confess your lack of respect<br>
to your parents.  BTW.  This doesn't work.  Confessing a lack of respect<br>
for a parent doesn't help you respect them and now they KNOW you don't<br>
because you've told them.<br>
<p>
I had a physician friend who really believed in Bill Gothard's approach.<br>
The idea that he was the "umbrella of protection (i.e. authority)" for<br>
his physician wife broke up his marriage.  He believed he was to be the<br>
final say on everything in his home and would not allow his intelligent<br>
and spiritual wife feel that she could think for herself.  Any doctrine<br>
that delegates personal responsibility to a male figure (father or husband),<br>
can't possibly be the Lord's way.<br>
<p>
BTW.  Bill Gothard was single.  When did he get married and have a son?<br>
I think we should be careful about pointing to one's children and making<br>
a statement about one's credibility based on their childrens' actions.<br>
Remember that George Vandeman's son tried to kill him by stabbing and<br>
has spent years in a mental institution.  Several other prominent SDA<br>
evangelists or church leaders raised some raunchy kids.  In the Bible we<br>
have the prodigal son, Absolom (son of King David), the sons of Jacob<br>
who sold Joseph into slavery.  How about the parents of Cain, the first<br>
murderer who talked with God face to face before the fall?  Esau, the son<br>
of Jacob, was trying to kill his brother, Jacob.  I think the Scriptures<br>
are full of stories of children who didn't turn out as they should.  This<br>
is a lesson to all parents.  That many times spiritual parents raise very<br>
ungodly children.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0052.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Michael the archangel"</a>
