<title>Oct_1992: Re: Family values: Teaching our children well</title>
<h1>Re: Family values: Teaching our children well</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 12 Oct 92 11:12:20 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#54">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#54">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#54">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#54">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0055.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Michael, Jesus, and God the Father"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0053.html">cheryl berthelsen: "RE:  Bill Gothard"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0041.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Family values: Teaching our children well"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Steven Timm writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; 1)  I thought that this group was essentially out of business now, the </i><br>
<i>&gt; damage having been caused when Bill's own son rebelled against him.  Are </i><br>
<i>&gt; they still actually giving seminars?</i><br>
<p>
Between my wife and I, we have attended IBLP seminars fairly regularly<br>
since 1973.  The incidence in 1980 that may be in your mind is when there<br>
were problems with one of Bill's brothers (as someone else mentioned, Bill<br>
has never been married).  Bill stepped out of IBLP (previously known as IBYC)<br>
presentations for one year in order to minister to his family's needs.<br>
As for being out of business, quite the contrary: IBLP seminar attendance<br>
is growing by leaps and bounds; seminars have recently been given in<br>
Australia, New Zealand, Europe and Russia.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; 2)  The view of "chain of command" as he presents it is in my opinion</i><br>
<i>&gt; not Biblically based, but rather designed to enforce in the minds of parents</i><br>
<i>&gt; with problems that they must be right after all.</i><br>
<p>
Given the fairly large body of relevant Scripture on authority, I have<br>
difficulty agreeing with you.  Can you suggest another Scriptural model?<br>
<p>
We should remember to give him the same space for growth that we would<br>
like for ourselves.  For perhaps the first 10 years of seminars, "chain<br>
of command" stood alone and probably rubbed some people the wrong way.<br>
Since around 1978, the Basic Seminar includes material on making appeals<br>
to authority (and ultimately God; see Prov 21:1) which balances the<br>
material on authority.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; 3)  He damaged his credibility seriously by making a number of false</i><br>
<i>&gt; accusations against Christian recording artists.</i><br>
<p>
I'm not sure what you have in mind, but my personal experience and<br>
observations make me inclined to agree with him re rock music.  I have his<br>
materials on rock and would be willing to post them (they are free of<br>
copyright) so that folk can make their own judgements.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Gothard is part of the Christian parapsychology which arose in the 70's</i><br>
<i>&gt; and early 80's, baptizing worldly concepts and clinging to them when the </i><br>
<i>&gt; world of psychology had long since abandoned them because research had</i><br>
<i>&gt; shown them to be false.  </i><br>
<p>
I'll take the Word of God over the word of man any day; "proofs" from<br>
psychology research do not carry much weight with me.  Here and there they<br>
may stumble across some truth, but, in general, they are foolish (in the<br>
sense of Proverbs).  Rom 8:7a is a law and a truism.  One's morality<br>
practically dictates one's theology/philosophy; a lot of the "psych"<br>
greats were really messed up, into spiritism, etc.  (EGW has some very<br>
pointed comments about these guys.)<br>
<p>
I do not always agree with Gothard (e.g., eschatology) but have always<br>
found his ideas to be based upon Scripture (i.e., I may differ over<br>
interpretation or feel that other relevant verses, when taken as a whole,<br>
lead to a different conclusion).  I cannot agree with "baptizing worldly<br>
concepts", sorry.<br>
<p>
The vast majority of Christians (even SDA's 8-) I know who have attended<br>
have expressed their appreciation for Gothard's seminars.  I would encourage<br>
critics to hold their peace until they have attended at least the Basic<br>
Seminar.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  On Attitude &amp; the Immune System:  A sound heart is the life of the flesh:
    but envy the rottenness of the bones.  Prov 14:30
</pre>
