<title>Oct_1992: Michael, Jesus, and God the Father</title>
<h1>Michael, Jesus, and God the Father</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 12 Oct 1992 18:35:12 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#55">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#55">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#55">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#55">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0056.html">Ian Brown: "inquiry"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0054.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Family values: Teaching our children well"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Recently my uncle, a SDA Theology scholar, told me he has come to the<br>
conclusion that Jesus the Son is also God the Father--they are One person.<br>
They seems to be considerable Scriptural evidence to back up this conclusion.<br>
Do all SDAs believe this or do you believe differently?<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<p>
<p>
[I have never heard this view expressed by an SDA theologian before, unless<br>
it was very early SDA stuff before the church came around to the mainline<br>
doctrine of the Trinity.  I certainly don't believe that myself, and <br>
it contradicts the Statement of Fundamental Beliefs.  There is, however,<br>
some very interesting Bible study surrounding the topic, and I had planned<br>
to bring it up myself later this month.  If anyone has any insight, <br>
please share.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
