<title>Oct_1992: Re: Home-schooling</title>
<h1>Re: Home-schooling</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 12 Oct 92 10:30:22 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#58">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#58">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#58">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#58">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0059.html">Trevor: "Re: Family Values: Religion in public life"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0057.html">Cam Litvin: "Bill Gothard"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0046.html">Raylene: "Home-schooling"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0081.html">Eric Snyder: "Re: Home-schooling"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Our personal experience with home schooling is that it is the best<br>
option available for those who have that option.<br>
<p>
I recall a radio host interviewing the author of a book on how their<br>
family had home schooled.  They home schooled all the way up through<br>
highschool.  The idea was to go to college to get acredited for what<br>
they had learned.  The biggest problem their children had was that<br>
college was too easy.  The author explained that in public school<br>
(somewhat similar in church school) teachers are so bogged down with<br>
required paper work and large classes that its easy for a mediocre<br>
parent to out perform a top notch teacher in terms of the benefit<br>
to the individual student.<br>
<p>
Another story, of a girl home schooling.  The local school district<br>
threatened them . . . . came up with the idea of testing her and<br>
if she fell below expectations for 4th grade, she would have to<br>
go to public school.  She scored as being 6th grade proficient.  So,<br>
the school district insisted she had to be placed in public school<br>
in order to take their excelleration problem so she could excellerate<br>
to 6th grade where they felt she belonged according to the test<br>
scores.<br>
<p>
We have not done home school on a steady basis.  A year here and there.<br>
Our boys have done remarkably better the year following home school.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; What is the attitude towards home-schooling? Is it generally viewed as a</i><br>
<i>&gt; positive move by SDAs? Or are there some questions about its benefit?</i><br>
<p>
We get most of our flack from one of the retired pastors in our church<br>
and some from the pastor.  Some of our pastors have filed away very<br>
strong sermons on sending your children to church school instead of<br>
public school and they have a hard time seeing the difference between<br>
home school and public school.  But frankly, I place home school, if<br>
its an option, as the top most of choices.  I have yet to find anything<br>
in EGW to contradict that, rather her strong endorsement.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
