<title>Oct_1992: Re: Family Values: Religion in public life</title>
<h1>Re: Family Values: Religion in public life</h1>
Trevor (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 13 Oct 1992 00:37:27 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#59">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#59">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#59">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#59">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0060.html">Steven Timm: "101 members now"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0058.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Home-schooling"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0043.html">Steven Timm: "Family Values:  Religion in public life"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I must make a reply to Steve's reporting of what happened at Carnegie<br>
Mellon University regarding the Gospel Choir and funding, in order to<br>
clarify the issue--I believe that it is now slightly obscurred.  <br>
<p>
It was reported in the university paper (The Tartan) that the VUGC<br>
(Voices United Gospel Choir) would be deprived of its funding until<br>
further review on the religoius nature of the organization.  A student<br>
senator leading the charge, was quoted as saying that he did not want to<br>
fund anything on campus that would be offensive to others.  This was<br>
obviously faulty logic; a logic that really should not exist on a<br>
university campus promoting freedom of expression  and exploration.  <br>
Steve Timm made a reply to the paper pointing out the ridiculousness of<br>
what this student senator had said (basically showing that anything<br>
could be considered as offensive and therefore nothing funded).  In the<br>
same paper the senator retracted his statement as to WHY the VUGC should<br>
not be funded, and gave more of the history of the VUGC and the events<br>
precipitating the action (in reality, I think he was rather embarrassed<br>
about what he said realizing its implication).<br>
<p>
Apparently, the student senate has a set of bylaws that does not fund<br>
ANY religious or political organization.  These organizations are not<br>
barred from existing, they just cannot receive senate funding.  Further,<br>
it was reported to the student senate that the VUGC was essentially<br>
operating as a front for evangalizing people to christianity, NOT merely<br>
singing gospel music.  Albeit there are student senators who would like<br>
to get rid of VUGC just because it does sing christian music, the basis<br>
for the senate's action was that it was not just merely singing but<br>
envangelizing.<br>
<p>
The logic of their argument is that if they fund VUGC, they could not<br>
refuse to fund the KKK, College Democrats, College Republicans (no<br>
implication that any of these are related) etc.  <br>
<p>
It should be noted that the paper wrote an editorial against the senate<br>
on how this matter was handled and asked them to clarify issues with<br>
student organizations and to fully investigate charges against a student<br>
organization instead of freezing funds immediately on an unsubstantiated<br>
accusation only. There has been an investigation but I don't know what<br>
the outcome was.  Steve seems to have been closer to this.  <br>
<p>
 From the senate's position as I understand it, VUGC can maintain its<br>
funding ONLY if it shows that it is SINGING gospel music and not using<br>
the occasion to practice christianity or evangelize.  For some people,<br>
these go hand in hand, but it IS possible to sing gospel music solely<br>
for its musicalness and not as a tool for conversion.<br>
<p>
Steve states that many who led the charge against VUGC didn't even like<br>
the fact that the songs were christian, and THAT was their basis. <br>
However, I don't think this was the reason why the senate stopped the<br>
funding.<br>
<p>
Steve's conclustion that PCer's are not his friend is true.  His<br>
conclusion that the student senate fits this category I think is false.  <br>
<p>
<p>
--Trevor<br>
Carnegie Mellon University<br>
<p>
----------------<br>
[Since I'm reading this post from Fermilab and have not yet seen <br>
the issue of the Tartan Trevor refers to, I have to take his word for it.<br>
All I knew was that funding was cut off, I didn't know exactly why.  SCT]<br>
