<title>Oct_1992: Re: Family Values: Religion in public life</title>
<h1>Re: Family Values: Religion in public life</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 13 Oct 92 00:41:35 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#62">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#62">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#62">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#62">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0063.html">Raylene: "Different people in our churches"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0061.html">Glen Pringle: "Re: 101 members now"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0069.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Family Values: Religion in public life"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Here at University of Wisconsin, we have an interesting situation.  State<br>
law prohibits the existance of student associations which are political in<br>
nature but religious associations are totally acceptable.  At the Student<br>
Union on any given day, there may be a meeting of Lutheran, Baptist, LDS,<br>
Catholic, Unitarian, or Muslim students.  The only requirement is that the<br>
student association be "registered" with Office of Student Life and at<br>
least four legitimate student names and addresses be included on the form.<br>
Rooms in the Student Union may be reserved for use by any registered<br>
student club or association.  People from the community may attend and<br>
clubs are prohibited from discriminating in who can attend a meeting.  The<br>
LDSSA (LDS student Association) welcomes anyone who wants to attend.  We're<br>
studying the Writings of Luke and meet every Tuesday Noon.  Does the<br>
University "fund" this activity?  No, but we do get free use of a meeting<br>
room.  What is the situation at your state university?<br>
<p>
cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
