<title>Oct_1992: Different people in our churches</title>
<h1>Different people in our churches</h1>
Raylene (<i>CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>13 Oct 1992 16:21:39 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#63">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#63">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#63">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#63">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0064.html">Tony: "Re: Home Schooling"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0062.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Re: Family Values: Religion in public life"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Mime-Version: 1.0<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;We have mentally ill person who</i><br>
<i>&gt;has been attending some of our Sabbath services and has been disturbing</i><br>
<i>&gt;some of the people, particularlly at pot luck.  </i><br>
<i>&gt;Ian.</i><br>
<p>
Avondale College, being in a rural location, finds itself in the area of<br>
a couple of homes for the mentally ill. There have been a number of people<br>
from these homes, over the years, who have found Avondale College to be a<br>
nice place to be (things always happening socially etc etc). And they have <br>
often been seen at church.<br>
<p>
One looks as though he has suffered burns to his face at one time. He is<br>
often seen wandering the streets and came to early church (run before Sabbath<br>
School) quite consistently. He also turned up to Friday night meetings with<br>
all the students and once gave a very touching testimony.<br>
<p>
Another paced consistently around outside the church mumbling to himself in<br>
a cloud of cigarette smoke (that probably was the most off-putting bit). He<br>
also came inside the church (didn't smoke there fortunately) and when there<br>
was no program on could be seen pacing the aisles mumbling hail mary's to<br>
himself and asking when was mass to be performed.<br>
<p>
The third is a very large guy (though not so tall) who rolls his R's very<br>
strongly. He is very friendly and has been known to start walking at 8:00am<br>
to church functions in the bush. He frequently attends the church fellowship<br>
lunch and eats phenomenal amounts of food. He has also recently been baptised<br>
and included by some of the church members - given little jobs to do so he<br>
can feel involved.<br>
<p>
As a woman I want to keep away because I don't know what to do when they<br>
look at my top shirt button instead of my eyes.<br>
As a *Christian* I feel impelled to accept these people and be friendly to <br>
them. Others have obviously made the effort.<br>
In reality I have done nothing. Then I feel that the King's banquet is for<br>
them and not for me!?<br>
<p>
Is there an answer?<br>
<p>
Raylene<br>
---*---<br>
CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au<br>
---*---<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
