<title>Oct_1992: Re: Home Schooling</title>
<h1>Re: Home Schooling</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>13 Oct 1992 17:19:38 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#64">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#64">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#64">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#64">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0065.html">patricio d navia: "Re: 101 members now"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0063.html">Raylene: "Different people in our churches"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0133.html">Dan Hamstra: "Home Schooling"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0122.html">Russell Yonkers: "Re: Home Schooling"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Mime-Version: 1.0<br>
<p>
Isn't it interesting that SDAs like to criticize educational<br>
institutions for their emphasis on book learning, while at the<br>
same time the benefits of home schooling are discussed in terms<br>
of academic performance.<br>
<p>
I'm not having a go at anyone here, because I certainly believe<br>
that aspect is important. However my personal concerns with home<br>
schooling are more in the area of socialization.<br>
<p>
Now there is an argument that says we don't want our children<br>
socialized into modern Western culture. I can see the point in<br>
trying to ensure that as they grow up the adopt the appropriate<br>
values, and that many of these are not widely held today.<br>
<p>
I am not confident that after years of home schooling a person<br>
would really know how to relate to their peer group, or even to<br>
the general public as a whole. This to me is a serious factor,<br>
and is almost enough to convince me that I am not in favour of<br>
home schooling.<br>
<p>
The idea of home schooling interleaved with regular schooling<br>
would negate this to a large degree, and I was interested to<br>
read about that. I myself was home-schooled for one year only,<br>
and although I felt "out of it" with my peers, I survived due<br>
to already being a member of a social group, and going back<br>
to school the year after.<br>
<p>
Surely anything EGW had to say on home schooling would have to<br>
be read with the understanding that it was written under very<br>
different social conditions. Modern education is very different<br>
to that of the Victorian era, and modern lifestyles are very<br>
different as well. Didn't many students in those days end up<br>
living at school instead of with their families? Having<br>
a child living at home, attending a Christian school for a few<br>
hours a day, and the rest of the time being under the direct <br>
influence of Godly parents, seems to fit with EGWs ideas on a<br>
worthwhile education.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
