<title>Oct_1992: The Trinity</title>
<h1>The Trinity</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>13 Oct 1992 17:02:03 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#66">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#66">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#66">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#66">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0067.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Mental Illness &amp; the Church"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0065.html">patricio d navia: "Re: 101 members now"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Mime-Version: 1.0<br>
<p>
Personally I see the doctrine of the trinity as yet another situation<br>
where God is trying to explain something to me that I cannot possibly<br>
understand. He is giving me a simple description of some aspects of his<br>
being, simple enough to be meaningful to my limited mind.<br>
<p>
I think it is more important to ask "what does the doctrine of the<br>
trinity have to say" than to make statements about whether God is<br>
"really" made up of three distinct components. One important thing<br>
that the doctrine says, for example, is that Jesus is God.<br>
<p>
We're setting ourselves up for a certain amount of embarrassment on<br>
the day that we see these things for ourselves if we try to make too<br>
much of it at this stage.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
