<title>Oct_1992: Mental Illness &amp; the Church</title>
<h1>Mental Illness &amp; the Church</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 13 Oct 92 14:37:12 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#67">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#67">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#67">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#67">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0068.html">Richard Guy: "Re: Antartica"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0066.html">Tony: "The Trinity"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0070.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: Mental Illness &amp; the Church"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I was interested in the comments about mentally ill attending church services<br>
and sometimes bothering people.  Mental Illness is still misunderstood by<br>
most Christians and there seems to be the tendency to exclude them, avoid<br>
them, and keep them from bothering others.  At the Wasatch Hills SDA Church<br>
in Salt Lake City (where I attended before I converted to Mormonism), we<br>
have several "strange" individuals who attended regularly.  One was a<br>
"homeless" person who begged on the streets during the week and then attended<br>
SDA church services on Saturday.  If it was a potluck day, he didn't miss!<br>
Another was a very outspoken and perhap "obnoxious" soul who would contantly<br>
interrupt the Sabbath School lesson with extraneous remarks and inappropriate<br>
comments.  Yet the church never discouraged them from coming and in fact<br>
provided transportation for them to attend.<br>
<p>
I have a sister who has been committed to state mental institutions many times<br>
and for the past 5 years has been in a board and care facility for the<br>
mentally ill.  She attended Church with my parents every week.  Her clothes<br>
smelled of cigarette smoke and sometimes she would walk out to the parking<br>
lot to have a smoke during services and return to sit by my parents.  All<br>
out lives, we sibs tried hard to conceal the problem.  I remember refusing<br>
to sit with my family as an adult because I felt ashamed and embarrassed.<br>
She didn't always disturb the class but sometimes she would make a weird<br>
comment.  If there was punch and cookies after services, she would go to<br>
the table and stuff her purse with cookies to take home for her "friends"<br>
at the home where she lived.  We tried very hard to "control" her but to<br>
no avail.  Yet my father felt very committed to her and always went to<br>
pick her up to attend services.  Through this experience and the great<br>
love my own parents had for my sister, I have witnessed what God's love<br>
must be like.  How repulsive our sin and selfishness must be to our Elder<br>
Brother!  Yet He does not withdraw from us.  He cradles us in His arms of<br>
love and identifies with fallen man.<br>
<p>
I have a much more philosophical view now of the purpose of church<br>
attendence and what to do about disturbances in church.  The elderly<br>
resent young children and babies crying and many members don't know what<br>
to do about "strange and different" people.  Isn't it selfish for us to<br>
feel that the services are there for our personal spiritual benefit?  My<br>
sister rarely had meaningful contacts during the week.  Yet she knew that<br>
on Sabbath, she could enjoy spiritual music, love and understanding from<br>
Christians, and hear the Word of God.  It meant so much to her that she<br>
would walk 5 miles to attend if my parents where out of town.  The mentally<br>
ill are the downtrodden of this society.  They are "loathsome" than common<br>
criminals.  Yet they did nothing to deserve this from society.  They were<br>
born with a physical defect in their brains which cause the bizarre and<br>
repugnant behavior.  I think the mercy and kindness Jesus Christ showed<br>
to Lepers and Demoniacs should demonstrate how we are to treat the<br>
schizophrenics and manic-depressives of this earth.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
