<title>Oct_1992: Thoughts on the Trinity Paradox</title>
<h1>Thoughts on the Trinity Paradox</h1>
Dave Thomas (<i>umsfdtho@deimos.oscs.montana.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 13 Oct 92 18:16:10 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#72">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#72">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#72">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#72">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0073.html">Tim Swensen: "Religious Organizations at Public Universities"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0071.html">Computer Science student: "Re: Light Bearers"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0076.html">Tony: "Re: Thoughts on the Trinity Paradox"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On the concept of a Trinity:<br>
<p>
As strange as it may seem, I think that an understanding of the<br>
Trinity paradox cannot be achieved without the aid of mathematics.<br>
Anyone who has read Flatland by Edwin Abbott will know what I mean.<br>
<p>
The Bible seems to be trying to teach us to think of God as Three<br>
Persons: Father, Son, and Holy Spirit.  At the same time, it is clear<br>
that these Three think of Themselves as One Person.  Under what<br>
circumstances would that dichotomy of perspectives makes sense?<br>
<p>
An analogy will help set the stage for my answer.  Imagine that you<br>
discovered a two dimensional universe (flat ... like a sheet of paper)<br>
in which shadow-like beings moved about under your gaze.  At a glance,<br>
you could see both their outsides (perimeters) and their insides<br>
(interiors).  You would have a God-like perspective on their world<br>
and, by approaching from above (a notion that the flatlanders could<br>
never comprehend), you could appear and disappear by "touching down" at <br>
various points in their universe.  You could also remain invisible by<br>
hovering above their plane.  You could do surgery without cutting<br>
through their skins (perimeters).  You could work miracles.<br>
<p>
Suppose that you set down three fingers in their world.  From their<br>
point of view, each finger would look like a different "being".  From<br>
your point of view, it's just one hand.  The thing is a 3-dimensional<br>
hand is beyong their powers of imagination, being 2-dimensional<br>
creatures.<br>
<p>
Reasoning by analogy (always dangerous), suppose that God is a <br>
4 or higher dimensional Being.  Compared to Him, we would be as<br>
insubstantial as the 2-dimensional shadows would appear to us.  He<br>
could perform miracles by virtue of His higher dimensionality.  And,<br>
from His point of view, God is One, while to us, They are Three.<br>
<p>
I have no idea whether God is indeed a 4 or higher dimensional Being.<br>
All I am saying is that the kinds of miracles reported in the Bible<br>
and the statements God makes about Himself are consistent with such<br>
a model.  And if He is as I think, a higher dimensional Being, then even<br>
in eternity, we will be mere shadows of His glory.  <br>
<p>
For interested readers, I do recommend Flatland.  It's easy reading<br>
by a 19th century mathematics teacher and theologian at a London<br>
teacher's college.  You can find it in most libraries.<br>
<p>
Dave Thomas<br>
Montana State University<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
