<title>Oct_1992: Re:  Making the church safe</title>
<h1>Re:  Making the church safe</h1>
Paul Johnston (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 15 Oct 1992 11:40:08 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#77">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#77">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#77">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#77">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0078.html">Raylene: "Different people in our churches"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0076.html">Tony: "Re: Thoughts on the Trinity Paradox"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Paul Johnston reporting<br>
<p>
<p>
PITTSBURGH--This network has had some discussion on a reported incident at <br>
Shadyside SDA Church in Pittsburgh.  No one who's written about it so far was<br>
 there at the time.  For those of you who've followed the correspondence, here <br>
are some additional facts from one who was there.<br>
<p>
<p>
The church board was consulted by the senior pastor of Shadyside several weeks<br>
 in advance of the proposed date with the choir.  He carefully made no <br>
recommendation.  He asked the board to discuss and vote on the return of these <br>
regular visitors.  (By the way, it's almost impossible to get Blue Mountain <br>
Academy or Columbia Union College to send groups here.)  Shadyside's board is <br>
a highly representative body, cutting across the congregation's diverse <br>
subsets.  On the<br>
 whole, the board is more cautious and conservative than the pastoral staff.<br>
<p>
<p>
I was at that board meeting.  It was a unanimous decision to invite <br>
Shippenburg's musicians back.  The pastor, surprised I think, asked again if <br>
everyone realised that this meant the drums and electric bass would be back <br>
too.  Yes, the board knew that.  Some members said that, though the music <br>
wasn't always to their taste, that was no reason to be ungrateful.  A year <br>
before, when the choir brought a similar program, no one had raised a scene.<br>
  The board did not anticipate one this time either.<br>
<p>
<p>
True enough, the makeup of the congregation hadn't changed much in a year.  <br>
But what was underestimated by the board was the potential behavior by one <br>
new arrival, a former pastor.  He--his presence, his personality, his tactics-<br>
-was the one and only significantly different factor.<br>
<p>
<p>
It has been reported elsewhere on this network that some of the congregation's<br>
 younger members were seeking to consider disfellowshipping this ex-pastor<br>
 (back in Pittsburgh after being booted out of another conference). <br>
[Paul supplied an alternate wording for the following sentences at my request<br>
SCT]<br>
In contrast to one of our previous correspondents, I have not heard young <br>
adults--or old--discussing disfellowship; however, I have heard mention of <br>
censorship, a somewhat different action, among church members.<br>
<p>
One correspondent wrote that it's "our duty to affirm this man as our brother"<br>
 and that there must be "some way to open a channel of communication with him.<br>
"  The pastoral staff and board have gone the extra mile to try and do just <br>
that.  But the attempt has been frustrated.  Speaking personally, as Sabbath <br>
School superintendent, I reached out.  When he returned to Pittsburgh, he was <br>
obviously a hurting man.  My wife and I entertained him and his wife in our <br>
home.  With my encouragement and the blessings of the pastors and board, the <br>
Sabbath School Council invited him to be one of our Sabbath School class <br>
teachers.  We felt he needed something positive and constructive to do.  He <br>
has gone on to use that forum for critical and undermining work with a small <br>
(and diminishing) group of people.  The biggest concern of all those I know is<br>
 that he's about to self-destruct.<br>
<p>
<p>
The ex-pastor's behavior is not exclusively, or even initially, the concern of<br>
 young adult members.  The board is about one-third young adults.  But the <br>
dismay and disillusionment with this man is all-inclusive.  The flap over the <br>
music was not and is not a young versus old issue.  It's not a liberal versus<br>
 conservative issue.  For example, most of Shadyside's symphony-goers are from<br>
 the young professional subset.  Young adults on the board have, in fact, been<br>
 among the most critical about poor management of change--including <br>
Shadyside's liturgical and musical trends.  The folks who feel most <br>
comfortable with what's happening are newer converts, by no means a young <br>
group of people in our case.<br>
<p>
<p>
By the way, this is just one cloud in Shadyside Church's life.  Overall, <br>
miraculous things are happening and many are finding it to be a rewarding <br>
place to be on Saturday mornings.  The community is starting to notice it.  <br>
There have been positive articles in newspapers and a good review of its <br>
services on WQED-FM's "Sunday Arts Magazine."  I think you'd like our<br>
 potlucks too.<br>
<p>
<p>
[The "correspondent" so obliquely referred to by Paul is none other than <br>
myself.  I too wish to make clear that any references to disfellowshipping<br>
were only wishful thinking and no move has been organized to carry that out.<br>
SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
