<title>Oct_1992: Different people in our churches</title>
<h1>Different people in our churches</h1>
Raylene (<i>CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>15 Oct 1992 14:49:52 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#78">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#78">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#78">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#78">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0079.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  Questions on the Trinity"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0077.html">Paul Johnston: "Re:  Making the church safe"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0100.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Homeschool"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;DaveB</i><br>
<i>&gt;Our personal experience with home schooling is that it is the best</i><br>
<i>&gt;option available for those who have that option.</i><br>
<p>
One of the reasons why I questioned home-schooling in the first place was<br>
because of an experience I had while practice teaching a few years ago.<br>
<p>
There was a girl in one of my classes who had not gone to school because her<br>
parents had been caught up in some conservative movement that questioned<br>
the morality and spirituality of both state and SDA schools. When I saw<br>
her she had just begun school against her parents wishes.<br>
<p>
She was a 16 year old girl in a class of 14 year olds. She was a very nice, <br>
cooperative student, and aimed to please.I don't know how she was going in <br>
English or History but I know how she was going in Mathematics and Science:<br>
she had no knowledge of these subjects at a high school level at all.<br>
Her maths teacher was giving her a lot of individual tutoring, starting with<br>
topics from the first year of high school. In science, it was very much the<br>
same. I would be conducting a practical class in science and needed to be<br>
constantly giving her that extra bit of assistance.<br>
<p>
At the time I felt it was very unfair of her parents to put her in that<br>
position at that age. When I was 16 my parents encouraged me towards<br>
academic achievement, and I believed that it was my Christian responsibility<br>
(and a few other things) to work at achieving in school. I felt this girl<br>
had been given an unfair disadvantage. What chance did she have, in one year,<br>
of catching up all that she had missed? And if she couldn't catch up then<br>
her career options would be greatly limited. As a science teacher in training,<br>
and realizing how much I had learned as opposed to how little MY parents knew<br>
on the subject (though I do believe they could pick it up and that content<br>
isn't the be all and end all) I questioned the ability of parents to teach <br>
these subjects. Though my concern was limited more to the topics covered in <br>
the last two years of high-school more than anything prior to that.<br>
<p>
At the same time I thought that her parents may have decided that academic<br>
performance was not what was important in life and what she gained would by<br>
far outweigh what she lost. What good is a good education if it means you<br>
have to forfeit eternal life for instance? <br>
<p>
This may be one of the few disaster stories of homeschooling, I don't know.<br>
But it really got me thinking. <br>
<p>
Obviously schools are not the best places. I know that. I went to school.<br>
But I highly value education, and I feel that if I had not done as I have then<br>
there would be people in the Chemistry Department at the University of<br>
Newcastle that would have less of a contact with Christianity and basically no<br>
contact with Adventism.<br>
<p>
What wisdom have others got to offer on the subject?<br>
<p>
Raylene<br>
---*---<br>
