<title>Oct_1992: The Trinity</title>
<h1>The Trinity</h1>
Eric Snyder (<i>ESNYDER%PSUHMC.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>15 Oct 1992 10:15 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#80">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#80">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#80">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#80">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0081.html">Eric Snyder: "Re: Home-schooling"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0079.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  Questions on the Trinity"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0075.html">Paul Gates: "Re: The Trinity"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
      I have done quite a bit of study on this topic.  The best I understand<br>
    this.  There is but one God.  Not three gods. Not two gods, and certainly<br>
    not many gods as the Mormons believe.  This One God has manifested<br>
    Himself to us in Three persons.  The term person I have heard is not the<br>
    best term to use, but its difficult to come up with one better.  These<br>
    3 persons are distinct.  But all three are fully God.  Each one is not<br>
    1/3 God, but each is fully God.  Many times the Jehovah's Witnesses will<br>
    say "Oh..so was Jesus Praying to Himself in the garden of Gethsemane?"<br>
    Their questions isn't an honest question, but a sort of mockery of the<br>
    orthodox position of the Trinity.  Jesus, the Son ( a distinct ) person<br>
    was praying to His Father ( a distinct person ).  I admit the mystery is<br>
    great, but these 2 distinct personalities are both God.  Not half but,<br>
    fully God.  If we say there are then 2 gods, we then become polytheists.<br>
    The Scriptures teach that there is one, and only one God.  There are three<br>
    persons who are referred to as this One God.<br>
<p>
    Well, I have babbled enough...<br>
    Eric Snyder<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
