<title>Oct_1992: Family Values:  Equal Access</title>
<h1>Family Values:  Equal Access</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 15 Oct 1992 23:40:53 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#83">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#83">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#83">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#83">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0084.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Light Bearers"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0082.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Home Schooling"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
We recently discussed availability of rooms and such on college campuses.<br>
One fact that is not widely known among SDA's is that there is a great<br>
deal of opportunities available on public high school campuses due to the <br>
Equal Access law.  My understanding of that act is that public schools must<br>
allow the same access for church groups in after school hours as they do<br>
for any other group.  This gives opportunities for outreach on high<br>
school campi which by and large are being ignored by our church's youth <br>
leaders (myself included).  <br>
<p>
Closely related to this is the Youth To Youth program.  (Old SDA hacks knew<br>
this as A.Y.B.L.)  Dr. Patricia Mutch of Andrews University has been a <br>
leader in developing the Adventist Youth to Youth program to be a <br>
counterpart of the Youth to Youth program which goes on in public schools.<br>
The chief aims of Youth to Youth are to show that one can have fun and<br>
celebrate in a drug-free lifestyle, and to develop positive peer<br>
pressure. <br>
<p>
The combination of the Youth to Youth program and Listen magazine<br>
provides powerful outreach tools.  I would like to see it happen in my <br>
city, unfortunately the money is often prohibitive to get it going.  <br>
Has anyone had experience with this or other equal-access programs in <br>
the area in which they live?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
