<title>Oct_1992: Re: Home Schooling</title>
<h1>Re: Home Schooling</h1>
Dave Buxton (<i>davidbu@loowit.wr.tek.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 14 Oct 92 10:14:00 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#85">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#85">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#85">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#85">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0086.html">Steven Timm: "Time for a SDAnet digest?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0084.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Light Bearers"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0133.html">Dan Hamstra: "Home Schooling"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0094.html">Tony: "Re: Home Schooling"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; I'm not having a go at anyone here, because I certainly believe</i><br>
<i>&gt; that aspect is important. However my personal concerns with home</i><br>
<i>&gt; schooling are more in the area of socialization.</i><br>
<p>
Our younger son is home schooling 8th grade.  We have two church<br>
schools about equal distance from us.  One school has a somewhat<br>
active home school support program where, for a very reasonable fee,<br>
home schoolers can participate in a wide variety of school activities,<br>
such as field trips to the zoo, science fair, etc.  We made similar<br>
arrangements with the other school so that he can show up for recess any<br>
time he likes, etc.  He is also playing bass clarinet in the academy band.<br>
So, his social life is rather full.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
