<title>Oct_1992: Music for the cultured</title>
<h1>Music for the cultured</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>16 Oct 1992 10:53:24 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#87">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#87">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#87">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#87">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0088.html">Tony: "SDA Forum on Compuserve"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0086.html">Steven Timm: "Time for a SDAnet digest?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I was interested to read the account of the confrontation in the Pittsburgh<br>
church, which seems to have been sparked by the issue of music in worship.<br>
<p>
Having often been involved in organizing, producing and performing music<br>
in my church, I also can vouch for the fact that the music issue is not<br>
a "young Vs old" thing at all, and is not *always* a "liberal Vs conservative"<br>
thing either.<br>
<p>
Recently at Avondale College we had a prominent Australian professional<br>
entertainer, James Morrison, hold a Saturday night concert in the<br>
Auditorium. He is an excellent musician, grew up a Christian, and directed<br>
his performance very much toward the Christian audience present. I was<br>
operating the mixer, not a very taxing job because the quartet wanted<br>
very much an acoustic, "40s"-type sound, and James's brass instruments<br>
hardly required amplification. The program consisted of a mix of gospel<br>
songs and jazz standards, with a vocalist who popped out a couple of times<br>
to sing some hymns. At one stage the audience was most impressed by this<br>
white retired pastor cum jazz musician singing When The Saints, a la Louis<br>
Armstrong.<br>
<p>
Strangely enough, even though I was working, I actually felt at times that<br>
the program had a bit of a spiritual atmosphere. I haven't always felt<br>
like that during College concerts - student "talent" productions are often<br>
such that a prayer at the end almost seems out of place, unfortunately.<br>
<p>
Most people touted this concert as the "concert of the year", with one<br>
notable exception. Someone wrote to the College newsletter, quoting<br>
passages from EGW regarding teachers leading young people astray, and<br>
pointing out the following quote from the church manual.<br>
<p>
     Great care should be exercised in the choice of music. Any melody<br>
     partaking of the nature of jazz, rock, or related hybrid forms, or<br>
     any language expressing foolish or trivial sentiments, will be<br>
     shunned by persons of true culture. Let us use only good music in <br>
     the home, in the social gathering, in the school, and in the church.<br>
         SDA Church Manual, 1990, p146<br>
<p>
Having read this a few times, I can't help feeling that it sounds a bit<br>
like an advertisement for an Apple Macintosh. You know, "Macintosh.<br>
For the power user with true culture." Now I have nothing against Apple,<br>
and I enjoy "serious" music, where I say serious in the sense of serious<br>
versus popular.<br>
<p>
I also agree with what I think this section of the Church manual is<br>
trying to say. Rewrite the middle sentence something like: "The best<br>
music is a meaningful and beautiful expression of human experience, <br>
tempered by the Christian world view.", and I am totally comfortable<br>
with it.<br>
<p>
But let's face it, this argument about the evils of popular music has<br>
been around for centuries. I'm sure I could dig up a quote about the<br>
debased nature of music with a tune, as compared with the Gregorian<br>
chant. And a couple of centuries down the line, another about the<br>
disgraceful harmony now being introduced into the music of the church,<br>
when harmoncame straight from the theatre and the pub. As for<br>
musical instruments in church, well, clearly these were an abomination,<br>
when God gave man vocal cords with which to make song.<br>
<p>
These days the argument has moved along to certain instruments, and<br>
certain styles which now represent the popular music trend. I think<br>
statements such as the one I quoted from the Church Manual only serve<br>
to increase the confusion between "taste", "culture" and "morality".<br>
We need to avoid these "true culture" judgments, otherwise we fall into<br>
the trap of making class distinctions within the church, just like those<br>
in general society.<br>
<p>
If there's nothing we can do to change the Church Manual, then maybe<br>
we should at least refrain from quoting such parts of it!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
