<title>Oct_1992: High School Church Programs</title>
<h1>High School Church Programs</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 15 Oct 92 23:41:50 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#90">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#90">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#90">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#90">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0091.html">Daniel Turk: "Re: SDA Forum on Compuserve"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0089.html">Tony: "Re: Michael the archangel"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The LDS Church has a strong high school youth program.  It is called<br>
"Seminary" and the young people meet for religious instruction at 6 in<br>
the morning every school day.  They usually meet in the church building<br>
nearby or even in a home.  Parents of high school students can also choose<br>
"home seminary" where they study on their own and meet once a week with<br>
the seminary as a group.  They have done this for years and it is more or<br>
less expected for young people to attended seminary.  To get into Brigham<br>
Young University now, a young person must have attended seminary all 4<br>
years of high school.  This is used a test of spiritual commitment.  If the<br>
person didn't care about seminary, he/she won't be happy with the religious<br>
requirements at the church's university.<br>
<p>
I sometimes wonder if a program like this could not be done in the SDA church<br>
for young people attending public high school.  In fact, the fact that the<br>
LDS Church as seminary is why the church has never established its own<br>
church school system.  The LDS high school students can talk about things<br>
they're being taught in Science class or health during seminary.  This helps<br>
put a spiritual perspective on the "worldly knowledge".  One of my new LDS<br>
friends here in Wisconsin just moved here from Wichita, Kansas.  She has a<br>
16 year old son who attended a very rough, gang-infested high school in<br>
Wichita.  She said that seminary in the mornings before school was what<br>
made life tolerable for him at the high school.  He received spiritual help<br>
and companionship before the each day which made a real difference.  His<br>
new school in Wisconsin is in a middle-class neighborhood where the biggest<br>
"problem" is scholastic competition.  This year, he is in "home seminary"<br>
which he really enjoys.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
