<title>Oct_1992: Re: SDA Forum on Compuserve</title>
<h1>Re: SDA Forum on Compuserve</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 16 Oct 1992 09:34:30 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#92">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#92">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#92">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#92">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0093.html">Daniel Turk: "Re: SDA Forum on Compuserve"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0091.html">Daniel Turk: "Re: SDA Forum on Compuserve"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0091.html">Daniel Turk: "Re: SDA Forum on Compuserve"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0093.html">Daniel Turk: "Re: SDA Forum on Compuserve"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dan Turk asks with regard to the proposal to set up an SDA Forum <br>
on Compuserve, why not do it on Internet where non-compuserve subscribers<br>
can get at it.<br>
<p>
Two reasons:<br>
<p>
1)  We already have such a forum on Internet and this is it.<br>
<p>
2)  Those few people that subscribe to us via compuserve are taking <br>
a per-message charge to receive the Internet-based messages of SDAnet,<br>
as far as I understand.  (Correct me if I'm wrong.)  A compuserve<br>
based forum would make it accessible to more people and also to<br>
people that didn't subscribe, since Compuserve forums are open for everyone<br>
to read (as far as I know.)<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
