<!-- id="01GQ3CIYI2YG8WW42P@cc.newcastle.edu.au" -->
<!-- inreplyto="Home Schooling" -->
<title>Oct_1992: Re: Home Schooling</title>
<h1>Re: Home Schooling</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>18 Oct 1992 11:45:21 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#94">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#94">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#94">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#94">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0095.html">Raylene: "Religious associations at state universities"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0093.html">Daniel Turk: "Re: SDA Forum on Compuserve"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0133.html">Dan Hamstra: "Home Schooling"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0116.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Home Schooling"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
----&gt;<br>
<i>&gt; I'm not having a go at anyone here, because I certainly believe</i><br>
<i>&gt; that aspect is important. However my personal concerns with home</i><br>
<i>&gt; schooling are more in the area of socialization.</i><br>
<p>
Our younger son is home schooling 8th grade.  We have two church<br>
schools about equal distance from us.  One school has a somewhat<br>
active home school support program where, for a very reasonable fee,<br>
home schoolers can participate in a wide variety of school activities,<br>
such as field trips to the zoo, science fair, etc.  We made similar<br>
arrangements with the other school so that he can show up for recess any<br>
time he likes, etc.  He is also playing bass clarinet in the academy band.<br>
So, his social life is rather full.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
Just to clarify, I was meaning  "socialization", not "socializing". <br>
Socialization is one of those words I discovered during my education <br>
course, and some of the aspects it addresses have to do with the<br>
integration of a person into society and so on. A person can be<br>
socialized into SDA culture, for example, or into any other type<br>
of society/culture with norms, mores and expectations. (You psychologists<br>
out there - help me out!)<br>
<p>
When I was being home schooled I too was allowed to turn up at school for<br>
recess, and still associated with my friends. However I can still remember<br>
feeling that I didn't really qualify to be part of the group, and often<br>
felt quite out of place. For a ten year old, this can be quite devastating,<br>
even though he or she may not admit it to anyone else.<br>
<p>
I know that just attending school doesn't mean that you are going to feel<br>
part of the group. I had to deal with that too as a child. But that's <br>
different to feeling that you don't even qualify.<br>
<p>
It would be interesting to do some kind of longtitudinal study on this<br>
topic, because I personally suspect that anybody who was homeschooled<br>
for long periods of time, particularly during those years where peer-group<br>
issues are so significant, is going to carry that feeling of being an<br>
"outsider" for quite some time to come.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
