<title>Oct_1992: Religious associations at state universities</title>
<h1>Religious associations at state universities</h1>
Raylene (<i>CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>18 Oct 1992 13:13:29 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#95">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#95">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#95">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#95">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0096.html">Paul Gates: "Re: SDA Forum on Compuserve"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0094.html">Tony: "Re: Home Schooling"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Mime-Version: 1.0<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Here at University of Wisconsin, we have an interesting situation.  State</i><br>
<i>&gt;law prohibits the existance of student associations which are political in</i><br>
<i>&gt;nature but religious associations are totally acceptable.</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;What is the situation at your state university?</i><br>
<p>
At the University of Newcastle, Australia, any association, including religious<br>
and political associations, may form unless an association with identical aims<br>
already exists. An association must have 25 members to exist. They must not<br>
disallow any person from joining, or from attending functions, but members may<br>
be expelled under extreme circumstances (not much short of illegal actions). <br>
The Student Union then provides a small amount of funding each year for <br>
administrative purposes ($50) and an equal sum for 6 official gatherings of<br>
the association in that year. This sum is doubled if the group has 50 members<br>
rather than 25. The Union also covers up to $100 in losses for some functions.<br>
<p>
We have a group called NASA (Newcastle Adventist Students Association) which<br>
essentially <br>
	* plans periodic Friday night and Saturday programs for Uni students<br>
	to get together and socialize and listen to various speakers or <br>
	discuss a range of topics<br>
	* conducts occasional church programs for various churches in the <br>
	disctrict<br>
	* and plans "recovery" weekend outings after exams each semester.<br>
It also liases with similar groups at Universities around the rest of Australia<br>
for larger functions.<br>
<p>
Raylene<br>
---*---<br>
