<!-- received="Mon Jan 01 01:01:01 1990 PST" -->
<!-- sent="Mon, 19 Oct 92 0:07:05 EST" -->
<!-- name="Richard Mazzaferri" -->
<!-- email="mazz@shockley.newcastle.edu.au" -->
<!-- subject="Re: Music for the cultured, and a lot of other things.  (Long!)" -->
<!-- id="9210181407.AA00322@shockley.newcastle.edu.au" -->
<!-- inreplyto="Music for the cultured, and a lot of other things.  (Long!)" -->
<title>Oct_1992: Re: Music for the cultured, and a lot of other things.  (Long!)</title>
<h1>Re: Music for the cultured, and a lot of other things.  (Long!)</h1>
Richard Mazzaferri (<i>mazz@shockley.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 19 Oct 92 0:07:05 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#97">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#97">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#97">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#97">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0098.html">Paul Gates: "Re: SDA Forum on Compuserve"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0096.html">Paul Gates: "Re: SDA Forum on Compuserve"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Tony writes:<br>
[ Description of a James Morrison concert at Avondale College... ]<br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt; Most people touted this concert as the "concert of the year", with one</i><br>
<i>&gt; notable exception. Someone wrote to the College newsletter, quoting</i><br>
<i>&gt; passages from EGW regarding teachers leading young people astray, and</i><br>
<i>&gt; pointing out the following quote from the church manual.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt;      Great care should be exercised in the choice of music. Any melody</i><br>
<i>&gt;      partaking of the nature of jazz, rock, or related hybrid forms, or</i><br>
<i>&gt;      any language expressing foolish or trivial sentiments, will be</i><br>
<i>&gt;      shunned by persons of true culture. Let us use only good music in </i><br>
<i>&gt;      the home, in the social gathering, in the school, and in the church.</i><br>
<i>&gt;          SDA Church Manual, 1990, p146</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
Having written this, I can see that it has turned in to a long article.<br>
Hopefully, you will have time to read it because I believe there is a<br>
lot in it that is worth reading/discussing, even if I cannot be very<br>
active (due to Ph.D. commitments).  I'm sorry that I haven't had time<br>
to rewrite it which may have lead to a better format.<br>
<p>
    If you don't notice as you read through, there are a lot of<br>
personal opinions in this post.  I reserve the right to be totally<br>
human, which includes but is not limited to being cynical, being wrong, <br>
being right, being somewhere in between wrong and right, being uninformed,<br>
and not knowing everything :-)<br>
<p>
The incident which is related to the quote appearing above occurred<br>
at the North New South Wales Conference Camp at Stuart's Point a couple of <br>
weeks ago.  I am writing an account based on my eye-witness experience, and <br>
my conversations with various people involved.  Any errors or misleading <br>
statements are mine (and unintentional!)<br>
<p>
    In the Youth tent on Sabbath afternoon, there was a program which was <br>
basically a presentation of various activities of the youth around the <br>
Conference which have a charitable and/or evangelical flavour.  There were<br>
things such as:<br>
  *  The "Bike For Bibles" group cycling 1000km to raise money for<br>
     the Bible Society (?). <br>
  *  Interviews with past Student Missionaries and a live phone conversation <br>
     with one in the Middle East.<br>
  *  The story of a church youth group who organised a community touch-football      competition which raised community consciousness of Adventism (and <br>
     dispelled a few myths about those 'wierd' Adventists).<br>
  *  Interviews with the small team who travelled to Barcelona just<br>
     before the Olympics to street witness (via drama/mime/clowning and<br>
     other non-orthodox methods) - they left before the Olympics to<br>
     visit other countries, including at least one Muslim country where<br>
     any offence to Mohammed is a serious crime, but found many people<br>
     were interested and moved by their work, and they were not charged<br>
     with any crime!  Language was not as big a barrier as it could have<br>
     been for performances which were simply mime.<br>
  *  A presentation by the "Bus Team" - one church group on its own has<br>
     purchased and renovated a London Bus as a drop-in centre/coffee<br>
     shop type of place, and it has "Megalife" emblazoned on the side.<br>
     It's known as "The Big Red Bus" and a small team of Conference-sponsored <br>
     volunteers now travels around the conference helping local youth to run <br>
     programs, running Scripture programs in state schools, and operating the <br>
     bus as a drop in centre for any one on the streets at night times.  As you<br>
     may imagine, this is leading edge evangelism, dealing with people<br>
     where they are (usually straight off the street) and whatever state they <br>
     are in.  They have had many amazing experiences (and people have had life <br>
     changing experiences, including street kids, prostitutes, alcoholics, <br>
     drug addicts and even one guy who came onto the bus and admitted to <br>
     being a murderer.)  <br>
<p>
To conclude the program, a group of 5 guys came on to sing a couple of<br>
songs as an item.  I happen to know all of them reasonably well (and one<br>
is my flatmate!)  They are not professional singers, and they know it,<br>
but they were there intending to praise God.  Their first song was reasonably<br>
good for amateurs in my opinion (and I believe I have had enough<br>
experience with music/performances/bands to be more discerning than the<br>
average person - conversations with the average Youth Tent attendee<br>
about the music tend to confirm this.)  Their style was somewhat jazzy, <br>
and they were moving on stage in a fashion which was fairly natural <br>
considering the effort and soul they were putting into their<br>
performance.  Adventists have a strong history of vocal groups (e.g. The<br>
Heritage Singers, Reunion, The Jackson Family, Endless Praise (from<br>
Australia)) so what they were doing was nothing new to most SDA's.  <br>
    They then proceeded to start "Amazing Grace" in a similar<br>
fashion, with not quite the same technical mastery, and requesting that<br>
the audience join them in praising God.  However, Some people in the audience <br>
had begun to feel that the performance had a comical air, and began to laugh <br>
or snigger.  <br>
    Right at the start of the song (from my memory), a man (in his late <br>
30's/early 40's ?) got up from his seat and wandered down to the front, ending <br>
up next to one of the performers right at the end of the first verse.  He <br>
asked for the microphone and was given it.  He said words to the effect that <br>
after the program we had seen about the work being done in the name of God, he<br>
felt that it was inappropriate for us to be "mocking God", at which<br>
point he returned to his seat.<br>
<p>
    For those who want to know what happened, they continued singing in<br>
a more subdued fashion, but the audience did not feel inclined to join<br>
in as they were again asked to.  I personally felt emotions ranging from <br>
embarassed (both for the performers and myself) to horrified.  Afterwards, <br>
there was serious discussion between various people involved in the incident <br>
and other interested parties.<br>
<p>
    During those conversations, this man (or someone arguing for his<br>
"side" apparently quoted the exact same words from the Church Manual<br>
that appear near the beginning of this article.  The group was told that<br>
they should have prayed about what they were going to do beforehand.<br>
When they replied that they had spent time in serious prayer and that<br>
they believed that they were praising God and that God was with them,<br>
they were told that when they prayed, they should have also listened,<br>
and that if they felt that God was with them they obviously hadn't<br>
prayed hard enough.  <br>
    There were perhaps other concerns involved - this man appeared to be <br>
trying to link this incident to the work of the Bus Team (which was <br>
presented prior to the item) and claim that it would damage the ministry <br>
and credibility of the Bus Team - and later said that he had been following <br>
the Bus Team around the Conference keeping an eye on them, and now he had <br>
the evidence he needed.  He also said things like "right is right, and <br>
wrong is wrong", and that what they had done was entertainment and <br>
therefore wrong.<br>
<p>
My personal observations are:<br>
    *  if the performers had been black (like the Jackson family perhaps, <br>
       or the award winning group of Adventists, "Take 6") then the mannerisms <br>
       and even style of music would have seemed perfectly natural.  Their<br>
       movement on stage was not perceived as any form of dance (which<br>
       we all know we can't have) but was consistent with (black?) singers<br>
       putting their heart and soul into their song.<br>
           I do not know what the reaction would have been if noone<br>
       saw the item as humourous.  In the Youth Tent, at any given time,<br>
       there is almost certainly at least one person who finds humour in<br>
       the program, given the age group and maturity of those present.<br>
    *  While techincally was far from the best item I heard during the<br>
       Camp, it was also far from the worst.<br>
    *  I know these guys and they were seriously intending to praise God.  <br>
       (It was suggested to the man involved that this was either an argument <br>
       about musical standards - which are not black/white, OR he was calling <br>
       the performers liars in that they had the intention of mocking God.  <br>
       He was unable to accept either position nor suggest an alternative.)  <br>
    *  It would have been better that the item be performed at a<br>
       different time, as the program was reasonably "Traditional<br>
       Adventist" except that the activities described were often very<br>
       unorthodox!  It was also Sabbath (though not during "Sabbath School"<br>
       time nor "Church".<br>
    *  Though I appreciate that this man must have felt _very_ strongly about <br>
       the item to do as he did, from talking to various youth I felt that far <br>
       more harm than good had been caused - various people (including but not <br>
       limited to performers in the item) felt that their spiritual experience <br>
       and their expression of that experience had been rejected, and this was <br>
       profoundly disturbing.  <br>
    *  More trivially, anyone who linked the item with the Bus Team must have <br>
       either difficulty in appreciating that the presenter announces each new         segment of the programme, or thought that the Bus Team was linked with <br>
       the Olympics witnessing team, which was linked with the touch football  <br>
       competition, which was linked ...<br>
    *  The man stated his reasons and opinions in a calm and rational<br>
       manner.  There were no histrionics or arm waving - it was perceived<br>
       to be well handled given the strength of feeling that he must have <br>
       had about the item.<br>
<p>
<p>
    Now, take your music as you like it and appreciate what you will,<br>
but this incident raises a small host of questions.<br>
<p>
    * Firstly, this guy had apparently asked the sound mixer to turn<br>
      them off before he made his stage appearance.  Can we please stop<br>
      pressuring the sound man about the content of the program?!<br>
      (Tony, do you want to comment?)  I was the sound man for 3 years for<br>
      a contemporary band of Christian musicians, and copped a lot of flak<br>
      from various directions, so I know a little of what it is like.<br>
      The sound man is not there to make musical judgements - he's<br>
      there to do the sound in the way that the performers/program producers<br>
      want it done.  Get off his back.  (It is rumoured that the man<br>
      threatened to pull the plug, as happened to another performance<br>
      in Sydney a year/two ago when the person responsible for the <br>
      programme felt unable to support what was going on.  Pulling the<br>
      plug can have nasty effects on sound gear sometimes, and it's _very_<br>
      expensive gear.)<br>
<p>
    * Secondly, is "performance" wrong?  Or, is "performance = entertainment"?<br>
      I wondered if this man had been in the Youth Tent during "Church"<br>
      when a performer named "Francene" who used to be a night-life type<br>
      entertainer in Paris before she became a Christian, sang "Amazing <br>
      Grace", solo - she has an amazing voice and puts it to awesome use<br>
      for God, but her singing is even more a performance than that of<br>
      the guys above.  One could certainly view it as entertainment if<br>
      one had that desire.  Does this make it wrong?  <br>
<p>
    * How do we deal with the "it's all black and white" attitude, which<br>
      usually goes hand in hand with "I can prove it to you by quoting <br>
      selected excerpts from EGW/The Bible/The Church Manual".  <br>
          Firstly,if you disagree with me that this is a problem - fine.<br>
      I'm happy to hear your viewpoint.  However, I have seen so much of<br>
      this attitude during my growing up in the Church, and so many<br>
      situations where the attitude is:<br>
          (a) arguably very wrong and utterly simplistic<br>
          (b) regardless of right/wrong-ness, causes great harm to the <br>
              interests of God, the Church, and people around the<br>
              Church.<br>
      I see many (particularly young) people completely turned off anything to <br>
      do with God/religion, and the cause is often directly traceable to this <br>
      attitude.  As one of my friends said to me recently, "Can you think<br>
      of anyone from your final year at school who still goes to church?"<br>
      The common experience is often that it is hard to recall such people.<br>
          As one pastor related to me, he once had some members of the<br>
      Church Board come to him, complaining that an elder's wife was wearing<br>
      jewellery, and asking him if he was going to do something about it.<br>
      "Sure," he said.  "When?" he was asked.  "Well," he said, "I have<br>
      a list of priorities.  First, there are about 5 billion people who<br>
      have never heard of Jesus Christ.  Secondly, there are thousands<br>
      upon thousands of street kids, people with alcohol problems,<br>
      people going hungry, victims of violence and oppression etc.<br>
      After I deal with those two, I'm going to worry about jewellery."<br>
<p>
      I wonder if the black/white attitude comes from education of a <br>
      particular type where the attitudes and conclusions of the parents<br>
      are passed on without the reasoning behind them, or if it results<br>
      from a lack of education which makes it desirable to see the world<br>
      in black and white terms - a user's manual, if you like:  for<br>
      those in situation 173(b), rules 13 and 132(f) mean that you will<br>
      do action x.  Life is so utterly secure, because you _know_ that<br>
          (a) you are always right.<br>
          (b) your course of action is always mapped out for you.<br>
          (c) you never have to change your mind.<br>
          (d) you have no opinions - you simply _know_.<br>
          (e) you don't even need rules 13 and 132(f), because you know<br>
              you have to do action x.<br>
          (f) you can leave your brain asleep in bed when you get up.<br>
              (My opinion only.)<br>
      I'm sorry if I seem cynical about this - to quite an extent I am,<br>
      and so are _lots_ of young people that know.<br>
<p>
      I have to admit that there are people who see the world in much<br>
      more black and white terms than I do, and have thought their position<br>
      through thoroughly.  To such people I say, I respect your opinions<br>
      because you have thought them through for yourself, but you must <br>
      allow me to think my position through and reach a different conclusion.<br>
      Unfortunately, the stereotype that I see is that people with such a<br>
      world view love to attempt to impose their world view on others.<br>
      Those who see the world more in shades of gray _tend_ to be more<br>
      accepting of alternative viewpoints and thus to see no particular <br>
      need to attempt to impose their viewpoints on others.  This can<br>
      look like weakness - if I am not willing to ram my argument down<br>
      your throat just because you are trying to do the same to me, then<br>
      there must be something wrong with my position.<br>
<p>
      This is at least partially related to the next item.<br>
<p>
    * How should we use The Bible/EGW/The Church Manual, especially with<br>
      regard to our own behaviour and with behavioural standards we wish<br>
      to enforce on others?  (Should we attempt to enforce standards on<br>
      others, and if so, how should they be deteremined, who should<br>
      enforce, how should enforcement be conducted etc?)<br>
 <br>
      If I have time (or enough people ask me to ;-) I will attempt to <br>
      write another article containing my recollections of a series of<br>
      3 meetings that Pastor Graham Bradford ran in the Youth Tent, dealing<br>
      with questions of inspiration/function/authority with respect to<br>
      The Bible and EGW, and touching on Truth in a way that seems to me<br>
      to be related to the black/white attitude.  These series of<br>
      meetings gave me hope that Adventism can exhibit common sense and<br>
      sanity at a time when I have often felt a great lack of those two<br>
      commodities.  It is especially confidence inspiring that these words<br>
      are coming from a reasonably high position in the Church heirarchy,<br>
      because in my opinion many people will listen simply because of the <br>
      position of the presenter, and hopefully start thinking on these things.<br>
          There were lots of interesting observations on the life of EGW<br>
      and the way in which she (and her contemporaries) saw the inspiration<br>
      of her writings and the way in which they should be used.  I haven't<br>
      got time to go into details now.  The meetings were being recorded,<br>
      but unfortunately the tape recorder broke during the second session.<br>
      Graham was quite worried that people would take what he had to say<br>
      out of context and use it to say things that he did not say, so I<br>
      don't imagine that they'll be releasing copies of only sessions 1 &amp; 3.<br>
      (It's funny to remember that when my father was an SDA pastor, he used<br>
      to tape record his own sermons for the very same reason.  Is it a<br>
      uniquely SDA phenomenon that we are eager to take things out of<br>
      context and use them as weapons?)<br>
<p>
    * Is this a "youth versus oldies" issue?  Do older generations and<br>
      younger have different views on what is appropriate in expressing<br>
      praise to God?  Do we insist that when separate meetings exist,<br>
      that older people stay out of the Youth Tent?  Or do we refuse to<br>
      tailor programs more towards Youth because of the potential non-Youth <br>
      audience?<br>
<p>
    * How do I personally deal with someone who appears to me to be out to<br>
      damage the Bus Team ministry and youthful expression and experience<br>
      of spirituality?  A particular problem appears to be that he has no<br>
      way to allow anyone else to disagree with him and entertain the <br>
      possibility that they are correct, or even that the truth is not<br>
      totally captured by either of us.<br>
          To the best of my perception, the Bus Team is performing a great<br>
      and mighty and even necessary ministry on behalf of a Church which<br>
      would like to call itself "The Caring Church".  In addition, people<br>
      must be able to express their spirituality in all the different ways<br>
      that (I believe) God has given without being rejected for their style<br>
      or sincerity of expression.<br>
          In short, I profoundly disagree with this man.  Yet to some extent<br>
      the way that I believe allows me to accept his different beliefs, but<br>
      his belief system does not appear to allow him to accept mine.  How <br>
      do we deal with this tension, which some have characterised as between<br>
      "young and old" or "liberal and conservative" or "immature and mature"?<br>
      The generalisations probably obscure the issue.<br>
          <br>
By the way, one of the most profound experiences of my life was the<br>
first time I heard live jazz, with James Morisson in a little room at<br>
Uni set up as a small jazz club.  I couldn't stop grinning broadly for three<br>
days!  Personally, I'm looking forward to playing jazz (or something<br>
even better!) when I get to heaven.<br>
<p>
      Mazz.<br>
<p>
PS If you have read this far, you have come a long way.  Thanks!<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
