<!-- id="9210161713.AA20469@dsacg2.dsac.dla.mil" -->
<!-- inreplyto="The Trinity" -->
<title>Oct_1992: Re: The Trinity</title>
<h1>Re: The Trinity</h1>
Jim Dunn (<i>nol2321@dsacg2.dsac.dla.mil</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 16 Oct 92 13:13:02 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#99">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#99">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#99">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#99">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0100.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Homeschool"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0098.html">Paul Gates: "Re: SDA Forum on Compuserve"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0080.html">Eric Snyder: "The Trinity"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
(1)<br>
<i>&gt;I think it is more important to ask "what does the doctrine of the</i><br>
<i>&gt;trinity have to say" than to make statements about whether God is</i><br>
(2)<br>
<i>&gt;"really" made up of three distinct components. One important thing</i><br>
<i>&gt;that the doctrine says, for example, is that Jesus is God.</i><br>
(3)<br>
<i>&gt;We're setting ourselves up for a certain amount of embarrassment on</i><br>
<i>&gt;the day that we see these things for ourselves if we try to make too</i><br>
<i>&gt;much of it at this stage.</i><br>
<i>&gt;  Tony</i><br>
<p>
Tony, this was very well said, I especially appreciate the intent to find<br>
out what God is trying to tell us about Himself without actually expecting<br>
to understand Him as you would something under a microscope (he's too awe-<br>
some for any microscope!!!)  However, it should be noted that the trinity<br>
doctrine does not say that Jesus is God, it says that Jesus is 1/3 God.<br>
<p>
Don't misunderstands me, I believe in the Father, the Son, and the Holy<br>
Ghost, but I don't like to use the wording of the trinity doctrine, or<br>
even the word trinity itself, here's why.<br>
<p>
A few people I study with, from work, think that Jesus didn't really die.<br>
"After all," they say, "since He was 1/3rd of the Trinity, and God cannot<br>
die, then 1/3rd of God could not have died, so Jesus didn't really die on<br>
the cross, just His body, and His soul went back to heaven until the<br>
resurrection."<br>
<p>
In an attempt to explain the state of the dead, I had to ask them to agree<br>
to use the Bible definitions for Body, Soul, Spirit, Life, Death, etc.  So<br>
they agreed and we started with Genesis.  But even after convincing them<br>
of what the Bible teaches concerning the state of the dead, they still<br>
would not accept that Jesus really had died.  This led me to examine the<br>
doctrine of God, the God-Head, the Trinity, etc.  Anyway, to make a long<br>
story a little longer &lt;smile&gt; I found more mystery than answers.  I kept<br>
trying to define God using my own terms and definitions which would run<br>
me into some obstacle, forcing me to go back to the Bible.  Thus, I've<br>
become very sensitive to the word Trinity since it's not even used in the<br>
Bible.  (nor in any of EGW's writings, for that matter)<br>
<p>
I've ran into some who don't even believe in the Trinity, and others who<br>
claim that there is no Holy Spirit, and others still who claim that Jesus<br>
was created; but I hold to none of these.  I only know that He has told<br>
us that "Faith cometh by Hearing, and Hearing by the Word of God."  This<br>
is the promise I'm holding on to, and I know He has provided all knowledge<br>
that I need for Salvation in His Word and will provide all Understanding<br>
of His Word through His Spirit.<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
  | James Dunn, USA-DoD-DLA-DSAC-OLC, Tech-N-Logistics, FTS(614)692-9713 |
  | &gt;INTERNET:jdunn@dsac.dla.mil -- {uunet}!osu-cis!dsac!jdunn -- AV/850 |
  |  "Remember, Truth Isn't Relative, It's Superlative and Imperative."  |
<pre>
--
</pre>
