<!-- inreplyto="01GPZCDEDB4Y8WWWHC@cc.newcastle.edu.au" -->
<title>Oct_1992: Re: Homeschool</title>
<h1>Re: Homeschool</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 16 Oct 92 11:03:50 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#100">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#100">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#100">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#100">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0101.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: Homeschool"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0099.html">Jim Dunn: "Re: The Trinity"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0078.html">Raylene: "Different people in our churches"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0124.html">Russell Yonkers: "Re: Homeschool"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[CHRMD@cc.newcastle.edu.au writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; &gt;[DaveB]</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;Our personal experience with home schooling is that it is the best</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;option available for those who have that option.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; One of the reasons why I questioned home-schooling in the first place was</i><br>
<i>&gt; because of an experience I had while practice teaching a few years ago.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I don't know how she was going in </i><br>
<i>&gt; English or History but I know how she was going in Mathematics and Science:</i><br>
<i>&gt; she had no knowledge of these subjects at a high school level at all.</i><br>
<p>
Alas, the same thing could be said of far too many public school students<br>
(at least here in the US) and perhaps also of some private school kids.<br>
My observation is that one will find variation of thoroughness and preparation<br>
among home schooled children just as one will find among traditionally<br>
schooled children.  Statistics cited by Dr Raymond Moore indicate that,<br>
on average, home schooled children outscore schooled children on all<br>
normative (or is it "normalized"?) achievement tests.<br>
<p>
As for socialization (which I find to be a "red herring"):  Dr Moore, Greg<br>
Harris, and others have found published articles in refereed journals<br>
indicating that home schooled children, on average, are markedly better<br>
socialized than their peers.  In such aspects as resistance to peer<br>
pressure, ability to interact in a meaningful manner with individuals<br>
outside their age group, the differences are significant:  home schooled<br>
students stand head and shoulders above.<br>
<p>
Drawing generalizations from observation of extreme examples (alas, it<br>
is not always clear that they are extreme), whether on the positive or<br>
the negative side, informs one little about the average case.  Having said<br>
that 8-), it may be of interest that Harvard has accepted home schooled<br>
students into their accelerated PhD track program (featured in Reader's<br>
Digest some years back).  There's a high school age home schooler doing<br>
materials research with NASA and medical researchers (cited in ATIA<br>
newsletters published by IBLP).<br>
<p>
Factual data is obtainable from the Moore Foundation; I imagine that<br>
ATIA (708-323-9800) would be another source.  Resources such as the Adventist<br>
Home Educator newsletter have both factual and anecdotal info.  I imagine<br>
that publishers such as Rod&amp;Staff, Sonshine Resources, A Beka, Alpha Omega,<br>
Christian Liberty Academy, et al, also have relevant info.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; What wisdom have others got to offer on the subject?</i><br>
<p>
The continuing compliments we receive on the graciousness, respectful<br>
attitudes, vivaciousness, and wisdom of our home schooled children is<br>
a source of great joy.  The name of the Lord is to be praised!<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  On Attitude &amp; the Immune System:  A sound heart is the life of the flesh:
    but envy the rottenness of the bones.  Prov 14:30
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
