<!-- body="start" -->
[Raylene]<br>
<i>&gt; One of the reasons why I questioned home-schooling in the first place was</i><br>
<i>&gt; because of an experience I had while practice teaching a few years ago.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; There was a girl in one of my classes who had not gone to school because her</i><br>
<i>&gt; . . . . . .</i><br>
<p>
You do raise a valid concern.  A concerned parent needs to be careful<br>
that the same thing not happen even in a school situation.  In the<br>
news we hear about highschool grads who cannot even read.  But of<br>
course its less likely for a student to be blind in a given area if he/she<br>
has had several teachers over the years.<br>
<p>
In our case, our boys have done very well at math and science.  My wife<br>
was especially concerned about her ability to teach them english.<br>
Because of this concern she made a special effort in this area.  When<br>
the boys were back at church school the following year they were top<br>
of their class over all and especially in math, science and english.<br>
<p>
Many of the problems of home school can be avoided by working with<br>
an established program, and there are several of them out there.  Many<br>
of these programs include testing materials that will show up<br>
deficiencies in any area.  Of course the risks are greatest if parents<br>
want to go strictly on their own.<br>
<p>
DaveB<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
