I was surprised when Paul said it was costing 15 US cents per message <br>
for  getting SDAnet plus his phone time.  I had no idea the cost to <br>
Compuserve readers was so high per message.  In light of that, I am prepared<br>
to make a weekly digest of the traffic to send to Compuserve readers<br>
and others that are interested.  I would like to hear from all the compuserve<br>
subscribers we have (5-10) to see if they would use such a service, and <br>
I will make the service available if enough of them wanted it.<br>
<p>
What about America Online?  What's the charge for their subscribers<br>
per message received from the Internet?<br>
<p>
In answer to Paul's question, the Internet is not really free to anyone.<br>
It's just that some educational institutions absorb the cost of maintaining<br>
the high-speed network connections and don't pass it on to their students<br>
or employees.  Other places, such as Fermilab, absorb the cost but then<br>
stipulate it must be used only for official business.  <br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
