<title>Oct_1992: Home Schooling</title>
<h1>Home Schooling</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 18 Oct 92 23:12:17 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#108">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#108">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#108">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#108">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0109.html">Dan Blake: "Help obtaining 1 John articles"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0107.html">Steven Timm: "Angels' choir"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I suspect the success/failure of home schooling depends a great deal on<br>
the temperment and personalities of the children and the instructing<br>
parent.  I have a friend in Loma Linda who claims to be home schooling<br>
her 6th grader.  He was kicked out of the SDA elementary school due to<br>
severe behavior problems and rather than send him to public school, she<br>
decided to "home school" him.  Unfortunately, she does not even have a<br>
high school diploma herself.  She works full-time at a department store<br>
and leaves this young lad home by himself to complete his lessons.  As<br>
you may suspect, this was a miserable failure and he is now more than<br>
a year behind scholastically.<br>
<p>
The underlying question of whether to home school should be why?  What<br>
is motivating this choice?  Are the parents truly committed to the<br>
concept or are they trying to avoid high SDA tuition?  I think the<br>
education and talents of the mother (because it is almost always the<br>
mother who teaches home schooled kids) should play a big part of the<br>
decision.  Not all adults have the knack or talent to teach children.<br>
It is not wise to place this burden on a mother who is not prepared for<br>
it.<br>
<p>
I saw a 60 Minutes special a while back about home schooling and the<br>
successes of families choosing this method of education.  It was<br>
impressive.  However, all the kids were very bright and with very bright<br>
parents.  I suspect that bright kids with average parents or bright<br>
parents with only average kids would have problems.<br>
<p>
Two socialization problems I forsee is: (1) lack of experience with<br>
people of other races, cultures, or mores and (2) public speaking.  If<br>
a child never has to present idea to a group of peers, never has to<br>
raise his/her hand to participate in a discussion, he/she will not learn<br>
proper social courtesies.  Home schooled kids typically interact with<br>
adults very well but have a difficult time with kids their own age.  They<br>
may have a wealth of knowledge and feel compelled to tell all they know<br>
when faced with a group situation.  At home, they're rewarded for this<br>
behavior but in the real world, nobody likes a "know-it-all".  I remember<br>
at situation with my cousin's boy when he was just five years old.  In<br>
Sabbath School, the teacher was explaining that a "group of lions" were<br>
resting in the shade.  He pipes up that she should have said a "pride of<br>
lions".  Cute for a 5 year old but obnoxious for a 10 year old.  The<br>
lack of experience with people of other races, cultures, or mores is more<br>
difficult.  Children learn about these from experience.  How can a parent<br>
teach a child racial tolerance, social-class tolerance, or religious<br>
tolerance.  I remember attending SDA elementary school and seeing a black<br>
child for the first time.  I remember when a girl from Japan enrolled in<br>
our school.  I remember when some nonSDAs enrolled (uncommon 30 years ago).<br>
All of these experiences helped shape my attitudes about race, culture,<br>
and religion.  I didn't just learn about them.  I experienced them.  I<br>
remember feeling very bad when all the white boys called the black child<br>
by a derogatory name.  I remember sticking up for her and becoming her<br>
friend.  I remember trading stuff in my lunch with the Japanese girl.<br>
And I remember how nice the nonSDA kids could be.  It was revealing to<br>
me.  I learned that some SDAs are not very nice and that some nonSDAs<br>
were.  Where will the home schooled kids experience this?  Where will<br>
they learn what bigotry is and how to respond to it?  Where will they<br>
learn tolerance to differences?<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
