<title>Oct_1992: Sharing Christianity</title>
<h1>Sharing Christianity</h1>
Ben Clausen (<i>GRIBCL%LLUVM.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>20 Oct 1992 15:26:13 -0800 (PST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#113">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#113">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#113">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#113">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0114.html">Steven Timm: "Family Values:  Sexual Ethics in the Adventist Ministry"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0112.html">Steven Timm: "Now we can reach Genie"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
     Several months ago Nancy Vyhmeister requested information on witnessing<br>
experiences university students and professionals have had in a non-SDA<br>
environment. I consider it to be an important topic and have felt that the<br>
Geoscience Research Institute should get more involved along that direction.<br>
At her suggestion, I am giving my response to her to the network.<br>
     In the June issue of the Adventist Association of Physicists newsletter<br>
I included a questionnaire asking for suggestions (among other things) on<br>
making the Gospel credible and acceptable to non-Adventists, particularly<br>
scientists. Jon Paulien at Andrews has suggested several concepts that are<br>
useful:<br>
          personal relationships (creative listening)<br>
          cosmic relationships (great controversy model)<br>
          creation (we are caretakers, not owners)<br>
          the Incarnation (God's concern for each person)<br>
          a Saviour (release from failure at one's own standards)<br>
          hope (Biblical eschatology / a resurrection)<br>
          SDA uniqueness (rejecting established religion)<br>
          purpose/commitment (demands of SDA life style).<br>
Those responding to the questionnaire have felt the most important of these<br>
are (1) a personal relationship and (2) the Incarnation.   I agree.<br>
     The general approach that has worked best for me is this: Get personally<br>
involved with people in the scientific community. Don't obnoxiously emphasize<br>
differences in lifestyle, but don't hide them either. I'm sure to be asked<br>
questions---mostly curious ones, but occasionally serious ones; so I try to<br>
be ready with a simple answer that is meaningful.<br>
     My research is done at about half a dozen nuclear physics accelerator<br>
laboratories in the United States and Europe where I spend a week or two per<br>
experiment. That (along with writing papers and giving papers at meetings)<br>
gives me plenty of opportunity for interaction, since we work together, eat<br>
together, stay in the same motel room together, etc. Usually we run 24<br>
hours/day and 7 days/week. Getting off on Sabbath usually ends up leading to<br>
questions somewhere along the line. I have had plenty of opportunities to<br>
share what Adventists believe, most of which continue to be opportunities.<br>
Although no one has been baptized as a result, I can still see that the<br>
influence is there. I like to think that maybe Daniel had somewhat similar<br>
results. Here are some examples:<br>
---A girl in a lab I taught at University of Colorado seemed interested in<br>
Adventism so I gave her a copy of The Great Controversy. I guess she<br>
appreciated it because she gave my wife and me a box of chocolates for<br>
Christmas.<br>
---An office mate at CU once told me that any born-again Christian in his<br>
office would get booted out pretty quick. When I suggested that maybe he<br>
would have to boot me out, he said I wasn't a problem because I wasn't always<br>
badgering him.<br>
---I put a paragraph in my dissertation acknowledgements at CU expressing<br>
appreciation that God had made such a marvelous creation to appreciate.<br>
Several years later the wife of a post-doctoral student asked me at length<br>
about SDAs as a result of reading it.<br>
---A fellow student and good friend at CU would occasionally ask me questions<br>
about SDAs. We kept up correspondence until we worked together at University<br>
of Virginia. There he and his wife became quite interested in attending<br>
church with us.<br>
---I worked with a professor from Catholic University of America on an<br>
experiment in Amsterdam. The first Sabbath I explained I couldn't work and he<br>
was very understanding. Unfortunately, however it meant he had to work a 24<br>
hour shift. Fortunately, I was able to repay him several days later when he<br>
wanted to leave on vacation early and I took a 24 hour shift. He has given me<br>
an interesting book he wrote called, "Two Faces of Time," which suggests<br>
relationships between physicists views of time and that of several of the<br>
world religions.<br>
---The professor I worked with at UVa has asked me on several occasions about<br>
Adventist beliefs. His girl friend was studying with Jehovah's Witnesses and<br>
he wanted to know how that related to what SDAs believe. I thought that one<br>
of the main differences was our understanding of who Jesus is, so sent him a<br>
copy of Desire of Ages.<br>
---I go back to UVa about once a year to collaborate on experiments. Each<br>
time one of the other professors asks about my work. I've told him it is<br>
studying the relation between science and religion. He is the one who always<br>
brings up the subject.<br>
---One physics graduate student at UVa was a Christian and believed in a<br>
recent creation. We shared an office with plenty of resulting conversation.<br>
She is a geology doctoral student at CU now and has asked for information on<br>
creation so she will at least have some answers for her professors. She is<br>
giving a paper next week at the Geological Society of America meetings in<br>
Cincinatti, where she plans to get together with our lady geologist from GRI.<br>
---Another student I shared an office with at UVa took a philosophy of<br>
science class and was involved in a very civic minded fraternity that<br>
engendered discussions. A third student there said his brother was a born<br>
again Christian who was always pestering him about being saved. He said he<br>
got tired of that, but didn't mind talking to me.<br>
---When I visited Russia last year to work with several nuclear physicists at<br>
Dubna, I let them know before hand that I couldn't work on Sabbath. As a<br>
result, they made arrangements for me to visit the Moscow church 100km away<br>
even though I hadn't asked for that. In fact one of them attended part of a<br>
church service. The Bibles that I off-handedly gave to two of them, they very<br>
much appreciated. One professor at Moscow State University asked me<br>
extensively about our church, based on TV information she had heard about the<br>
gardens at the Zaokski seminary.<br>
---This summer I spent two weeks on an experiment at Brookhaven on Long<br>
Island, NY. One of the graduate students spent half an hour asking about my<br>
beliefs, and finally said that he wished he could believe too.<br>
---Just last month I spent a week on an experiment at Los Alamos. During the<br>
day shift a janitor would come in and talk awhile. He seemed to have a great<br>
concern about the scientists who were workaholics and spent little time with<br>
their families and then ended up with a divorce. He was impressed with a<br>
scientist who was also a Christian and was studying the interface between<br>
science and religion.<br>
     In these cases and more the approach is probably the same as everyone<br>
else uses: first, the personal element of showing people that you are<br>
interested in them; and second, not hiding your life style but letting them<br>
see that your Christianity makes a positive difference in your life (it makes<br>
you happy and it makes them happy to be associated with you). In thinking<br>
about improving the approach, I would like to have several more book titles<br>
in mind to suggest to people, which I could send to them if they are<br>
interested.<br>
     I'll quit; this is longer than I planned. Hearing some other people's<br>
experiences would give me some encouragement.           ---  Ben Clausen<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
