<title>Oct_1992: Family Values:  Sexual Ethics in the Adventist Ministry</title>
<h1>Family Values:  Sexual Ethics in the Adventist Ministry</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 20 Oct 1992 21:59:34 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#114">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#114">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#114">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#114">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0115.html">Tony: "Re: Sexual ethics"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0113.html">Ben Clausen: "Sharing Christianity"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
A couple months ago I posted some numbers from Len McMillan's study on <br>
sexual ethics in the Adventist ministry.  My post raised some questions<br>
which I didn't have time to answer.  I don't remember what those questions<br>
were now, but I'll try to answer them as best I can.<br>
<p>
He starts out by delineating the problems inherent in the ministry<br>
1)  Ministers feel they must deny that they have ever been sexually <br>
tempted, for fear of seeming common.<br>
2)  Ministers may suffer "sin saturation", becoming desensitized to sin<br>
by hearing people's problems day in and day out.<br>
3)  Ministers sometimes forget to take time away from the "things of God"<br>
to spend time with God and their families.<br>
<p>
A Christianity Today survey of ministers  ("Sins of the Body{" p 9-11)<br>
revealed that one in four admitted to having done something sexually<br>
inappropriate since they had entered the ministry.  One in eight confessed<br>
to actually committing adultery since entering the ministry.  Three out of <br>
four said that sex was never talked about or explained in the home in <br>
which they grew up.<br>
<p>
<p>
McMillan has given similar surveys in his seminars to Adventist workers<br>
on sexuality.  The sample he reports has 416 male and 167 female respondents.<br>
More than half of the females were pastor's spouses, 5% were pastors, 19%<br>
were teachers, 7% were counselors.  Of the males, 88% were pastors, 2%<br>
were teachers, 4% were counselors  (his percentages don't add up.)<br>
<p>
Had they ever engaged in premarital sex?  Half of males, 47% of females<br>
answered yes.  The percentage was less for those raised in Adventist homes.<br>
<p>
Had they ever had sex with someone other than their spouse since marriage?<br>
11% males, 10% females answered yes.  12% for those raised in SDA homes.<br>
<p>
Had they ever been attracted to a client/student/parishioner without<br>
actually engaging in sex?<br>
65% of males said yes, 31% of females.<br>
<p>
Would they feel comfortable discussing above attraction with spouse?<br>
47% said no.<br>
<p>
Ever had an affair?  (more broad than sex)<br>
12% of males yes (mostly pastors) 16% of females yes (mostly spouses)<br>
<p>
Ever sexually abused?<br>
6% of males yes, 19% of females,  less in those that grew up in SDA homes.<br>
<p>
He suggests in his last page a suggested code of sexual ethics for<br>
SDA employees, which I won't repeat here.<br>
<p>
Questions, comments?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
