<!-- inreplyto="Sexual ethics" -->
<title>Oct_1992: Re: Sexual ethics</title>
<h1>Re: Sexual ethics</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>21 Oct 1992 14:21:08 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#115">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#115">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#115">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#115">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0116.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Home Schooling"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0114.html">Steven Timm: "Family Values:  Sexual Ethics in the Adventist Ministry"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I've got two things I'd like to say which are related to Steve's post.<br>
<p>
1) Surveys and statistics<br>
<p>
   It is clear that voluntary surveys often do not reflect the<br>
   actual statistics. This is largely attributed to the fact that<br>
   respondents are mostly those who have some kind of motivation <br>
   for responding. In a survey on premarital sex, for example,<br>
   the respondents may largely reflect those that "have" or "did"<br>
   rather than the "haven't" and "didn't" group. Although survey<br>
   results can still be interesting and sometimes meaningful, this<br>
   does need to be considered in order to put the numbers in<br>
   perspective. (Just making an arbitrary correction is not enough<br>
   either, because you can never  predict the response pattern.)<br>
<p>
2) Discussions of sexual behaviour and standards<br>
<p>
   The difficulty in coming up with accurate statistics notwithstanding,<br>
   it is also clear that there is a significant proportion of young<br>
   Adventists today who "have", "did" and sometimes "are". Yet I still<br>
   hear almost every pastor/counsellor, when speaking about sex, <br>
   emphasize the point about "saving yourself" to the exclusion of most<br>
   other things. They say firstly that extramarital sex is wrong, and<br>
   secondly that it's really important to save yourself for the one you<br>
   marry.<br>
<p>
   I agree with both of those points, but it seems to me that the portion<br>
   of the audience who "have" are not being addressed by this message.<br>
   It's a bit like the alcohol one which you have probably heard yourself,<br>
   "you never know whether you're an alcoholic or not until you have a <br>
   drink. One drink is all it might take for you to be hooked, and your<br>
   life will be ruined." That scare-tactic only works for the person who<br>
   has never tasted alcohol, and it may be enough to dissuade them from<br>
   ever doing so. But for a person who has tried it, and is not hooked,<br>
   a more sensible and mature discussion is required.<br>
<p>
   We do need to face up to the reality that Adventist young people, just<br>
   like the rest of Western society, are participating in extramarital<br>
   sex, and that this is increasing. We need to ask ourselves why we<br>
   feel that our beliefs on sexual behaviour are important, and then<br>
   these things need to be the focus of our sermons and discussions.<br>
   Pretending that premarital sex will ruin your sex life forever is not<br>
   a constructive approach, and although "saving yourself" is very<br>
   important it cannot constitute the focus of a message in a time when<br>
   it is too late for a significant proportion of the listeners!<br>
<p>
<p>
Not totally on the topic, I know, but there you have it.<br>
<p>
Tony]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
