<title>Oct_1992: mentally ill at church</title>
<h1>mentally ill at church</h1>
Lola (<i>AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>26 Oct 1992 14:09:20 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#117">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#117">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#117">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#117">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0118.html">Tony: "Re: Home Schooling"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0116.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Home Schooling"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Every week Chester Christie comes to church.  Chester is 65 and not<br>
quite right in the head.  He wanders in and out during the service, but<br>
always waits to see if we're having potluck.  If we are, one of the<br>
women makes sure he gets through line early and gets a seat.  He<br>
generally goes back several times and often takes a plate away with<br>
him afterwards.  If there is no potluck then he asks for a ride down<br>
to the other end of town or somewhere else.  Occasionally his friend<br>
Bill Caudill comes too.  Bill doesn't speak clearly, but he loves to<br>
talk, and at potluck has been known to hold forth on a subject for<br>
10 minutes at a time, with his audience only understanding about every<br>
third word.<br>
<p>
In our congregation of 20-25 (on a good day) these guests are definitely<br>
noticable, by their odor if nothing else.  But they are tolerated and<br>
even welcomed.  We have discussed Jesus' reaction to the outcast of his<br>
day among ourselves, and decided as a congregation to be as genuinely<br>
accepting of these men as possible.  We try to keep in mind the fact that<br>
if you do it unto the least of these, you have done it unto Jesus.<br>
<p>
That doesn't mean that we don't set limits occasionally.  For instance,<br>
Chester collects things in sacks -- junk, aluminum cans, etc.  Often<br>
the sacks are also full of ants and are filthy besides.  One family has<br>
told him that they will take him places, but not the sacks.  I tell him<br>
that the sacks have to go in the bed of the pickup.  Or we limit him<br>
to one destination after church, meaning no, we will not stop and wait<br>
for him to buy milk at the store before taking him on home.  That sort<br>
of thing.<br>
<p>
I know I haven't given any real advice about the problem with the guy<br>
at your church, but thought it might help to hear how it's being handled<br>
somewhere else.<br>
<p>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
