<title>Oct_1992: RE: Home Schooling</title>
<h1>RE: Home Schooling</h1>
Russell Yonkers (<i>ryonkers@mis.mi04.zds.com</i>)<br>
<i>26 Oct 1992 12:50:54 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#119">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#119">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#119">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#119">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0120.html">Lola: "dimensionality of God"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0118.html">Tony: "Re: Home Schooling"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Received-Date: Mon, 26 Oct 92 12:51:04 EST<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I'm not having a go at anyone here, because I certainly believe</i><br>
<i>&gt; that aspect is important. However my personal concerns with home</i><br>
<i>&gt; schooling are more in the area of socialization.</i><br>
<p>
<p>
Russell responds:<br>
<p>
I have 5 kids at home of which 3 are home schooled currently. We made sure <br>
to really investigate the issues involved before taking this step.  We <br>
have found that socialization is not a problem, as a matter of fact studies<br>
show that home schooled kids are better socialized then kids taught<br>
in traditional schooling situations.  <br>
<p>
For a complete discussion on socialization of home schooled kids and the <br>
studies that I mentioned read the book "Home Schooled Kids" by <br>
Dr. Raymond Moore (who also happens to be an SDA).  He is a Phd in <br>
education and has written exhastively about home schooling.  He also<br>
has an excellent show that is broadcast on 3ABN television.  <br>
<p>
To give you a really short summary of the socialization issue the studies<br>
find that home schooled children can interact with all age groups easily<br>
and readily, where traditionally schooled kids develop peer lock and can <br>
only relate well with thier direct peers.  Also the traditionally schooled<br>
kids have a much greater problem with dealing with peer pressure then home<br>
schooled kids due to the dependancy of traditionally schooled kids develop <br>
to peer acceptance.<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Now there is an argument that says we don't want our children</i><br>
<i>&gt; socialized into modern Western culture. I can see the point in</i><br>
<i>&gt; trying to ensure that as they grow up the adopt the appropriate</i><br>
<i>&gt; values, and that many of these are not widely held today.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
We find that our kids have a better education and also better socialization<br>
then other kids.  It is this reason that we home school rather then trying<br>
to schelter (sp) them from the world.  We find that they relate with the world<br>
much better then thier peers.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
