<title>Oct_1992: dimensionality of God</title>
<h1>dimensionality of God</h1>
Lola (<i>AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>26 Oct 1992 13:53:04 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#120">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#120">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#120">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#120">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0121.html">Lola: "homeschooling"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0119.html">Russell Yonkers: "RE: Home Schooling"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Thank you Dave Thomas for the discussion awhile back on the possible<br>
multi-dimensionality of God and the comparison to Flatland.  I read<br>
Flatland years ago but hadn't thought of it since.  This idea of God<br>
being beyond our number of dimensiions and therefore very difficult,<br>
if not impossible, for us to comprehend makes a great deal of sense<br>
to me.  It also makes a lot of our theological arguements somewhat<br>
pointless...   Although I'm not sure I agree with Tony that we will<br>
be embarassed in heaven when we find out hhow wrong we were -- I think<br>
we will just be so overwhelmed and happy to be there that any other<br>
emotions will be insignificant in comparison.<br>
<p>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
