<title>Oct_1992: homeschooling</title>
<h1>homeschooling</h1>
Lola (<i>AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>26 Oct 1992 13:57:48 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#121">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#121">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#121">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#121">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0122.html">Russell Yonkers: "Re: Home Schooling"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0120.html">Lola: "dimensionality of God"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
As others have pointed out, a lot depends on the quality of the<br>
various schools, whether public, private, or at home.  Here in our<br>
little church we have some homeschooled kids who I believe would be<br>
schooled at home even if we had a church school nearby, which we don't.<br>
But, they belong to some homeschool cooperatives that organize field<br>
trips, etc. and they are also active in the youth programs of other<br>
(non-SDA) churches in the area.  These kids get PLENTY of interaction<br>
with their peer groups and do not feel at all out of it because they<br>
go to school at home.  Home school doesn't necessarily mean that the<br>
kids are home with just mom all day anymore...<br>
<p>
There is an interest in the educational research field in homeschooling.<br>
However, I haven't seen the lastest reports of what has been found.<br>
Given that I started in public school at age 4, then switched to church<br>
school at 6, I don't feel it did me any harm.  However, I may well<br>
homeschool my children (first one due in 2 weeks!) because I have seen<br>
it work so well for the family here and they could provide me with<br>
all kinds of support and resources.<br>
<p>
Slightly off the topic, but still in the area of socialization of kids,<br>
do you have any idea how hard it is to explain to people why you would<br>
rather they didn't give you baby gifts that are keyed to TV?  Anyone<br>
who asks me what I would like or not like as shower gifts gets this<br>
little spiel from me:  no Sesame Street, no Ninja Turtles, no Little<br>
Mermaid, etc.  We don't have a TV, so these would be meaningless to my<br>
child anyway.  The predominance of these sorts of images in the public<br>
schools is enough to make me consider home schooling, not to mention<br>
the wholeheartedness with which they celebrate Halloween here in KY!<br>
<p>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
