<title>Oct_1992: Re: Homeschool</title>
<h1>Re: Homeschool</h1>
Russell Yonkers (<i>ryonkers@mis.mi04.zds.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 26 Oct 92 13:08:54 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#124">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#124">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#124">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#124">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0125.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Resurrection of Moses"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0123.html">Russell Yonkers: "Re: Home Schooling"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0078.html">Raylene: "Different people in our churches"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;DaveB</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;Our personal experience with home schooling is that it is the best</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;option available for those who have that option.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; One of the reasons why I questioned home-schooling in the first place was</i><br>
<i>&gt; because of an experience I had while practice teaching a few years ago.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; There was a girl in one of my classes who had not gone to school because her</i><br>
<i>&gt; parents had been caught up in some conservative movement that questioned</i><br>
<i>&gt; the morality and spirituality of both state and SDA schools. When I saw</i><br>
<i>&gt; her she had just begun school against her parents wishes.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; She was a 16 year old girl in a class of 14 year olds. She was a very nice, </i><br>
<i>&gt; cooperative student, and aimed to please.I don't know how she was going in </i><br>
<i>&gt; English or History but I know how she was going in Mathematics and Science:</i><br>
<i>&gt; she had no knowledge of these subjects at a high school level at all.</i><br>
<i>&gt; Her maths teacher was giving her a lot of individual tutoring, starting with</i><br>
<i>&gt; topics from the first year of high school. In science, it was very much the</i><br>
<i>&gt; same. I would be conducting a practical class in science and needed to be</i><br>
<i>&gt; constantly giving her that extra bit of assistance.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
Russell replys:<br>
<p>
I would, as a home schooling family, state that the most important thing<br>
to remember about home schooling is that you have to be dedicated to home<br>
schooling.  It is not an easy choice and you need to constantly study and <br>
prepare so that  you can give your kids the ultimate education.<br>
<p>
My wife works full time at keeping the home and home schooling the kids.<br>
I help out with the education in the areas that she feels a little lacking.<br>
We make constant trips to the teachers store and spend a significant amount<br>
of funds on magazenes and books.  Anyone can tell that we run a school in our<br>
house when they go the school room and see all of the posters and other school<br>
nicknacks on the wall.  If a parent has trouble in a certain area there are <br>
several excellent correspondance programs to assist.  Of course if the parents<br>
have a complete distrust of anyone from the "establishment" then they will <br>
be reluctant to get any of the needed and available help.<br>
<p>
Please make sure that you don't judge all home schoolers by one or two <br>
problems.  Most of the home schoolers I have met are exceptional!!<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
