<title>Oct_1992: Re: Home Schooling</title>
<h1>Re: Home Schooling</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 28 Oct 1992 09:32:48 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#127">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#127">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#127">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#127">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0128.html">Tony: "Re: Resurrection of Moses"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0126.html">David Plaisted: "Home Schooling"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0133.html">Dan Hamstra: "Home Schooling"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I've noticed that some people who are home schooling are posting from the <br>
state of Michigan.  This is interesting because I knew an SDA family <br>
in Michigan who were home-schooling their children, and as a result of this<br>
when they refused to send the children to public school custody was taken<br>
from the father and stepmother and given to the natural mother of the<br>
children.  It was my understanding of the law that if home schooling is <br>
to be attempted in the state of Michigan, a certified teacher must be<br>
associated with the home school.<br>
Of course, I am also acquainted with several families in a different city<br>
who didn't follow this rule and got away with it.<br>
<p>
The position of most conference education departments (and again I speak<br>
of Michigan as the case I know best) is that as long as there is not a <br>
SDA church school within driving distance, home schooling is fine and they <br>
will support it.  Also for the children of evangelists and such who are <br>
always on the road.  They look less favorably on those who do it to "get<br>
even" with a local church school (and believe me there are plenty of <br>
those cases.)<br>
<p>
Tony mentioned that sometimes those who home school are viewed as anti-<br>
establishment or disloyal.  At one point my home church was faced with <br>
a situation where the pastor decided to home-school his kids for a year,<br>
partly because of a feud with the local teacher.  Resentment built up<br>
against the pastor, and the pastor led a counter-move against the teacher,<br>
which eventually culminated in both of them being asked to move.  (I must say<br>
that at the end of the year his kids were none the worse for wear and<br>
advanced to the next grade normally when they re-entered church school.)<br>
<p>
This has influenced my feelings about home school and was the background<br>
of the statement a few months ago when I made statements about home school<br>
and the Moores that I was trying to retract.  On the other hand, some of the<br>
most kind, cultured, and intelligent people I know have been products of <br>
home schools.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
