<title>Oct_1992: Re: Resurrection of Moses</title>
<h1>Re: Resurrection of Moses</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>29 Oct 1992 01:05:00 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#128">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#128">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#128">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#128">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0129.html">Tony: "Re: Resurrection of Moses"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0127.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Home Schooling"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0125.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Resurrection of Moses"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0129.html">Tony: "Re: Resurrection of Moses"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Good questions all, Cheryl, I say. Here are a couple of things that<br>
occurred to me off the top of my head...they're a bit silly, but what<br>
the heck, it *is* one o' clock in the morning...<br>
<p>
Hypothesis 1: God can do whatever he/she wants<br>
<p>
	Maybe God wanted to resurrect Moses, and translate those<br>
	other guys. So, if Jesus hadn't ended up winning the war,<br>
	maybe God would have had to give the gentlemen back to<br>
	Satan in the end.<br>
<p>
Hypothesis 2: God is not subject to chronology<br>
<p>
	We like to say in roundabout ways that God is outside<br>
	of time somehow. So just because we perceive things in<br>
	a certain order doesn't mean that God and everybody<br>
	else is subject to our determination of past and future.<br>
<p>
Hypothesis 3: Everybody knows that Jesus always *was* going to win<br>
<p>
	If God knows all events in space-time then he/she knew<br>
	that Lucifer would rebel, that mankind would rebel, and<br>
	that eventually Jesus would have to become a man and <br>
	die. But God went ahead and created life anyway. Maybe<br>
	sin was inevitable...finite probability, infinite time<br>
	equals inevitable. So the "plan of salvation" really<br>
        was always there, and was not just a fallback measure<br>
        in case things went wrong. Then the predetermination<br>
        of Jesus' death was acceptable, so Enoch, Moses and<br>
        Elijah went ahead in advance.<br>
<p>
<p>
Thought experiments only...no SOP quotes or Bible texts, so don't<br>
think I'm trying to suggest that these ideas be adopted by<br>
anyone with integrity...<br>
<p>
<p>
Tony<br>
<p>
P.S. The secret rapture is supposed to occur in exactly fifty six<br>
     minutes time, according to some guy I saw on the TV news<br>
     earlier. Yes, he did remember to include daylight saving<br>
     which started last weekend.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
