<title>Oct_1992: Re: Resurrection of Moses</title>
<h1>Re: Resurrection of Moses</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>28 Oct 1992 09:22:05 +1100</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#129">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#129">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#129">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#129">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0130.html">Tony: "Re: Dimensionality of God"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0128.html">Tony: "Re: Resurrection of Moses"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0125.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Resurrection of Moses"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
For those of you who have chosen to home school your kids, I would<br>
be interested to hear whether you have elected to do so as an alternative<br>
to church school, or due to the lack of a church school in your area. The<br>
reason I ask is that some day in the future I could end up working within<br>
the SDA education system, and I would like to be sure I understand the<br>
motivation behind home schooling. I don't know what things are like in<br>
the US, but here in the South Pacific our schools are generally only<br>
just surviving financially, and I know that church members who "withhold"<br>
their kids from the local church school are sometimes viewed with some<br>
disdain by other "loyal" church members. I don't like to misinterpret<br>
what people are doing, so I'd like to hear what you people have to say.<br>
<p>
Also, my feelings regarding home schooling are tempered somewhat by the<br>
types of people who tend to promote it in Australia. Typically these<br>
people will be very right wing, anti-establishment, anti-leadership<br>
and all the other things that go with that mindset. For example, one<br>
such person in my local neighbourhood who has just taken his children<br>
out of school and moved to the country (not that Cooranbong is a<br>
metropolis) is also involved with the publication of a nasty little<br>
paper called "The Protestant". This paper is an independent ministry-<br>
type thing I think, and is very offensive to the general reader. So much<br>
so that when the church authorities couldn't persuade the publishers to<br>
desist, they eventually had to obtain a court order to ensure that the<br>
publication was clearly marked as not officialy sanctioned by the SDA<br>
church. Following this, these guys still print it, and recently it was<br>
mailed to every household in this region. It was also distributed <br>
around the area where the North New South Wales camp meeting was held<br>
a couple of weeks ago. Much of the good relationship which had been<br>
established with the local community was destroyed instantly, when<br>
people discovered what SDAs were "really like".<br>
<p>
I myself am quite the opposite, I am anti-separationist if you like, and<br>
so I have found myself a bit negative towards home schooling partly <br>
because it seems to represent the whole separationist attitude.<br>
<p>
So, home-schoolers, if you do not see yourselves as anti-establishment<br>
and separationist, please let me know, and tell me why you've still<br>
gone ahead and home-schooled your kids!<br>
<p>
Thanks,<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
