<title>Oct_1992: Election</title>
<h1>Election</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 28 Oct 1992 09:53:13 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#132">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#132">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#132">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#132">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0133.html">Dan Hamstra: "Home Schooling"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0131.html">Sheryl Skinner: "Introduction"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0136.html">Daniel D Deavours: "Re: Election"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Sheryl Skinner's post is one of the few who has dared ask the question<br>
of what candidate are people going to support in the US presidential<br>
election.  As moderator, I don't think it's appropriate that I make my<br>
choice known until after the election.  There will be no editorial <br>
endorsements from SDAnet.  (Although now, as opposed to a couple weeks<br>
ago, I have made a choice.)  I must admit it was all a lot simpler back<br>
in the days when God was a Republican and Mrs. White said to vote straight<br>
Republican and no on all the proposals.  (She did say that somewhere,<br>
didn't she?  (&lt;---Note:  Sarcasm alert the last two sentences)<br>
<p>
With apologies to our overseas readers (20% or so) who couldn't care less<br>
about the US elections, we will make a few comments.  Traditionally <br>
religious liberty has been a big concern to SDA voters, although I have<br>
always wondered, why not vote for the most anti-religious freedom<br>
character you can get, thus hastening the Sunday Law, persecution, and<br>
the growth of the church that will result?  In 1984, the issue came up<br>
in the presidential<br>
debate, but in this campaign it's not been mentioned.<br>
<p>
Sheryl voiced concern about Perot.  I attended his rally in Pittsburgh<br>
on Sunday and saw him in person.  It seems to me that he views the<br>
constitution almost as a roadblock; he has proposed more amendments to it<br>
than even Bush has.  <br>
<p>
None of the candidates has mentioned HR2797, the Religious Freedom<br>
Restoration Act, which Bush might well have signed but which died in<br>
committee due to much lobbying from anti-abortion groups, based on the<br>
false notion that it is really designed to protect abortion rights. <br>
Note that this act is sponsored in the Senate by Senator Kennedy (you<br>
know what religion he is.)  <br>
<p>
I think we face an election where the choice is important but not obvious.<br>
If anyone has more information on the religious liberty stands of the<br>
candidates, be sure to let us know.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
