<title>Oct_1992: Home Schooling</title>
<h1>Home Schooling</h1>
Dan Hamstra (<i>hamstra@peter.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 28 Oct 1992 08:46:47 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#133">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#133">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#133">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#133">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0134.html">Dan Hamstra: "U.S. Presidential Election"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0132.html">Steven Timm: "Election"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0064.html">Tony: "Re: Home Schooling"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I must confess that I have not been reading all of the discussion on home<br>
schooling that has been transpiring so pardon me if I point out something<br>
that has already been mentioned.<br>
<p>
While I am very much in agreement with the concepts of home schooling (I<br>
have 5 nephews and 2 nieces who are/were home schooled) there is a<br>
significant factor that I feel may skew home schooling effectiveness<br>
statistics to the positive end of the scale.  A number of those who home<br>
school in the U.S. are people who might be considered economically or<br>
professionally advantaged over the broader population.  Most of the home<br>
schooling situations that I am personally acquainted with involved families<br>
that would not be considered representative of the population as a whole. <br>
I read of one home schooling situation where both parents were PhD's<br>
teaching at a major university when one of them (I don't remember which)<br>
left their teaching position to home school their only child.  While having<br>
a PhD does not necessarily mean that someone will be a good teacher, I<br>
suspect that a home environment of that sort would result in an educational<br>
experience that would likely give the child(ren) a good likelihood of<br>
scoring high on standardized tests.<br>
<p>
dan<br>
hamstra@andrews.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
