<title>Oct_1992: U.S. Presidential Election</title>
<h1>U.S. Presidential Election</h1>
Dan Hamstra (<i>hamstra@peter.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 28 Oct 1992 11:39:52 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#134">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#134">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#134">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#134">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0135.html">Cam Litvin: "Election"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0133.html">Dan Hamstra: "Home Schooling"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have heard through two or three grapevines that the GC/NAD religious<br>
liberty dept is encouraging people to vote for Clinton due to Supreme Court<br>
appointee considerations.  I  cannot back these rumors up with any hard<br>
facts but I can believe that they are true. (sounds like Ross Perot)<br>
<p>
My personal assessment of the contest goes something like this:<br>
I generally agree with many of Clinton's ideas but I don't think he'll<br>
actually be able to accomplish them because he's indebted to too many<br>
special interests.  I also have a hard time trusting (that trust thing)<br>
that what he says is really what he believes.<br>
<p>
I like a lot of the ideas/attitudes of Perot but I have a major<br>
disagreement with his ideas on foreign relations, free trade, etc.  I am<br>
American who believes that it is inevitable that the rest of the world will<br>
"catch up" with our lifestyle.  If we try to use the White House as a<br>
"bully pulpit" to convince Mexico, Japan, the EC, etc. that we want fair<br>
trade but intend to "stay ahead" of them in wages, it will eventually lead<br>
to the isolation of the U.S. from the rest of the world.<br>
<p>
Then there's our incumbant.  I don't like the fact that he cozy's up to the<br>
religious right, his Supreme Court appointees tend to be a little too<br>
conservative for me, and I don't feel he's put much effort into trying to<br>
cooperate with an "uncooperative" congress.  I like most of his foreign<br>
policy, hate what he's done on education and the environment, and don't<br>
totally blame him for our economic.  I will probably end up voting for him<br>
or perhaps Perot.  I'm 90% certain I will not vote for Clinton.<br>
<p>
There is some interesting data on North American SDA political opinions<br>
that was published recently in "Focus" which is the Andrews University<br>
alumni magazine (I personally think "Focus" is one of the most<br>
professionally designed, written, and edited journals in Adventism - yes, I<br>
am a proud alumnus) and I believe I also saw the same article or a<br>
condensation in the "Adventist Review."  It pointed out how many SDA's have<br>
relatively liberal views, staunchly support church/state separation, and<br>
still end up voting republican.  Guess I'm just one of the crowd.<br>
<p>
dan<br>
hamstra@andrews.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
