<!-- inreplyto="Added.oevikfi00UkT8nZE4M@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<title>Oct_1992: Re: more on dimensions</title>
<h1>Re: more on dimensions</h1>
Trevor Tompkins (<i>tt17+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 28 Oct 1992 18:47:25 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#137">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#137">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#137">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#137">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0138.html">Trevor Tompkins: "Re: Election"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0136.html">Daniel D Deavours: "Re: Election"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Lola and I have been having a little discussion on the dimensionality. <br>
I thought it would be good for me to start posting since my response<br>
digresses and invlolves other aspects of how we as SDA's conceptualize<br>
God.<br>
<p>
	I think you will get the idea by following:<br>
<p>
Lola responds to my letter:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Thanks for your direct comments Trevor, and I can see your point about</i><br>
<i>&gt;not wanting to forsake logic when we come to something difficult to</i><br>
<i>&gt;understand.  However, I also see a danger on the other side:  that we</i><br>
<i>&gt;try to force God into our own boxes (of however many dimensions) and</i><br>
<i>&gt;then insist that He is like we imagine Him to be!  That's why the</i><br>
<i>&gt;Flatland analogy appealed to me -- the two-dimensional world has no</i><br>
<i>&gt;conception of what three dimensions are like, so would find it</i><br>
<i>&gt;difficult to explain 3-dimensional phenomena.  Same here with us.  We</i><br>
<i>&gt;only are good at understanding what happens with regularity HERE --</i><br>
<i>&gt;I don't think we can explain a lot about God and heaven and time, etc.</i><br>
<i>&gt;by using the earth as a model.  I'm always happy to hear people try,</i><br>
<i>&gt;but I reserve judgement on their accuracy!</i><br>
<p>
	My letter here is going to get off your original point, but I  think it<br>
informative to analyze exactly what dimensions are.  There seems to be a<br>
misunderstanding as to what two dimensions and three dimesnions are. <br>
They are only labels, describing area and volume.  In a two dimensional<br>
world, you have area but no volume.  In a three dimensional world you<br>
have  area AND volume.  It is a little absurd to think that anything in<br>
either dimenion can comprehend anything.  Cones in three dimensions<br>
cannot understand circles in two dimesnions, spheres in three<br>
dimensions, or hyperspheres in four dimensions.  The only things that<br>
can understand anything are humans.  But just because we are in three<br>
dimensions does not mean there is a major fundamental misunderstanding<br>
of higher dimensions.  There is no reason to think that anything above<br>
three dimensions is visual.  Dimensions could also lable color, and<br>
black and white. Let dimension 1 be black (can't see a thing), dimension<br>
2 be black and white (can see some things), dimension 3 be color(can see<br>
lots of different things).   What is beyond color?  who knows?  Our<br>
visual sense is only a way to interact in the world.  We say the world<br>
is 3-dimensional, because that is how we have described it.  There is<br>
nothing intrinsic about it.  To show you that different dimensions can<br>
relate think of a computer.  A computer only sees information in a two<br>
dimensional world.  Yet computers model three dimensional problems and<br>
solve them all the time.  We use them in physics constantly.   Further,<br>
we model 4, 5, on up to infinite dimensions on computers. So it is<br>
possible to comprehend, and even talk about other dimensions; you just<br>
have to be very careful when doing so. <br>
<p>
	One other point.  I agree that we should not try to put God in our own<br>
little box.  What is interesting is that we use this argument of not<br>
being able to understand him, in order to refute those who go against<br>
OUR conception of God.  Why do we insist on using ONLY the Bible to base<br>
our conception of God. Further, why is OUR interpretation of the Bible<br>
the right conception of God.  By doing this, we constrain God.  You<br>
might even say we make him 1-dimensional.  Certainly we make him dated.<br>
	<br>
	I doubt that anyone of us has the same connception of God.  We all have<br>
similar conceptions, hence we are Seventh-day Adventists.  But all the<br>
arguments within the church have to do with our different conceptions of<br>
what God is.  I think we get into serious trouble when we base our<br>
conception of God only on the Bible.  There is no way women in our<br>
church are going to be ordained ministers by basing our conception of<br>
God solely on the Bible.  It just isn't there.  Many people have not<br>
understood the history of the Bible nor read it completely.  The Bible<br>
is flat out sexist when it comes to women.  That does not mean it isn't<br>
a good book; or maybe even the best book.  But ordaining women is<br>
unbiblical.  But is ordaining women Ungodly? I don't think so.  I think<br>
the Bible seriously misrepresents God on this point.<br>
<p>
	Sorry about all the digression.  These are only my opinions. <br>
<p>
--Trevor<br>
Carnegie Mellon University<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
