<!-- body="start" -->
While not endorsing any candidate, and still making up my mind.  I think<br>
it should be noted that Perot's amendments have no religious goals in<br>
mind.  They might effect religion, but this certianly isn't his issue. <br>
Bush on the other hand tries to represent a section of religion and thus<br>
knows full well the implications of his ammendments.  Perot seems<br>
interested in making the constitution work better for our country.  The<br>
question is whether he can do it correctly.<br>
<p>
Note:  The constitution was written when people needed "rights."   There<br>
is no denying that we still need rights.  However, economics and history<br>
professors are noticing that this has been to the exclusion of any<br>
efficiency.  The country now is often hampered by the constitution. <br>
Japan's Constitution was set up in the 1940's and therefore reflects a<br>
more management style constitution.  Ours is still in the dark ages.  We<br>
are the only major industrialized country in the world that allows<br>
ordinary citizens to purchase handguns.  It is no wonder that our muder<br>
rate is more than double ALL of Europe.  In fact the murder rate in New<br>
York City alone is higher than all of England and France combined.<br>
<p>
--Trevor<br>
Carnegie Mellon University<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
