<!-- name="Steve Hix" -->
<!-- email="fiddler@dobbs.eng.sun.com" -->
<!-- subject="Re: Homeschooling" -->
<!-- id="9210282347.AA07712@dobbs.Eng.Sun.COM" -->
<!-- inreplyto="Homeschooling" -->
<title>Oct_1992: Re: Homeschooling</title>
<h1>Re: Homeschooling</h1>
Steve Hix (<i>fiddler@dobbs.eng.sun.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 28 Oct 92 15:47:23 PST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#142">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#142">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#142">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#142">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0143.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Dead woman on life support as incubator"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0141.html">Steven Timm: "Annual council:  statements on abortion, care for dying,"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; From: PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; For those of you who have chosen to home school your kids, I would</i><br>
<i>&gt; be interested to hear whether you have elected to do so as an alternative</i><br>
<i>&gt; to church school, or due to the lack of a church school in your area.</i><br>
<p>
We have a local SDA elementary school.  Our two daughters were home-schooled<br>
'till they were 9, then to the local school for a few years...<br>
<p>
We pulled them out after an horrific year involving a teacher/principal who<br>
finally was unable to keep his stories straight (I got one line, my wife got<br>
another, the kids got a third, and so on).  In any case, we pulled them out<br>
and went back to homeschooling.  We tried, though.  Really.  (He ended up<br>
calling the school board chairman one day in July and said, thanks, but I<br>
have a new position in another state, so don't expect me or my wife to be<br>
teaching the next session.  We'll ignore the financial issues which got<br>
cleared up during the next two years.)<br>
<p>
Rather than jerk the girls around in and out, we've kept them at home and<br>
put in the extra time and effort.  (Scholastically, the effort has been<br>
rewarded quite nicely.  In other areas, things have improved, too.)<br>
<p>
Socialization? I believe that both girls do better than their local peers,<br>
having to deal with people ranging from younger children to adults (most of<br>
their peers spend most of their time interacting with the same group of kids<br>
from grades school through high school.  Not all, but most.)<br>
<p>
I did have one fellow castigate me for "depriving" our kids of the<br>
inestimable benefits of regular television viewing: "...how can they hope to<br>
relate to their peers?..."<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; So, home-schoolers, if you do not see yourselves as anti-establishment</i><br>
<i>&gt; and separationist, please let me know, and tell me why you've still</i><br>
<i>&gt; gone ahead and home-schooled your kids!</i><br>
<p>
I have come to the feeling that formal schools are there for those<br>
families who are unable to devote time and resources to teaching their<br>
own children.  There are things that you can't do at home, but I feel that<br>
they are more than balanced out by the greater flexibility available to the<br>
home schooler: how long can a typical teacher afford to work with a single<br>
student who just doesn't seem to be able to "get" some basic part of<br>
algebra, or skim by unnecessary background to let a student maintain momentum<br>
when she's got it cold from the start.  (Or set up and run a baking business,<br>
or agricultural/science project for a third-grader or...)<br>
<p>
We still support the local school, btw, with things like computer equipment<br>
support, revising and reprinting the school bulletin, and so on.<br>
<p>
We're also planning on sending the girls to academy (probably Weimar, as far<br>
as we can tell right now) for two years before college, and from there to<br>
(probably) PUC.<br>
<p>
Some things we feel we can do better, some things the schools can do better,<br>
we try to figure out which is best for our kids and move accordingly.<br>
<p>
We pay taxes for the public schools that we don't use, we pay tithe and offering<br>
for the church schools (whether using them or not)...but others do need what the<br>
schools offer, so that's OK with me.<br>
<p>
Wonder where the money for college is going to come from, sometimes.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
