<title>Oct_1992: Dead woman on life support as incubator</title>
<h1>Dead woman on life support as incubator</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 28 Oct 92 23:14:15 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#143">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#143">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#143">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#143">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0144.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: Annual council:  statements on abortion, care for dying,"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0142.html">Steve Hix: "Re: Homeschooling"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Tonight on CNN there was a story about an 18 year old woman who is<br>
legally dead but is being kept on life support because she is pregnant.<br>
The woman is in a German hospital and is only 15 weeks along.  The doctors<br>
will keep her on life support until March 1993 when the baby will be near<br>
term.  Then they will deliver the baby by Cesearean section and then<br>
disconnect life support.  In fact, the death certificate has already been<br>
filled out according to the news story.<br>
<p>
What do you think about this?  Apparently the Pope has voice deep concern<br>
about the ethics of keeping a woman alive solely for this purpose.  Can<br>
you imagine the expense involved in this?  The grandparents have voiced<br>
strong support in keeping their daughter in this state until their grand-<br>
child is born.  They have been encouraged by the doctors to bring in toys<br>
and objects that make noice to "stimulate" the baby.  They have also been<br>
advised to hug and touch the woman's body as much as possible for the<br>
baby's sake.<br>
<p>
What do think about the effects this may have on the child?  Could it have<br>
serious consequences on its development and intellect?  Just curious. <br>
<p>
Personally, I think this is morally and ethically wrong.  To keep a dead<br>
person on life support solely as an incubator seems inhumane.  There is no<br>
question that this woman is brain-dead.  There is no chance (short of a<br>
true miracle) that she will live once life support is disconnected.<br>
<p>
What do you think about this?<br>
<p>
cheryl<br>
<p>
----------------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
          Cheryl L. Berthelsen, Ph.D., Assistant Professor<br>
              Health Information Administration Program<br>
                 School of Allied Health Professions<br>
                  University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee<br>
                  email:  cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu<br>
	          phone:  (414) 229-6051<br>
