<title>Oct_1992: Re: Election</title>
<h1>Re: Election</h1>
Steve Hix (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 29 Oct 1992 21:18:10 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#147">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#147">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#147">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#147">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0148.html">Pam Harris: "Life Support as Incubator"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0146.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Re: more on dimensions"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0151.html">Pam Harrris: "Election"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
This post is from Steve Hix<br>
[...Steve, I know this falls outside the normally-set<br>
limits of discussion in this group, but the comments<br>
below slipped through, and some corrections ought to<br>
be made...]<br>
[  I'm allowing all sorts of "politics" comments until the election.<br>
After all, the SDA church is as political as any other place.  SCT]<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; From st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu Wed Oct 28 18:57:53 1992</i><br>
<i>&gt; We are the only major industrialized country in the world that allows</i><br>
<i>&gt; ordinary citizens to purchase handguns.</i><br>
<p>
This is incorrect (although widely believed).  I have personal<br>
contact with citizens of many of the countries implied in the<br>
comment above, and almost without exception they have given me<br>
the required procedures for legally owning handguns in each of<br>
their respective countries.  (Most generally begin by the person<br>
joining a local shooting club.  Costs, pre-requisites, etc. change<br>
with the country in question.)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; It is no wonder that our muder rate is more than double ALL of Europe.</i><br>
<p>
Two points: <br>
<p>
1. The comparatively-lower homicide rates predate anti-gun<br>
   legislation in those countries whose rates are below the U.S. <br>
   (England, for instance had a rate about 1/16 ours when the<br>
   first laws passed around 1920, currently, their rate is about<br>
   1/4 ours.  Not a net gain.)<br>
<p>
2. If one subtracts the rates of about 10 major cities in the<br>
   U.S., such as New York City, Washington, D.C., Detroit, Chicago,<br>
   Los Angeles, etc., the remaining rate is at or below european<br>
   levels.  (Note that most of these cities prohibit or restrict<br>
   legal gun ownership: the laws aren't obviously helping.)<br>
<p>
The problem with gun laws is that the ones who obey them aren't<br>
the ones who cause most, if not all, of the trouble.  The laws<br>
are trying to deal with a symptom (if that) and ignoring the<br>
root problem, which is sin.  (It wouldn't be so bad, but the<br>
cure seems to make things worse, for a number of reasons I<br>
won't go into now.)<br>
<p>
I used to be strongly pro-gun-control, but I have reluctantly<br>
come to the decision that as a solution to a problem, it's<br>
barking up the wrong tree.  (It's a solution that is simple,<br>
elegant, and ineffective.)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; In fact the murder rate in New York City alone is higher than</i><br>
<i>&gt; all of England and France combined.</i><br>
<p>
Let's not mix up rates and raw numbers. Not the same thing.  :}<br>
<p>
If anyone wants to discuss/argue this or related subjects, you've <br>
got my email address.  This belongs offline.<br>
<p>
Back to our normal programming...  :}<br>
<p>
<p>
	Steve Hix	fiddler@concertina.Eng.Sun.com<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
