<title>Oct_1992: Life Support as Incubator</title>
<h1>Life Support as Incubator</h1>
Pam Harris (<i>HARRISP@UTKVX.UTCC.UTK.EDU</i>)<br>
<i>29 Oct 1992 20:59:12 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#148">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#148">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#148">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#148">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0149.html">Trevor Tompkins: "Re: Southeastern Calif. Conference"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0147.html">Steve Hix: "Re: Election"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
What is the difference in turning off the life support and letting the<br>
baby die and abortion? Shouldn't the child have a chance to live if we<br>
can at all make it possible? When my 8-month-pregnant sister-in-law was<br>
killed in an automobile accident, the baby died, too. What if the baby<br>
had been able to be saved? Be it a month or more, doesn't it make sense<br>
to try to preserve life rather than snuff it out?<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
