<title>Oct_1992: Re: Southeastern Calif. Conference</title>
<h1>Re: Southeastern Calif. Conference</h1>
Trevor Tompkins (<i>tt17+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 29 Oct 1992 23:04:35 -0500 (EST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#149">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#149">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#149">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#149">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0150.html">Pam Harrris: "Election and the Religious Right"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0148.html">Pam Harris: "Life Support as Incubator"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0139.html">Steven Timm: "Southeastern Calif. Conference"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0152.html">Pam Harrris: "Re: Southeastern Calif. Conference"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Having grown up in the SE California Conference I can tell you that no<br>
one really wants that job.  They (the conference leaders) lead the<br>
candidate to believe that he or she can run the conference  through his<br>
or her vision, but it is impossible to do so.  The president of the<br>
conference ends up being squeezed, by the local and general conference. <br>
While former president Gifford hasn't stated why he resigned, I can see<br>
why he stepped down.  Several times he tried to implement changes, and<br>
every time he was shot down. <br>
<p>
	The SE California Conference, has many large SDA institutions<br>
represented in it, and all of them are very powerful.  The LLU Medical<br>
Center, La Sierra University, Loma Linda Foods, University Church, etc. <br>
By the way, all of these institutions have there own problems, which<br>
makes it even more difficult.  Both La Sierra and LLU have financial<br>
problems, and LLU has been severley criticized by an independent<br>
academic freedom committee, which essentially said that it doesn't like<br>
the gastopo tactics used there.  Of course the attempt to unify the two<br>
universities has now put more than a few people at odds with eachother<br>
(Heavenly isn't it?).  <br>
<p>
	A similar vacancy problem occurred when Louis Venden left the<br>
University Church.  This is the largest SDA church in the country, and<br>
in the center of many of these other institutions.  They had to get Bill<br>
Loveless, former president of CUC, because he was really the only person<br>
with the experience to run the university church (he was the pastor<br>
before Louis Venden).  This church is not like running any other church.<br>
 You have to be more than a minister.  You really have to be a good<br>
politician.  I'm not making any analogies to American politics <br>
whatsoever.  My point is that if you are not a good politician, you will<br>
be pushed around by all of the other organizations there.  You have to<br>
live there to know what I mean.<br>
<p>
--Trevor<br>
Carnegie Mellon University<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0150.html">Pam Harrris: "Election and the Religious Right"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0148.html">Pam Harris: "Life Support as Incubator"</a>
