<title>Oct_1992: Election and the Religious Right</title>
<h1>Election and the Religious Right</h1>
Pam Harrris (<i>HARRISP@UTKVX.UTCC.UTK.EDU</i>)<br>
<i>29 Oct 1992 23:45:37 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#150">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#150">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#150">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#150">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0151.html">Pam Harrris: "Election"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0149.html">Trevor Tompkins: "Re: Southeastern Calif. Conference"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
There is deep cause for concern when one considers the Religious Right's<br>
agenda to make the U.S. a Christian nation. It is this political interst<br>
group which took credit for Reagan-Bush's election. Bush has not forgotten<br>
his debt to this organization. Consider:<br>
	* his record of Supreme Court nominees (Thomas, especially)<br>
	* his speech to religious broadcasters the day after the<br>
	  Republican Convention proclaiming that God was in the<br>
	  Republican platform and blaming the Democrats for leaving<br>
	  God out of theirs<br>
	* the Pat Robertson-organized Christian Warriors who are<br>
	  backing Bush and who will want pay back if he returns to office<br>
	* Bush's statement on the record that he will do anything to<br>
	  get elected.<br>
<p>
The balance of the Supreme Court is a serious issue. Although some may<br>
rate it way down the line when prioritizing the issues, remember that<br>
Justice Blackmun may retire soon creating another vacancy to be filled<br>
by the next president. This is a Court very interested in religious issues.<br>
Already for the 1992-93 term, the Court has accepted three church-state<br>
cases. The Court was split on the Weisman case (prayer at graduations) 5-4<br>
indicating how close these church-state issues are.<br>
<p>
Gov. Clinton has made clear his stand on separation of church and state.<br>
We can also look at his record of judicial appointments in Arkansas for<br>
a clue to the types of judges he appoints. He has a strong record for<br>
appointing minorities and women indicating his interest in balance.<br>
<p>
I became a much better informed Adventist by researching Jerry Falwell's<br>
attempt to get tax-free bonds for Liberty University. The Supreme Court<br>
of Virginia unanimously ruled against him on the issue of Separation of<br>
Church and State. However, the Religious Right was very interested in<br>
appealing this case to the Supreme Court as a test since they believe<br>
Christians are discriminated against since they are Christians. The<br>
expense and a technicality (the case was not in Liberty University's name)<br>
prevented the appeal. I was shocked at the deceit used in the case<br>
to represent Liberty University as a secular school in order to get<br>
the funding. I wrote a two-part article on this fascinating case.<br>
(Forgive me for saying it won a Society of Professional Journalists<br>
Mark of Excellence Award and the Associated Church Press's Award<br>
of Merit.) <br>
<p>
See this week's Washington Post Nation Weekly Edition (Oct.26-Nov. 1)<br>
for the article, "The Supreme Court Gets Religion," page 33.<br>
<p>
<p>
If you have access to a University Library, you might want to read<br>
an eye-opening chapter in the second edition of MEDIATED POLITICAL<br>
REALITIES, by Dan Nimmo and James E. Combs, Chapter 9, "The Fantasies<br>
of Religious Movements: Political Perspectives of Contemporary Evangelists."<br>
<p>
Pam Harris<br>
University of Tennessee<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
