<title>Oct_1992: Election</title>
<h1>Election</h1>
Pam Harrris (<i>71172.2044@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>30 Oct 92 03:32:22 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#151">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#151">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#151">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#151">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0152.html">Pam Harrris: "Re: Southeastern Calif. Conference"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0150.html">Pam Harrris: "Election and the Religious Right"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0147.html">Steve Hix: "Re: Election"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Two postings regarding the upcoming election raised some questions that I<br>
would like to address.  Since it's about politics AND religion, I won't<br>
hazard an opinion as to whether it is more heat or light...<br>
<p>
Like many voters, I find myself frustrated at the lack of moderate,<br>
responsible canditates, i.e., one with the courage to face up to fiscal<br>
realities but without a punitive social agenda.  Where are our Jeffersons<br>
and Madisons?<br>
<p>
While I appreciate Mr Perot's call to fiscal responsibility, and even find<br>
some of his proposals reasonable (higher fuel/tobacco taxes and lower<br>
defense budgets have been a mainstay argument of publications like the<br>
Economist for years!), it is all too obvious that the only way he could<br>
run the country on his own terms is by getting changes to the<br>
constitution.  Are we as a people this close to buying in to "emergency<br>
dictitorial power"?<br>
<p>
Mr Bush has practiced too much borrow and spend, and his links to the<br>
Religious Right are all too evident in his handling of anti-abortion,<br>
school prayer, and school voucher issues.  More tangibly, and with even<br>
more devastating long-term effect, are his right wing appointments to the<br>
US Supreme Court.  One more ultra-conservative on the court could trigger<br>
an avalanche of changes to the constitution and this nation as we know it.<br>
<p>
Mr Clinton's party has a long, expensive history of tax and spend.  Yet he<br>
has been the only canditate to make any clear separationist statement.  To<br>
qoute from his 11 Sept speech at Notre Dame, "All of us must respect the<br>
reflection of God's image in every man and woman and so we must value<br>
their  freedom, not just their political freedom, but their freedom of<br>
conscience in matters of family and philosophy and faith. ... Our freedom<br>
of conscience depends on mutual respect. ... I have been appalled to hear<br>
the voices of intolerance raised ... that some Americans aren't real<br>
Americans, and ... that what this country needs is a religious war.  Well,<br>
America does not need a religious war. ..."  <br>
<p>
Personally, I consider myself a political conservative.  So conservative,<br>
I tell my friends, that I am very nearly a Libertarian  (you know,<br>
someone who manages to infuriate both sides!).  This year, I have to put<br>
my consience and Jeffersonian ideals together with a hope that maybe,<br>
just maybe, Mr Clinton is not all rhetoric, and that the Democratic Party<br>
has learned something about fiscal reality.<br>
<p>
The difficulty I have (and I hope it was a rhetorical question) with<br>
voting for the least separationist canditate (either Perot or Bush) and<br>
therefore speed up the eschatological horrors, is that I cannot be part<br>
of the problem.  I will only appeal to biblical instances such as<br>
Abraham, Moses, etc., tried to accelerate God's plan ...<br>
 <br>
The latest issues of Liberty Magazine and Church &amp; State have several<br>
articles that I hope U.S. voters will take time to find (check with any<br>
SDA conference) and read.  Mr Clinton's speech should be available via. a<br>
local newspaper or the Democratic Party. (when I read excerpts in these<br>
magazines, and saw last night's posting, I had a copy of the full speech<br>
faxed to me, about 11 pages) <br>
<p>
Dave Johnson<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Distribution:<br>
  Steven Timm &gt;INTERNET:st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu<br>
  Steven Timm &gt;INTERNET:st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
