<!-- id="921030105411_71172.2044_CHK32-1@CompuServe.COM" -->
<!-- inreplyto="Southeastern Calif. Conference" -->
<title>Oct_1992: Re: Southeastern Calif. Conference</title>
<h1>Re: Southeastern Calif. Conference</h1>
Pam Harrris (<i>71172.2044@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>30 Oct 92 05:54:12 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#152">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#152">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#152">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#152">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0153.html">Fred Christiansen: "Halloween or Reformation Day?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0151.html">Pam Harrris: "Election"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0139.html">Steven Timm: "Southeastern Calif. Conference"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In for a dime, in for a dollar!  Sorry this is so long...<br>
<p>
The Southeastern California Conference (we use 'SECC' freqently!) met for<br>
its 7th Triennial Session on September 20 with four "major" issues:<br>
  1) Election of President<br>
  2) Authority/Relationship of Minority Leaders<br>
  3) Position on Gender Inclusiveness &amp; Ordination<br>
  4) Tithe Percentage<br>
<p>
SECC's requirements for conducting constituency sessions include: small<br>
meetings in various parts of the territory with delegates, for the<br>
purposes of discussing potential agenda items; the election of a<br>
nominating committee 7 weeks prior to the meeting; and that the committee<br>
and session chairpersons are not (unless so elected) the Union President.<br>
All toward the good end of open and democratic process as befits a<br>
representative form of governance.<br>
<p>
There was clear evidence of caucusing taking place when certian minority<br>
groups promoted uniform "straw votes" when polled at the various delegate<br>
meetings.<br>
The nominating committee received over 60 different names for the<br>
position of President, and finally nominated a relative unknown, Mr Craig<br>
Newborn.  He served as a teacher in San Diego Academy, then<br>
teacher/minister/administrator in Keyna, Iran, Lebanon, and then returned<br>
to the US where he currently serves as a bible teacher at Loma Linda<br>
Academy.  He was opposed by a vocal group in the African-American<br>
community (he is black) who preferred another name, and by the<br>
denominational heirarchy, who protested his qualifications.<br>
On the 20th, the vote on rules and agenda was delayed 4 hours by<br>
arguments and positioning from both opposing sides.  When Mr Newborn's<br>
name was put to the delegation, a motion to refer back to the nominating<br>
committee was, after some argument, passed.<br>
<p>
The delegation turned to reports and other business while waiting for the<br>
committee.  Among them was a proposal from the Gender Inclusiveness Task<br>
Force, a group established by mandate of the 1989 constituency.  The text<br>
of this proposal runs a full page and I can transcribe it if enough of you<br>
want it.  The heart of the proposal is:<br>
	... because of the gender discrimiation which that vote [1990 GC<br>
Session] represents, we request our conference leaders to devise a plan by<br>
which qualified women ministers whom we employ be ordained for ministry<br>
within our jurisdiction of the world church ...  SECC desires to eliminate<br>
further discrimination in our conference by uniformly conducting all<br>
future ordinations of qualified men and women ministers, ...<br>
This proposal passed (328/254) with little objection from the floor. <br>
Later on the 18th, a motion to take things even farther by removing the<br>
Union from the ordination process (it is standard that conferences merely<br>
recommend names to the union office, who then approve/deny ordination<br>
credentials) was defeated 214/272.<br>
The current feeling is that "uniformly conducting" may well mean that SECC<br>
will, until policies change at higher levels, forward NO names for<br>
ordination.  It is amazing how much heat that the MEN now have on this<br>
subject!<br>
<p>
The delegation proceeded with several constitutional changes, including<br>
naming the African-American, Asian, and Hispanic coordinators as Vice<br>
Presidents (they serve under the President, Secretary, and Treasurer)<br>
which then gives them permanent voting privileges on the Executive<br>
Committee.  That committee was then enlarged by 3 lay positions to<br>
maintain a 50% lay representation. <br>
<p>
The nominating committee reaffirmed after 5 hours of discussion the name<br>
of Mr Newborn.  Bitter debate and more parlimentary jockying followed,<br>
culminating in a vote against Mr Newborn, 202/361.<br>
The nominating committee immediately named Dr David Taylor, an<br>
African-American who has served in many churches, in 3 conferences as<br>
associate youth director (SE, Central and Northern Calif), and a religion<br>
professor at Oakwood and PUC.  He currenly serves as Vice President at<br>
Pacific Union Conference.  <br>
It seemed to the delegates that the nominating committee had even more<br>
names that evening, but we will never know.  Temporary chairman Richard<br>
Bates nearly spilled those beans, but an African-American representative<br>
of the nominating committee stalked up the front of the podium, seemingly<br>
grabbed the chairman, and made it clear he would not tolerate the spread<br>
of the name(s).  Within short order a quorum call was made, it was found<br>
that we were 10 delegates short, and the meeting dissolved at 9:30pm<br>
<p>
When reconvened on October 18, Dr Taylor had withdrawn his name, and the<br>
Nominating committee selected Dr Lynn Mallery, recently appointed<br>
Conference Secretary, previously Ministerial Director.  He has served as<br>
pastor in various churches including La Sierra, and was a professor of<br>
applied theology at La Sierra for 8 years.  With no debate he was elected<br>
on a 463/147 vote.  Gerald Penick, formerly director of African-American<br>
ministries, was elected Secretary (494/135), and Philip Robertson<br>
reelected treasurer (568/58).  Pastor Anthony Paschal (Riverside Kansas<br>
Avenue) was elected VP African American ministries (412/37), and Mario<br>
Perez was reelected VP Hispanic ministries (424/20).  The Asian group (no<br>
such thing as ONE asian group!) could not agree, and the delegates<br>
deferred to the Asian Caucus for further study.<br>
<p>
The tithe question, at one time considered the most controversial agenda<br>
item because it had suggested that the contribution sent by SECC be<br>
reduced from 20% to 19%, or about $300,000.  Cool heads prevailed, and it<br>
was voted that SECC, the Pacific Union, North America, and the General<br>
Conference continue to work out ways to allow North America to put more<br>
funds back into its own ministries, particularly at the local church<br>
level.<br>
<p>
We adjourned at 6:30 pm, exhausted but satisfied.  I can report that the<br>
office morale seems to be higher, a mental and in some cases physical<br>
logjam of work has broken open, and there is a slowly reemerging team<br>
spirit.  All of us are (and continue to be) thankful for the prayers and<br>
concerns raised up by God's people around the circle of faith.<br>
<p>
David Johnson<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
