<title>Oct_1992: Halloween or Reformation Day?</title>
<h1>Halloween or Reformation Day?</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 30 Oct 92 12:41:25 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#153">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#153">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#153">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#153">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0154.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Election Politics"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0152.html">Pam Harrris: "Re: Southeastern Calif. Conference"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In recent years I have found many thoughtful Christians are reconsidering<br>
how they celebrate certain Western holidays/festivities.  Despite the<br>
undisputed heathen origins of the days selected for Christmas and Easter,<br>
we can chose to celebrate the birth of Christ and His death &amp; resurrection<br>
on and around these days (and hopefully other times in the year as well).<br>
However, the Catholic observations of All Saints's Eve/Halloween (much <br>
different emphasis in Europe than in N.America) and All Saints Day have<br>
left many Protestants unsure of what to do .. and hence they go along with<br>
the Halloween aspect.  If you are not aware of its Satanic origins, I<br>
recommend you look this up.  Suffice it to say that the increasing level<br>
of overt occult trappings among adults, let alone children, during this<br>
time should give any Christian serious pause.<br>
<p>
I do not recall any Christian ever questioning Trick or Treating as I was<br>
growing up.  No one ever mentioned that the origin was/is for treats to be<br>
left out for the spirits lest they play some dirty trick; indeed it was<br>
transformed into a time of convivial shenanigans and sugar treats (enough<br>
to depress your immune system for a serious amount of time what with winter<br>
coming on and all).<br>
<p>
When we had children we determined to find a Godly focus for this time<br>
of year.  What we found was:  Oct 31 (some historians say Nov 1, but I find<br>
the weight of evidence for Oct 31) was the day Martin Luther nailed his<br>
95 Theses to the door of the church in Wittenburg.  Some Protestants<br>
refer to this as Reformation Day.  We have found this to be far preferable.<br>
<p>
When Ronald Reagan named Jeanne Kirkpatrick as his candidate for Ambassador<br>
to the UN the media wondered why he would chose a Democrat.  When questioned<br>
as to how a Democrat could work for a Republican, she referred reporters to<br>
an article she had written for a conservative journal entitled "Why We Are<br>
Not Republicans".  I make mention of this not because of her apparent<br>
ability to mold herself to either party but rather to borrow a thought<br>
from the title:<br>
	Why are we not Catholics?<br>
	Why are we Protestants?<br>
<p>
While the excesses may (or may not) have disappeared, the basic theological<br>
differences remain (RC &lt;-&gt; Lutheran and CofE dialogs notwithstanding).<br>
We do well to refix in our minds the principals the Reformers fought for.<br>
I highly recommend the fat two-volume set on Reformation history by Wylie<br>
(available thru Great Christian Books) and the several books by D'Aubigne<br>
on the Reformation (Baker House, Grand Rapids).<br>
<p>
As an example of some of the incredible things we've learned:  I'm sure we<br>
all remember how God prepared Pharoah, Nebuchadnezzar, and Belshazzar to<br>
receive God's messenger.  Here's what happened to Frederick the Wise,<br>
Elector of Saxony:  The night before, he had a "continued story" series of<br>
three dreams.  In them a monk, writings on the door of Wittenburg's church,<br>
the Pope's tiara, a large pen reaching to Rome, and the Elector figured<br>
prominently.  On the morning of Oct 31, Frederick discussed his dreams with<br>
Duke George and it was recorded by Spalatin.  They concluded from their<br>
knowledge of Scripture (cf. Prov 29:2) that God had something significant<br>
in mind for Frederick.  The rest, as they say, is history.<br>
<p>
Oh, yes, in the dream, Frederick asked the monk whence came the large pen.<br>
The monk answered, "From a goose in Bohemia."  Bonus points if you know<br>
who the goose was and why the symbolism was apt.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  On Attitude &amp; the Immune System:  A sound heart is the life of the flesh:
    but envy the rottenness of the bones.  Prov 14:30
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
