<title>Oct_1992: Election Politics</title>
<h1>Election Politics</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 30 Oct 92 14:22:25 -0600</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#154">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#154">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#154">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#154">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0155.html">Fred Christiansen: "Thoughts on the "Right Answers""</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0153.html">Fred Christiansen: "Halloween or Reformation Day?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Yes, I'm quite concerned about supreme court appointments.  Packing the court<br>
with ultra-conservatives will invariable result in the lose of personal<br>
freedom.  Those with religious beliefs different from the "majority" will<br>
lose their constitutional right to believe and worship as they choose.<br>
<p>
I'm concerned about dirty politics and the apparent "no holds barred" approach<br>
the republicans exhibit in their political quest to win.<br>
<p>
I'm concerned about increased governmental control under Bill Clinton.  He<br>
wants to the government to control health care, child care, family issues,<br>
foreign trade, and the country's finances.<br>
<p>
I'm troubled with Ross Perot and his insatiable appetite for power.  He is<br>
a very powerful man and has many "grassroot" supporters who are wanting to<br>
climb the power tree on his coat tails.<br>
<p>
This election is a very difficult one for the average voter.  The mainstream<br>
American moderate that wants financial responsibility, personal freedom,<br>
less government, and equal rights for everyone has a real dilemma.  No<br>
party or candidate presents mainstream American moderates.<br>
<p>
The press has essentially declared that Bill Clinton will win by an electoral<br>
college landslide but a marginal popular vote.  Will Ross Perot win any<br>
electoral votes?  No, probably not.  Will a vote for Ross Perot be a vote for<br>
George Bush?  Yes, it just might be.<br>
<p>
If one decides based on the Vice Presidential candidate, it's a bit easier.<br>
Al Gore is clearly the most competent of the three.  But the VP is only a<br>
figure head in American government so this doesn't help much in the decision.<br>
<p>
Who am I voting for?  Probably Bill Clinton.  Not because I believe in his<br>
platform but because there are fewer "rotton planks" in his than the others,<br>
in my opinion.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
