<title>Sep_1992: Vegetarians</title>
<h1>Vegetarians</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 2 Sep 1992 08:45 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#9">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#9">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#9">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#9">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0010.html">Steven Timm: "SDA-L:  Adventist Contact"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0008.html">Dave Buxton: "Re: social customs and rings"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0011.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Vegetarians"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Dave:<br>
<p>
You wrote<br>
----&gt;<br>
On our recent trip to Europe we witnessed to a considerable extent to<br>
two people, both of whom asked why we were vegetarians.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
I am interested to know what you said when asked why you are vegeterian.<br>
 <br>
So Dave ... why are you vegetarian?<br>
Does your vegetarian nature mean that you don't use animal products at all, or<br>
do you simply not eat meat?<br>
<p>
While I'm here, I'd also like to comment on the proposition that we are best<br>
served if our dress is simple and natural.<br>
<p>
I am inclined to agree here, although I wouldn't like to see that used as an<br>
argument to convince me not to wear my wedding ring. The kind of thing that<br>
really makes me laugh is people (mainly other men), typically church elders,<br>
who on the one hand make a strong verbal stand for the "simple and natural"<br>
thing - no makeup, no jewellery etc. etc., and at the same time won't let<br>
a visiting minister into the pulpit without a coat. (They themselves wouldn't<br>
be seen at church without a good suit.) The wearing of ties is also something<br>
which seems to be neither simple or natural!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
