<title>Sep_1992: Re: re: Rules and Culture</title>
<h1>Re: re: Rules and Culture</h1>
Bob Moynihan (<i>moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 31 Aug 92 14:09:16 EDT </i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#0">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#0">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#0">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#0">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0001.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Andrew &amp; Omar"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Paul Gates wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; We could carry the attitude that no one has a right to tell me what is</i><br>
<i>&gt; moral to immoral extremes.   </i><br>
<p>
  &lt; Two Live Crew / Geraldo appearence stuff deleted, including statistics &gt;<br>
  &lt; on the quantity of vulgarity on their disc/tape.                       &gt;<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Should we say the 2 Live Crew has the right to express themselves this</i><br>
<i>&gt; way?</i><br>
<p>
Hmmm... I hate to say this, but yes, we should.  This is the United States,<br>
that guarantees individuals the right to free speech, and by extension, the<br>
freedom of personal expression.  Morals are by definition subjective in<br>
society as a whole.   Closed groups (like the set of SDA's, or the set of<br>
all Christians) may have what amounts to an objective set of standards for<br>
their circle, but outside their group, those morals may not be considered<br>
as being generally acceptable.<br>
<p>
Censorship in any form is contrary to the founding principles of this country.<br>
Standards of behavior should be enforced only when behavior infringes on the<br>
human rights of others.  When you try to set conservative societal standards,<br>
invariably, those standards get tighter and tighter, and more and more people<br>
get oppressed as a result.<br>
<p>
I often hear people expounding the virtues of Christian values, and how they<br>
should be the law of the land because "this is a Christian nation."  This is<br>
-not- a Christian nation.  This is a nation founded on the principle of <br>
freedom.  Freedom of speech. Freedom of religion. Freedom of the press. In<br>
the spirit of freedom, we have no right to force our concept of morality on<br>
others.  In return, we expect that they will not force their concept of it on us.<br>
Two Live Crew can make their "music".  Bob Guccione can publish his pornography.<br>
But we don't have to listen, don't have to look, don't have to buy.  Others may,<br>
and when they stand before their Maker, will face His judgement, just as will<br>
we all.  We should adhere to our Christian values, and teach them to our chilren.<br>
We should tell them to those who will listen, and ask them to join us.  But we<br>
can never make someone hold them by force.<br>
<p>
-Bob<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
