<title>Sep_1992: Religious Liberty on Univ. Campuses</title>
<h1>Religious Liberty on Univ. Campuses</h1>
Alice Fay Martin (<i>armg9488@uxa.cso.uiuc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 1 Sep 1992 09:33:45 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#6">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#6">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#6">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#6">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0007.html">Steven Timm: "List Demographics"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0005.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Religious liberty on University campuses"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
--------&gt;<br>
I'd like those who are attending public institutions of higher education to<br>
respond......Wisconsin law requires that the university provide "reasonable <br>
accommodation of a student's sincerely held religious beliefs with regard <br>
to all examinations and other academic requirements."  (Chapter 36.43 of <br>
Wisconsin Law).  Along with the memo was a list of various religious holy <br>
days which may preclude students from attending class or examinations <br>
by religious affiliation........ <br>
<p>
Do other state universities have such a policy or law?  What degree of <br>
accomodation you required to make for student religious observance?  Are <br>
faculty and staff given the same liberties as students?......Cheryl<br>
--------&gt;<br>
<p>
In response, as another student from the University of Illinois in <br>
Champaign, I've dealt with this issue.  My cumulative exams were given <br>
once a month, Friday evenings @ 7PM.  The policy was to pass 6 exams <br>
(limit of 18 to be taken).  It one of the first concerns to be addressed when <br>
entering grad school, that is, to not have to take cumes on Sabbath. When I <br>
approached the professor in charge he sat back took a breath and then said <br>
" aaaah.. sure.... no problem" and proceeded to pull off the window (a sort <br>
of bulletin board) a similar statement which Cheryl described.  Special <br>
arrangements had to be made but it worked out well.  Interestingly, this <br>
same professor arranged ALL his exams for Sat. mornings.  It rather <br>
annoyed me, needless to say, but again the option for an early exam was <br>
given.<br>
<p>
I think my example has been consistent but on the otherhand I was rather <br>
embarrassed by an irresponsible undergrad who used his religious <br>
background not only to get out of taking his final exam on Saturday but <br>
leave campus early for X-mas break.  I say embarrassed because the TA in <br>
charge, a fellow lab mate, knew me well and knew the student had a <br>
legitimate reason so he asked me if I knew the student. (Rearranging final <br>
exams can be sticky and they were being careful.)  The TA proceeded to <br>
offer the exam just prior to Sabbath or after sundown that day to make <br>
accomodation.  Only then did the undergrad reveal that his plane to <br>
California was leaving Thursday sometime and he couldn't do that.  This <br>
didn't look good and both TA and undergrad fell into heated discussion of <br>
"responsibility and planning"  vs "religious rights".  Unfortunately, I don't <br>
think this was a positive witness.<br>
<p>
Just a few words from my experience.<br>
<p>
-Alice<br>
armg9488@uxa.uiuc.cso.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
