<title>Sep_1992: Sat v. Sun Sabbath</title>
<h1>Sat v. Sun Sabbath</h1>
Scott Mattes (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed,  2 Sep 1992 12:06:17 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#15">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#15">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#15">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#15">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0016.html">Pam Harris: "Culture/free speech/2LiveCrew"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0014.html">Jerome Grimmer: "OOOOOOOOOOOPS!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!!"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0023.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Re:  Sat v. Sun Sabbath"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On Wed, 2 Sep 1992 09:48:21 -0400 (EDT) Ruben said:<br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Furthermore Paul goes on to say that</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;Many Sunday keeping Christians are resting fully in Christ for their</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;salvation; they are keeping Sunday for the right reason....</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;There can be no right reason for keeping Sunday at all, ..................</i><br>
<p>
oh? not even God Himself telling you Sunday was the day would make it<br>
right?<br>
<p>
  As a member of a church that believes in latter day prophets (I am one<br>
of the LDS Steve mentioned) I believe that Joseph Smith Jr (the first<br>
prophet of this, the last, dispensation) received a revelation from<br>
Jesus Christ himself stating that Sunday was the day appointed by Jesus<br>
to have our latter day Sabbath on (D&amp;C 59:10,12-13).<br>
  For those who chose to look this up, the key is that date on which the<br>
revelation was given Aug 7th, 1831 - a Sunday.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;....................................................... it is unscriptural</i><br>
<i>&gt;and those who keep it do it solely because of the traditions of men.</i><br>
<p>
  You seem to deny that there is even the slightest shadow of doubt<br>
about this in the NT, which there is.  While I grant that it isn't iron<br>
clad proof for a Sunday Sabbath, it is enough to make one question your<br>
assertion.<br>
  I don't remember exactly when your church says the great apostacy took<br>
place, but in the early AD 100s Justin Martyr wrote about the Christian<br>
keeping the day Sunday as the Sabbath.<br>
<p>
--------------------------------------+----------------------------------------<br>
Scott (nmi) Mattes                    | No success can compensate for failure<br>
Work: COTRSSM@SEA04VM.NAVSEA.Navy.Mil | in the home.  David O. McKay, Prophet<br>
Home: 73027.3270@CompuServe.COM       | and President of the Church of Jesus<br>
Voice: (703) 769-2917                 | Christ of Latter-day Saints, 1951-70<br>
[SDA's don't deny that Sundaykeeping began as early as the mid 100's AD.<br>
As far as the New Testament itself is concerned, there is no doubt.  Some<br>
may have been generated in Scott's mind by reading the classic Mormon<br>
work "A Marvelous Work And A Wonder", in which LeGrand Richards makes <br>
outright lies in his interpretation of New Testament Greek.  Seventh-day<br>
Adventist also reject the notion that various periods called<br>
"dispensations" exist, or that God's Law or will change for different<br>
groups of people<br>
in different times.  Unlike the LDS, we require consistency between all <br>
prophetic messages.  SCT]<br>
