<title>Sep_1992: Culture/free speech/2LiveCrew</title>
<h1>Culture/free speech/2LiveCrew</h1>
Pam Harris (<i>HARRISP@utkvx.utk.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 2 Sep 1992 12:35 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#16">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#16">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#16">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#16">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0017.html">Steven Timm: "Address for Biblical Research Inst."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0015.html">Scott Mattes: "Sat v. Sun Sabbath"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Although this album "As Nasty as They Wanna Be" is foul, disgusting, offensive, and opposed to every value we may hold dear, we live in a country of freedom<br>
of speech. Protecting unpopular speech by those on the fringe was one of <br>
the objectives of our country's founders. If Adventists expect their own<br>
views to be heard without censure, they should be very careful about<br>
attacking viewpoints as "illegal" speech they disagree with. This doesn't<br>
mean they can't disagree with the message and express it, however. <br>
<p>
Although some complain, the journalism profession is very agressive in<br>
their watchdog role. They aggressively protect freedom of speech. In<br>
fact, the press may be an Adventist's best friend when it comes to the<br>
right to speak regardless of the message. In the marketplace of free<br>
ideas, there will always be the untrue, the false, the offensive, the<br>
tasteless. That's the price we pay for freedom of speech. However, we<br>
(children included) do not have to buy, turn on the set, or listen. We<br>
have freedom of choice to turn it off. It's the same risk God gave us--<br>
freedom of choice.<br>
<p>
The marketplace of free ideas is one of the most wonderful opportunities<br>
for Adventists. Just observe what is happening with the message of<br>
Christian hope in the former Soviet Union. Freedom of the press and<br>
freedom of speech are two of the most precious possessions we have in<br>
the free world. We may not agree with many of the messages in our<br>
culture, but we should be willing to defend to the death anyone's right<br>
to speak, no matter how offensive the speech. Dan Rather (or his colleagues)<br>
may provide you the opportunity to speak your opinion someday when it is very <br>
critical that your message enter the marketplace of ideas.<br>
<p>
Pam Maize Harris<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
