<title>Sep_1992: rebels</title>
<h1>rebels</h1>
Lola (<i>AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>02 Sep 1992 12:59:32 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#20">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#20">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#20">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#20">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0021.html">Lola: "women's role and jewelry come together in 1 Peter"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0019.html">Steven Timm: "SDA-L:  Directory of all current members"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I'm sorry, I can't believe that rebels are created by lists of rules.<br>
Agreed, lists of rules without foundation are not good, and I wish we<br>
would take a long look at revising them where-ever we find them (school,<br>
church, etc.), but they don't MAKE people rebel.  People CHOOSE to rebel.<br>
I went to SDA schools up through age 24, living on campus, eating at the<br>
caf, not wearing jeans, makeup, or jewelry, attening worships and handing<br>
in a worship card towards my quota, etc., yet I did not rebel.  I though<br>
(thought) a lot of the stuff was stupid, but I bent to it because that was<br>
where I wanted to be.  On some points I didn't go along, such as the<br>
fact that I was a frequent visitor at the little theater in St. Helena that<br>
showed wonderful revival films (Katheringe Hepburn, etc.).  Strictly off-<br>
limits, but unenforceable.  Yet, I am still active in the church, going<br>
to raise our children in the subculture to an extent, will probably home-<br>
school...    What makes the difference between me and those of my friends<br>
who did rebel, become substance abusers, have illegitimate children (and<br>
don't kid yourself that keeping them in the dorms tones down any of that!)?<br>
<p>
I believe it is due to a couple of things.  Parents, certainly.  My parents<br>
were always committed to the idea of establishing the concept and letting<br>
us make our own choices.  THEY did not lay down senseless rules, but helped<br>
us analyze the rules that were there to see why they were given.  Another<br>
point may be personality type -- I simply have always been the "go along,<br>
get along" type of person.  Stuff doesn't phase me to a great extent.<br>
Thirdly, commitment to God, to the church, reasons for being at college --<br>
perhaps my reasons were different than those of some of my more rebellious<br>
friends.<br>
<p>
Having said that, I do believe that senseless rules are unnecessary<br>
stumbling blocks for those of different personalities, parents, and<br>
commitment.  We should not do stuff that makes it easier for someone<br>
to choose rebellion over acceptance!  But people don't start taking<br>
drugs because of dress codes....  Something else is operating there, and<br>
perhaps we should exert some effort in the direction of finding out what<br>
that something else is.<br>
<p>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
