<title>Sep_1992: women's role and jewelry come together in 1 Peter</title>
<h1>women's role and jewelry come together in 1 Peter</h1>
Lola (<i>AAGAARD%morekypr.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>02 Sep 1992 12:33:16 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#21">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#21">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#21">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#21">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0022.html">David Plaisted: "Response to Tony's question about vegetarianism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0020.html">Lola: "rebels"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Did any of you study last weeks Sabbath school lesson in 1 Peter?  It<br>
hit two of these hot topics we've been discussing: women's role and<br>
jewelry.  It wasn't my week to teach, but I was interested in how it<br>
was handled by the head elder who was teaching.  He did very well,<br>
considering the nature of the topic.  In my personal study I use the<br>
commentary by Barclay and he always puts the passages into historical<br>
context, which helps me a great deal.  During the time Peter was writing<br>
women were essentially slaves, thus the advice to women to submit to<br>
their husbands came right after the same advice was given to slaves to<br>
submit to their masters!  Peter even starts out the section by saying<br>
"in the same way, women should submit...."   For a woman to become a<br>
Christian when her husband was not was extremely radical and would cause<br>
a lot of unpleasantness in the home -- she was not even to have opinions,<br>
much less act on them.  The jewelry issue was linked to the same cultural<br>
phenomenon:  after about the age of 14, women were seen as good only for<br>
men's bed partners.  They had lots of time on their hands and only one<br>
purpose in life: to be attractive to men.  Thus they spent an inordiante<br>
(oops, inordinate) amount of time and money to accomplish that purpose,<br>
by braiding, gilding, painting, dressing, adorning.  When Peter continued<br>
by telling the men that women were their equals in sharing God's grace,<br>
that too was EXTREMELY radical!  Women were not thought to be equals in<br>
any way at all, and this was an entirely new thought.  In some sense, the<br>
solution was for men to value their wives for more than the traditional<br>
purpose, then the women would perceive that they were worthwhile apart<br>
from their looks, and the adornment could then be less extreme.<br>
<p>
Typical of Adventism, we have formed some specific rules that we adhere<br>
to slavishly, while forgetting the overall concept that was behind the<br>
advice!  The same is true for Sabbath observance -- I hope  that the GC<br>
never bows to the pressure to establish guidelines for "proper" Sabbath-<br>
keeping, because then Sabbath will fall to the same level as the jewelry<br>
issue.<br>
<p>
This was an interesting lesson last week in another way too.  One of the<br>
university professors here in Morehead is very interested in the church.<br>
He is an organist and music professor and had been attending pretty<br>
regularly in the late spring.  Over the summer he had a job playing the<br>
organ for the Stephen Foster Story, and outdoor musical that runs all<br>
summer here in Kentucky.  (He has done it every summer for 20 years or so.)<br>
There are performances on Friday night and Sabbath afternoon.  Before he<br>
left for the summer he asked our pastor what he should do about that.  The<br>
pastor said that it was between him and God, and that God would help him<br>
work it out.  By the last month of the summer he asked for those times off<br>
and it was granted to him.  He was very pleased about this and so were we<br>
all when he told us.  I'm also pleased with our pastor's approach -- so<br>
\much better than coming down strong with a rule....  This man now has the<br>
concept of Sabbath observance that is motivated from the inside, not the<br>
outside.  He brought another professor with him this Sabbath, I believe<br>
it is someone he is dating, and she was wearing big gold earrings during<br>
our discussion on jewelry.  Of course, our head elder's wife was wearing<br>
a sapphire ring in addition to her wedding ring....  The elder spoke about<br>
this situation in his family and confessed that he opposed the sapphire ring,<br>
but didn't consider it a salvific issue, and thus would not lay down any<br>
law to his wife about what she could or could not wear.  She has Hodgkins<br>
disease and is undergoing chemotherapy and her hair is falling out, and I<br>
guess she feels better and more attractive with the ring, I don't know.<br>
<p>
Anyway, when the jewelry issue is seen in the light of "for what should<br>
men and women be valued?" it takes on an entirely different character.  We<br>
should not value each other for the amount of money we spend on our watches<br>
or cars or houses, or for the color or style of our hair, or for how much<br>
metal we can hang on our bodies -- not that owning or doing any of those<br>
things are inherently wrong, but that is not why we are valuable!<br>
<p>
I've gone on long enough.  I would be wearing my grandmother's gold wedding<br>
band, but I'm seven months pregnant and had to take it off while I still<br>
could!<br>
<p>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
