<title>Sep_1992: Response to Tony's question about vegetarianism</title>
<h1>Response to Tony's question about vegetarianism</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 2 Sep 92 13:56:03 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#22">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#22">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#22">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#22">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0023.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Re:  Sat v. Sun Sabbath"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0021.html">Lola: "women's role and jewelry come together in 1 Peter"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0034.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Response to Tony's question about vegetarianism"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In a recent message, PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au (Tony) asked<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I am interested to know what you said when asked why you are vegeterian.</i><br>
<p>
I usually say, For health and religious reasons.  This time, an Indian<br>
fellow asked me, Which religion?  I said, Seventh-day Adventist.<br>
Later he asked me what Adventists believe.  So I told him we were<br>
Christians, Protestants, accepted the Old and New Testaments, accepted<br>
Christ as our Savior, and something about the Sabbath and the second<br>
coming; I can't remember exactly but that should give the general<br>
idea.  I also asked him about his beliefs or about Hinduism and we<br>
talked about that for a while.<br>
<p>
The other time, we were out to dinner with friends and someone asked<br>
my wife about our children's schooling and she said we were sending<br>
them to church school.  She asked which church, and my wife said<br>
Seventh-day Adventist.  It turns out her neighbor is an Adventist so<br>
we had a little discussion about that.<br>
<p>
Tony also asked<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;So Dave ... why are you vegetarian?</i><br>
Does your vegetarian nature mean that you don't use animal products at all, or<br>
do you simply not eat meat?<br>
<p>
I am vegetarian for health and religious reasons.  :-)<br>
It's supported scientifically and also avoids causing suffering to animals.<br>
<p>
My eating habits (since you asked) have changed slowly over a long<br>
period.  When I became SDA someone mentioned about vegetarianism.  In<br>
a little while I dumped out my meat, that was that.  I still used<br>
milk, eggs, butter or margarine, and cheese.  Then a lady told me how<br>
good vegetable oils were, so I started pouring them on my toast<br>
instead of butter.  That at least got me off butter and margarine,<br>
which was a hard thing to do, since I used a lot of them.  Later I<br>
learned all those greasy vegetable oils weren't that good for you<br>
either.  (Especially in large quantities.)  After reading more EGW I<br>
dropped cheese.  But how can you have cereal without milk?  (I hadn't<br>
learned the habit of hot cereal.)  Later I started using hot cereal<br>
and putting pineapple and other fruit on it.  So, now my basic diet is<br>
total vegetarian, but when traveling we drink a lot of milk and use<br>
butter etc.  My family uses more milk than I do, and sometimes has<br>
pizza.<br>
<p>
It's interesting that our family traveled for a couple of weeks in<br>
Europe and had vegetarian food and only went to a restaurant once or<br>
twice.  We learned to buy stuff in the grocery store and eat in our<br>
motel rooms (without a kitchen).  It's a lot cheaper too.  In Europe<br>
they sell this milk that lasts for months without refrigeration, which<br>
helps.  You can go a long way on cereal and milk, nuts, fruit, bread,<br>
avocadoes, V-8 juice etc.  Even our children (ages 8, 11) didn't<br>
complain much.<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
