<title>Sep_1992: Re:  Sat v. Sun Sabbath</title>
<h1>Re:  Sat v. Sun Sabbath</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 2 Sep 92 14:23:28 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#23">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#23">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#23">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#23">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0024.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Re:  Sat v. Sun Sabbath"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0022.html">David Plaisted: "Response to Tony's question about vegetarianism"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0015.html">Scott Mattes: "Sat v. Sun Sabbath"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0024.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Re:  Sat v. Sun Sabbath"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Although SDAs may not believe in "dispensations", they do accept the notion<br>
of "old covenant" and "new covenant".  The historical SDA interpretation of<br>
these eras is that God did chance something.  The most obvious is that the<br>
sacrificial system of the Jews which was a type of the Jesus' sacrifice on<br>
the cross, was no longer needed under the new covenant.  However, under the<br>
old covenant it is very clear that without shedding of blood there was no<br>
remission of sin for the Jews.  This was not a symbolic shedding of blood<br>
but quite literally animal sacrifices which were required to be "clean."<br>
Although some may argue that this doesn't change God's eternal law, it<br>
clearly DOES appear to be a different "dispensation."  The requirements for<br>
salvation were clearly different for people living before the cross and<br>
those after the cross.  This does reflect a change in God's dealings with<br>
man on this earth.<br>
<p>
SDAs view the 4th commandment quite literally (as opposed to being symbolic).<br>
SDAs believe that the 7th day has been the very same literal 7th day of each<br>
week since the beginning of time on this earth (and before the existence of<br>
this earth).  However, this very literal interpretation of God's law is not<br>
as defensible as you may think.  With all the "leap years", "leap minutes",<br>
and changes in the calendar historically, nobody can "prove" that the same<br>
7th day has been kept ALWAYS.  If God's law is viewed symbolically as to<br>
its meaning, keeping every 7th day IS keeping God's law.  SDAs have established<br>
an entire doctrine and interpretation of much of the Bible and prophecy on a<br>
very literal interpretation of the 4th commandment.  Yet there is no Biblical<br>
support for the idea that there is a very specific 7th day and only that day<br>
is acceptable to God.  If this were true, SDAs may be shocked to find out in<br>
the next life that they were "accidently" keeping the wrong 7th day.  For all<br>
we know, SDAs are keeping a "Tuesday" as Sabbath right now.<br>
<p>
I think study of scripture in the original Hebrew might be enlightening.  For<br>
example, does it say "the SEVENTH day is the Sabbath" or "THE seventh day is<br>
the sabbath?  In other words, is what does the original text use for the word<br>
"the" and what is its grammatical usage in this context?<br>
<p>
cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
