<title>Sep_1992: Album Review:  Michael W. Smith  "Change Your World"</title>
<h1>Album Review:  Michael W. Smith  "Change Your World"</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed,  2 Sep 1992 21:40:51 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#27">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#27">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#27">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#27">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0028.html">Tony: "Re: women's role and jewelry etc."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0026.html">Bill Nickless: "Religious liberty on University campuses"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In this album, Mark Heimermann joins Michael W. Smith as lead producer.<br>
That is the most defining characteristic of the album.  Heimermann has<br>
produced extensively, mostly the "Prism" series for kids and the recent<br>
Lisa Bevill album.  The kids he's been producing for are growing up<br>
and this album is an obvious target to catch them as teenagers.  Also,<br>
Heimermann has a long association with Smith, having toured with him<br>
several times.<br>
<p>
The writers on this album have been previously mentioned here.  Diane <br>
Warren, who writes for Kathy Troccoli as well as a lot of more famous people,<br>
contributes a set of lyrics, as does Toby McKeehan (DC Talk).  Amy Grant<br>
co-wrote a couple songs and sings a duet on "Somewhere, Somehow"<br>
<p>
The sounds of this album are a Michael W. we've never heard before and<br>
hopefully will never hear again.  The strong keyboard lines and<br>
traditional harmonies that mark his music are a thing of the past.  The<br>
best song on <br>
the album is the re-make of "Friends" but this is marked by all-male backing<br>
vocals by the people who are his band and musicians on both of his albums<br>
(Harris, Rodriguez, Kirkpatrick)<br>
<p>
The words are stimulating as usual, "Give It Away", "Cross of Gold"<br>
and "Color Blind" providing most of the fireworks here.  But even so <br>
the God-and-Jesus meter is turned down a couple of notches.<br>
<p>
This is teeny-bopper music, not baby boomer music.  If you liked Lisa <br>
Bevill's album you will like this one, too.  The main difference between<br>
this and Lisa Bevill is that she can sing and M. W. Smith can't.  This<br>
is Smith's worst album since "The Live Set."  But on a bad day he's better<br>
than most people at their best, and although it's not a great album,<br>
it will provide much listening enjoyment for a long time to come.<br>
<p>
Steve's ranking:  Three thistles on a scale of -5 to 5<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
