Some of you may be able to relate to my situation.  If you can,<br>
I'd appreciate your thoughts.  <br>
<p>
I teach mathematics at a state university.  Out of about 11,000<br>
students, perhaps 25 are SDA's ranging in age from 18 to 45.  They<br>
are single, married, undergraduates, grad students, full-time,<br>
part-time, comfortable, poor, desperate, sick, and healthy.  What they<br>
are NOT is seen, appreciated, noticed, significant, etc. as far as<br>
the church is concerned.  Why is it that otherwise normal people<br>
are so totally incapable of manifesting any interest in SDA<br>
students living in their own town going to a state school?  All the<br>
theology in the world can't explain that away.  Our adult members<br>
are numb inspite of what they think of themselves.  This is also<br>
true with regard to the conference "leaders" who make this town<br>
home.  How do we get our members and "leaders" off their comfortable<br>
backsides with regard to this problem?<br>
<p>
Dave Thomas<br>
Montana State University<br>
umsfdtho@deimos.oscs.montana.edu<br>
