<title>Sep_1992: Day of rest</title>
<h1>Day of rest</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 3 Sep 1992 13:24 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#30">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#30">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#30">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#30">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0031.html">Tony: "Re: Vegetarians"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0029.html">Dave Thomas: "please post"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0052.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Day of rest"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
OK, so three posts in one session is a bit excessive, but I have a <br>
question to ask the net. I have had discussions about this with friends<br>
and so on at my church, but I'm interested in a wider perspective.<br>
<p>
SDAs have always made a point of defending their sunset-to-sunset every<br>
week. This has often been the cause of much hardship, as illustrated<br>
by countless stories of people losing jobs/failing courses/losing<br>
friends and so on. Usually the stories we read or hear have a happy<br>
ending, but let's face it, many real life ones don't.<br>
<p>
I am the head sound engineer for my church of 1500 weekly attenders.<br>
Our regular pattern is to have quite a varied presentation at 11am<br>
each Saturday, consisting of special music, a children's story, sometimes<br>
a small drama segment, and so on. Our Friday night vespers programs<br>
often involve concerts, audio-visual presentations and other interesting<br>
things.<br>
<p>
The job of technical production of these events falls to those few of us<br>
with the skills and experience necessary to handle the job. Even in a<br>
church of 1500 there are not too many people capable of taking the <br>
responsibility of a senior elder or deacon, and coordinating the team<br>
effort required to ensure that the programs "work". As far as sound<br>
production goes, we have a few people who are able to handle basic programs,<br>
but as soon as things become at all complex the job falls to the two or<br>
three who are more experienced.<br>
<p>
During times such as the beginning of the school year, and sometimes around<br>
Easter and Christmas, complex programs are the norm and I am often working<br>
three weekends out of four. My typical weekend program might go something<br>
like this:<br>
<p>
Friday arvo        set up for vespers<br>
Friday night      6:30pm spm sound check + operate for vespers<br>
Saturday          8:45am-12:30pm set up + sound check + operate for church<br>
                  (could go later if the preacher is over-enthusiastic)<br>
<p>
If there is an afternoon program I may have to handle it as well, but would<br>
usually delegate wherever possible.<br>
<p>
Operating a complex sound system for a variety-type program in a building<br>
this size takes concentration and organization. When I am working I almost<br>
always miss the lesson discussion groups because I am setting up gear for<br>
a choir or a drama, or someone wants to practice something. Sure, I do<br>
hear the sermon.<br>
<p>
So here's my question.<br>
<p>
Someone at uni wants me to do something on Saturday. Maybe it's help out<br>
with a public demonstration. Maybe it's just a social activity. I say,<br>
"thanks, but my Saturday's are booked to God, and besides, I don't want<br>
to miss church" or whatever. Perhaps then they ask me to explain about<br>
the Sabbath. My explanation would probably include "holy day", "worship",<br>
and "no work" if I am a typical SDA.<br>
<p>
The only problem is, I do often work on Saturday, and I do often miss many<br>
of the aspects of public worship. How can this contradiction be resolved?<br>
SDAs seem to be quite happy about work on Sabbath, so long as it is<br>
medical-related and/or unpaid.<br>
<p>
I have lots more to say on this issue, but this will do for now. Looking<br>
forward to hearing from you all soon!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
