<title>Sep_1992: Easter, Christmas and Festivals</title>
<h1>Easter, Christmas and Festivals</h1>
Drew Corrigan (<i>drew@dubhe.anu.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 3 Sep 92 14:04:06 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#37">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#37">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#37">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#37">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0038.html">Steven Timm: "Christian Nation"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0036.html">Paul Gates: "Re: re: Rules and Culture"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0103.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Easter, Christmas and Festivals"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Paul Gates enquires: <br>
<i>&gt; Drew, RU saying that you do not celebrate Easter or Christmas? Those are</i><br>
<i>&gt; the 2 most High Sabbaths in the churches that I pastor.</i><br>
<p>
Yes. Rather than observe Easter we observe the Christian Passover on the <br>
evening of the 14th of Nisan, and follow it with the 7 days of the Feast<br>
of Unleavened Bread. Prior to this time we deleaven our homes, and then<br>
during the Days of Unleavened Bread when we eat bread, we make sure it is<br>
unleavened. The first and last days of the Days of Unleavened Bread are<br>
annual Sabbaths (15th and 21st of Nisan) during which we have morning and<br>
afternoon Church services.<br>
<p>
We do not celebrate Christmas because to our way of thinking it is a<br>
compromise with paganism. It is not known when Jesus was born, but the<br>
available evidence indicates anything but December. If God had wanted us<br>
to remember the date of Jesus' birth we believe he would have been explicit<br>
about it - even as he has been about his Sabbaths.<br>
<p>
The lessons we rehearse from the annual Sabbaths and Festivals are these:<br>
<p>
 14 Nisan - Passover - Death of Jesus as sacrifice for all mankind's sins,<br>
    reconfirming our baptismal covenants with God, drinking wine and eating<br>
    unleavened bread as reminders of Jesus' broken body and shed blood,<br>
    foot washing as reminder of Jesus' example of service and that we should<br>
    do likewise.<br>
<p>
 15 Nisan - 21 Nisan - 7 Days of Unleavened Bread - The need for us to<br>
    come out of sin even as Israel came out of Egypt.<br>
<p>
 50 days after the weekly Sabbath that falls during the Days of Unleavened<br>
    Bread - Pentecost, or the Feast of Firstfruits - reminder that God<br>
    traditionally gave 10 Commandments on this day and historically poured<br>
    out his spirit in AD 31. With his spirit, Christ lives in us and we<br>
    can develop godly character and nature.<br>
<p>
  1 Tishri - Feast of Trumpets - teaches Jesus return as King of kings,<br>
    a time of war when nations fight Christ, beginning of regathering of<br>
    Israel.<br>
<p>
 10 Tishri - Day of Atonement - teaches that finally world will be at<br>
    peace and at-one-ment with God and Christ, reminds us again of Jesus<br>
    sacrifice which was penalty paid to remove the sin which separates<br>
    man from God and prevents at-one-ment with him today. Also reminds<br>
    us that Satan will be bound 1,000 years and unable to deceive the <br>
    nations.<br>
<p>
 15-20 Tishri - Feast of Tabernacles - teaches us of the wonderful utopian<br>
    conditions that world will experience for 1,000 years under rule of<br>
    Christ from Jerusalem. Law will go forth from Zion and nations will<br>
    not learn war anymore.<br>
<p>
 21 Tishri - Last Great Day - teaches us that following the millenium and<br>
    the brief release of Satan at its close, God will resurrect all those<br>
    who have lived and died not being called, and these will experience a<br>
    period of time to learn of God's way and be called. At the end of this<br>
    period of time (which we believe will last 100 years) any who are<br>
    rebellious and unrepentant will be destroyed in the lake of fire.<br>
    The heavens and the earth will be made new and God the Father will come<br>
    down from heaven with New Jerusalem to establish the earth as "head-<br>
    quarters" of the universe.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Our membership looks foward to these special Sabbaths all year long.</i><br>
<p>
Our membership looks forward to these Festivals all year long too. They are<br>
the highlight of our lives. Indeed, we count our years in terms of Passover<br>
to Passover or Feast (of Tabernacles) to Feast. The Feast of Tabernacles is<br>
especially meaningful to us as throughout the year we save a second tithe<br>
and then use this to travel to one of a number of designated Feast sites<br>
where for 8 days (FoT + LGD) we worship God and fellowship with our brethren.<br>
Christmas doesn't even come close to this experience :-).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; We still use the names of the days of the week and shake hands although</i><br>
<i>&gt; these too came from Paganism. (smile)</i><br>
<p>
I expect that in the millenium the days of the week will be renamed :-)<br>
<p>
  "For then will I turn to the people a pure language, that they may all <br>
   call upon the name of the LORD, to serve him with one consent." (Zep 3:9)<br>
<p>
Regards,<br>
<p>
Drew.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
