<title>Sep_1992: Christian Nation</title>
<h1>Christian Nation</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu,  3 Sep 1992 09:12:05 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#38">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#38">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#38">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#38">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0039.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: Sat v. Sun Sabbath"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0037.html">Drew Corrigan: "Easter, Christmas and Festivals"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0072.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Christian Nation"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In various religious liberty articles people try to make the point that<br>
the U.S. is not a Christian nation.  But in fact we are a Christian nation.<br>
The Supreme Court, in a decision in the 1880's which has never been <br>
overturned, _Holy Trinity_, ruled that "The United States is a Christian <br>
nation."  It was this decision together with the Sunday legislation that <br>
 was being considered in Congress at that time that catapulted A.T. Jones<br>
to the forefront of Adventism as a champion of religious liberty.<br>
<p>
We must be careful in the pursual of separation of church and state to <br>
make sure that we do not appear to be antireligious.  A lot of moral<br>
standards which seem to be the province of Adventism alone once were the <br>
values of the whole country.  As Richard Mullins said "I do not know <br>
that we can have a heaven here on earth, but I am convinced we need <br>
not have a hell."<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
