<title>Sep_1992: Re: Sat v. Sun Sabbath</title>
<h1>Re: Sat v. Sun Sabbath</h1>
Bill Oblitey (<i>OBLITEY@grove.iup.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 3 Sep 1992 07:50 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#39">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#39">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#39">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#39">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0040.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: Response to Tony's question about vegetarianism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0038.html">Steven Timm: "Christian Nation"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0015.html">Scott Mattes: "Sat v. Sun Sabbath"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0043.html">Lisa Parry: "Wedding Band"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;oh? not even God Himself telling you Sunday was the day would make it</i><br>
<i>&gt;right?</i><br>
<p>
I agree with you that God has the right to change whatever He chooses, but<br>
wht would He change His Memorial of creation?<br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;  As a member of a church that believes in latter day prophets (I am one</i><br>
<i>&gt;of the LDS Steve mentioned) I believe that Joseph Smith Jr (the first</i><br>
<i>&gt;prophet of this, the last, dispensation) received a revelation from</i><br>
<i>&gt;Jesus Christ himself stating that Sunday was the day appointed by Jesus</i><br>
<i>&gt;to have our latter day Sabbath on (D&amp;C 59:10,12-13).</i><br>
<i>&gt;  For those who chose to look this up, the key is that date on which the</i><br>
<i>&gt;revelation was given Aug 7th, 1831 - a Sunday.</i><br>
<p>
I have studied some of the LDS works and the greatest problem I have is with<br>
Peter showing up to J. Smith and this "Jesus' appointed day of Sunday" claim.<br>
Do you think that maybe He made a mistake in appointing Saturday as the<br>
original sabbath in the first place?<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;  I don't remember exactly when your church says the great apostacy took</i><br>
<i>&gt;place, but in the early AD 100s Justin Martyr wrote about the Christian</i><br>
<i>&gt;keeping the day Sunday as the Sabbath.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
Cardinal Gibbons makes no bones about the change being by Catholic ordination!<br>
<p>
Bill Oblitey<br>
[OBLITEY@OAK.GROVE.IUP.EDU]<br>
