<title>Sep_1992: SABBATH</title>
<h1>SABBATH</h1>
Paul Gates (<i>70516.420@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>03 Sep 92 08:26:19 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#41">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#41">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#41">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#41">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0042.html">Steven Timm: "Music ideas"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0040.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: Response to Tony's question about vegetarianism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
To the Network:<br>
<p>
Steve, I would like revisit the reason for my statements on the Sabbath<br>
since I believe everyone on the network that responded to me were<br>
misunderstanding my message.<br>
<p>
Let me back up and give some background ----<br>
<p>
The good news of salvation, realized in the holy history of Jesus Christ,<br>
is often described in the New Testament by the word, REST (Matt 11:28;<br>
Heb. 4:2,3) Since the Fall, this promised rest in Christ has been linked<br>
with the Sabbath. For this reason the major feast days in the Old<br>
Testament, pointing to the Messiah and His redemptive activities, were<br>
designated "a Sabbath day of rest." The Sabbath therefore, is more than a<br>
day of physical and mental rest but has definitely a redemptive<br>
significance and is a vital part of the new covenant. Hence, recovering<br>
and restoring the full gospel, necessitates the recovery and the<br>
restoration of the Sabbath doctrine. So where I am coming from is  trying<br>
to share that the Sabbath rest is related to the gospel and the doctrine<br>
of righteousness by faith.<br>
<p>
Probably I really should back up to the expression, "In Christ" and<br>
elaborate on that expression but will do that later.<br>
<p>
My first point is:<br>
<p>
1. THE SABBATH IS GOD'S REST DAY<br>
While the Sabbath was made for man (Mark 2:27), it does not belong to man<br>
but God: For proof texts please cite: <br>
	Ex. 20:10 "The Seventh day is the Sabb. of the Lord thy God."<br>
	Ex. 31:13 "My Sabbaths ye shall keep."<br>
	Isa. 58:13 "My holy day....the holy of the Lord"<br>
<p>
God created this world in six days and rested on the seventh day. Man was<br>
created at the end of the sixth day and therefore God's Sabbath was really<br>
his first whole day. ( Gen. 1:26-2:3)<br>
<p>
God first worked and rested, the pattern for man was the very opposite;<br>
Adam and Eve did not begin by working, but resting in God's finished work<br>
and then followed it by six days of work. This distinction is very<br>
important when Sabbath is applied to the gospel. God's seventh day is our<br>
Saturday ( Juke 23:54-56, T.E.V.)<br>
<p>
The reason God rested the seventh day was not because He was tired or<br>
needed a break but because His work was PERFECT AND FINISHED.<br>
<p>
Both creation as well as redemption were accomplished through Christ.<br>
Further, both were finished on the sixth day and in each case Christ<br>
rested on the seventh day from all His work.<br>
<p>
Creation: Jn. 1:3;Eph. 3:9;Col. 1:16; Rev. 3:14.<br>
Redemption: Rom. 3:24; 1Cor. 1:30;Gal. 3:13; Col 1:14; Titus 2:14; Heb.<br>
9:12; 1Pet. 1:18.<br>
<p>
Therefore Christ could rightfully claim to be "Lord also of the Sabbath."<br>
Mk 2:28; Luke 6:5.<br>
<p>
God's Sabbath was made for man is my next point but I will comment on that<br>
next time.<br>
<p>
To some on the network, what I am saying is foreign and "untried." But<br>
the Sabbath must be judged by the gospel.<br>
<p>
...........Paul<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
