<title>Sep_1992: Re: Sat v. Sun Sabbath</title>
<h1>Re: Sat v. Sun Sabbath</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>COTRSSM@sea04vm.navsea.navy.mil</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 03 Sep 92 11:26:45 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#47">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#47">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#47">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#47">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0048.html">Stan Macasieb: "Re: Music ideas"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0046.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Day of rest"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On Thu, 3 Sep 1992 09:12:47 -0400 (EDT) you said:<br>
<i>&gt;I agree with you that God has the right to change whatever He chooses, but</i><br>
<i>&gt;wht would He change His Memorial of creation?</i><br>
<p>
  To a memorial of the atonement, a rememberance of Christ's<br>
resurrection.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I have studied some of the LDS works and the greatest problem I have is with</i><br>
<i>&gt;Peter showing up to J. Smith and this "Jesus' appointed day of Sunday" claim.</i><br>
<p>
  Really?  Not with polygyny or eternal marriage, or the Father having a<br>
body, or baptism for the dead, or the apostles John and the 3 Nephites<br>
being alive and on earth to this day, or Christ in America after leaving<br>
the apostles to ascend to heaven?<br>
<p>
  There are precedence in the Bible for a dead prophet coming to a<br>
living person (Moses and Elias coming to Jesus on mount).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Do you think that maybe He made a mistake in appointing Saturday as the</i><br>
<i>&gt;original sabbath in the first place?</i><br>
<p>
  No mistake with the original 7th day sabbath.  It was a rememberance<br>
of the completion of creation.  Then of the deliverance of Israel from<br>
Eypgt.  Now we have the 1st day sabbath in rememberance of the<br>
completion of the redemptive work of Jesus Christ.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;&gt;  I don't remember exactly when your church says the great apostacy took</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;place, but in the early AD 100s Justin Martyr wrote about the Christian</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;keeping the day Sunday as the Sabbath.</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Cardinal Gibbons makes no bones about the change being by Catholic ordination!</i><br>
<p>
  So, the catholics have been known to be wrong before.  :) Actually,<br>
since they claim apostlic succession then, they are 'sort of' correct<br>
(the apostles did make the change.  See my remarks about Steve's<br>
addition to my last note where I mention the Epistle to the Magnesians,<br>
written 101 AD).<br>
<p>
