<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0049.html">Bob Moynihan: "A Christian Nation (was: Rules and Culture)"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0047.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Sat v. Sun Sabbath"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0042.html">Steven Timm: "Music ideas"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi, Stever,<br>
<p>
I liked your review of the latest MWS album. I'm going to get it<br>
in the next few weeks.<br>
<p>
Anyway, back home we had a little row over music and appropriateness.<br>
Brett Barry made a weekend swing through the Chicago area a couple<br>
of weekends ago. He made a stop at North Shore for a Saturday evening<br>
concert at 6 PM. For you sticklers to details, that did put the<br>
performance at the tail end of the Sabbath. Not only that, the youth<br>
leader insisted that the concert be held in the sanctuary for<br>
acoustic reasons. The church gym's acoustics, for the lack of a<br>
better word, stink and the sanctuary's A/V equipment has been updated<br>
over the last five years.<br>
<p>
The leader also took the initiative to invite an opening act, a local<br>
Christian rock group, to perform before Barry. This whole issue<br>
was taken before the church board for approval. I, and a number of<br>
others, didn't mind having Barry there. He had agreed to keep his<br>
musical set in harmony with the Sabbath, but we couldn't get assurances<br>
that the opening act would. Also, the board feared a backlash from<br>
the more conservative members complaining that anything resembing<br>
CCM doesn't belong in the sanctuary. Period. You know, the types who<br>
cringe when a singer uses recorded backing music for special music.<br>
<p>
I really wanted to have both of them in there, esp the opening act.<br>
If we really want to give our support for our local musicians, no<br>
matter what your persuasion, you need to give them some kind of<br>
platform to be noticed. The board ended up allowing Barry to perform<br>
w/o an opening act. The review is forthcoming in the next church<br>
newsletter. I haven't even seen the review yet.<br>
<p>
I've got other comments on music and appropriateness, but I'll save<br>
it for another time. Hope I didn't scare you, Steve.<br>
<p>
--Stan Macasieb (stanm@comm.mot.com)<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
