<title>Sep_1992: A Christian Nation (was: Rules and Culture)</title>
<h1>A Christian Nation (was: Rules and Culture)</h1>
Bob Moynihan (<i>moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 3 Sep 92 10:23:33 EDT </i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#49">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#49">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#49">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#49">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0050.html">Bill Nickless: "Wedding Band"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0048.html">Stan Macasieb: "Re: Music ideas"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Paul Writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; It is interesting to read some accounts of American history where it would</i><br>
<i>&gt; appear to be very evident that America was more of a Christian nation</i><br>
<i>&gt; then some like to admit. </i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; I am sure probably we all know on the network that originally for instance</i><br>
<i>&gt; and example, there were church related, church sponsored colleges and</i><br>
<i>&gt; universities. And as follows:</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Harvard (1636)</i><br>
<i>&gt; Yale (1701)</i><br>
<i>&gt; Princeton (1746)</i><br>
<i>&gt; University of King's College (1789)</i><br>
<i>&gt; Rutgers (1766)</i><br>
<p>
There is a difference, Paul, between a being a nation that allows Christian<br>
belief and teaching, and a "Christian Nation."  For the United States to be<br>
offically a Christian Nation would be, in effect, to say that if one is a<br>
Jew, Hindu, Buddhist, Muslim, Atheist, or a member of any other non-Christian<br>
faith, then one is not an American.  To do this would, I believe, be a <br>
chilling first step towards being declared a "Sunday worshipping Christian<br>
Nation", or a "Papal following Christian Nation."    <br>
<p>
God gave us the freedom to choose to follow Him, or not.  Billions of people<br>
believe they -are- following Him, and there are many paths that these billions<br>
follow, each convinced their way is the right one.  We need to show them why<br>
we feel the way we walk is the proper path, and allow them to choose it if they<br>
will.  We cannot force them to follow it through governmental decree.  That is<br>
not God's way.  Christ asks for our love, Satan demands our fealty.  If we work<br>
to force people to be Christian by making this a Christian Nation, we are not<br>
working for the Lord at all. <br>
<p>
-Bob<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
