<!-- body="start" -->
[(Tony) PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; SDAs have always made a point of defending their sunset-to-sunset every</i><br>
<i>&gt; week. This has often been the cause of much hardship, as illustrated</i><br>
<i>&gt; by countless stories of people losing jobs/failing courses/losing</i><br>
<i>&gt; friends and so on. Usually the stories we read or hear have a happy</i><br>
<i>&gt; ending, but let's face it, many real life ones don't.</i><br>
<p>
This is an instance of the broad topic of suffering, esp. for doing right.<br>
There are some verses which are relevant to this (e.g., I Pet 2:15,19, 3:17,<br>
4:19; all the texts in Rev. re those who endure with patience).  None of<br>
them suggest that one has an out if the going gets tough.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The only problem is, I do often work on Saturday, and I do often miss many</i><br>
<i>&gt; of the aspects of public worship. How can this contradiction be resolved?</i><br>
<i>&gt; SDAs seem to be quite happy about work on Sabbath, so long as it is</i><br>
<i>&gt; medical-related and/or unpaid.</i><br>
<p>
May I suggest that the elaborateness of the preparations necessary for<br>
such type of services might encourage one to reconsider whether making a<br>
real production out of things is in harmony with Sabbath keeping.<br>
<p>
By the way, while Sabbath is comparatively restful for most folk, it's<br>
incredibly busy for pastors.  Is their work wrong on the Sabbath?<br>
(Hint:  There's a verse in Scripture addressing this specifically.  Extra<br>
bonus points to the finder.) Those who help with the church services<br>
would be in the same boat, I reckon.<br>
<p>
As for the medical work:  The basis is that Christ healed on the Sabbath.<br>
Therefore, any medically-related work is OK, right?  I would suggest a careful<br>
reading of EGW's counsel on Sabbath keeping at our health institutions.<br>
The index is a good place to start research.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  On Attitude &amp; the Immune System:  A sound heart is the life of the flesh:
    but envy the rottenness of the bones.  Prov 14:30
</pre>
