<title>Sep_1992: Re:  Sat v. Sun Sabbath</title>
<h1>Re:  Sat v. Sun Sabbath</h1>
Adam David (<i>adamd@rhi.hi.is</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 3 Sep 92 16:46:48 GMT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#53">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#53">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#53">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#53">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0054.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Saturday versus Sunday"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0052.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Day of rest"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0015.html">Scott Mattes: "Sat v. Sun Sabbath"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Cheryl wrote:<br>
<i>&gt; SDAs believe that the 7th day has been the very same literal 7th day of each</i><br>
<i>&gt; week since the beginning of time on this earth (and before the existence of</i><br>
<i>&gt; this earth).  However, this very literal interpretation of God's law is not</i><br>
<i>&gt; as defensible as you may think.  With all the "leap years", "leap minutes",</i><br>
<i>&gt; and changes in the calendar historically, nobody can "prove" that the same</i><br>
<i>&gt; 7th day has been kept ALWAYS.</i><br>
<p>
Depends what constitutes proof. I was curious about this issue once, and was<br>
sure that through the ages some discrepancy had occurred. Thus I proceeded to<br>
calculate the days and dates back into history, rather a non-trivial task as<br>
it turned out. There are other calendars and historic records which can be<br>
compared to get a triangulation on a particular day if the same event is<br>
recorded in both histories. (no, I didn't do all this research myself, but<br>
the calculations were exact and meticulous - based on verifiable research).<br>
It is a rather complex matter because from 10 to 15 calendar dates (depending<br>
on when the change from Julian to Gregorian calendar took place in different<br>
countries) were deleted from the calendar.<br>
<p>
The results showed conclusively that the day we call Saturday is in fact the<br>
same Sabbath that Judaic people kept before the time that Jesus walked this<br>
earth. If it can be shown that the weekly Sabbath was kept without changing<br>
days during the entire Old Testament period, then we can be sure that it is<br>
indeed the same Sabbath today.<br>
<p>
Of course whether sabbath is to be interpreted literally or symbolically is a<br>
different matter altogether.<br>
<p>
<pre>
--
Adam David. (adamd@rhi.hi.is)
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
