<title>Sep_1992: Saturday versus Sunday</title>
<h1>Saturday versus Sunday</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 3 Sep 92 14:15:31 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#54">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#54">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#54">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#54">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0055.html">Tony: "Re: Day of rest"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0053.html">Adam David: "Re:  Sat v. Sun Sabbath"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
SDAnet,<br>
<p>
I posted what I did to try to stimulate some thinking.  (I get tired of the<br>
memorized standard replies posted without thought.)  To give you a good<br>
example of what I was trying to convey (which appears to have been misunderstood), try this one.<br>
<p>
SDAs believe in the law of tithing.  Although tithing has not been a test of<br>
membership in general, it certainly has been used for purposes of selecting<br>
church leaders and employees.  Well, the tithing system set up for Israel<br>
required that the FIRST fruits be given as tithe.  Not the 2nd or 3rd tenths.<br>
Yet, I have never heard an SDA vehemently argue that your tithing was not<br>
acceptable to God unless it was the VERY FIRST CHECK you wrote after getting<br>
your paycheck (First fruits).  How many SDA belief their tithe is acceptable<br>
if paid AFTER the rent or mortgage but before anything else?  Is that the<br>
FIRST fruits?  No!!!  Is it acceptable to God?  Absolutely!  Why?  Because<br>
the spirit of the law of tithing is to give 10% to God.  Yet SDAs do this<br>
literal thing on the 7th day Sabbath.  Is worship on the first day of the<br>
week acceptable?  Absolutely!  How about the 2nd, 3rd, 4th..etc.  Absolutely!<br>
I think God would be thrilled if we became devout enough in our submission<br>
and worshipped EVERY DAY of the week!  Does it break God's law to worship<br>
on the First day of the week if you also kept the 7th?  No!  This is why I<br>
cannot understand the idea that my entire Salvation rests on whether I keep<br>
the "right" day of the week!  I don't believe God is that dogmatic or<br>
arbitrary (I know, using arbitrary will bring a flood of EGW quotes from the<br>
Great Controversy).  But I use it here to make a point.  Is God arbitrary<br>
about anything in the plan of salvation?  Yes, Jesus was the only one to<br>
live a perfect life and worthy to offer as an atonement.  But if there had<br>
been a second being, did it have to be Jesus?  Would only Jesus' blood have<br>
paid the debt?<br>
<p>
I also don't understand how SDAs can claim that pre-cross and post-cross<br>
requirements for salvation were NOT different.  What would have happened<br>
to an Israelite if he said his family wasn't going to offer animal sacrifices<br>
because they believed the Jesus future blood would be sufficient?  Would he<br>
and his family been allowed to stay in the encampment?  No!  The sacrifice<br>
was REQUIRED and NECESSARY.  Without spilling of animal blood, there was<br>
no atonement for sin before the cross.  Whether the cross was the fulfillment<br>
of a covenant that could not be kept by pre-cross Israel is immaterial.  There<br>
are clearly two different "dispensations."  SDAs quickly agree that the Law of<br>
Moses "was nailed to the cross."  Was the Law of Moses given of God?  Yes!<br>
Was it God's Law then?  Yes, to Israel it was the requirements of God.  Did<br>
God change or overturn His own law?  Absolutely!  I'm not buying a lamb and<br>
slaughtering it every time I need to repent and ask for forgiveness!  So does<br>
God change His laws?  Yes, we have clear evidence that He did for Israel.  Could<br>
God change His law(s) now or in the future?  Yes.  I have frequently heard<br>
SDAs liken the pre-cross era to the toddler-young child age when parents make<br>
rules (i.e. laws) that may seem abitrary because not mature enough to understand.  Then after the cross, man had matured in his ability to know and understand<br>
God, so the "demanding jealous God" became more "loving."  As your children<br>
grow, the rules of behavior and living in your household will change (and must<br>
change) to allow them maximum opportunity for growth and self-actualization.<br>
We don't make them go to bed at 8pm or take a nap.  We allow them more freedom<br>
by lessening (and changing) the rules.  This is what "dispensations" are all<br>
about.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
