<title>Sep_1992: Re: Day of rest</title>
<h1>Re: Day of rest</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 4 Sep 1992 09:56 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#55">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#55">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#55">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#55">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0056.html">Tony: "Re: Women's role &amp; jewellery..."</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0054.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Saturday versus Sunday"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0030.html">Tony: "Day of rest"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0057.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Day of rest"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Jim writes:<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
  I would beg to differ; it would seem to me that IF a person became <br>
convicted that it was still important to God that he keep His commandments, <br>
THEN no matter WHAT happens, as long as he keep them, thru Christ's <br>
strength, then a happy ending is GUARANTEED.  :-)<br>
  Don't forget, "All things work together for good to them that love the <br>
Lord," and "if you love me, keep my commandments."<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
I guess the point here is that none of our stories have ended yet. As for<br>
things always having a happy ending in the temporal sense, I'm sure you<br>
could think of some examples yourself where this isn't the case.<br>
<p>
As for "keep my commandments", the problem is in working out what God is<br>
saying with each one. In my opinion the commandments would read differently<br>
if God were to repost them in 1992. They would add up to say the same thing,<br>
but would read differently. In the meantime, we're left with the x000 B.C.<br>
version and a bit of help from Jesus at around 25 A.D.<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
  I will admit that sometimes it appears that some would use their <br>
"medical-related" or "unpaid" work to justify certain actions on the <br>
Sabbath, but remember that Jesus is our example, not others.  See what he <br>
did on the Sabbath - how did he work and act on the Sabbath?  You'll see <br>
that Christ's emphasis is one of WORKING for others and not being engrossed <br>
in the work of self-gratification or "thine own pleasure."<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
The interesting thing about Jesus' Sabbath miracles is that none of them were<br>
urgent medical things. ie they all could have waited until Sunday. People born<br>
blind or lame, or with a withered hand, could all have held on for one more <br>
day out of 40-odd years! So he was obviously trying to make a point, and I<br>
think the thing about liberation of people and working for others could well<br>
be an important aspect of Sabbath.<br>
<p>
This idea first occurred to me when reading Isaiah 58. I wondered whether <br>
perhaps the whole chapter could be applied to the Sabbath instead of just the<br>
last two verses (which is what is usually done). If so, then this chapter<br>
says that we shouldn't waste holy time in introspection etc., but that we<br>
should use the day constructively, helping others. But is that a fair<br>
way to read the chapter? I'm no Hebrew scholar!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<p>
p.s. I believe that an important communication method for God is using his<br>
     human representatives on Earth. Hence I don't believe that I am cutting<br>
     God out by going to you guys with these questions etc. Quite the opposite!<br>
     <br>
<p>
----------------<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
