<title>Sep_1992: Re: Day of rest</title>
<h1>Re: Day of rest</h1>
Drew Corrigan (<i>drew@dubhe.anu.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 4 Sep 92 10:57:50 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#57">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#57">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#57">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#57">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0058.html">Russell Grau: "Re: Day of rest"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0056.html">Tony: "Re: Women's role &amp; jewellery..."</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0030.html">Tony: "Day of rest"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0058.html">Russell Grau: "Re: Day of rest"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Tony writes:<br>
<i>&gt; SDAs have always made a point of defending their sunset-to-sunset every</i><br>
<i>&gt; week. This has often been the cause of much hardship, as illustrated</i><br>
<i>&gt; by countless stories of people losing jobs/failing courses/losing</i><br>
<i>&gt; friends and so on. Usually the stories we read or hear have a happy</i><br>
<i>&gt; ending, but let's face it, many real life ones don't.</i><br>
<p>
Christ said his yoke is easy, but nowhere did he promise Christians they<br>
wouldn't experience problems. My reading of the NT in fact suggests that<br>
trials are guaranteed to Christians. Yes our problems might be great -<br>
and I do not intend in anyway to indicate lack of sympathy for those<br>
who experience Sabbath trials (I've had my share in the past) - but in<br>
the midst of these, we must remember that nothing can separate us from<br>
God's love for us, that he is working out a greater purpose than we might<br>
be able to comprehend, that he will not let us be tested beyond our <br>
limits, and that in the end, his promise of eternal life is certain.<br>
The Church also has a responsibility to support those for experience<br>
trials - when one member of the body suffers, we all suffer.<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; So here's my question.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Someone at uni wants me to do something on Saturday. Maybe it's help out</i><br>
<i>&gt; with a public demonstration. Maybe it's just a social activity. I say,</i><br>
<i>&gt; "thanks, but my Saturday's are booked to God, and besides, I don't want</i><br>
<i>&gt; to miss church" or whatever. Perhaps then they ask me to explain about</i><br>
<i>&gt; the Sabbath. My explanation would probably include "holy day", "worship",</i><br>
<i>&gt; and "no work" if I am a typical SDA.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; The only problem is, I do often work on Saturday, and I do often miss many</i><br>
<i>&gt; of the aspects of public worship. How can this contradiction be resolved?</i><br>
<i>&gt; SDAs seem to be quite happy about work on Sabbath, so long as it is</i><br>
<i>&gt; medical-related and/or unpaid.</i><br>
<p>
I am a deacon in a congregation of about 180 people. My Sabbaths tend to be<br>
quite busy, especially so if I have the sermonette or youth Bible Study.<br>
The Sabbath is much busier still for the pastor. I see no contradication<br>
in the work I, or the pastor does on the Sabbath. The Sabbath was probably<br>
the busiest day of the week for the Levitical Priesthood, yet their service<br>
was necessary for the worship of God as ordained by God himself. Their<br>
service (and my service) is an act of sacrifice on behalf of the greater<br>
needs of the congregation. It is not doing my "pleasure" or "business" -<br>
ie. my interests, my concerns and my work - as such (Is 58:13).<br>
<p>
To attend my place of employment however would most certainly be doing my<br>
interests - putting other things ahead of the worship of the True God.<br>
<p>
Regards,<br>
<p>
Drew Corrigan.<br>
