<title>Sep_1992: Re: Day of rest</title>
<h1>Re: Day of rest</h1>
Russell Grau (<i>reg@ctsx.celtech.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 4 Sep 92 05:34 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#58">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#58">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#58">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#58">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0059.html">Russell Grau: "Re: Day of rest"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0057.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: Day of rest"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0030.html">Tony: "Day of rest"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0059.html">Russell Grau: "Re: Day of rest"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Cheryl writes:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Subject: Saturday versus Sunday</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;SDAnet,</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;I posted what I did to try to stimulate some thinking.  (I get tired of the</i><br>
<i>&gt;memorized standard replies posted without thought.)  To give you a good</i><br>
<i>&gt;example of what I was trying to convey (which appears to have been misunderstood), try this one.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;SDAs believe in the law of tithing.  Although tithing has not been a test of</i><br>
<i>&gt;membership in general, it certainly has been used for purposes of selecting</i><br>
<i>&gt;church leaders and employees.  Well, the tithing system set up for Israel</i><br>
<i>&gt;required that the FIRST fruits be given as tithe.  Not the 2nd or 3rd tenths.</i><br>
<i>&gt;Yet, I have never heard an SDA vehemently argue that your tithing was not</i><br>
<i>&gt;acceptable to God unless it was the VERY FIRST CHECK you wrote after getting</i><br>
<i>&gt;your paycheck (First fruits).  How many SDA belief their tithe is acceptable</i><br>
<i>&gt;if paid AFTER the rent or mortgage but before anything else?  Is that the</i><br>
<i>&gt;FIRST fruits?  No!!!  Is it acceptable to God?  Absolutely!  Why?  Because</i><br>
<i>&gt;the spirit of the law of tithing is to give 10% to God.  Yet SDAs do this</i><br>
<i>&gt;literal thing on the 7th day Sabbath.  Is worship on the first day of the</i><br>
<i>&gt;week acceptable?  Absolutely!  How about the 2nd, 3rd, 4th..etc.  Absolutely!</i><br>
<i>&gt;I think God would be thrilled if we became devout enough in our submission</i><br>
<i>&gt;and worshipped EVERY DAY of the week!  Does it break God's law to worship</i><br>
<i>&gt;on the First day of the week if you also kept the 7th?  No!  This is why I</i><br>
<i>&gt;cannot understand the idea that my entire Salvation rests on whether I keep</i><br>
<i>&gt;the "right" day of the week!  I don't believe God is that dogmatic or</i><br>
<i>&gt;arbitrary (I know, using arbitrary will bring a flood of EGW quotes from the</i><br>
<i>&gt;Great Controversy).  But I use it here to make a point.  Is God arbitrary</i><br>
<i>&gt;about anything in the plan of salvation?  Yes, Jesus was the only one to</i><br>
<i>&gt;live a perfect life and worthy to offer as an atonement.  But if there had</i><br>
<i>&gt;been a second being, did it have to be Jesus?  Would only Jesus' blood have</i><br>
<i>&gt;paid the debt?</i><br>
<p>
Yes, Jesus was the only one who could have paid the debt.  You could have<br>
lived a perfect life, but that would not pay the debt.  You were born as a<br>
woman, under the penelty of sin.  This was handed down from our mutual father<br>
Adam and our mutual mother Eve.  NO ACT OF MINE CAN SAVE ME OR OTHERS.<br>
<p>
Jesus died ONCE for mankind.  Only the substitutionary death of Jesus would<br>
pay the debt that I have with God.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;I also don't understand how SDAs can claim that pre-cross and post-cross</i><br>
<i>&gt;requirements for salvation were NOT different.  What would have happened</i><br>
<i>&gt;to an Israelite if he said his family wasn't going to offer animal sacrifices</i><br>
<i>&gt;because they believed the Jesus future blood would be sufficient?  Would he</i><br>
<i>&gt;and his family been allowed to stay in the encampment?  No!  The sacrifice</i><br>
<i>&gt;was REQUIRED and NECESSARY.  Without spilling of animal blood, there was</i><br>
<i>&gt;no atonement for sin before the cross.  Whether the cross was the fulfillment</i><br>
<i>&gt;of a covenant that could not be kept by pre-cross Israel is immaterial.  There</i><br>
<i>&gt;are clearly two different "dispensations."  SDAs quickly agree that the Law of</i><br>
<i>&gt;Moses "was nailed to the cross."  Was the Law of Moses given of God?  Yes!</i><br>
<i>&gt;Was it God's Law then?  Yes, to Israel it was the requirements of God.  Did</i><br>
<i>&gt;God change or overturn His own law?  Absolutely!  I'm not buying a lamb and</i><br>
<i>&gt;slaughtering it every time I need to repent and ask for forgiveness!  So does</i><br>
<i>&gt;God change His laws?  Yes, we have clear evidence that He did for Israel. Could</i><br>
<i>&gt;God change His law(s) now or in the future?  Yes.  </i><br>
<p>
Cheryl, you obviously have confused several things.  First, what law are we<br>
speaking of here?  Is it a law that was contained in ordinances and sacrifices?<br>
If so, then this law had to change.  Why, because it pointed to the one whom <br>
would be the "Lamb of God".  Does that change the law of God?  No, it does not.<br>
There is only one law that I know sin by.  This law points up to what is wrong<br>
in my life.  That is the law of God.  Is this law arbitrary?  Yes, it is.<br>
<p>
Why is it arbitrary?  Because we would never understand what God was like <br>
without God telling us.  His character is so far from ours we could never<br>
even imagine a God like this.  The law was not given to Israel only.<br>
Remember, long before there was Abraham, there were sacrifices.  Noah was not<br>
a Jew.  Neither was Adam and Eve.  Yet these had knowledge of sacrifices.<br>
They understood the covenant that had been made in Eden, when Jesus promised<br>
to provide the sacrifice Himself.<br>
<p>
Dispensations?  No, there is only one way in mankind has been saved.  Re-read<br>
Hebrews 11 for more information.  The sacrifices were a confirmation that the<br>
believer accepted God as his Lord and Saviour and that God would save him<br>
from the sins he/she was confessing.  Re-read the Psalms again.  Do you see<br>
the man there praising what he had done in sacrificing to God?  No you see a<br>
man, repentant pleading for the salvation that cannot come from sacrifices.<br>
Check out Isaiah again.  You see God unsatisfied with the blood of bulls and<br>
rams.  Why, because they had not been offered in faith.  The blood pointed to<br>
Jesus.  Without the faith that was to come, then the sacrifices were nothing<br>
more than a MEANINGLESS round of cerimonies that did NOT bring salvation.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I have frequently heard</i><br>
<i>&gt;SDAs liken the pre-cross era to the toddler-young child age when parents make</i><br>
<i>&gt;rules (i.e. laws) that may seem abitrary because not mature enough to </i><br>
<i>&gt;understand.  Then after the cross, man had matured in his ability to know and </i><br>
<i>&gt;understand God, so the "demanding jealous God" became more "loving."  As your </i><br>
<i>&gt;children grow, the rules of behavior and living in your household will </i><br>
<i>&gt;change (and must change) to allow them maximum opportunity for growth and </i><br>
<i>&gt;self-actualization.  We don't make them go to bed at 8pm or take a nap.  We </i><br>
<i>&gt;allow them more freedom by lessening (and changing) the rules.  This is what </i><br>
<i>&gt;"dispensations" are all about.</i><br>
<p>
Sorry, the rules of the house remain the same.  Don't lie, steal, etc.  Naps<br>
are for their physical benefit and do not have anything to do with basic<br>
rules of the household.  Allowing them the freedom to make their own<br>
decisions does not change the rules, nor does it give them leave to break<br>
them without any consequences.<br>
<p>
No, Cheryl, there is no such thing as "dispensations" under God's universe.<br>
We are saved by one thing, faith.  Jesus was trying his entire life to get<br>
the Jews to recognize that this is what was missing in their lives.  From<br>
Adam to the last man who has faith right before Jesus returns at the last, we<br>
are saved by one thing, not our actions - though they speak of our faith, but<br>
by our faith.<br>
<p>
If we have faith, then we follow what Jesus tells us to do.  How do we do<br>
that?  Only by the power of the indwelling of the Holy Spirit.  He is the<br>
power to give me a change in my heart.  He provides the oil that I so<br>
desperately need.<br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Cheryl</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
