<title>Sep_1992: Re: Day of rest</title>
<h1>Re: Day of rest</h1>
Russell Grau (<i>reg@ctsx.celtech.com</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 4 Sep 92 05:10 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#59">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#59">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#59">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#59">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0060.html">Ian Brown: "Re.Satv. Sun Sabbath"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0058.html">Russell Grau: "Re: Day of rest"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0030.html">Tony: "Day of rest"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0062.html">Tony: "Re: Day of rest"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;Subject: please post</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Some of you may be able to relate to my situation.  If you can,</i><br>
<i>&gt;I'd appreciate your thoughts.  </i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
Good, you're about to get some.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I teach mathematics at a state university.  Out of about 11,000</i><br>
<i>&gt;students, perhaps 25 are SDA's ranging in age from 18 to 45.  They</i><br>
<i>&gt;are single, married, undergraduates, grad students, full-time,</i><br>
<i>&gt;part-time, comfortable, poor, desperate, sick, and healthy.  What they</i><br>
<i>&gt;are NOT is seen, appreciated, noticed, significant, etc. as far as</i><br>
<i>&gt;the church is concerned.  Why is it that otherwise normal people</i><br>
<i>&gt;are so totally incapable of manifesting any interest in SDA</i><br>
<i>&gt;students living in their own town going to a state school?  All the</i><br>
<i>&gt;theology in the world can't explain that away.  Our adult members</i><br>
<i>&gt;are numb inspite of what they think of themselves.  This is also</i><br>
<i>&gt;true with regard to the conference "leaders" who make this town</i><br>
<i>&gt;home.  How do we get our members and "leaders" off their comfortable</i><br>
<i>&gt;backsides with regard to this problem?</i><br>
<p>
There is only one way for this to happen.  Have the students, even one or two<br>
is enough, and have them start to make some noise.  At our church, we started <br>
our own Valuegenesis evaluation.  Part of that included getting the students<br>
involved.  We invited the church family to participate in two nights (Tuesday<br>
evenings from 6:30 til ??:??) over two weeks to evaluate where the youth<br>
program should be going.<br>
<p>
One of the things that came out of this was a couple of the local Adventist <br>
youth said that we had nothing for the local state university students.  Perhaps<br>
we need to start an Adventist student association at some of our local colleges<br>
and university's.  Having this association would allow for some formal manner<br>
of reaching out to our youth, fellowship among the youth, and also a platform<br>
for reaching out to others in the university.<br>
<p>
But, I can honestly say this, until someone brings it up in a STRONG manner, <br>
nothing will happen.  Sad to say, but quite often, the squeeky wheel gets the<br>
greese.   :-(<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Dave Thomas</i><br>
<i>&gt;Montana State University</i><br>
<i>&gt;umsfdtho@deimos.oscs.montana.edu</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
Never be afraid of speaking out for our young people.  Do it strongly, and with<br>
love and conviction.  The Lord will be with you as you endevor to perform the<br>
work of the God.<br>
<p>
