<title>Sep_1992: Re.Satv. Sun Sabbath</title>
<h1>Re.Satv. Sun Sabbath</h1>
Ian Brown (<i>Malachi.Robertson@lambada.oit.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 3 Sep 92 23:51:58 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#60">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#60">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#60">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#60">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0061.html">Lisa Parry: "Re: please post"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0059.html">Russell Grau: "Re: Day of rest"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0094.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Re.Satv. Sun Sabbath"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Recently Scott mentioned Ignatius of Antioch's letter to the Magnesians. <br>
It appeared to me that he was pointing to the text as a proof that<br>
Ignatius was somehow supporting a Sunday Sabbath.  The text in question is<br>
Magnesians 9:1 : which has the portion that says, "no longer sabbatizing<br>
but living according to the Lord's life [or Lord's day]."  The text in<br>
context refers not to the Christians of that day but to the prophets of<br>
the Old Testament.  The chapter before directly refers to the prophets<br>
living according to Christ Jesus.  Then in the passage in question<br>
Ignatius makes a contrast between "those who were brought up in the<br>
ancient order of things" and "we".  Then the contrast is reemphasized with<br>
him returning to the prophets:  "how shall we be able to live apart from<br>
Him, whose disciples the prophets themselves in the Spirit did wait for<br>
Him as their Teacher?"  The prophets clearly kept the Sabbath, so it<br>
appears that Ignatius was probably refering to the way in which the<br>
Sabbath was being kept.  <br>
<p>
"Malachi Robertson" better known as Ian Robertson Brown<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
