<title>Sep_1992: Re: please post</title>
<h1>Re: please post</h1>
Lisa Parry (<i>parry@gandalf.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 4 Sep 92 8:08:29 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#61">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#61">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#61">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#61">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0062.html">Tony: "Re: Day of rest"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0060.html">Ian Brown: "Re.Satv. Sun Sabbath"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0029.html">Dave Thomas: "please post"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0063.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: please post"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; Some of you may be able to relate to my situation.  If you can,</i><br>
<i>&gt; I'd appreciate your thoughts.  </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I teach mathematics at a state university.  Out of about 11,000</i><br>
<i>&gt; students, perhaps 25 are SDA's ranging in age from 18 to 45.  They</i><br>
<i>&gt; are single, married, undergraduates, grad students, full-time,</i><br>
<i>&gt; part-time, comfortable, poor, desperate, sick, and healthy.  What they</i><br>
<i>&gt; are NOT is seen, appreciated, noticed, significant, etc. as far as</i><br>
<i>&gt; the church is concerned.  Why is it that otherwise normal people</i><br>
<i>&gt; are so totally incapable of manifesting any interest in SDA</i><br>
<i>&gt; students living in their own town going to a state school?  All the</i><br>
<i>&gt; theology in the world can't explain that away.  Our adult members</i><br>
<i>&gt; are numb inspite of what they think of themselves.  This is also</i><br>
<i>&gt; true with regard to the conference "leaders" who make this town</i><br>
<i>&gt; home.  How do we get our members and "leaders" off their comfortable</i><br>
<i>&gt; backsides with regard to this problem?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
I have no easy answer, only an observation.  Example is a good teacher, and it<br>
doesn't have to start with the "leaders".  I live in a college town (about 10<br>
colleges within 30 miles (that's not counting Andrews U and LMC which are 60<br>
miles away).  There is a couple in the church that has a large house and they<br>
have a social every week for college students from anywhere (they invite the<br>
SDA's and urge them to bring a friend if they wish).  This allows for get <br>
togethers, feeling included, etc.  This couple also goes out of there way to<br>
offer temporary housing or other assistance to those who find themselved in<br>
need.  They aren't really leaders in the church (though I'm sure they hold some<br>
position), but they do a lot toward <br>
keeping the young adult population there, and sometimes getting it active in the<br>
church.<br>
<p>
Anyway, I know everyone can't do something like that, but my point is it can<br>
be small, it can start with one interested person, and it doesn't have to be<br>
a leader.<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
"If God is for us, who can be against us?"            Lisa Parry
--Romans 8:31, last sentence                   parry@andrews.edu
</pre>
