<title>Sep_1992: Re: Day of rest</title>
<h1>Re: Day of rest</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 4 Sep 1992 07:29 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#62">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#62">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#62">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#62">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0063.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: please post"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0061.html">Lisa Parry: "Re: please post"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0030.html">Tony: "Day of rest"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0071.html">Paul Gates: "Re: Day of rest"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Fred writes<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
May I suggest that the elaborateness of the preparations necessary for<br>
such type of services might encourage one to reconsider whether making a<br>
real production out of things is in harmony with Sabbath keeping.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
Yeah, that was the direction my thoughts first started to turn when the<br>
more complex programs became the rule rather than the exception. I mentioned<br>
the way I was feeling to a couple of worship committee people, often the<br>
ones who would ring me up during the week and say "I know you're busy, but<br>
how about a practice...I've been working flat out on this program for two<br>
weeks now" etc. etc. Their usual response was mixed, basically the same<br>
way I was feeling.<br>
 <br>
On the one hand we wonder whether a worship service requires this much <br>
preparation and "production". On the other hand we all admit that were we<br>
to give up our jobs as program coordinators/producers/presenters we would<br>
almost certainly keep coming along were someone else to take over in the<br>
same way. Secondly, we like to put as much quality into the services as we<br>
can, in keeping with the concept of giving your best to God. Thirdly, the<br>
whole issue of worship style is involved here, and as long as that issue<br>
remains controversial any steps we may take would appear to be statements<br>
on the actual style rather than its inherent production requirements.<br>
<p>
So we are still pondering that one. That's one of the reasons I'm interested<br>
in hearing all of your opinions.<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
By the way, while Sabbath is comparatively restful for most folk, it's<br>
incredibly busy for pastors.  Is their work wrong on the Sabbath?<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
I'm not sure about the bonus text, but besides that I would say that most<br>
of the comments in the previous paragraph would still apply. Some types of<br>
Sabbath activities keep pastors much busier than others. It seems to me that<br>
if the Sabbath is really important, even a pastor could arrange things so<br>
that it was having its correct function for him/her.<br>
<p>
But this is one of the things that bugs me a bit. When I demonstrate at uni<br>
in winter I don't leave the prac until just after sunset. By the time I get<br>
home Sabbath has started 45 minutes to 1 hour ago. Some people raise their<br>
eyebrows when they find out I don't get home until 6pm on a Friday afternoon,<br>
but some of those same people are the ones ringing me up at 8am on Saturday<br>
morning wanting me at church in half an hour for a practice. They have no <br>
problem expecting the pastor to work hard all Sabbath morning, help with the<br>
pot luck lunch, help coordinate ingathering in the afternoon and whatever else.<br>
I'm trying to work out whether or not that's a double standard. I think it<br>
probably is!<br>
<p>
By the way, myself and the program coordinators in my church do enjoy what we<br>
do. I am just wondering whether it really is in keeping with the Sabbath. If<br>
we didn't enjoy it we probably would have stopped long ago. :)<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<p>
As for the medical work:  The basis is that Christ healed on the Sabbath.<br>
Therefore, any medically-related work is OK, right?  I would suggest a careful<br>
reading of EGW's counsel on Sabbath keeping at our health institutions.<br>
The index is a good place to start research.<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  On Attitude &amp; the Immune System:  A sound heart is the life of the flesh:
    but envy the rottenness of the bones.  Prov 14:30
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
