<title>Sep_1992: vegetarianism</title>
<h1>vegetarianism</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 4 Sep 92 13:33:54 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#64">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#64">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#64">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#64">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0065.html">Dave Plaisted: "plant suffering"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0063.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: please post"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In response to Tony, I don't really separate health and religious<br>
reasons.  I view it as a religious duty to preserve health.<br>
<p>
I don't eat meat ever.  The reason is that if I started it would be<br>
easy to slide more and more till I always did it.  (Since I grew up<br>
eating meat.)  I don't think occasional meat eating is harmful<br>
unless you happen to get disease or antibiotics etc. from it, which<br>
is quite possible today.<br>
<p>
In an emergency I would eat meat.<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
