<title>Sep_1992: Students at state Univ.</title>
<h1>Students at state Univ.</h1>
Tim Swensen (<i>swensen@ecn.purdue.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 4 Sep 92 11:00:57 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#67">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#67">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#67">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#67">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0068.html">Steven Timm: "Re: students ... addendum"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0066.html">Tim Swensen: "students ... addendum"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
SDAnet,<br>
<p>
With regard to Dave Thomas' post concerning SDA students at public<br>
colleges/universities, let me offer the following points.<br>
<p>
I am the President of Adventist Christians for Abundant Living -- a <br>
student organization here at Purdue University.  When we organized a <br>
year and a half ago, we were enthusiastic about the possibilities for <br>
evangelism and vibrant social life that awaited us.  I remember typing<br>
up a list of the goals we had -- sort of a statement of purpose.  That<br>
was 1990.  We still exist as an organization, but have had a hard time<br>
maintaining our enthusiasm.<br>
<p>
Students are pulled in many directions.  We are busy.  When I was <br>
employed as an engineer I simply had more free time than I do these<br>
days.  I see lack of time as probably the biggest practical impediment<br>
to a vibrant, active SDA student organization.  The married students <br>
(especially those with children) really need to devote the bulk of their<br>
free time to strengthening their family ties.<br>
<p>
Lack of money is also a significant concern.  To bring a speaker for a <br>
series of weekend meetings costs money.  I believe we could make more<br>
of an impact at Purdue if we could invite students to a lecture where<br>
someone affiliated with one of the church's colleges/universities could<br>
speak to issues they are interested in from an Adventist perspective.<br>
<p>
Last school year, our organization collected funds from our members and<br>
a few others at church to place excerpts of Steps To Christ in the <br>
Purdue student newspaper.  A small excerpt was printed one day per week.<br>
We were able to print all of the first two chapters during the Spring <br>
semester.  A number of students and one staff member requested a free<br>
copy of the book.  We even had one student and his girlfriend (wife?) <br>
visit our local church.  Our dillema is that we don't have a good follow-up<br>
program in place.  Without the commitment of our own members to regularly<br>
attend meetings (especially planning meetings) it is hard to see how we<br>
are going to be able to hold the interest of students who become acquainted<br>
with us.<br>
<p>
In spite of our troubles getting going we have made a small impact on the<br>
campus.  We were involved in a group Bible study with one student.  Though<br>
he quit studying with us after a few weeks, seeds have been planted.<br>
<p>
There are so many organizations on campus, but I've not seen any that<br>
are portraying God in quite the way Adventists understand Him.  I pray that<br>
we can become an influence for good on this campus.  There is a real need<br>
here.<br>
<p>
Dave, I would be cautious in stating that the denomination (and,  by <br>
implication, many local congregations) do not appreciate, notice, or <br>
value the contributions of the students at public colleges/universities.<br>
I have received words of thanks from a number of members in West Lafayette<br>
for the contributions I have made to our worship services.  If students<br>
involve themselves in the local church they will be noticed.  <br>
<p>
Still, a general lack of understanding as to what are the particular needs <br>
of the students remains.  I see this as part of a larger problem -- the <br>
growing isolation of many groups, brought on in part by the rapidly changing<br>
world in which we live.  I don't think more than 15% or so of our members<br>
(indeed, of society at large) understand much about what an electrical<br>
engineering student studies.  Likewise, the daily activities of many of<br>
our older members are largely unknown to me.<br>
<p>
To end this somewhat lengthy post, let me offer one suggestion that I <br>
believe would draw us closer to our local church members.  Get together<br>
for Sabbath lunch!!  I enjoy very little mealtime communion with anyone <br>
most days.  Sabbath could be different, for God has graciously mandated <br>
that we take a rest.  I don't have in mind just potlucks.  Those members<br>
who have homes large enough to have a few mealtime guests need only provide<br>
a pot of soup and some bread.  Students will flock to where the food is.<br>
<p>
Tim Swensen<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
