<!-- body="start" -->
Three years ago when I was resident on the Carnegie Mellon campus,<br>
as I am now, I registered our church with the Campus Ministry Council,<br>
thus putting us in the directory of churches that is handed to all students.<br>
(Our church in Pittsburgh is about 3/4 mile from campus.)  We called<br>
our on-campus presence Sigma Delta Alpha.  For one semester I ran a program<br>
called "Let's Talk Relationships" where people would just get together <br>
and talk about issues in human relations.  Free food guaranteed that <br>
someone would always come, although I was handicapped due to an obscure<br>
location.<br>
<p>
Sometimes professionals in the community that could relate well to students<br>
don't because they are not sensitive to the fact that students are on a<br>
limited budget.  Our pastor has been very hospitable to the various<br>
students within our congregation, and if he didn't live 20 miles from<br>
campus, I'm sure he would have us over even more.  <br>
<p>
As far as involvement in the local church is concerned, this is sometimes <br>
handicapped when churches start their church offices in Jan., when the<br>
school year is already half over and people can't commit to the next<br>
full calendar year.  I solved the problem personally by finding niches<br>
that don't necessarily require a church office.  In all the positions of<br>
responsibility I have held in various churches, I have somehow managed<br>
to avoid a title that would put me on the Church Board.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
