This is a post from Scott Mattes, edited by me:<br>
On Wed, 2 Sep 1992 12:06:17 -0400 (EDT) you said:<br>
<i>&gt;[SDA's don't deny that Sundaykeeping began as early as the mid 100's AD.</i><br>
<i>&gt;As far as the New Testament itself is concerned, there is no doubt.  Some</i><br>
<i>&gt;may have been generated in Scott's mind by reading the classic Mormon</i><br>
<i>&gt;work "A Marvelous Work And A Wonder", in which LeGrand Richards makes</i><br>
<i>&gt;outright lies in his interpretation of New Testament Greek.</i><br>
<p>
Steve,<br>
  Did I catch you on a bad day or something?  At the very least the<br>
wording of your response is very out of character.  It is also of the<br>
type used by most, if not all, of the groups/people who rail against<br>
what they perceive as cults.  That is, make a bold and negative<br>
statement against something/one of the 'other side' but offer no<br>
proof/explanation of your statement.  The reader/hearer is therefore<br>
presented with a problem, do I believe the person making the statement<br>
about the 'cult' or do I go and research it for myself and make sure.<br>
99 times out of 100 the reader/hearer will accept the bold and negative<br>
statement and never question it.  I had thought better of you.<br>
[I didn't have the book at hand.  If I had, I would have checked.  As<br>
you will see, I should have checked.  SCT]<br>
<p>
  To clarify, as a Lutheran I was brought up 'keeping' Sunday (I now<br>
know that the keeping I was taught was a joke, at best).  As LDS I read<br>
D&amp;C 59 and knew that the Lord had sanctioned the keeping of the 1st day<br>
of the week as the Sabbath.  I also learned what it meant to truly keep<br>
that day holy.  It wasn't until much later that I ever read the book you<br>
speak against.<br>
<p>
  To those who are in the 1 out of the 100 and want to know for<br>
yourself, I offer a copy of the book maligned by Steve at no cost to<br>
you, just email me with your address and I'll ship it to you (anywhere<br>
in the world!  Right Ruben?).  Then you can judge for yourself.<br>
<p>
  On to Steve ascertains.  Since he wasn't at all specific I went back<br>
and read the chapter he 'must' be referring to (the one on the Sabbath)<br>
and still I wonder exactly what Steve takes exception to.  Brother<br>
Richards list Mk 16:2,19 Lk 24:1 Jn 20:1,19 Acts 20:7 and 1 Cor 16:2 as<br>
places that the original Greek had the word 'sabbaton' or Sabbath.  When<br>
I look in my Strong's concordance I see that he is correct.  From the<br>
context of the passages I think that they refer to Sunday.<br>
<p>
[These words from Scott forced me to check.  After the check, I must retract<br>
and say that the author of that book is not lying, although he is certainly<br>
misinterpreting.  In Mark 16:2  "In the end of the sabbath, as it began<br>
to dawn towards the first day of the week...."   The word 'sabbaton' appears<br>
twice in this verse, once referring to the sabbath and once as part of <br>
a phrase 'mia sabbaton' which is translated 'first day of the week'.  The <br>
people of that time reckoned all their days according to the Sabbath.<br>
You will notice if you look at the second definition of 'sabbaton' it also<br>
refers to the weekly cycle itself.  So the case above is just a<br>
misinterpretation of the context in which the word is found.   SCT]<br>
<p>
[Some of Scott's post edited out here]<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;in different times.  Unlike the LDS, we require consistency between all</i><br>
<i>&gt;prophetic messages.  SCT]</i><br>
<p>
  This smacks of the same "believe me when I tell you what these others<br>
believe, you don't have to check it out for yourself" attitude.  For<br>
shame.<br>
[Mormon missionaries said to me that it's not the internal consistency <br>
of the works that really matter.  I did check it out for myself,  I'm<br>
not afraid if others do the same.  SCT]<br>
<p>
  P.S. you might want to also include in your list of lying books the<br>
one 'Evidence that demands a verdict by Josh McDowell'.  He has stuff in<br>
there about Sunday sabbath also.  It agrees with the LDS book (or maybe<br>
the agreement is the other way around, or just complimentary).<br>
[The agreement is there because Josh is also willing to suspend belief<br>
at times and make evidence out of stuff that is really not evidence.  SCT]<br>
<p>
