<!-- body="start" -->
To Network:<br>
<p>
Steve, I think you handled the answer about work on the Sabbath very well.<br>
While I was beginning to type this post, I was thinking of the Wright<br>
Church in Mich. located not too far from Grand Rapids at Coopersville,<br>
MD. When I first went to pastor there in 1982. the Head Deacon would go to<br>
the church about 2:30 AM to turn on the heat so it would be warm by<br>
Sabbath School time!! Of course he could have done it before he went to<br>
bed! We helped him out a bit on that burden. The church had a high ceiling<br>
so we installed some ceiling fans to push to heat downward. By doing that<br>
the deacon did not have to turn on the heat till 6 AM!!<br>
<p>
Anyway, as you suggested for the Pastors, Sabbath can almost be the<br>
busiest day. At least two Sabbaths a month I do spend some time with my<br>
wife in relaxing activities. We enjoy driving a short distance to Oxford<br>
or St. Michael's at one of their parks watching the sail boats etc. We<br>
usually take some Sabbath reading material with us. We are just a few<br>
minutes from water in practically any direction so there are a lot neat<br>
things we can do on Sabbath.<br>
<p>
At our camp meeting I am in charge of the Public Address System and<br>
usually work from 6AM onward on Sabbaths getting mikes ready queing up<br>
tapes for the singers etc.<br>
<p>
At our home churches Evelyn and I are always arriving at church between<br>
7:30 AM - 8 AM (we are early birds) and seeing that everything is in<br>
order. Sometimes I set out the mikes etc for the sound engineer so she<br>
doesn't have to come extra early.<br>
<p>
.........Paul<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
