<title>Sep_1992: Modern prophets and the Sabbath</title>
<h1>Modern prophets and the Sabbath</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon,  7 Sep 1992 10:21:21 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#76">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#76">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#76">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#76">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0077.html">Tony: "Sunday-keeping SDAs"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0075.html">Dan Blake: "Re: plant suffering"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Scott Mattes (and the rest of the LDS denomination) has made the claim that<br>
the Sabbath was changed, citing the authority of Joseph Smith, who in<br>
turn claims the authority of Peter, James, and John.  Most churches<br>
would respond to that claim by denying the latter-day gift of prophecy<br>
altogether, SDA's<br>
cannot do this since we also claim a latter-day prophet, namely Ellen G.<br>
White.  There are few people who accept the authority of both people.<br>
And since the two have made contradictory statements about the continuity <br>
of the Sabbath, we would think, at least in the SDA tradition, that one <br>
of them is wrong.<br>
<p>
Those who follow Joseph Smith as a prophet must accept the assumption he<br>
made, or revelation he claimed to have received, that the law of God is <br>
changeable in time.  When the Psalms refer to the law of the Lord as <br>
perfect, and Psalm 119, the longest chapter in the Bible, devotes all <br>
of that to praising the law of God, this tells me that the Law has<br>
not changed and cannot be changed any more than the character of God <br>
can change, since the law is a transcript of His character.  To this we <br>
add Christ's statement that "not one jot or tittle shall pass away from <br>
the Law until all be fulfilled," and Paul's warning "if any man preach <br>
a gospel unto you different that what we have preached to you, let him<br>
be accursed."<br>
<p>
We need to look carefully at how prophets gain validity for us.  For <br>
most Mormons, it is the 'burning in the bosom' as referred to and<br>
recommended by the Book of Mormon.  I wonder how many SDA's also begin<br>
and stop at <br>
that level.  The emotional feeling and conviction of truth must and does<br>
come first, but we should then move from faith to understanding.  If we<br>
are to merely accept at face value every claim of inspiration (and this<br>
includes <br>
the Bible) we would have to believe a lot of contradictory things, perhaps<br>
even have to hire an "Electric Monk" as described by Douglas Adams.  <br>
We need to study inspired writings and those that claim to be inspired to see<br>
if their writings and their conclusions validate their claim to inspiration,<br>
and not go about postulating that which we can prove.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0077.html">Tony: "Sunday-keeping SDAs"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0075.html">Dan Blake: "Re: plant suffering"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
