<title>Sep_1992: Sunday-keeping SDAs</title>
<h1>Sunday-keeping SDAs</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Sun, 6 Sep 1992 11:47 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#77">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#77">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#77">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#77">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0078.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Re.Satv. Sun Sabbath"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0076.html">Steven Timm: "Modern prophets and the Sabbath"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0097.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: Sunday-keeping SDAs"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
After having read in various posts that<br>
<p>
* Saturday is almost certainly the correct seventh day<br>
* There is no "right reason" to keep Sunday as the Sabbath<br>
<p>
etc. etc., I just thought I'd like to add something extra to this discussion.<br>
<p>
Did you know that in Tonga Seventh-day Adventists worship on/keep Sunday?<br>
ie instead of, not as well as, Saturday.<br>
<p>
The story goes that they used to keep Saturday while the international date<br>
line went straight from one pole to the other. But then someone had the bright<br>
idea to bend it so that Fiji, a close neighbour of Tonga, would have the same<br>
calendar day as Tonga. (Check an atlas and you'll understand what I mean.)<br>
<p>
SDAs in the South Pacific had a quick panic session and decided that it wasn't<br>
really the day of the week that was important, but it really did have to be<br>
an even multiple of seven days since that original Sabbath in the garden. So<br>
when the weekday labels changed, they kept observing the seven day cycle,<br>
and now they keep Sunday!<br>
<p>
Fiji, just across the water, still keeps Saturday, as they weren't directly<br>
affected by the date line change.<br>
<p>
So how about that. All the Sunday-keeping Christians in Tonga may actually be<br>
worshipping on the "correct day", if the multiple-of-seven thing is right.<br>
<p>
Those who adhere to this point of view really should construct their own date<br>
line through Iraq, figure out which day of the week corresponds to the seventh<br>
day when this date line is the reference, and then start keeping it! :)<br>
<p>
For all those who have wished they didn't have to keep Saturday due to it <br>
being so weird, I have it on good authority from friends of mine in Tonga<br>
that it is definitely preferable to Sunday. Consider finishing work on <br>
Friday afternoon, having your do what you want day, then having Sabbath,<br>
then back to work the next day. One of my friends is a teacher, and has to<br>
prepare his classes on Saturday because he can't on Sunday. After years of<br>
being an SDA he finds it very hard to get motivated to do anything like that<br>
on Friday night and Saturday!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
