<title>Sep_1992: Re: Re.Satv. Sun Sabbath</title>
<h1>Re: Re.Satv. Sun Sabbath</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon,  7 Sep 1992 10:41:30 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#78">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#78">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#78">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#78">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0079.html">Paul: "LOST TIME"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0077.html">Tony: "Sunday-keeping SDAs"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
On Fri, 4 Sep 1992 09:04:44 -0400 (EDT) you said:<br>
<i>&gt;Recently Scott mentioned Ignatius of Antioch's letter to the Magnesians.</i><br>
<i>&gt;It appeared to me that he was pointing to the text as a proof that</i><br>
<i>&gt;Ignatius was somehow supporting a Sunday Sabbath.  The text in question is</i><br>
<i>&gt;Magnesians 9:1 : which has the portion that says, "no longer sabbatizing</i><br>
<i>&gt;but living according to the Lord's life [or Lord's day]."  The text in</i><br>
<i>&gt;context refers not to the Christians of that day but to the prophets of</i><br>
<i>&gt;the Old Testament.  The chapter before directly refers to the prophets</i><br>
<i>&gt;living according to Christ Jesus.  Then in the passage in question</i><br>
<i>&gt;Ignatius makes a contrast between "those who were brought up in the</i><br>
<i>&gt;ancient order of things" and "we".  Then the contrast is reemphasized with</i><br>
<i>&gt;him returning to the prophets:  "how shall we be able to live apart from</i><br>
<i>&gt;Him, whose disciples the prophets themselves in the Spirit did wait for</i><br>
<i>&gt;Him as their Teacher?"  The prophets clearly kept the Sabbath, so it</i><br>
<i>&gt;appears that Ignatius was probably refering to the way in which the</i><br>
<i>&gt;Sabbath was being kept.</i><br>
<p>
the texxt that I was refering to is this;<br>
<p>
  "Those who were brought up in the ancient order of things, have come<br>
to the possession of a new hope, no longer observing the Sabbath, but<br>
living in the observance of the Lord's day on which also our life was<br>
sprung by him and his death.  (Epistle to the Magnesians, 101 AD,<br>
Chapter 9, Ignatius)"<br>
<p>
  This sounds like he was refering to people living at his time and not<br>
the prophets of old.<br>
<p>
  Coupled with this<br>
<p>
  "...The Christians of this century, in piety, assemble for the worship<br>
of God and for their advancement of the first day of the week, the day<br>
on which Christ reassumed his life; for that this day was set apart for<br>
religous worship by the apostles themselves, and that, after the example<br>
of the church at Jerusalem, it was generally observed, we have<br>
unexceptional testimony.  (Moshiem's Church History, Book 1, Century 1,<br>
part 2 Chap 4:4)"<br>
<p>
  Led me to believe that Sunday was observed VERY early in the church's<br>
history.  Note that Moshiem's Church Histoy, Book 2, Century 4, part 1,<br>
Chap 1:8 Constantine is talked about and the year 324 AD is used for<br>
him, so I am assuming that book 1, century 1 is refering to the years<br>
BEFORE 100 AD.<br>
<p>
--------------------------------------+----------------------------------------<br>
Scott (nmi) Mattes                    | No success can compensate for failure<br>
Work: COTRSSM@SEA04VM.NAVSEA.Navy.Mil | in the home.  David O. McKay, Prophet<br>
Home: 73027.3270@CompuServe.COM       | and President of the Church of Jesus<br>
Voice: (703) 769-2917                 | Christ of Latter-day Saints, 1951-70<br>
<p>
[We need some help on this one, I've misplaced my 'From Sabbath To Sunday.'<br>
and I don't have my copy of Magnesians handy.  Any response is helpful.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
