<title>Sep_1992: LOST TIME</title>
<h1>LOST TIME</h1>
Paul (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon,  7 Sep 1992 10:44:34 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#79">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#79">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#79">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#79">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0080.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "God's Law - Moses's Law"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0078.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Re.Satv. Sun Sabbath"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0093.html">Paul Gates: "Re: LOST TIME"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Network:<br>
<p>
Steve, I talked to Dr Shea this morning about the business of lost time<br>
and we may not be worshipping truly Sunday or Saturday. He mentioned to me<br>
that there is no way time could have been lost because of Sabbath keepers,<br>
Sunday keepers, and Moslems. He didn't have time to go into any scientific<br>
approach because I was teaching the SS class at the time.<br>
<p>
I am sure he could give you some scientific data though if he were<br>
contacted.<br>
<p>
..........Paul<br>
<p>
[The calendar history is well-known since the days of Julius Caesar,<br>
when the Julian Calendar was promulgated.  Since that point it has <br>
been documented by any astronomical society you care to find that<br>
the weekly cycle has not slipped a day.  Up to that point, there<br>
were various communities of Jews, none of whom disagree on what day <br>
is the Sabbath, even to this day, and some of them have been separated<br>
(as in the case of those recently rescued from Ethiopia) for hundreds of<br>
years.  SCT]<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
