<title>Sep_1992: SDA-L:  New policy on forwarding</title>
<h1>SDA-L:  New policy on forwarding</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+%ANDREW.CMU.EDU%CMU.EDU@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>07 Sep 1992 15:08:25 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#84">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#84">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#84">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#84">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0085.html">Ian Brown: "Re: Sat. v. Sun Sabbath"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0083.html">Steven Timm: "SDA-L:  Let the personals begin"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
For most of the past year SDAnet members have sent replies to me about SDA-L<br>
posts.  In most cases I have not forwarded them to SDA-L.  This has resulted<br>
in discussion getting trapped on SDAnet and lower traffic on SDA-L.<br>
<p>
The policy will change as follows:  All posts sent to me with<br>
SDA-L in the subject line (which will put it in a special mailbox)<br>
will be forwarded  to SDA-L.  Note:  This is only for SDAnet members<br>
who have not subscribed directly to SDA-L, which is the majority.<br>
<p>
I urge everyone who posts to SDA-L  (yes, that means both of you)<br>
to begin every post with SDA-L just so we know which one is coming<br>
from what and the two networks do not seem to be one amorphous mass.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
