<title>Sep_1992: Re: Sat. v. Sun Sabbath</title>
<h1>Re: Sat. v. Sun Sabbath</h1>
Ian Brown (<i>Malachi.Robertson@lambada.oit.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 7 Sep 92 19:48:45 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#85">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#85">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#85">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#85">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0086.html">cheryl berthelsen: "God's Law portrays His character?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0084.html">Steven Timm: "SDA-L:  New policy on forwarding"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Scott,<br>
<p>
that was the verse I was talking about.  What I used was a translation of<br>
the verse that was more in line with the actual Greek.  But regardless of<br>
whether the word life or day is included the context makes it clear that<br>
he is refering to the prophets.  I quote from the ANF version closing off<br>
parenthetical clauses.<br>
<p>
"If, therefore, those who were brought up in the ancient order of things<br>
have come to the possession of a new hope, no longer observing the<br>
Sabbath, but living in the oberservance of the Lord's Day, {on which also<br>
our life has sprung up again by Him and by His death--whom some deny, by<br>
which mystery we have obtained faith, and therefore endure, that we may be<br>
found the disciples of Jesus Christ, our only Master --} how shall we be<br>
able to live apart from Him,{whose disciples the prophets themselves in<br>
the Spirit did wait for Him as their Teacher}?"  <br>
<p>
In fact, just looking at this whole question once again I can see why one<br>
scholar said it actually makes more sense to translate the word life in<br>
there (which does appear in Greek manuscripts but is ignored it seems). <br>
There is a contrast in this passage between "we" and "those who were<br>
brought up in the ancient order of things."  This constrast makes more<br>
sense if the word life is included as then Ignatius's statements would be<br>
the following (leaving out the {} part above and inserting an alternative<br>
translation for the first part so life is included)<br>
<p>
"If, therefore, those who were brought up in the ancient order of things<br>
have come to the possession of a new hope, no longer observing the<br>
Sabbath, but living in the observance [or as the ANF editors note<br>
"according to"] the Lord's life ... how shall we be able to live apart<br>
from Him...?"<br>
<p>
Again, I don't see how the text can point to early Christians keeping<br>
Sunday as a Sabbath.  <br>
<p>
As far as the historian you mention, I am unfamiliar with him.  I must,<br>
however, question his statements given the texts of the New Testament and<br>
the statements of other historians.<br>
<p>
Ian.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
