<title>Sep_1992: God's Law portrays His character?</title>
<h1>God's Law portrays His character?</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 8 Sep 92 00:23:21 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#86">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#86">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#86">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#86">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0087.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Bible to interpret itself"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0085.html">Ian Brown: "Re: Sat. v. Sun Sabbath"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0126.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re:  God's Law portrays His character?"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben,<br>
<p>
Would you mind giving me a few scriptures that support the idea that<br>
God's Law is intended to portray or symbolize His character?  thank you.<br>
I appreciated your analysis of God's Law versus The Law of Moses.  However,<br>
I fail to see how the fact that God gave the law to Moses to give to the<br>
Isrealites would render it Moses's law rather than God's Law.  If God<br>
gave it (directly or indirectly), is it not still from God?<br>
<p>
Lisa also gave some interesting questions about God saying "Thou shalt<br>
not commit adultery unless you just can't get along with your spouse" (my<br>
paraphrase.)  But we do have scriptural evidence that God did make<br>
exceptions to Law.  Although He said "Thou shalt not kill", He instructed<br>
the Isrealites to kill men, women and children on several occasions.  In<br>
other words, "Thou shalt not kill unless I direct you to do so because<br>
they are a wicked nation."  Did the Isrealites break God's Law when they<br>
murdered and killed innocent women and children at His direction?<br>
<p>
If it is God's Law, does He have authority to change it?  (I'm not asking<br>
IF He would change it?)  If He has the authority to change it and a<br>
Christian bases his/her belief on a Sunday Sabbath on a direct command<br>
given to an individual whom they accept and believe is a prophet of God,<br>
then doesn't that Christian have a basis for accepting a changed Sabbath<br>
day?<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
