<title>Sep_1992: Daniel 7:25</title>
<h1>Daniel 7:25</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 8 Sep 92 02:07:13 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#88">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#88">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#88">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#88">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0089.html">Tony: "Re: Vegetarianism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0087.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Bible to interpret itself"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have done some study on the verse you referred to about changing<br>
times and laws.  Daniel 7:25 says:<br>
<p>
        "And he [the king that subdued 3 kings] shall speak great<br>
        words agains the most High, and shall wear out the saints<br>
        of the most High, and think to change times and laws: and<br>
        they shall be given into his hand until a time and times<br>
        and the dividing of time."<br>
<p>
Firstly, the Hebrew word used in this verse for laws is 'dath' rather<br>
than 'torah'.  'dath' is translated to mean law or sentence while<br>
'torah' is translated to mean direction or teaching.  Whenever the<br>
Law of God is referred to in Scripture, the word 'TORAH' is used.  But<br>
in this verse it is not.  So is this king thinking to change the<br>
10 commandments?  Not according to the Hebrew word used.  Also notice<br>
that Daniel says this king shall "think" to change times and laws.<br>
The Hebrew for "think" used here is "sebar" meaning to hope or purpose<br>
to change laws.  This king is hoping or purposing to change some laws<br>
but it is clearly NOT the torah or The Law of God.  And it doesn't<br>
indicate what the times are that are hoped to be changed.  The Hebrew<br>
word used here for times is "zeman" meaing season and is distinct from<br>
"iddan" which is used at the end of the verse "a time and times and<br>
the dividing of time."  I'm not certain what the "times" and "laws"<br>
are that this 3rd king hopes to change.  But it isn't God's Law (torah)<br>
and it isn't the calendar because the Hebrew word for day or days is<br>
"yom" or "yamin".<br>
<p>
This is a good example of how I feel SDA doctrine has been based on<br>
incorrect interpretation of scripture.  The original Hebrew does not<br>
support the idea that God's Law (10 commandments) are being changed<br>
here.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
