<title>Sep_1992: Pre-existent law</title>
<h1>Pre-existent law</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 8 Sep 1992 18:25 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#90">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#90">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#90">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#90">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0091.html">Tony: "Re: Plant suffering"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0089.html">Tony: "Re: Vegetarianism"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Ruben writes:<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
The scriptures tell us of two main sets of laws, the moral and the ceremonial<br>
or if you wish the Decalogue and the Levitical Law (the Law of Moses).<br>
One was preexistant, and eternal it is the standard of righteousness, the<br>
revelation of the righteousness of Christ, the other was given to Israel at<br>
Sinai which was a "shadow of things to come" and pointed forward to the Messiah.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
Genesis 2:2-3<br>
<p>
"And on the seventh day God finished his work which he had done, and he rested<br>
on the seventh day from all his work which he had done. So God blessed the<br>
                                                        ^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^^<br>
seventh day and hallowed it, because on it God rested from all his work which<br>
^^^^^^^^^^^                  ^^^^^^^<br>
he had done in creation."<br>
<p>
<p>
Exodus 20:11<br>
<p>
"...for in six days the Lord made...and rested...therefore the Lord blessed the<br>
                                                 ^^^^^^^^^<br>
sabbath day..."<br>
<p>
<p>
Somewhere else<br>
<p>
"...the sabbath was made for man, not man for the sabbath."<br>
<p>
<p>
Seems that the fourth commandment, at least, refers to something which may<br>
just have been invented especially for our race. Why doesn't it say somewhere<br>
in the Bible, "...because everybody else keeps the seventh day holy"?<br>
<p>
Besides, the concept of a universal sabbath seems a bit strange, given the<br>
way in which we measure our days.<br>
<p>
Personally, I am of the opinion that the law is, as many others have said,<br>
purely a particular revelation of God. Its purpose is to help us diagnose<br>
our sinful condition, and to point towards God. Were God to give the law<br>
to late-twentieth-century western society, it would probably read quite <br>
differently. Jesus himself showed remarkable flexibility in his approach to<br>
the law when he was around. <br>
<p>
Progression on the part of the human race as<br>
a whole has affected the way God reveals himself, and the way he is perceived.<br>
I don't believe in dispensations in the sense that salvation is available<br>
through different means at different periods in history, but I do believe<br>
that God's relationship to man has changed over time.<br>
<p>
Obviously there are aspects of God which would come through any particular<br>
revelation, and through any moral law given to any culture.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
