<title>Sep_1992: Re: Plant suffering</title>
<h1>Re: Plant suffering</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 8 Sep 1992 17:55 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#91">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#91">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#91">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#91">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0092.html">Paul Gates: "Rest In Christ"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0090.html">Tony: "Pre-existent law"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Here's an interesting point.<br>
<p>
Many Christians paint the picture of the Garden of Eden as a place where<br>
there was no death, and I mean none. I think (correct me if I'm wrong)<br>
EGW speaks of Adam and Eve watching the first leaf die or the first flower<br>
or something after they had eaten the fruit.<br>
<p>
So here's the question. If there was no death of plants, what were the fruit<br>
and flowers for anyway? Don't say for the initial reproduction of plants,<br>
because presumably man and animals would have still needed to eat fruit etc.<br>
after that initial period.<br>
<p>
btw, those who are concerned about plant suffering will obviously never<br>
walk on the grass!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
