<title>Sep_1992: Rest In Christ</title>
<h1>Rest In Christ</h1>
Paul Gates (<i>70516.420@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>07 Sep 92 23:05:46 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#92">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#92">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#92">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#92">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0093.html">Paul Gates: "Re: LOST TIME"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0091.html">Tony: "Re: Plant suffering"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Network:<br>
<p>
Steve,<br>
I wanted to reinterate once more what I was trying to share with the net<br>
when I brought up the matter of "resting fully in Christ for our<br>
salvation." <br>
<p>
Really, I thought I would get some praise from the Mormons (especially<br>
Cheryl) and other Sunday keepers that might be on the net when I said,<br>
"Many Sunday keeping christians are resting fully in Christ for their<br>
salvation!" I still believe that! And, I still believe that a few, or<br>
some Adventists are keeping the Saturday/Sabbath for the wrong reasons<br>
when they believe their Sabbath keeping will save them. In other words<br>
another way of expressing it is this way: "How many Sabbaths does an<br>
Adventist have to observe or keep in order to be Saved?"<br>
<p>
I guess I threw up the "proverbial red flag" when I mentioned the wrong<br>
day as Sunday and the right day or Sabbath as Saturday. In my own thinking<br>
I was targeting 7th-day Adventists when I said what I did. SDAs usually I<br>
would think, would refer to Saturday as the right day and Sunday as the<br>
wrong day to worship.<br>
<p>
I suppose you could say that I do worship on Sunday because I visit Sunday<br>
churches to be able to fellowship with my "Sunday preaching brothers" and<br>
to get some fresh insights, illustrations from their sermons. However, I<br>
think the net understands where I am coming from, I believe that Saturday<br>
is the day I primarily should be worshiping God and I consistently do<br>
that. Some of my "Sunday preaching brothers" visit our church on<br>
Saturday. Once a year we exchange pulpits. I preach in one of the Sunday<br>
churches and their pastor preaches at our church on the previous day. I<br>
really enjoy it and it is a tremendous way for me to share my faith with<br>
them. When we can, our church choir combines with a choir from a Sunday<br>
church and have concerts in our church. At present we are developing a<br>
concert series that our church will be sponsoring once a quarter and it<br>
will be held in our church on Sunday afternoons. Some of the concerts will<br>
be done by Adventist groups. In December the Episcopalian choir will be<br>
doing a "Messiah Sing-a-long" at our church on Sunday afternoon.<br>
<p>
As far as Saturday Sabbath keepers are concerned I strongly believe that a<br>
person needs to be convinced in his own mind that Saturday is the day of<br>
worship that God requires. A neighbor friend of mine was quite upset about<br>
the Sabbath when it was presented in a seminar that we were conducting. My<br>
advice to him was not to concern himself about it, that I would be happy<br>
to study it with him later but that the important thing was to learn as<br>
much as he could from the Seminar. By the time the seminar was over, he<br>
was convinced in his own mind that Saturday was the day that God was<br>
asking him to observe and worship Him. <br>
<p>
Also, have been thinking of starting a preaching service in our Adventist<br>
church on Sunday mornings as an outreach for church growth. I would be<br>
targeting the unchurched people in our community who perhaps would be<br>
willing to attend church on Sunday at first but maybe not as willing on<br>
Saturday at first. <br>
<p>
I am not trying to "bash" the people who worship on Sunday. As far as I am<br>
personally concerned Sunday just does not hold any special significance<br>
for me other than just being another day like any other day of the week<br>
other than Saturday Sabbath.<br>
<p>
Hope I have made my point and position clear this time!!<br>
<p>
THOUGHT FOR THIS WEEK: "People cannot change truth, but truth can change<br>
people."   --------  Old Union Reminder<br>
<p>
..........Paul<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
