<!-- body="start" -->
Cheryl writes:<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
paraphrase.)  But we do have scriptural evidence that God did make<br>
exceptions to Law.  Although He said "Thou shalt not kill", He instructed<br>
the Isrealites to kill men, women and children on several occasions.  In<br>
other words, "Thou shalt not kill unless I direct you to do so because<br>
they are a wicked nation."  Did the Isrealites break God's Law when they<br>
murdered and killed innocent women and children at His direction?<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
When I was in college my Hebrew-scholar Old Testament lecturer pointed<br>
out to use that in fact the translation "thou shalt not kill" is a<br>
little generous. Apparently the original hebrew text had two words which,<br>
literally translated, say "don't murder". Murder here means the killing<br>
in anger of another person.<br>
<p>
It seems fairly obvious that God never meant "don't kill at all", given<br>
the number of offences for which the penalty was death in the Levitical<br>
laws  eg a woman pretending she was a virgin when she wasn't.<br>
<p>
(So where *do* the hard-line pro-lifers get their ethical motivation??)<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
