<title>Sep_1992: Re: Sunday-keeping SDAs</title>
<h1>Re: Sunday-keeping SDAs</h1>
Bill Oblitey (<i>OBLITEY@grove.iup.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 8 Sep 1992 09:18 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#97">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#97">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#97">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#97">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0098.html">Tony: "Scripture &amp; prophets"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0096.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: Women's role &amp; jewellery..."</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0077.html">Tony: "Sunday-keeping SDAs"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;* Saturday is almost certainly the correct seventh day</i><br>
<i>&gt;* There is no "right reason" to keep Sunday as the Sabbath</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;etc. etc., I just thought I'd like to add something extra to this discussion.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Tony</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
I feel like I have shared this too many times anbd have stopped talking about<br>
it but this discussion calls for it since I've never shared it on the net.<br>
<p>
In Ghana, West Africa, we are named accoring to the day of the week on which<br>
we were born (the so called god-given names).  I still use mine to this day.<br>
<p>
God (the omnipotent - to distinguish Him from the lesser gods) is called "The<br>
grat God whose day is Saturday".  The white man (who brought Christianity to<br>
Ghana and insisted on worshiping on Sunday) is called "The white man whose<br>
day is Snuday".  If I should take you (assuming your skin color is lighter<br>
than the normal sking color in Ghana) to Ghana today, people will refer to you<br>
as "Kwesi Broni" - literally "Sunday white person".<br>
<p>
There are other customs in the land that seem to run parallel with Bible time<br>
traditions, but this Saturday issue stands out like a sore thumb.  Many <br>
people use it in their Sabbath Sermon topics.<br>
<p>
Let me just stop here and not add anything of mine to the "story".<br>
<p>
Bill Oblitey<br>
[OBLITEY@OAK.GROVE.IUP.EDU]<br>
----------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
 "The direction in which education starts a 'man' will determine 'his'<br>
  future life." -- Plato, The Republic.<br>
----------------------------------------------------------------------<br>
