<title>Sep_1992: Scripture &amp; prophets</title>
<h1>Scripture &amp; prophets</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 8 Sep 1992 22:46 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#98">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#98">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#98">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#98">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0099.html">Lola: "students and food"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0097.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: Sunday-keeping SDAs"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Cheryl writes:<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
If a prophet is relied upon to provide enlightenment to the scriptures, are<br>
the scriptures being allowed to interpret itself?<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
I identify with the questions raised by Cheryl in this post. Thanks for<br>
the quotes Cheryl, I will definitely chase Schaefer's book up and read<br>
the whole thing.<br>
<p>
On the one hand I believe that the scriptures should stand alone.<br>
<p>
On the other hand I also believe that the influence of the Holy Spirit is<br>
important in the interpretation. I don't think the self-interpretation thing<br>
is such that the Holy Spirit is not required.<br>
<p>
The following questions arise in my mind.<br>
<p>
* Was God totally in control of the formation of the Biblical canon as we<br>
  know it today?<br>
<p>
* Why does the Bible stop at Revelation?<br>
<p>
* How did people relate to what we call the New Testament at the time during<br>
  which it was being written?<br>
<p>
* What is the role of a prophet?<br>
<p>
On the final question, I have heard it said that prophets always have a very<br>
contemporary role. That is, they are sent at a certain time, to a certain<br>
group of people, and for a certain reason. This pattern is certainly apparent<br>
in the Old Testament prophets. Apparently there were heaps more prophets around<br>
at that stage whose existence didn't make it into the Biblical record, apart<br>
from warnings to beware of the false ones.<br>
<p>
That's not to say that another group of people in another time can't benefit<br>
from the message delivered by the prophet. Only that the primary role of the <br>
prophet is very much contemporary.<br>
<p>
This fact should strongly influence the way we relate to the work of EGW. Her<br>
writings were mainly directed at individuals or groups, and were never intended<br>
to be broad messages to all generations of the future church. At the same<br>
time, much of what she wrote can be beneficial today if read with the correct<br>
perspective.<br>
<p>
I have heard it said from the pulpit and elsewhere that EGW is a messenger<br>
from God for our time. This may have been true when it was first said back<br>
whenever in the late nineteenth century. Now - the fact is that the lady has<br>
been dead for a long time. In the true spirit of conservatism, our church<br>
continues to refer to her message as though it has only just arrived.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<p>
P.S. My favourite book on prophets and people is 'Angry Saints' by <br>
     George Knight. A "must read" for all SDAs.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
