<!-- body="start" -->
Yup, when you have free food available you can get acquainted with<br>
students!  And as Lisa said, it doesn't have to come from the leaders<br>
of the church or conference.  At the Univ. of OK there were a few<br>
SDA students that we knew about and we and another few couples made<br>
sure that every student was invited over for Sabbath lunch somewhere<br>
EVERY Sabbath!  We had a small church and there weren't more than 5<br>
or so students, so it wasn't too difficult.  In a larger church you<br>
would need a few more cooperative families perhaps.  We were students<br>
ourselves and living in married student housing or a single wide<br>
trailer while there, but for 1 year we had an undergrad student come<br>
to dinner and stay most of the afternoon almost every week.<br>
<p>
We also registered with the campus organizations and started a campus<br>
ministry in a house close by the campus.  On Friday nights we offered<br>
free supper, singing, Bible study, and general socialization to SDA<br>
and non-SDA students who were interested.  This was somewhat less<br>
successful than the Sabbath afternoon efforts, possibly because it<br>
operated on a drop-in basis rather than weekly personal invitations.<br>
<p>
Even grad students with families (or perhaps ESPECIALLY those with<br>
families) would appreciate being asked over for Sabbath.  And Tim<br>
was right, it doesn't have to be a fancy meal.  We often had pasta --<br>
quick, cheap, and everyone likes it.<br>
<p>
Lola<br>
Aagaard@Morekypr<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
