<!-- body="start" -->
Scott writes:<br>
<i>&gt; &gt;[The calendar history is well-known since the days of Julius Caesar,</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;when the Julian Calendar was promulgated.  Since that point it has</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;been documented by any astronomical society you care to find that</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;the weekly cycle has not slipped a day.  Up to that point, there</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;were various communities of Jews, none of whom disagree on what day</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;is the Sabbath, even to this day, and some of them have been separated</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;(as in the case of those recently rescued from Ethiopia) for hundreds of</i><br>
<i>&gt; &gt;years.  SCT]</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt;   So the folks from Adam up until the Jews leaving Eygpt didn't mess up</i><br>
<i>&gt; the calendar even once?</i><br>
<p>
This is a non-issue. If the Sabbath day I keep today is the same day of<br>
the week as Jesus kept (in terms of a regularly repeating cycle of seven<br>
days, the days being defined as sunset to sunset), then that is sufficient.<br>
<p>
Jesus was (is) the Son of God who did not sin. Sin is the trangression of<br>
God's Law, including the law of observing the Sabbath. Therefore, Jesus<br>
observed the correct period of time within a 7-day week. And since Sabbath<br>
keeping Christans observe the same period of time as Jesus, they are<br>
observing the correct day of the 7 day week as the Sabbath.<br>
<p>
The Sabbath one of the signs identifying the people of God (Ex 31). It is an<br>
eternally binding covenant - as a memorial of creation and anticipation of<br>
the Millenium.<br>
<p>
Drew.<br>
