<title>Sep_1992: Re: Easter, Christmas and Festivals</title>
<h1>Re: Easter, Christmas and Festivals</h1>
Drew Corrigan (<i>drew@dubhe.anu.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 9 Sep 92 11:33:56 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#103">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#103">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#103">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#103">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0104.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: LOST TIME"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0102.html">Drew Corrigan: "Re: LOST TIME"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0037.html">Drew Corrigan: "Easter, Christmas and Festivals"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Paul writes:<br>
<i>&gt; Drew,</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I am not sure if you are an Adventist or not.</i><br>
<p>
I am a member of the Worldwide Church of God.<br>
 <br>
<i>&gt; I believe we can celebrate both times of the year without giving the</i><br>
<i>&gt; impression that we are following paganism [...]</i><br>
<i>&gt; I certainly respect your views on Easter and Christmas; however, there are</i><br>
<i>&gt; things that we do in our society today that actually came from paganism</i><br>
<i>&gt; but does not have that connotation today -- as I mentioned in my previous</i><br>
<i>&gt; post to you -- the idea of hand shaking came from Paganism but I do not</i><br>
<i>&gt; think we refrain from it because it did originate with paganism. We use</i><br>
<i>&gt; the pagan names of the week and think nothing of it.</i><br>
<p>
I respect your views on this. But there is a distinction between Easter and<br>
Christmas observance and handshaking, days of the week, etc. In Deuteronomy<br>
God says:<br>
<p>
  "Take heed to thyself that thou be not snared by following them, after that<br>
  they be destroyed from before thee; and that thou enquire not after their<br>
  gods, saying, How did these nations serve their gods? even so will I do<br>
  likewise. Thou shalt not do so unto the LORD thy God: for every abomination<br>
  to the LORD, which he hateth, have they done unto their gods; for even their<br>
  sons and their daughters they have burnt in the fire to their gods. What<br>
  thing soever I command you, observe to do it: thou shalt not add thereto,<br>
  nor diminish from it." (Deut 12:30-32)<br>
<p>
Our understanding of this passage is that we should neither add to, nor take<br>
from God's commandments on how to worship him. He explicitly commands against<br>
taking foreign modes of worship and applying them to the worship of himself.<br>
Granted that the nations around Israel worshipped in horrific ways (such as<br>
putting their children through fire) that we seldom see today, but I believe<br>
the principle of this verse applies today. It is a warning against syncretic<br>
religious practises.<br>
<p>
Easter and Christmas are most definitely syncretic religious festivals. <br>
Nowhere are Christians told to remember Jesus' birth. Christmas is derived<br>
from cultic sun-god worship, the Roman Saturnalia and like. Nor are we <br>
commanded to remember (in a formal sense with a religious service) Jesus'<br>
resurrection. The Friday crucifixion/Sunday resurrection, 1st Sunday after<br>
the vernal equinox, rabbit and egg motifs, etc., are all syncretic additions<br>
from non-Biblical sources. [As an aside, the WCoG believes Jesus was killed<br>
on Passover, Wednesday 14th Nisan, AD 31, buried as the annual Sabbath of<br>
the 15th of Nisan drew on, and then resurrected 3 days and 3 nights later<br>
at the close of the weekly Sabbath.]<br>
<p>
In contrast, handshaking, and even the names given to the days of the week<br>
have nothing explicitly to do with the commanded worship of the True God.<br>
<p>
Regards,<br>
<p>
Drew.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
