<!-- body="start" -->
For the OT scholars on SDA NET:<br>
Daniel 7:25 is written in Aramaic, a Semitic language, very similar to Hebrew,<br>
used throughout the Near East in antiquity and into the times of Christ.  Dan<br>
2:4 through 7:27 are written in Aramaic, the common language of Babylon in the<br>
time of Daniel.  The book of Ezra is also written in Aramaic.<br>
<p>
For this specific text, the Aramaic dictionaries give as follows:<br>
Holladay--"law of God = torah"<br>
Brown Driver Briggs -- "Law of God in mouth of non-Jews"<br>
<p>
The same word dath appears in Ezra 7 six times specifically tied to the phrase<br>
"of God."  See verses 12, 13, 16, 21, 25, 26.<br>
<p>
In Esther the word appears in the Hebrew narrative referring to laws and<br>
edicts of the Persian empire.  Evidently we have here a loanword, from Aramaic.<br>
The time of Ezra and Esther is approximately the same.<br>
<p>
Nancy Vyhmeister<br>
<p>
B<br>
B<br>
<p>
B<br>
<p>
D<br>
D<br>
Brown, Driver and Briggs--"law of God"--in mouth of non-Jews"<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
