<title>Sep_1992: Sabbath</title>
<h1>Sabbath</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 9 Sep 92 13:15:45 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#107">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#107">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#107">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#107">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0108.html">Bob Moynihan: "Re: Lost time"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0106.html">Tony: "Re: LOST TIME"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Africa, Europe, and Asia are on a contiguous land mass with Israel.  So<br>
their Sabbath should be defined in a continuous way, so that a traveler<br>
from Israel would not have an abrupt change of day.  North and South<br>
America are closer to the west side of this land mass than to the<br>
east, so it's natural for us to align our days as if we could be<br>
reached by a continuous path from the west.  The Pacific Ocean is a<br>
grey area, I suppose;  depends which continent you are closest to.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
