<title>Sep_1992: Re: Lost time</title>
<h1>Re: Lost time</h1>
Bob Moynihan (<i>moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 9 Sep 92 10:37:50 EDT </i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#108">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#108">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#108">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#108">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0109.html">Alice Fay Martin: "Re: Lost time"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0107.html">David Plaisted: "Sabbath"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve Timm wrote:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;&gt;[The calendar history is well-known since the days of Julius Caesar,</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;when the Julian Calendar was promulgated.  Since that point it has</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;been documented by any astronomical society you care to find that</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;the weekly cycle has not slipped a day.  Up to that point, there</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;were various communities of Jews, none of whom disagree on what day</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;is the Sabbath, even to this day, and some of them have been separated</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;(as in the case of those recently rescued from Ethiopia) for hundreds of</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;years.  SCT]</i><br>
<p>
Scott Mattes replied: <br>
<p>
<i>&gt; So the folks from Adam up until the Jews leaving Eygpt didn't mess up</i><br>
<i>&gt; the calendar even once? </i><br>
<p>
Sorry Scott, but if you wish to put forth the argument that the days -were-<br>
lost, it is up to you to present the evidence in support of your position.<br>
It is not up to the rest of the readers to prove that it -didn't- happen.<br>
Negative proofs are logically impossible.<br>
 <br>
For example:  Prove you're not a communist.<br>
<p>
The impossibility of such an effort is one of the main reasons that in our<br>
society, criminals are innocent until proven guilty.<br>
<p>
But back to the subject at hand:  It is not sufficient to say, "Well, in the<br>
many thousands of years since Adam and Eve walked the Earth, some days -must-<br>
have been lost,"  because that argument is not true.  Some days -may- have<br>
been lost, but there is no proof that it must be so, nor any that it did indeed<br>
happen.  Or at least, none that I have ever been apprised of.   There -is-<br>
historical evidence that numbered days were dropped off the calendar, but not<br>
the named days.  In other words, let's say that five days were lopped off the<br>
calendar starting the day after Saturday, July 12.  The next day would be Sunday,<br>
July 18, not Friday, July 18.<br>
<p>
