<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;From: Alice Fay Martin &lt;armg9488@uxa.cso.uiuc.edu&gt;</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Does anyone have some insight on renting practices of an SDA church to a </i><br>
<i>&gt;Sunday keeping church?  I understand there may be some view points on </i><br>
<i>&gt;both sides, those for and against it.  I realize the identity of the church </i><br>
<i>&gt;may be an issue but if it is considered not to be of "radical" theology and</i><br>
<i>&gt;temperament, should we rent to a Sunday keeping church?  Would it be</i><br>
<i>&gt;promoting Sunday worship?    </i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;(This is to be debated at the next church board meeting and wonder what </i><br>
<i>&gt;the debate is all about.)</i><br>
<p>
Let's turn the argument on its head:<br>
<p>
Is there any reason why a Sunday-keeping church should rent to an SDA<br>
congregation? They could reason that the SDAs are promoting worship<br>
other than Sunday. The West Madison, WI, SDA Church, back in 1988, was doing<br>
just that. They were meeting in rented facilities.<br>
<p>
If the revenue from renting the church to a Sunday-keeping congregation<br>
palys a significant role in keeping the doors open in the first place,<br>
and as long as the board is keeping watch on the kinds of congregations<br>
they allow in there, I would have no qualms. That church in Madison<br>
certainly didn't.<br>
<p>
