<title>Sep_1992: Re: Sabbath issues</title>
<h1>Re: Sabbath issues</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 10 Sep 1992 10:26 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#113">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#113">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#113">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#113">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0114.html">David Plaisted: "Sabbath"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0112.html">Cam Litvin: "RE: renting churches"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0110.html">Alice Fay Martin: "Sabbath issues"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I'm sorry if I've been a bit verbose on the net, but I am genuinely<br>
concerned about the issues I have been trying to raise and about the<br>
discussions I have contributed to. I don't make a habit of arguing<br>
pedantically about every little point, and that's not what I am<br>
intending to do on the net either. I just appreciate the opportunity<br>
to discuss these things with a fresh group of people, and particularly<br>
with a group of people living elsewhere!<br>
<p>
I guess the reason I am bringing up this stuff about the Sabbath is<br>
because I am (I admit) a rationalist at heart. I'll give you a couple<br>
of examples to illustrate what I mean.<br>
<p>
* I believe that love (in the "God is love" sense) is the set of<br>
  behaviours which works to maintain a cohesive and harmonious<br>
  universe. I don't believe that it is some arbitrary ideal whereby<br>
  God said "I'd like everybody to behave this way because it is a<br>
  nice idea".<br>
<p>
* I believe that sin is the complementary set. ie sin is those things<br>
  which do not work to maintain a cohesive and harmonious universe.<br>
<p>
* I believe that any directions we may receive from God regarding <br>
  anything at all are designed purely and simply to help us reach <br>
  the stage where we are contributing to the harmony and not the<br>
  disharmony. I don't believe that God arbitrarily assigns rules and<br>
  regulations for no reason.<br>
<p>
etc.<br>
<p>
I hasten to add that I don't expect to understand or even perceive God's<br>
reasons for everything. But I still believe that there are reasons, and<br>
I will continue to try and dig out as much meaning as I can.<br>
<p>
As far as the ten commandments go, some of them have at least a <br>
superficial obvious motivation. It probably goes deeper as well, but<br>
for example "don't steal" is fairly easy to deal with.<br>
<p>
The fourth commandment is a little tougher. It is discussed in various<br>
places in the text, and in some of those places the motivation for the<br>
Sabbath is mentioned. It's not always the same: even in the comparison<br>
between the Exodus and Deuteronomy versions of the X, the explanation<br>
differs.<br>
<p>
So I try to pull out the essence of the thing, and I have a fair amount<br>
of difficulty. I have even more difficulty when I look at the way SDAs<br>
typically treat the Sabbath, because I don't think we always approach<br>
it properly.<br>
<p>
To give you some examples of the sorts of thoughts I sometimes have,<br>
consider the following self-debate.<br>
<p>
a. The sabbath is mainly a memorial of creation. As such it is important<br>
   that it be kept exactly 7n days after the original sabbath.<br>
<p>
b. That doesn't really make sense. Memorials of other things don't have<br>
   to be kept on exactly the same day. Take communion, easter, christmas...<br>
   sure, these don't appear in the X, and not everybody sees them as<br>
   valid memorials of the original events, but they still serve a <br>
   worthwhile purpose for me. Besides, Genesis 1 really does read more<br>
   like a cosmological polemic than an account of an actual week, and<br>
   if that's the case then that throws the historical-seven-day-cycle<br>
   thing, hey.<br>
<p>
a. Yes, well that's one good reason to see the creation story as a literal<br>
   account. There are other good reasons as well. Besides, why do you<br>
   think that you can understand all God's reasons? You may never really<br>
   understand the fourth commandment, but that's no reason to doubt its<br>
   validity.<br>
<p>
b. I agree on both points, which is why I have trouble with both items.<br>
   But don't you think there must be some human-related reason for the<br>
   sabbath? After all, it was made for man, Jesus said so himself. And<br>
   it was made for Earth, because it was the last act of creation.<br>
<p>
a. Well, one should always refer to the manufacturer's instructions, right?<br>
   God created man, and he said that we should rest on every seventh day.<br>
   People function best on a seven-day cycle. Other cycles have been tried,<br>
   but the seven-day one works best. God knew that, because he made us in<br>
   the first place.<br>
<p>
b. Ah, but then why does it matter which day the cycle starts on? Surely<br>
   if the seven-day-cycle is the important thing, we could choose any day<br>
   of the week that we like.<br>
<p>
a. That's where we just have to trust God. He said the "seventh day", and<br>
   he meant what is now Saturday. Who are we to arbitrarily change the<br>
   historical cycle?<br>
<p>
b. OK, but we certainly have to use a certain amount of human interpretation<br>
   when it comes to keeping the Sabbath worldwide. How about places where<br>
   the sun never sets or never rises? How about the fact that it's not<br>
   the same day everywhere at once? The fact is that the Bible reads as<br>
   though the earth is flat and the sun goes around it once a day. It <br>
   reads as though there is a dome above the ground holding off the waters<br>
   above, and that God sends the weather around like some omnipotent version<br>
   of Thor. We know that isn't really how it is. The original text was<br>
   written in a world without technology, drugs, pollution and a whole lot<br>
   of other things we deal with today.<br>
<p>
a. God gave us a mind, he gave us the Holy Spirit, and it's up to us to<br>
   use those God-given resources to discover his will in these areas.<br>
<p>
b. Yeah, well that's what this is all about, right??<br>
<p>
<p>
For those of you still reading, thanks. Please don't form a definite<br>
opinion on what I must be like from reading these posts I'm making.<br>
As you know yourselves, you can only express a few ideas at once when<br>
you're writing, so some of my statements are certainly wide open for<br>
total slaughter. But I have thought most of these things over fairly<br>
carefully, and I have reasons for the opinions I express - it's just<br>
that this post is already too long!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
