<title>Sep_1992: Sabbath</title>
<h1>Sabbath</h1>
David Plaisted (<i>plaisted@cs.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 10 Sep 92 13:11:53 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#114">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#114">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#114">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#114">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0115.html">cheryl berthelsen: "re: Renting Churches"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0113.html">Tony: "Re: Sabbath issues"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The question is raised, when does the Sabbath begin and end if the<br>
sun never rises or sets, as in Alaska in the winter or summer.<br>
This puzzled me for a while.  Then the following idea occurred to<br>
me.  The logical time to begin/end the Sabbath is when the sun is<br>
closest to the horizon, either above the horizon at its lowest<br>
point or below the horizon at its highest point.  So in the<br>
summer the Sabbath would be from midnight to midnight if the sun<br>
did not set, and in the winter the Sabbath would be from noon to noon<br>
if the sun did not rise.  This is appealing because it makes the<br>
beginning and end of the Sabbath change continuously with ones<br>
position, if you think about it.<br>
<p>
In grey areas, I think that the Lord honors our best attempt to<br>
follow him.<br>
<p>
	Dave Plaisted<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
