<title>Sep_1992: re: Renting Churches</title>
<h1>re: Renting Churches</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 10 Sep 92 12:12:28 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#115">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#115">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#115">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#115">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0116.html">Russell Grau: "re: Renting Churches"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0114.html">David Plaisted: "Sabbath"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
My own humble opinion is that renting a church out to a congregation is not<br>
a doctrinal issue.  It is one of convenience and perhaps meeting a need for<br>
both congregations.  The one renting out their building will receive needed<br>
money for their budget.  The other will have a place to worship until they<br>
can afford to buy or build their own.<br>
<p>
But there are issues that need to be seriously addressed if an SDA church is<br>
to rent out their facility to Sunday keepers of a practical nature.  For example,<br>
SDAs usually have their weddings on Sunday.  What happens to the Sunday-keeping<br>
congregation?  What will the wedding party do when they cannot have access to<br>
the church on Sunday morning for decorating and preparation because their<br>
renters are there?<br>
<p>
Another question.  SDAs schedule "work bees" for grounds clean-up on Sundays.<br>
If the church is rented out, can't have a work bee.<br>
<p>
What about occasional Sunday functions such as parties and social gatherings<br>
for the SDA congregation?  If the church is rented on Sunday mornings, be<br>
sure to stipulate exactly WHAT TIME the renters must be finished or you will<br>
find conflicts.  And, remember.  You can't schedule an pathfinder functions<br>
on Sunday morning.  Don't even plan to have young people meet in the parking<br>
lot Sunday morning to travel elsewhere.  The renting congregation will not<br>
appreciate it.<br>
<p>
So, ask these questions of the SDA congregation BEFORE you decide to rent.<br>
If all agree that they won't find the lack of flexibility and the inability<br>
to schedule anything for Sunday mornings, then go ahead.  But if your<br>
congreation has scheduled such things in the past, be sure you stipulate in<br>
the rental agreement exactly what hours the renters are allowed access to<br>
avoid problems in your own programs.<br>
<p>
That's my two cents.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
