<title>Sep_1992: re: Renting Churches</title>
<h1>re: Renting Churches</h1>
Russell Grau (<i>reg@ctsx.celtech.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 10 Sep 92 13:41 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#116">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#116">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#116">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#116">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0117.html">Tony: "Re: SDA-bashg"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0115.html">cheryl berthelsen: "re: Renting Churches"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have been watching this thread before I went on vacation last week (short one<br>
after some minor surgery) and then picked it up after I came back today.  I <br>
hope that what I say will be taken in the spirit that it is given.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Subject: Sabbath</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;On Mon, 7 Sep 1992 10:44:34 -0400 (EDT) you said:</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;[The calendar history is well-known since the days of Julius Caesar,</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;when the Julian Calendar was promulgated.  Since that point it has</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;been documented by any astronomical society you care to find that</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;the weekly cycle has not slipped a day.  Up to that point, there</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;were various communities of Jews, none of whom disagree on what day</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;is the Sabbath, even to this day, and some of them have been separated</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;(as in the case of those recently rescued from Ethiopia) for hundreds of</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt;years.  SCT]</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;  So the folks from Adam up until the Jews leaving Eygpt didn't mess up</i><br>
<i>&gt;the calendar even once?</i><br>
<p>
This is a non-arguement.  Even if the calendar was "messed up" and days were<br>
lost, there have been some fairly significant events that have set it<br>
straight.  Namely the exodus and the 1st advent of Jesus.  The 1st advent<br>
clearly points out that God knew that the Jews were worshipping on the proper<br>
day by what He did.  He is a deliberate God after all and He healed on the<br>
Sabbath to make a point.<br>
<p>
Besides that idea, if the Jews were worshipping on the wrong day, don't you<br>
think that He would have sent a prophet to make sure that the day was correct<br>
before the advent?  How could Jesus have made the points that He did if it was<br>
on the wrong day?  Do you honestly think that Jesus would have made any<br>
disciples if he openly broke the commandments?  How could Jesus be the perfect<br>
sacrifice if the law was not kept?  The Jews would have noticed if Jesus kept<br>
some other day as the sabbath.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;--------------------------------------+----------------------------------------</i><br>
<i>&gt;Scott (nmi) Mattes                    | No success can compensate for failure</i><br>
<i>&gt;Work: COTRSSM@SEA04VM.NAVSEA.Navy.Mil | in the home.  David O. McKay, Prophet</i><br>
<i>&gt;Home: 73027.3270@CompuServe.COM       | and President of the Church of Jesus</i><br>
<i>&gt;Voice: (703) 769-2917                 | Christ of Latter-day Saints, 1951-70</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;The question is raised, when does the Sabbath begin and end if the</i><br>
<i>&gt;sun never rises or sets, as in Alaska in the winter or summer.</i><br>
<i>&gt;This puzzled me for a while.  Then the following idea occurred to</i><br>
<i>&gt;me.  The logical time to begin/end the Sabbath is when the sun is</i><br>
<i>&gt;closest to the horizon, either above the horizon at its lowest</i><br>
<i>&gt;point or below the horizon at its highest point.  So in the</i><br>
<i>&gt;summer the Sabbath would be from midnight to midnight if the sun</i><br>
<i>&gt;did not set, and in the winter the Sabbath would be from noon to noon</i><br>
<i>&gt;if the sun did not rise.  This is appealing because it makes the</i><br>
<i>&gt;beginning and end of the Sabbath change continuously with ones</i><br>
<i>&gt;position, if you think about it.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;In grey areas, I think that the Lord honors our best attempt to</i><br>
<i>&gt;follow him.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;	Dave Plaisted</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
The sad thing about most of the questions that have been put forth are that<br>
they question the motive of the Lord directly.  Slighting the majesty and<br>
knowledge that the Lord had BEFORE He gave the 10 commandments.<br>
<p>
Thinking as a man thinks is what Jesus wanted us NOT to do.  We conjure up all<br>
kinds of notions about what is right in an attempt to better our position<br>
before the Lord.  There is nothing we can do to change our position except<br>
accepting the sacrifice that Jesus made for us.  All of my sabbath-keeping<br>
doesn't change what I am.<br>
<p>
Pointing to a group of SDA's that keep Sunday because of a change in the<br>
international date line.  For shame.  Does the sun still rise and set?  Can <br>
you still count from one to seven?  The same can be done to YOU to.  There are<br>
radical sects within the Morman church that others use on a regular basis to<br>
bash Morman theology.  Let's get above the level that this discussion has<br>
dropped down to.<br>
<p>
There has not been enough "Thus sayeth the Lord..." in this discussion.  You<br>
claim that there is something in scripture that justifies your claim for<br>
Sunday-keeping, fine, show me.  I will do the same for Sabbath-keeping.<br>
<p>
To be sticking out our tongues and saying nyah, nyah, nyah, nyah does not<br>
belong on this network.<br>
<p>
Come on gang, we can do better......<br>
<p>
:-(<br>
<p>
