<!-- body="start" -->
Russell,<br>
<p>
I'm afraid I have a confession to make.<br>
<p>
I am the one who brought up the thing about SDAs in Tonga. I myself an<br>
am SDA. I am not SDA-bashing, neither am I trying to suggest that the<br>
observance of the seventh-day sabbath is not important, or that it is<br>
non-biblical.<br>
<p>
Nor am I trying to question the majesty of God. The fact is that God<br>
has chosen to reveal himself (in the most part) through men, and *everything*<br>
we read in *any* written form has come through the work of men. We were<br>
created in his image, with a mind, which I presume he meant us to use. So<br>
doing our best to see the principles behind the law and other things in<br>
God's revelation, with the guidance of the Holy Spirit, shouldn't be <br>
classified as any form of rebellion. Quite the reverse!<br>
<p>
The founders of our denomination were renowned for their radical views, and<br>
that was because they dared to examine their beliefs and actions in the light<br>
of scripture. Quotations can be given (but not by me at the moment :) ) which<br>
say things to the effect of "the day we stop searching the scriptures and<br>
examining our beliefs is the day we stop growing spiritually", and other such<br>
things. EGW herself is strong on the idea of continuing to search for "truth".<br>
<p>
Those of us who are looking at the Bible, looking at our church, and trying<br>
to put the most into our spiritual lives and our religious families are not<br>
trying to buck the system. That is, unless the system says "the truth was<br>
discovered over 100 years ago, we've found it now, so let's stop looking for<br>
more<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
