<title>Sep_1992: Translation Faith</title>
<h1>Translation Faith</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 10 Sep 1992 19:30:52 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#118">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#118">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#118">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#118">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0119.html">Steven Timm: "1994"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0117.html">Tony: "Re: SDA-bashg"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
It seems like there may be a nice little offshoot growing up here in <br>
Western PA.  Since I'm slated to work at a youth event next week with <br>
the pastor whose church it started in, and who is either a ringleader or <br>
an innocent bystander depending on whom you believe, I'll have more <br>
details soon.  <br>
<p>
So far all I know is that it begins with a deep study of the sanctuary<br>
and goes from there to holy flesh ideas, casting out demons, and anti-<br>
organizational issues.  The third has got the conference leadership involved.<br>
We are having a mini-campmeeting for this area next weekend, and we can <br>
expect to hear a lot from both sides.<br>
<p>
But I want to dwell briefly on the question of "translation faith" as it was <br>
first put forth by the "holy flesh" movement around 1900 and still crops<br>
up today.  The question is the following:  "Will the generation that is<br>
translated to heaven without seeing death at the end of time have a<br>
character any different than those who have died in Christ over the<br>
years?"<br>
<p>
Things that would seem to indicate NO:<br>
1) No transformation of character is made at the Second Coming (or is it)<br>
The things we take unchanged to heaven are our character and our friends.<br>
This means the millenium in heaven is a time of adjusting, learning to live<br>
with each other even in the absence of sin and temptation.  It's clear <br>
that not everyone taken to heaven will have completed the process of<br>
sanctification upon arrival.<br>
<p>
<p>
Things that would seem to indicate YES:<br>
1)  Those in the Bible that were translated (Enoch, Elijah, Jesus)<br>
were extraordinary men of God.<br>
2)  Ellen White's statements about God waiting for His character to <br>
be reproduced in His people before He comes.<br>
3)  The experimental fact that no one is persecuting us right now<br>
because we're not doing anything to deserve it.<br>
<p>
I think most of us would agree that in Christ, freedom from sin is <br>
possible.  The question is, is it necessary?<br>
<p>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
