<title>Sep_1992: Sabbath</title>
<h1>Sabbath</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 10 Sep 92 20:17:34 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#120">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#120">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#120">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#120">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0121.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Bible to interpret itself"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0119.html">Steven Timm: "1994"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Although it is interesting to speculate on when one should begin the Sabbath<br>
North of the Arctic Circle--and this is a real problem for some SDAs--I am<br>
much more concerned that too often the meaning of the Sabbath is linked<br>
only to Creation.  <br>
<p>
I see the Sabbath as the most Christian of all Christian doctrines.  Let me<br>
tell you why.<br>
<p>
The Sabbath is a reminder of my Creator, so Exod 20:8.  And in John 1:3 we<br>
are told that through Christ "all things came into beingl?  Paul wrote the<br>
Colossians that Christ was preeminent because "in him all things were <br>
created" -- 1:16.<br>
<p>
The Sabbath is a reminder of the one who sanctifies me, my Lord who is in<br>
the process of making me holy as he is.  Exod 31:13-17 says the Sabbath is<br>
a sign of sanctification--of being set apart for a holy purpose, for special<br>
companionship with the one who makes me holy.  Keeping the Sabbath shows I<br>
am willing for Christ to make me holy, even as God is holy --Lev 11:45.  In<br>
the NT all three persons of the Godhead are involved in sanctification, but <br>
Paul tells the Corinthians that they have "been sanctified in Christ Jesus" <br>
--1 Cor 1:2.  Christ is sanctification to those who believe -- 1 Cor 1:30.<br>
<p>
The Sabbath reminds me of my Liberator.  Deut 5:15 shows the Sabbath as a<br>
sign of the liberation from Egypt.  The Israelites could celebrate freedom.<br>
I, too, celebrate on the Sabbath the freedom that Christ gives me.  See<br>
John 8:32-36.  On the Sabbath I celebrate the liberation, the ransom, the<br>
freedom from sin that Christ has made possible for me.<br>
<p>
The Sabbath brings to my attention the relation Christ wants between himself<br>
and me.  Ezek 20:20 says the Sabbath is a sign between God and his people--<br>
a sign that they are his.  This relation is expressed in more intimate terms<br>
in the Song of Songs: "I am my beloved's and my beloved is mine" --6:3.  In<br>
the OT, the relation is between the people and God.  In the NT, the individual<br>
relation is important.  Believers belong to Christ -- 1 Cor. 3:23.  The Sabbath<br>
is a sign of a close relation--between myself and my divine lover, who loved<br>
me so much that he gave his life for me.<br>
<p>
The Sabbath is a symbol of the rest that is mine--now as I walk this earth I<br>
have peace; then, in the glorious beyond, I will have eternal rest.  The rest<br>
motif appears in Heb 4.  It points back to the first Sabbath rest and the not-<br>
yet rest of the believer.  Christ said: "Come unto me and I will give you rest"<br>
-- Matt 11:28.  Each Sabbath day is a celebration of the peace and rest my<br>
Jesus provides for me.<br>
<p>
So you see why Sabbath is important to me.  The original blessings were for <br>
this day only.  The holy time is not transferable.  I gladly embrace the<br>
precious hours as a token of all the Christ is to me.<br>
<p>
Nancy Vyhmeister<br>
<p>
D<br>
D<br>
D<br>
D<br>
(Matt 11:28.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
