<title>Sep_1992: Re: Bible to interpret itself</title>
<h1>Re: Bible to interpret itself</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 10 Sep 1992 20:54:15 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#121">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#121">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#121">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#121">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0122.html">Steven Timm: "Epistle to the Magnesians"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0120.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Sabbath"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0087.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Bible to interpret itself"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Cheryl's question essentially asks:<br>
How can the scriptures be interpreting themselves if a [latter-day] prophet<br>
is used to interpret them instead?  <br>
This is a serious issue that got lost in a 40-message day.<br>
<p>
Alden Thompson stresses this in his book on Inspiration, in which he<br>
says  "If you want to understand the old testament, read the old testament,<br>
if you want to understand Matthew, read Matthew, and if you want to<br>
understand Ellen G. White, read Ellen G. White."  However, he goes on to <br>
point out that the New Testament has several places, particularly in the <br>
gospel of Matthew, where Matthew takes an Old Testament passage to mean <br>
something quite different than its original context.  So, though the practice <br>
may not be desirable, it has been with us since there have been commentators.<br>
<p>
The way to avoid the danger of "isogesis" (reading ones own meaning into<br>
the text) as opposed to "exegesis" (extracting the author's intent from<br>
the text,<br>
is to come to the Bible without an agenda.  Instead of trying to string <br>
together a string of texts to support our own ideas, we need to read the<br>
Bible and let it speak to us.<br>
<p>
If you study early SDA history you will find that this is what was done.<br>
The doctrines came from careful Bible study, not dictation from Ellen G.<br>
White.  But as a movement grows, people find it easier to hide behind the<br>
authority of a prophet than study out the truth for themselves.  Probably<br>
the reason why there hasn't been more than one prophet in the SDA church<br>
is that one has given those people who use the club of authority all the <br>
ammunition they need from now until the end of time.  And those who<br>
ignore her wouldn't listen to other ones anyway.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
