<title>Sep_1992: searching for the truth</title>
<h1>searching for the truth</h1>
Ian Brown (<i>Malachi.Robertson@lambada.oit.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 10 Sep 92 21:09:08 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#123">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#123">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#123">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#123">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0124.html">Dan Blake: "Re: 1994"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0122.html">Steven Timm: "Epistle to the Magnesians"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Tony,<br>
<p>
First, I can sympathize with your internal debate over the Sabbath.  I<br>
have my own internal debates concerning some of the other Adventists'<br>
beliefs.  I have these debate as I want to have knowledge of the truth.  I<br>
want to be that kind of person that continually searches for the truth. <br>
Many times I have come to study one of our doctrines only to have<br>
questions arise.  These questions impel me to study the scriptures and<br>
find answers to firm up my what I consider the beliefs that I on one level<br>
ascribe to.  For example, concerning the Sabbath and the belief that in<br>
1844 Jesus began the investigative judgment, I answered many of my<br>
questions and at this point accepting those beliefs on a far deeper level<br>
than before.  Many of the questions you bring up about the Sabbath aren't<br>
ones I have ever dealt with before.  Correct me if I am wrong, but they<br>
seems to be mostly ones that deal with how the Sabbath pans out in<br>
practice.  I am not sure how to answer them.  My questions are more of a<br>
theological/interpretive fair.  One of my lastest quandries has to do with<br>
whether the New Jerusalem is really in heaven during the Millenium.  I<br>
have not rejected the Adventist view, but I do question it.  Which brings<br>
me to my next message for SDAnet...<br>
<p>
"Malachi Robertson" better known as Ian Robertson Brown<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
