<title>Sep_1992: Re: 1994</title>
<h1>Re: 1994</h1>
Dan Blake (<i>dblake@hprnd.rose.hp.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 10 Sep 92 18:40:31 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#124">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#124">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#124">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#124">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0125.html">Paul: "Re: Vegetarianism"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0123.html">Ian Brown: "searching for the truth"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0119.html">Steven Timm: "1994"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0131.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: 1994"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; 1994 is the title of a book by Hal Camping which claims to have a </i><br>
<i>&gt; prediction of the 2nd coming.  Rather than having us all going out </i><br>
<i>&gt; and buy it, thus enriching him, why doesn't someone go to a bookstore</i><br>
<i>&gt; and read it, find out what it says, and then let us know.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Steve Timm</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
     Author:  Harold Camping<br>
      Title:  1994<br>
  Publisher:  Vantage Press<br>
Distributor:  Baker &amp; Taylor<br>
       ISBN:  0-533-10368-1<br>
       Cost:  $14.95<br>
<p>
I have the book on order and should get it in a few days.  However, I<br>
am a terribly slow reader, and _1994_ is a sizable book (&gt;500 pages).<br>
If you want timely and varied feedback, I suggest several mature<br>
Christians read it.  Don't worry about making Mr. Camping rich.  He<br>
does not claim any special revalation from God.  He bases his<br>
conclusion on a careful exegesis of the Bible.  He goes (I believe)<br>
rather heavily into numerology.<br>
<p>
Resist the impulse to slam him.  I have no doubt that he is a true<br>
believer.  His defense of the Bible as the word of God is powerful.<br>
He did not want to write this book.  He did not want to draw such<br>
attention to his ministry.  But believing as he did, he was compelled;<br>
wouldn't you be?  The worst you could say is that he is deluded, and<br>
you shouldn't say that until you have read the book, hence, my order.<br>
On the other side of the coin, if he is right, he has an urgent message<br>
to proclaim, one to be sure that is already written:<br>
<p>
2 Corinthians chapter 6<br>
  1 We then, as workers together with him, beseech you also that<br>
ye receive not the grace of God in vain.<br>
  2 (For he saith, I have heard thee in a time accepted, and in<br>
the day of salvation have I succoured thee: behold, now is the<br>
accepted time; behold, now is the day of salvation.)<br>
<p>
<p>
God bless,<br>
<p>
Dan Blake<br>
