<!-- body="start" -->
Tony, &amp; Network<br>
<p>
Hi Tony, <br>
<p>
Yes I am a pastor and I cannot remember any church members being uptight<br>
about eating meat. Usually our members feel that it is a personal decision<br>
on the part of the individual. When I take Adventists out for a meal, I<br>
usually try to clear the air by telling them to order what ever they<br>
would like.<br>
<p>
I have been mentoring a ministerial intern who pastor's a neighboring<br>
church and we get together once a month for a meal. In the beginning I<br>
asked him if he was a vegetarian so I would better know which restaurant<br>
to take him to. Incidently Crabs, Oysters, seafood in general is the big<br>
thing here on the eastern shore of Maryland. We frequent a restaurant<br>
called the Blue Crab! The cook makes a vegetable lasagna that in my<br>
opinion is excellent!!<br>
<p>
Anyway, hope I have answered your question.<br>
<p>
........Paul<br>
<p>
I very rarely ever eat meat -- perhaps a corn beef sandwich if I can not<br>
find anythingelse to eat, but that is very rarely done by me. So I think<br>
of myself as a vegetarian because 95-99% of the time that is the case.<br>
<p>
I do not believe eating meat is a sin. I may have eluded to it in my<br>
previous post, I do not eat meat on a regular basis because of the disease<br>
and fat content.<br>
<p>
BTW, check with McDonald's  on their chicken mcnuget sandwiches. I<br>
understand that most if not all of the meat is from vegetable protein. It<br>
would be interesting to really know.<br>
<p>
.......Paul<br>
<p>
<p>
For many years we had the policy that no meat in lunches of children in<br>
grade school (church school). Bad or good this is how we are handling it<br>
today. We have quite a few non-Adventist parents -- We have a<br>
recommendation in the school handbook that the teachers would prefer the<br>
students not bring meat in their lunches and the teachers do not allow<br>
students to trade lunches. The problem was that students were trading<br>
lunches and some parents who did not want their children to eat meat were<br>
doing so by trading.<br>
<p>
[Paul is signed off the net for about a month, so any responses to this<br>
or his other threads should be by E-mail to him.  SCT]<br>
