<title>Sep_1992: Re:  God's Law portrays His character?</title>
<h1>Re:  God's Law portrays His character?</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 11 Sep 92 13:48:39 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#126">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#126">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#126">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#126">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0127.html">Tony: "Re: Sabbath"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0125.html">Paul: "Re: Vegetarianism"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0086.html">cheryl berthelsen: "God's Law portrays His character?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all,,<br>
<p>
Cheryl asks  :<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Would you mind giving me a few scriptures that support the idea that</i><br>
<i>&gt; God's Law is intended to portray or symbolize His character?  thank you.</i><br>
<p>
Ok thats fairly easy to do. We can do this by looking at God's character<br>
<p>
God is :<br>
<p>
eternal		Ps 45:6<br>
righteous	Ezra 9:15<br>
perfect		Matt 5:48<br>
holy		Lev 19:2<br>
good		Ps 34:8<br>
truth		Deut 32:4<br>
unchanging/immutable	Ecc 3:14 / Mal 3:6<br>
<p>
Now we know htat the law is a revelation of God's will, what are its<br>
characteristics, <br>
<p>
God's Law is :<br>
<p>
eternal		Ps 111:8<br>
righteous	Ps 119:172<br>
perfect		Ps 19:7<br>
holy		Rom 7:12<br>
good		Rom 7:12<br>
truth		Ps 119:142<br>
unchanging/immutable	MAtt 5:17-18<br>
<p>
So we see they have the same character. We can also do this comparison <br>
another way. We know that one becomes like the thing one spends time <br>
comtemplating : by beholding we become changed. So what was it that <br>
JEsus comtinously contemplated - God's law Ps (40:6-8) We also<br>
know that character can be defined as ones feelings + ones actions<br>
well we know what Christ's feelings and actions were MAtt 5:17-18, <br>
John 15:10, He loved and kept God's law perfectly.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; I appreciated your analysis of God's Law versus The Law of Moses.  However,</i><br>
<i>&gt; I fail to see how the fact that God gave the law to Moses to give to the</i><br>
<i>&gt; Isrealites would render it Moses's law rather than God's Law.  If God</i><br>
<i>&gt; gave it (directly or indirectly), is it not still from God?</i><br>
<p>
<p>
Well as you saw one was publicaly given to the entire nation personally<br>
by God and written by His own hand. The other was given to the Levites<br>
by Moses who wrote it with his hand. God chose to make this very LARGE<br>
distinction Himself, why do you think He did this for ? Nobody denies<br>
that both laws originated from God but I am sure you do not fail to<br>
note the preminence given to the Decalogue by God himself.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; other words, "Thou shalt not kill unless I direct you to do so because</i><br>
<i>&gt; they are a wicked nation."  Did the Isrealites break God's Law when they</i><br>
<i>&gt; murdered and killed innocent women and children at His direction?</i><br>
<p>
I am sorry but I must disagree with you here. No one that God commanded to<br>
be killed was innocent.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;If it is God's Law, does He have authority to change it?  (I'm not asking</i><br>
<i>&gt;IF He would change it?)  If He has the authority to change it and a</i><br>
<i>&gt;Christian bases his/her belief on a Sunday Sabbath on a direct command</i><br>
<i>&gt;given to an individual whom they accept and believe is a prophet of God,</i><br>
<i>&gt;then doesn't that Christian have a basis for accepting a changed Sabbath</i><br>
<i>&gt;day?</i><br>
<p>
Nope, because that would make God a liar, and it is impossible for God<br>
to lie. (Heb 6:18)<br>
<p>
Ps 89:34 My covenant will I not break, nor alter the thing that is gone out of <br>
         my lips. (KJV) <br>
<p>
Matt 5:17 Think not that I am come to destroy the law, or the prophets: I am <br>
          not come to destroy, but to fulfil. (KJV) <br>
Matt 5:18 For verily I say unto you, Till heaven and earth pass, one jot or <br>
          one tittle shall in no wise pass from the law, till all be <br>
          fulfilled. (KJV) <br>
<p>
Eze 20:12 Moreover also I gave them my sabbaths, to be a sign between me and <br>
          them, that they might know that I am the LORD that sanctify them.  <br>
 <br>
Eze 20:20 And hallow my sabbaths; and they shall be a sign between me and you, <br>
          that ye may know that I am the LORD your God. (KJV) <br>
 <br>
Ecc 12:13 Let us hear the conclusion of the whole matter: Fear God, and keep <br>
          his commandments: for this is the whole duty of man. (KJV) <br>
 <br>
<p>
"Ye are my witnesses saith the LORD, and my servant whom I have chosen:<br>
that ye may know and believe me, and understand that I am he: before me<br>
there was no God formed, neither shall there be after me." Is 43:10<br>
<p>
"Thus saith the LORD the King of Israel, and his redeemer the LORD of hosts;<br>
I am the first and I am the last; and beside me there is no God." Is 44:6<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
