<title>Sep_1992: New Jerusalem and 1000 years</title>
<h1>New Jerusalem and 1000 years</h1>
Ian Brown (<i>Malachi.Robertson@lambada.oit.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 10 Sep 92 22:17:14 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#129">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#129">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#129">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#129">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0130.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Translation Faith"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0128.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Translation Faith"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
After being questioned by postmillenialist concerning my views on the<br>
millenium, I came upon some questions of my own concerning the Adventist<br>
position that the New Jerusalem will not be on the earth during the<br>
millenium.  My first question is this:  historically where does this<br>
position come from?  In other words, did the early Adventists first hold<br>
this position or did they accept after studying it from someone else?  Now<br>
my second question comes after I give a brief overview of what I see and<br>
don't see within Revelations verses about the millenium.<br>
<p>
Revelation 19:17-21 appears to indicate the 2nd coming (this goes along<br>
with Paul's statements in II Thess. 2).<br>
<p>
Revelation 20:1-3 shows Satan being bound for 1,000 years so he can't<br>
deceive (this is typical portrayed as the time in which Satan is alone on<br>
a desolate earth.  It is argued that the bottomless pit refers to this. <br>
Also, verses from Isaiah and Jeremiah are alluded to as supporting this. <br>
Now I can see that the verses in Isaiah 24 might refer to this time, but I<br>
have trouble seeing how taking those verse in Jeremiah 4 to refer to the<br>
millenium doesn't render them out of context.)<br>
<p>
Revelation 20:4-6  Righteous reign with Jesus and it is noted that the<br>
righteous are resurrected (this meets up with Paul in I Thess. 4:13-17<br>
where it is clearly shown that the saints meet Jesus in the air; it makes<br>
no mention about Jesus stepping on the earth).  The righteous judge, whel<br>
the rest of the dead sleep until the end of the thousand years.  No where<br>
in these verses does it say where everyone is.  Are they on the earth or<br>
in heaven?<br>
<p>
Revelation 20:7-10  Satan deceives again.  Note that the city and the<br>
saint are portrayed in these verses as being upon the earth.  Were they<br>
already there during the millenium or did they just arrive?  It doesn't<br>
say here, it only says that when Satan is loosed and the wicked are<br>
gathered to attack that the city and saints are on the earth (some<br>
Adventists point to Zech. 14:4,5 as describing the return of Jesus with<br>
his saints at the end of the millenium, but can this be done without<br>
taking this verse out of context?  Also, the usual interpretation takes<br>
Revelation 21:2 and then refers it to John seeing the holy city descending<br>
at the end of the millenium, but I question this interpretive move and<br>
will note my question in a second).  It should also be noted that these<br>
verses speak of the wicked being consumed and the Devil being placed in<br>
the lake of fire.<br>
<p>
Revelation 20:11-15  This brings up imagery similar to Daniel's portrayal<br>
of the Ancient of Days.  Here the dead are before the throne and the<br>
books.  Death, Hades, and the unrighteous go into the lake of fire/second<br>
death.  Seeing as how we just saw the wicked consumed, it seems reasonable<br>
to say that this is an expansion of the events in the last few verses.<br>
<p>
Revelation 21:1-8  Verse 1 says there is a new heaven and a new earth. <br>
Verse 2 shows the New Jerusalem coming down out of heaven.  After this<br>
follow comments on this new situation (Now if the verses from chapter 19<br>
and the the verses from chapter 20 are taken to be somewhat<br>
sequential--excepting the expansion on the fate of the wicked-- then why<br>
should verse 2 not be seen as sequential with verse 1?  This is my<br>
question concerning the usage of the 2nd verse to refer to the end of the<br>
millenium.)  <br>
<p>
Now given all the verses above I see a few possibilites:<br>
scenario 1:  Jesus meets saints in the air and they go to the heavenly<br>
city which then lands on the desolate earth.  After the millenium, when<br>
the wicked are destroyed, the city rises from the earth.  After the new<br>
heaven and the new earth it rests again on the earth.  I should note<br>
something that I forgot to mention above:  when the wicked are consumed<br>
fire comes out of heaven, which makes one wonder if God isn't in the air<br>
when he destroys the unrighteous.  This brings up a further question: <br>
when it says the wicked lay seige to the saints and the city does that<br>
necessitate that the city is on the earth?  Which suggests another<br>
possibility...<br>
<p>
Scenario 2: Jesus and the saints go to the New Jerusalem that does not<br>
exist upon the earth at the moment.  After the millenium, when the wicked<br>
are destroyed, the city approachs the earth such that the wicked are able<br>
to at least see it.  The judgement's last phase is preformed and the earth<br>
and heaven are made new.  Then the city descends.<br>
<p>
Scenario 3: Jesus and the saints go to the New Jerusalem that does not<br>
exist upon the earth at the moment.  After the millenium, when the wicked<br>
are destroyed, the city descends upon the earth. Then the city rises after<br>
the final acts of judgment are done and fire rains down to consume the<br>
wicked.  The heavens and earth are made new.  The city descends again.<br>
<p>
Now none of these is what I consider the usual Adventist position on the<br>
millenium and New Jerusalem.<br>
<p>
Now I know some verses like John 14:1-3 are used to support the notion that<br>
the saints are not on the earth in any way during the millenium.  I see<br>
this as potentially ok.  Now comes my second and it seems my third questions.<br>
<p>
Are there other verses to support the idea that the New Jerusalem will not<br>
be on the earth during the millenium?<br>
<p>
Given any answers to this, are there comments on what else I said such<br>
that I might figure out which view is right concerning the sequence of<br>
events (scenarios 1-3, and the usual Adventist view which doesn't include<br>
the reascent and redescent of scenario 3).<br>
<p>
Whew!  This is a lot of stuff!<br>
<p>
Thanks for any help in figuring out my dilemmas,<br>
"Malachi Robertson" better known as Ian Robertson Brown<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
