<title>Sep_1992: Re: Translation Faith</title>
<h1>Re: Translation Faith</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 11 Sep 1992 08:53:37 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#130">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#130">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#130">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#130">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0131.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: 1994"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0129.html">Ian Brown: "New Jerusalem and 1000 years"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0201.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Translation Faith"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0135.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Translation Faith"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
ME:<br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; I think most of us would agree that in Christ, freedom from sin is </i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; possible.  The question is, is it necessary?</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Christ came to save us from SIN. MAtt 1:21</i><br>
<i>&gt;have we really been saved unless we have been saved from sin ?</i><br>
<i>&gt;Are you asking whether salvation from sin is necessary ?</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Ruben.</i><br>
<p>
Yes, this is exactly the question I am asking.  In times past on this list<br>
I have been so bold as to answer it *NO*.  But now I am rethinking my<br>
position.  The difficulty for me is trying to reconcile all the verses<br>
in the<br>
Bible that say it is easy to be saved with the requirements on us during <br>
the time of trouble.  When I read the Bible, I read such verses as<br>
"Whosoever shall call on the name of the Lord shall be saved" and<br>
"Believe on the Lord Jesus Christ, and thou shalt be saved."  <br>
<p>
So salvation in my mind is an important first step, but not a<br>
time-consuming one that should occupy our whole Christian experience to<br>
the day of our death.  It's a free gift that we should receive and build<br>
our relationship with Christ on that basis.<br>
<p>
It seems to me that everyone begins a walk with Christ at salvation and<br>
proceeds down the road to sanctification.  But not everyone has a chance<br>
to <br>
complete this walk and come to full sanctification by the time they die.  <br>
The thief on the cross provides the classic example, but he is only one of<br>
many who will have some real learning to do once he gets to heaven.<br>
<p>
Yet I strongly believe that there will be a sanctified people at the end<br>
of time, sanctification which is complete by the time of trouble.  What<br>
this means to me is a group of people who will love God supremely and<br>
their <br>
neighbor as themselves ("Loving God supremely and your neighbor as yourself<br>
is genuine sanctification"--EGW)  This unconditional love displayed to<br>
those who have rejected it will infuriate them and bring about<br>
persecution and the time of trouble.<br>
<p>
So I suppose the question is:  Will everyone who is translated to heaven<br>
without seeing death be part of the above group?  Is it fair to identify <br>
the above group as the 144000  (Something Ellen G. White refused to do when <br>
asked a specific question on that topic)?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
