<title>Sep_1992: Re: Epistle to the Magnesians</title>
<h1>Re: Epistle to the Magnesians</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 11 Sep 92 9:31:38 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#132">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#132">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#132">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#132">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0133.html">Tony: "Re: Translation faith"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0131.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: 1994"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0122.html">Steven Timm: "Epistle to the Magnesians"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The Epistle to the Magnesians was written by Ignatius of Antioch, early in the<br>
second century.  The passage in question is 9.1<br>
<p>
What makes the passage difficult is that different editions of the letter read<br>
differently.  Most read: no longer sabbatizing but living according to the <br>
"lordly".  One MS reads "no longer sabbatizing but living according to the<br>
lordly life--meaning the Lord's life."<br>
<p>
First problem: Sabbatizing.  The verb is used by other early church fathers to<br>
refer to "judaizing"--living like Jews.  It may or may not refer specifically<br>
to observing the seventh-day Sabbath.  <br>
<p>
Second problem:  The adjective "lordly" has no noun.  Lordly what?  Lordly day?<br>
Lordly life?   Since the adjective is in the feminine, we have to think of<br>
feminine nouns.  The two most commonly suggested are day and life.  The same<br>
adjective is used, without a noun, in Rev 1:10.  So was John in vision on the<br>
lordly day?  If so, which was that?  The emperor's day?  Christ's day? And if it<br>
was Christ's day, was that Sabbath or Sunday?<br>
<p>
Sunday observance came in very early in some places, mostly as an attempt by<br>
Christians to dissociate themselves from Judaism.  In part this was a natural<br>
reaction to persecution.  Jews were persecuted; they did not want the same fate.So they became different from Jews--and the Sabbath was a good symbol, so it <br>
went easily in some areas.<br>
<p>
As to what day the lordly day of Rev 1:10 is, one must follow the principle of<br>
unity of Scripture.  What does the rest of the Bible say on the day of rest?<br>
If we believe Scripture does not contradict itself, we cannot examine only one<br>
verse, although that is where we will start.<br>
<p>
I trust you will all have a blessed Sabbath, full of the promised gifts.<br>
<p>
Nancy<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
