<title>Sep_1992: Re: Translation faith</title>
<h1>Re: Translation faith</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 12 Sep 1992 21:01 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#133">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#133">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#133">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#133">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0134.html">Scott Mattes: "Off net"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0132.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: Epistle to the Magnesians"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Here is a similar issue which may help us sort out the original one.<br>
<p>
Enoch was translated to heaven without dying, and well before the<br>
sacrifice of Christ. I have tried real hard to find references which<br>
answer the question "Did Jesus die for Enoch?" and to this point have<br>
been unable to. The Bible only has about one verse on the topic, and<br>
EGW has less than a page.<br>
<p>
Reading the text at face value would seem to indicate that Enoch's<br>
relationship with Jesus was enough. Does this contradict the doctrine<br>
of salvation by faith? Does Enoch's "walking with God" constitute the<br>
faith required? But faith in what - Jesus hadn't died yet. Or are <br>
salvation by faith and salvation by achieving perfection both<br>
legitimate alternatives?<br>
<p>
My gut reaction is to reject the entire holy flesh concept, including<br>
the translation faith variant. I instinctively reject anything which<br>
implies that God's favour can be earned. At the same time I'm not<br>
sure that the Biblical record supports my instincts on this one!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
