<title>Sep_1992: Re: Translation Faith</title>
<h1>Re: Translation Faith</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 14 Sep 92 14:56:44 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#135">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#135">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#135">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#135">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0136.html">Steven Timm: "About origin and creation"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0134.html">Scott Mattes: "Off net"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0201.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Translation Faith"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0202.html">Daniel D Deavours: "Re: Motivations for Translation Faith"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all,<br>
<p>
Tony writes :<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Enoch was translated to heaven without dying, and well before the</i><br>
<i>&gt; sacrifice of Christ. I have tried real hard to find references which</i><br>
<i>&gt; answer the question "Did Jesus die for Enoch?" and to this point have</i><br>
<i>&gt; been unable to. The Bible only has about one verse on the topic, and</i><br>
<i>&gt; EGW has less than a page.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
Yes Jesus did die for Enoch because we are told that "All have sinned"<br>
Enoch's translation was only possible because of the Lamb that Revelation<br>
tells us "was slain from the foundation of the world"<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt; My gut reaction is to reject the entire holy flesh concept, including</i><br>
<i>&gt; the translation faith variant. I instinctively reject anything which</i><br>
<i>&gt; implies that God's favour can be earned. At the same time I'm not</i><br>
<i>&gt; sure that the Biblical record supports my instincts on this one!</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<p>
before we through anything out we must understand it to ensure we<br>
are not throwing away a jewel encrusted within dirt.<br>
<p>
What exactly are you refering to as the Holy Flesh concept ?<br>
<p>
In EGW's day it meant that one could attain such a state as that<br>
in would be impossible for him/her to sin, ie that the carnal nature<br>
was replaced by a divine nature even while on this earth, at no<br>
particular time and so henceforth they were holy in their own right.<br>
<p>
Let me just say that I have never heard anybody teach or suggest<br>
this concept in my lifetime (it not that long) within the SDA church. <br>
That does not say someone may not<br>
believe it, but I am totally unaware of it. What I do know of<br>
is people coming to wrong conclusions regarding valid doctrines<br>
and labelling them "holy flesh"; this being an easy way to discourage others<br>
from studying for themselves.<br>
<p>
The point of overcoming all sin in ones life has nothing at all to do<br>
with earning God's grace. Instead it has everything to do with God's<br>
grace working in one's life so fully that in every thought, word and<br>
act one simply reflects Christ image. Do we love God enough to permit <br>
Him to so transform our lives ? or are we content to continue <br>
dishonouring God with our petty (somtimes) sins. Those who truely have <br>
the saving faith - constant dependance on God's saving grace - "the faith<br>
of Jesus" will live a life in complete conformity to that which Jesus lived<br>
while on earth. Was He not our example ? Do we not have recourse to the<br>
same power to overcome sin that He had while on this earth ? was He not <br>
tempted in all point such as we are ? <br>
<p>
Living a life that is pleasing to God has nothing at ALL to do with earning<br>
His favor, it has everything to do with how much we love Jesus and wish<br>
to please Him and what gratitude we have for all that He has done for us.<br>
<p>
Do we love God enough to please Him in all that we say and do ?<br>
God is able and willing to empower us to live to His honour are we<br>
willing to take up the challenge ?<br>
<p>
<p>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
