<title>Sep_1992: Listening session with Columbia Union officers</title>
<h1>Listening session with Columbia Union officers</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 14 Sep 1992 14:41:32 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#142">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#142">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#142">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#142">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0143.html">Russell Grau: "Translation Faith"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0141.html">Lola: "renting churches"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The young adults of western Pennsylvania were treated to a listening<br>
session.  Ron Wisbey and Dick Duerksen, president and vice president of <br>
the union, respectively were there, as well as Jerry Page and Don Baker,<br>
president and youth leader of the Penn. Conference.  We met at a Howard<br>
Johnson's, they paid for lunch and didn't even ask for money.<br>
<p>
About 18 people attended this session.  The previous day they had<br>
130 some in Eastern PA.<br>
<p>
The format was to consist of first caucusing in groups to figure out what are<br>
the major high points and low points in the church today, then the last<br>
part came up to what are we going to do about it.  <br>
<p>
Throughout the process the leaders all seemed very receptive and <br>
eager to make changes.  The bottom line, of course, is that there is nothing<br>
that a union administration or conference administration can do to<br>
activate a congregation, it has to come from the grass roots.  They<br>
wanted to see <br>
what resources they could provide to facilitate the process.<br>
<p>
In another post I'll cover some of the main points that were brought up.<br>
But as a side effect of this meeting, we could be seeing Dick Duerksen on <br>
SDAnet in a couple weeks.<br>
<p>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
