<title>Sep_1992: Translation Faith</title>
<h1>Translation Faith</h1>
Russell Grau (<i>reg@ctsx.celtech.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 14 Sep 92 13:59 PDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#143">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#143">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#143">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#143">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0144.html">Tony: "SDA-L: What makes a biography interesting?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0142.html">Steven Timm: "Listening session with Columbia Union officers"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;Subject: Re: Translation faith</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Here is a similar issue which may help us sort out the original one.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Enoch was translated to heaven without dying, and well before the</i><br>
<i>&gt;sacrifice of Christ. I have tried real hard to find references which</i><br>
<i>&gt;answer the question "Did Jesus die for Enoch?" and to this point have</i><br>
<i>&gt;been unable to. The Bible only has about one verse on the topic, and</i><br>
<i>&gt;EGW has less than a page.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Reading the text at face value would seem to indicate that Enoch's</i><br>
<i>&gt;relationship with Jesus was enough. Does this contradict the doctrine</i><br>
<i>&gt;of salvation by faith? Does Enoch's "walking with God" constitute the</i><br>
<i>&gt;faith required? But faith in what - Jesus hadn't died yet. Or are </i><br>
<i>&gt;salvation by faith and salvation by achieving perfection both</i><br>
<i>&gt;legitimate alternatives?</i><br>
<p>
No they are not.  We are incapable of achieving perfection by ourselves.  Only<br>
by beholding the One sent to be sin for us can we be changed.  This is why <br>
James says that the law is like a man who looks into a mirror, sees himself<br>
for what he is and then goes away and forgets what he actually looks like.  The<br>
law or the keeping of the law cannot and will not save us. (See Romans and <br>
Galations on this one...:-)<br>
<p>
As far as Enoch being saved by works, examine Heb 11.  There you will see that<br>
Jesus died for Enoch also.  You see that the inspired writer says, "By faith<br>
Enoch was translated that he should not see death; and was not found, because<br>
God had translated him: for before his translation he had this testimony, that <br>
he pleased God.  [Now, if we stop here your arguement has some weight.  But,<br>
if we read the next verse the weight vanishes. - REG] 6 - But without faith it<br>
is impossible to please him: for he that cometh to God must believe that he is<br>
and that he is a rewarder of them that diligently seek him."<br>
<p>
The entire 11th chapter of Hebrews tells the story of salvation before Jesus.<br>
It was the same then as it is now, faith saves, actions do not.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;My gut reaction is to reject the entire holy flesh concept, including</i><br>
<i>&gt;the translation faith variant. I instinctively reject anything which</i><br>
<i>&gt;implies that God's favour can be earned. At the same time I'm not</i><br>
<i>&gt;sure that the Biblical record supports my instincts on this one!</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
Your instincts regarding faith are correct.  Only faith saves, actions merely<br>
show that faith exists (if you love Me, keep My commandments).<br>
<p>
Most of the holy flesh movement really circles around the very nature of the<br>
Messiah when He came to be among us.  Was He just like you and I?  Or was He<br>
like a second Adam?  This is the really critical question.  Be careful how you<br>
answer it.  Be careful how you use the Bible and SoP quotations on this.  What<br>
may appear to serve one end actually may serve the other when taken in<br>
context.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Tony</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
