<title>Sep_1992: SDA-L: What makes a biography interesting?</title>
<h1>SDA-L: What makes a biography interesting?</h1>
Bob Moynihan (<i>st0o+%ANDREW.CMU.EDU%CMU.EDU@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>15 Sep 1992 21:55:15 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#152">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#152">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#152">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#152">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0153.html">Wil Clarke: "SDA-L response"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0151.html">Lisa Parry: "SDA-L response"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; I am sometimes shy, but the main reason I haven't written any personal</i><br>
<i>&gt; interest stuff for the net is because I am married.</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Now, I may have misread the initial posts regarding this, but I have</i><br>
<i>&gt; gotten the impression that this was some kind of SDA dating service...</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Please correct me if I have misunderstood the situation!</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Tony</i><br>
<p>
Oh yeah, big time.  (Well, I don't know about SDA-L, but SDAnet<br>
isn't a dating service. :-)<br>
<p>
Let me provide a hand, brother Tony...<br>
<p>
I'm 35 years old, married, with two terrific daughters, ages 5 and<br>
1.  I work for Hewlett-Packard Company, (whom I don't speak for,)<br>
with a job title that says nothing about the actual work I do, so I<br>
won't bore you with it. :-)<br>
<p>
I've been Adventist for about 4.5 years, and was led to God by my<br>
wife, whom I met when I was 27, and married on my 28th birthday.  I<br>
always refer to her as "the angel that saved me from myself." (She<br>
hates it when I say that. :-)<br>
<p>
I work with the Pathfinder club at my church as the marching and<br>
drilling instructor, and on occasion have been known to preach as a<br>
guest speaker.<br>
<p>
For recreation I enjoy playing darts and soccer (though not at the<br>
same time, :-) and playing with my daughters, the older of which<br>
plays soccer, and also takes gymnastics classes.  My younger<br>
daughter thus far prefers "peek-a-boo" and helping me with the<br>
groceries. (I put them away, she takes them back out. :-)<br>
<p>
Becoming Adventist was something I did because I thought the<br>
Scripture was preached there, not because I thought Ellen G. White<br>
was a prophet.  Based on the fact that she spoke according to the<br>
Word, I accept her as one, but not that every word she ever wrote<br>
must have been divinely inspired.  Even she never claimed that, nor<br>
did she ever claim that the Spirit of Prophecy was even on an equal<br>
footing with Scripture, let alone above it.  "A lesser light to<br>
lead people to the Greater Light," I believe she called it.<br>
<p>
I was raised Catholic, and left shortly after my confirmation at 13.<br>
I did not accept the concept of Catholic tradition being able to<br>
supercede Scripture.  As such, I do not accept the teachings of any<br>
church that will say "When Scripture and our writings of &lt;fill in<br>
the blank&gt; don't agree, our &lt;fill in the blank&gt; is correct, as it is<br>
a more recently revealed truth."   As it says in Isaiah (I believe<br>
it is 8:6, Paraphrased, as I don't have my Bible with me,) "If they<br>
speak not according to *this Word*, it is because there is no light<br>
in them." (Emphasis mine, of course)<br>
<p>
To me, The Seventh-day Adventist Church speaks according to the Word.<br>
I think there are portions of the teachings that go a bit further<br>
than what Scripture indicates, but nothing that I can find clearly<br>
contradicts Scripture, or condones conduct that Scripture clearly<br>
advises against, and those areas where I feel the church 'goes<br>
beyond' Scripture are not, in my opinion, of any consequence to<br>
salvation.  (I cite, for example, my previous postings about jewelry<br>
in general, and wedding rings in particular.  As jewelry has never<br>
been something I wore anyway (except for my wedding ring,) I don't<br>
consider it an issue.<br>
<p>
Thanks to the Lords help, I've been able to grow spiritually, and<br>
feel far closer to Him than I did before I came into His church.<br>
With help from the Holy Spirit, I hope to continue in the quest for<br>
spiritual perfection.<br>
<p>
Wow... way too long winded.  God bless you all...<br>
<p>
===================================================================<br>
Bob Moynihan                         Bush/Quayle '92: Just say noe.<br>
moynihan_r@apollo.hp.com             Go Ipswich Town!<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
