<title>Sep_1992: Re: Summary of listening session</title>
<h1>Re: Summary of listening session</h1>
Daniel D Deavours (<i>ddd42961@uxa.cso.uiuc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 15 Sep 92 9:47:09 CDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#154">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#154">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#154">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#154">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0155.html">Stan Macasieb: "Re: Summary of listening session"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0153.html">Wil Clarke: "SDA-L response"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0147.html">Steven Timm: "Summary of listening session"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0155.html">Stan Macasieb: "Re: Summary of listening session"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Steve Timm writes]<br>
<i>&gt;Some of the troubles that our group of young adults agreed were the major </i><br>
<i>&gt;problems in the church to us:</i><br>
<p>
	Without quoting them all, I found the things you wrote very<br>
interesting.  Many of those things I've thought of myself and haven't<br>
gotten the chance to get anyone else's opinion.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;2)  The education gap between college-educated and not, and the difficulty</i><br>
<i>&gt;of constructing a church to appeal to both.</i><br>
<p>
	I've found this to be true.  I live in a town with a large college,<br>
and there are some Ph. D's that have come across as intimidating and proud<br>
to some.  It may be true, but I think it's more of a matter of manner than<br>
attitude.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;3)  The problem of separate conferences for blacks and whites above</i><br>
<i>&gt;the local church level.</i><br>
<p>
	Yep.  It's frustrating to try to coordinate anything with another<br>
(black) church in town.  I have probably not met some of their members yet<br>
after being here for two years.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;7)  A crisis in spiritual authority.</i><br>
<p>
	Something I've been thinking about for a while.  I wonder how much<br>
of this lies on the GC president?  I know the GC conferences are<br>
responsible for making any doctrinal decisions, but it seems rescently<br>
that they shy away from making touchy decisions (maybe rightly so.)  Example:<br>
women elders...  I think this also falls into the cultural vs. moral<br>
uncertainty.  I wonder what can be done about this.  Some say the church is<br>
too structured already.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;8)  A power gap between those who feel they 'own' the church and the </i><br>
<i>&gt;younger generations</i><br>
<p>
	Nothing new.  More generally I think /everyone/ has a problem with<br>
letting it be God's church instead of their own.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Some of the visions we came up with to change this</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;1)  Improve quality of church's educational system</i><br>
<p>
	And policies.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;2)  Develop a union-wide support group for young adults, with a recognized</i><br>
<i>&gt;leader in each church, who should serve on church board.</i><br>
<p>
	I know there's a need there, but I really question if that's the<br>
best way to go about fixing the problem.  (Not that I disagree, just<br>
question.)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;4)  Build trust between the generations by giving of ourselves.</i><br>
<p>
	Much of what you have written here seems (to me) to be problems<br>
on the local church and individual level.  I think the church leadership<br>
on the conference and union level should take a more agressive role in<br>
the education and providing of survices on the local level.  Many of the<br>
services are simply unknown to many people to even ask!<br>
	For example:  Conference senses the tension between the generations.<br>
Conferences should approach churches (not just pasters, *sigh*) with this<br>
problem and a propose some kind of solution, like a sermon, literature,<br>
or retreat on how one can build trust by giving of ourselves.<br>
	I see people in churches and local churches waiting for it's<br>
leadership to take a leadership roll, while those in positions are waiting<br>
for grass roots to take leadership.  While there really may not be anything<br>
wrong with the way things are organized, I think that there are<br>
misperceptions, and if nothing else, the leadership should take an agressive<br>
roll in dispelling these misperceptions.  (Enough opinions for one day.)<br>
<p>
Dan Deavours<br>
zeos@uiuc.edu<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
