<!-- body="start" -->
The issue of educated vs. noneducated members has always been a problem.  I<br>
have to agree that to some congreations, PhDs are arrogant and think they know<br>
everything.  But this is less common than the problems with MDs.  In some<br>
SDA congretions, an MD was considered the authority on everything (including<br>
theology).  They were typically selected as SS teachers, elders, school board<br>
members, and almost always church board.  Only until recently, when new MDs<br>
just into practice were too busy, did we see a decline in the number of medical<br>
professionals in church office.  Some of these MDs were dearly loved by there<br>
congregations.  Others have been considered downright snobs.  Recent statistics<br>
on the SDA church make-up indicate that it is an middle-class church.  The<br>
disparity between education/noneducated is less marked.  Yet, the inner city/pp9(poor and less educated) feel disenfranchised.<br>
<p>
cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
