<title>Sep_1992: biography</title>
<h1>biography</h1>
Jeffrey Tosk (<i>UMBJTO%LLUVM.BITNET@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>16 Sep 1992 17:13:25 -0800 (PST)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#162">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#162">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#162">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#162">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0163.html">Tony: "Taste and see"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0161.html">Cam Litvin: "Another Bio..."</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I'm glad to see more traffic on the list.  I didn't mean to flame<br>
anyone with my concerns regarding "personals".  In any case I'll<br>
introduce myself.<br>
<p>
I am a research neurobiologist at the Jerry L Pettis Veterans' Affairs<br>
Medical Center in Loma Linda.  I am also Assistant Research Professor<br>
of Psychiatry and Physiology at LLU School of Medicine.  My research<br>
in in the area of Parkinson's disease.  I am particularly interested<br>
in the brain pigment neuromelanin and its role in neurodegenerative<br>
disease.  My approach is biophysical as I use several forms of<br>
spectroscopy and electrochemistry to understand the midbrain<br>
dopamine system.<br>
<p>
I have been interested in Christianity most of my life (I'm forty).<br>
I was raised in a Jewish family and as a young student sang in the<br>
choir.  That is how I heard about Jesus.  We usually sang early<br>
church music for its artistic value and I listened to the words<br>
more carefully than most.  I was raised in NY City and had little<br>
opportunity to attend many churches other than Mass at St. Patricks<br>
and the like.  I loved the music of Bach and became aware of the<br>
Gospels.  I could never square the fact that Jesus is the Prince<br>
of Peace and during the Vietnam war the vicar of the armed forces,<br>
a prominant NY churchman, preached some really hate-filled sermons<br>
suggesting that killing in Vietnam was OK, even important.  I could<br>
never imagine Jesus with an M-16.  I came to believe that Christianity<br>
was dead and that most Christians used the name of God to maintain<br>
a conservative social order.  Most of the Protestant preaching I heard<br>
was on the radio on Sundays and dealt with condemnation of people for<br>
lack of patriotism or liberal moral views.  I never heard much about<br>
the love of God being healing or descriptions of the Cristian life as<br>
one of service to others, a view I learned from the Bible.  I met SDA's<br>
about 8 years ago and was supprised to meet people who actually<br>
believed that God is a real living being who cares about us.  In retrospect<br>
the folks I met then were rare indeed.  I was baptized and accepted God's<br>
love and healing in my life.  I will not preach here but I want to pose<br>
a question:  Do you think that it is appropriate to advocate an experimental<br>
relationship with God?  This has worked for me.  Could this be what is meant<br>
by "Taste and see that the Lord is good"?<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
