<title>Sep_1992: Taste and see</title>
<h1>Taste and see</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Fri, 18 Sep 1992 09:08 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#163">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#163">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#163">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#163">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0164.html">Tony: "References on origins debate"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0162.html">Jeffrey Tosk: "biography"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Jeff (?) writes:<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
a question:  Do you think that it is appropriate to advocate an experimental<br>
relationship with God?  This has worked for me.  Could this be what is meant<br>
by "Taste and see that the Lord is good"?<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
I for one think it's appropriate, and I would be very interested to hear what<br>
you have to say on this, Jeff. All my life people have said to me sentences<br>
involving the phrase "relationship with God", and very few of them actually<br>
elaborated on it. I remember during my late teens thinking that the phrase<br>
was probably passed down from generation to generation and nobody really knew<br>
what it meant!<br>
<p>
Also, I read with interest your comments regarding the chaplain of the armed<br>
forces. Isn't it strange how that the vast majority of professed Christians<br>
who are in the public eye project a most unfortunate view of Christianity. We<br>
have guys like that, using "the will of God" to justify their own personal<br>
actions and decisions whatever they may be. We have the tele-evangelists, <br>
using God to make money and to become stars. In Australia we have the <br>
Reverend Fred Nile, who if he was in the U.S. would be a leading light for<br>
the moral majority I suspect. His idea of Christianity is anti-abortion,<br>
anti-gay, anti-alcohol and drugs, anti- anti- anti-, and people get the idea<br>
that Christians are just a bunch of do-right losers.<br>
<p>
This really leaves us with a big responsibility: to be a true representative<br>
of God ourselves. If we let the average non-Christian form their impression<br>
of Christ purely on the basis of these guys, whom I would label "false<br>
witnesses", then we have let our Lord and friend down in a big way. This<br>
challenges me every day - now I just need to rise to the challenge a bit<br>
more frequently!<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
