<title>Sep_1992: Blues for the dying SDA subculture</title>
<h1>Blues for the dying SDA subculture</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 17 Sep 1992 22:21:23 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#165">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#165">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#165">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#165">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0166.html">Jeff Tosk: "SDA-L: Re: Taste and see"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0164.html">Tony: "References on origins debate"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I originally got the idea for the project which appears below about a month<br>
ago when my baby actually did leave me.  Those of you who have been following<br>
SDAnet closely for a while know that I have never dated anyone as virtuous<br>
as the hypothetical 'baby' described below, so both characters in the<br>
following piece are totally fictitious.  The place, however, is quite<br>
real.<br>
This is the first draft of something which may eventually be revised <br>
into a song, some of the words don't quite fit the rhythm yet.<br>
<p>
These preliminaries aside, I give you<br>
<p>
Got those baby left me in Berrien Springs blues....<br>
<p>
Well it was after vespers, and I was feeling doubt<br>
So I walked down by the cinema where the angels all hang out.<br>
Said "have you seen my baby?  She really was a gem<br>
Made that Special K loaf up there with the best of them."<br>
<p>
Boy, he said, we see lost babies all the time,<br>
But your baby won't come down here, she is just too fine.<br>
It's nine-thirty and they're going to close the gate.<br>
Why not see if she went to Johnson Gym to roller-skate?<br>
<p>
I was just there, Gabe old boy, that's why I'm feeling low<br>
We skated to Texas' Yellow Rose so sweet and slow<br>
But when Heritage Singers played she got in a huff<br>
She walked right off and left me 'cause the music was too rough.<br>
<p>
They just feed us Numete sandwiches, so we could use a cook<br>
Maybe we can't find your baby, but we're sure gonna look<br>
Sometimes during church we hang out outside Pioneer,<br>
so tell us just how we'd spot your baby dear.<br>
<p>
She wore her hemlines always just an inch below the knee<br>
so at the beach on Sabbath we'd not go too far to sea.<br>
She wore a jeweled stick-pin in her cowl-neck sweater,<br>
and golden watches from the last three guys who met 'er.<br>
<p>
We promised to be pastor and nurse in foreign lands,<br>
The moonlight shimmered from the clear nail polish on her hands,<br>
Little Debbie, I told her, we've made the right connection,<br>
and we held hands until the dean stopped our display of affection.<br>
<p>
I gave a Birthday-Thank offering, when I first learned her name<br>
But now the banquet, even Ingath'ring won't be the same.<br>
I'm not Historically Correct, and so she says for spite,<br>
She's going to date a direct descendant of Ellen G. White.<br>
<p>
Wow, that's heavy, man, for you to watch her go away,<br>
but listen for her where you hear piano playing "Trust And Obey."<br>
If you find her soon, have her bring us a video,<br>
and a double order of Special K, and Kaffree tea, to go.<br>
<p>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
Sept. 17, 1992<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
