<title>Sep_1992: Meaning of Dispensations</title>
<h1>Meaning of Dispensations</h1>
Scott Mattes (<i>73027.3270@compuserve.com</i>)<br>
<i>20 Sep 92 11:21:40 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#169">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#169">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#169">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#169">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0170.html">Minna: "SDA-L: A Bio from Finland"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0168.html">C. Allen Roy: "sda-l Ark-athon II"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Steve,<br>
I know I am not on SDAnet anymore after having lost my access to Internet,<br>
but I wanted to explain what the LDS church means by a dispensation, since a<br>
poster just before I left seems to think that we mean something which is<br>
incorrect.<br>
 <br>
The post gave the impression that my church thought that a dispensation<br>
was a time that the Lord changed the gospel meaning.<br>
 <br>
In popular parlance here in the US today, NOT.<br>
 <br>
To the LDS church a dispensation is a period of time during which the gospel<br>
message is restored to what it had originally was. Dispensations are needed<br>
because men slowly reject the truth of the gospel and change it to fit their<br>
needs, rather than changing their lives to what God has said. This falling<br>
away is called an apostacy. Such an apostacy occured shortly after the death<br>
of the Lord's apostles and extended until the 1800's. On this we agree, I<br>
think. On who and how the apostacy was ended, at least for some, we<br>
disagree.<br>
 <br>
  I don't know how to set the Reply-To: in a note coming from Compuserve,<br>
but feel free to send directly to me, or cc me, on any comments to this<br>
topic.<br>
 <br>
--------------------------------------+----------------------------------------<br>
Scott (nmi) Mattes                    | No success can compensate for failure<br>
