<title>Sep_1992: Sabbath</title>
<h1>Sabbath</h1>
Danny Kumamoto (<i>kumamoto@verisys.slb.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 21 Sep 92 13:22:26 JST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#172">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#172">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#172">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#172">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0173.html">Steven Timm: "Need Apple ][ software"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0171.html">Steven Timm: "Making the church safe for the Geritol set"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0127.html">Tony: "Re: Sabbath"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
To SDAnet,<br>
<p>
Does anyone know (if any) of a book/article which details the origin<br>
of Sunday-as-the-Lord's-day, told from an impartial and unaffliated<br>
scholar?  Preferably a non-Christian one, who is respected by both<br>
Catholic and Protestant Christians.  I ask because I know Adventists<br>
and Roman Catholics have their bais (papal authority), while<br>
Sunday-Protestants have their own (anything but papal authority).<br>
Or do I have to settle with several authors and make the ends meet?<br>
Thanks!<br>
<p>
Danny<br>
<p>
Internet:  kumamoto@verisys.slb.com or kumamoto@sj.ate.slb.com<br>
