<title>Sep_1992: Re:  Need Apple ][ software</title>
<h1>Re:  Need Apple ][ software</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 21 Sep 92 14:41:07 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#174">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#174">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#174">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#174">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0175.html">Steven Timm: "More on translation faith"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0173.html">Steven Timm: "Need Apple ][ software"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0173.html">Steven Timm: "Need Apple ][ software"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
There are over 10,000 public domain programs for the Apple II computers.<br>
The best place to look for these is in the back of one of the computer<br>
magazines published specifically for Apple IIs such as A+ or InCider.  There<br>
are ads at the back.  You'll find several vendors that will send you a catalog<br>
of PD software they have available.<br>
<p>
Another place you might look is through CompuService special interest groups.<br>
I used to have an Apple IIe until I bought a Mac 4 years ago.  Nice little<br>
machines but not powerful enough for me.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
