<title>Sep_1992: More on translation faith</title>
<h1>More on translation faith</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 21 Sep 1992 22:07:47 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#175">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#175">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#175">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#175">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0176.html">Dan Blake: "Re: Day of rest"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0174.html">cheryl berthelsen: "Re:  Need Apple ][ software"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0184.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: More on translation faith"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
In the last "translation faith", someone examined the question of whether <br>
or not Jesus died for Enoch.  It was agreed that this answer was "yes."<br>
Enoch stood no more or no less than anyone else in need of the grace of God.<br>
<p>
Yet Enoch remains, along with Elijah, one of the few to be translated to <br>
heaven without seeing death.  Let me state what I think everyone agrees on,<br>
then try to phrase the question more carefully.<br>
<p>
Agreed:  There will be some in heaven for whom the work of<br>
sanctification was not complete at the time of their death<br>
<p>
Agreed:  There will be some alive at the second coming who keep the<br>
commandments of God and the faith of Jesus, examples of the fact that God<br>
can and does save from sin.<br>
<p>
The question:  Will all those translated (taken to heaven without seeing<br>
death) be totally and completely sanctified before that time?  Is there<br>
any<br>
difference between the requirements for being translated without seeing death<br>
and the requirements for being saved if one dies before the Second Coming?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
