<title>Sep_1992: Re: Sabbath</title>
<h1>Re: Sabbath</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 22 Sep 1992 08:27 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#177">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#177">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#177">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#177">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0178.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0176.html">Dan Blake: "Re: Day of rest"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0172.html">Danny Kumamoto: "Sabbath"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
So you're after an unbiased account of how the Lord's day has popularly become<br>
recognized as Sunday.<br>
<p>
The best I can come up with off the top of my head is a certain Jewish rabbi<br>
who has written some good stuff about the Sabbath. I suppose you could hardly<br>
call a Jew unbiased, but at least they don't get too excited either way about<br>
the pope. I'm going up to the College library today to borrow a book about<br>
molecular orbital theory :-) so I'll check the reference while I'm there.<br>
<p>
You probably won't have any success finding any work where the author hasn't<br>
got their own personal beliefs to back up. Particularly with a topic like this,<br>
the only people who are even interested in it are those with something at<br>
stake.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
