<!-- name="Fred Christiansen" -->
<!-- email="fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com" -->
<!-- subject="Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set" -->
<!-- id="9209220146.AA22507@quad4.phx.mcd.mot.com" -->
<!-- inreplyto="4ejQy5C00WB7Qe1n4l@andrew.cmu.edu" -->
<title>Sep_1992: Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set</title>
<h1>Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set</h1>
Fred Christiansen (<i>fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 21 Sep 92 18:46:03 MST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#178">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#178">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#178">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#178">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0179.html">Daniel R. Bidwell: "Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0177.html">Tony: "Re: Sabbath"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0171.html">Steven Timm: "Making the church safe for the Geritol set"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0179.html">Daniel R. Bidwell: "Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Steven Timm writes:]<br>
<i>&gt; One of our church members teaches at Shippensburg State.  For the last </i><br>
<i>&gt; several years she has brought the girls choir she directs there to give</i><br>
<i>&gt; us a worship service of all sacred music, and they have always been well-</i><br>
<i>&gt; received and given an appropriate program.  None of them is to my knowledge</i><br>
<i>&gt; SDA.  This past spring they also brought along their gospel choir.</i><br>
<i>&gt; [...]</i><br>
<p>
My beliefs on CCM (contemporary christian music) aside for the purposes<br>
of this discussion, I have a couple of comments and an anecdote that<br>
might be helpful.<br>
<p>
During the first year that I was at a certain church that I attended a<br>
number of years ago the men's choral group from Azusa Pacific University<br>
sang at our church service.  The program included an eclectic mix of<br>
traditional, ancient (monophonic), gospel, jazz, and contemporary (some<br>
of which was "light rock") Christian music.  They were accompanied by<br>
electric guitars, drums, and a saxaphone (on the jazz number).  While a<br>
few people did get up and leave, they seemed to be trying to do so<br>
discreetly; those who remained gave heartier "Amens" to the songs whose<br>
styles they preferred.<br>
<p>
During discussions over potluck following, I was interested to observe that<br>
many baby boomer types were not at all comfortable with certain of the pieces;<br>
hence, it was not just the "Geritol set" who had concerns.<br>
<p>
In response to those who were considering "setting them straight!",<br>
a number of us pointed out the following:<br>
1) The gentlemen truly believed they were offering worship to God; hence,<br>
   we should not speak in any way to offend them (I Cor 10:32).<br>
2) They had put their heart and soul into practising and performing the<br>
   music.  One could certainly appreciate that, in light of Eccl 9:10.<br>
3) The "surprise" or "shock" factor should have been removed; folk should<br>
   have known in advance what kind of program was coming up so that they<br>
   could absent themselves if they so chose.<br>
4) The group had been invited by the pastor with the cognizance of the<br>
   church board (not that they knew what was in store, tho), i.e., channels<br>
   of authority had been respected.  (This is where many who are wanting<br>
   to bring in CCM get themselves into trouble; they fail to follow proper<br>
   channels; indeed they are often confrontational or else subversive.)<br>
5) The gentleman were indeed Christian gentleman in their behavior.  One<br>
   girl (a member, altho a rare attendee) came to church wearing a quite<br>
   short red dress, down off the shoulders, and flirted endlessly with<br>
   the fellows.  Their response showed that they understood Job 31:1.<br>
   You *have* to respect them for that.<br>
6) It might have been better to schedule the program for other than church<br>
   service hours (like, in the afternoon).<br>
7) It might have been wiser to steer them towards the local celebration church<br>
   than our more conservative (even tho largely baby boomer) congregation.<br>
8) In the future (the pastor had already asked them to come back next year),<br>
   we would request that the drumset and bass guitar be skipped and that<br>
   they could pull from their repertoire pieces that would be more appreciated<br>
   once they were familiarized with their audience (which they, in fact,<br>
   did the following year).<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Personally, I feel we are challenged to the core by this incident.  If our</i><br>
<i>&gt; church is a loving, caring, affirming church (as we declare ourselves in </i><br>
<i>&gt; our local mission statement to be) then it is our duty to affirm this man</i><br>
<i>&gt; as our brother in the Lord and find some way to open a channel of </i><br>
<i>&gt; communication with him.</i><br>
<p>
I appreciate and admire your attitude towards this gentleman.  Approaching<br>
him will take great wisdom (cf. Prov 18:19).<br>
<pre>
-- 
Fred Christiansen, Motorola, 2900 S Diablo Way, Tempe, AZ 85282  "Canajun, eh?"
fredch@phx.mcd.mot.com  ||  uunet!phx.mcd.mot.com!fredch  ||  +1 602-438-3464
  On Attitude &amp; the Immune System:  A sound heart is the life of the flesh:
    but envy the rottenness of the bones.  Prov 14:30
</pre>
<!-- body="end" -->
