<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0180.html">Raylene: "Spiritual Biographies"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0178.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0171.html">Steven Timm: "Making the church safe for the Geritol set"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0183.html">Russell Yonkers: "Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; We will not build consensus and be of one accord by running roughshod</i><br>
<i>&gt; over any segment of the population of our church.  Yet the</i><br>
<i>&gt; misrepresentation of </i><br>
<i>&gt; God to 40 young people from Shippensburg plus other visitors that were</i><br>
<i>&gt; there is severe and we need to make sure it doesn't happen again.  Any</i><br>
<i>&gt; suggestions</i><br>
<i>&gt; are helpful.  I would appreciate if people would focus on the issue of</i><br>
<i>&gt; communication and not on whether the outrage over wild music was</i><br>
<i>&gt; justified or not.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
Our church is a relatively small church near Mecca, (Berrien Springs),<br>
with about 150 members.  To a large extent it is a youthful church with<br>
a fair number of Seminary student families, and many in the 30's age<br>
group.<br>
<p>
During a remodeling and addition that occured a few years ago, three<br>
crosses where designed into a wooden mosaic in the Youth room that was<br>
added to the church and a wooden cross was put on a stone face wall in<br>
the front of the church behind the podium.  This was done after some<br>
discussion with the board and church at large.  There was one elderly<br>
elder in his late eighties or early nineties that object vehemiently.<br>
The church board and the board of elders had listened to his objectsions<br>
and overruled him.  All of the elders of the church were asked to not<br>
speak on the issue from the pulpit.  The issue was closed.<br>
<p>
Some time later, the elderly elder was scheduled to preach.  The special<br>
music this Sabbath was a group of elementary school children from one of<br>
the Berrien Springs SDA schools.  The elder started his sermon by<br>
decrying this symbol of evil and of the Catholic church and daring<br>
anyone in the church to come down to the front and tear it down from the<br>
wall.  All of this was in front of visiting school children and a few of<br>
their parents.  The visiting parents eventually got up and took the<br>
children home so that they wouldn't have to see what was going on.  A<br>
couple of our members, one of which is one of the elders, was raised as<br>
a Catholic and did not see anything particularly evil about the cross as<br>
a symbol to remind us of what Christ has done for us.<br>
<p>
The elderly elder was subsequently banned from the pulpit by not<br>
scheduling him to preach or partake on the platform at all.  He was very<br>
much hurt by this action.  Many of the church members tried to make a<br>
special point of stopping by his home and their affirmation of him as a<br>
person in inspite of their differences of opinion on some subjects.<br>
<p>
He became sick and many of the church brought food, encouragement, and<br>
assistance to them before he eventualy passed away.  Before he passed<br>
away he was convinced that the church did truely love and respect him<br>
even if they didn't all agree with him on everything.<br>
<p>
I don't know if this situation can give you any insights in dealing with<br>
your situation or not, but it did sound somewhat similar.  It is at<br>
least one churchs attempt in dealing with this kind of situation.<br>
<p>
<pre>
-- 
Daniel R. Bidwell	|	bidwell@andrews.edu
Andrews University	Computer Science &amp; Information Systems Department
If two always agree, one of them is unnecesary
</pre>
