<!-- body="start" -->
These biographies are great, with many including comments about spiritual <br>
encounters - at least, when people became SDA or whatever. It is this aspect<br>
that interested me the most.<br>
<p>
For instance, so many people seem to have discovered Adventism fairly<br>
recently, unlike me - a mere 'ministers kid' grown up in the subculture.<br>
I'd like to ask those in that category and others who feel qualified to <br>
answer:<br>
"What is it about Adventism/Christianity that captured your interest?",<br>
"What do you think our best features are?"<br>
<p>
And:<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;From: Jeffrey Tosk</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I will not preach here but I want to pose</i><br>
<i>&gt;a question:  Do you think that it is appropriate to advocate an experimental</i><br>
<i>&gt;relationship with God?  This has worked for me.  Could this be what is meant</i><br>
<i>&gt;by "Taste and see that the Lord is good"?</i><br>
<p>
I'd really like to see more on this. I think I like the sound of it.<br>
<p>
When I read the book on Keith Green's life, I felt excited to be able to<br>
see inside someone like I never see inside those around me. To see how<br>
they felt about God, and how they developed in their understanding of God.<br>
<p>
I sometimes think that if I knew a bit more about others struggles, I might<br>
do better in my own.<br>
<p>
What about spiritual bios?<br>
<p>
Raylene<br>
