<title>Sep_1992: Re: Making the church safe</title>
<h1>Re: Making the church safe</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 22 Sep 1992 15:11 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#182">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#182">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#182">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#182">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0183.html">Russell Yonkers: "Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0181.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: More on translation faith"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
There seems to be two broad groups into which SDAs can mostly be divided.<br>
<p>
Some would class these groups the "conservative" and the "liberal", others<br>
would class them the "traditional" and the "open-minded", etc. Whatever <br>
labels one chooses to use, a lot of us can be fairly easily categorized<br>
this way. I will use the conservative/liberal labels for the purpose of<br>
this post.<br>
<p>
Ideally there is room for many different views of things within the umbrella<br>
of Adventism. However even this statement in itself is difficult for a<br>
conservative SDA to make. The idea of unity in the fundamental doctrines and<br>
diversity otherwise seems to be supported by all, but the dispute comes in<br>
deciding what is fundamental and what is more peripheral.<br>
<p>
What does this have to do with the problem? Well, if any of us was to <br>
perceive the actions of the church to be wrong in a significant area, it<br>
would be our responsibility to speak up. If we did not, then we could<br>
ourselves be held accountable for allowing the heresy to continue and<br>
to propagate.<br>
<p>
The conservative SDA is in the unfortunate position where many of the<br>
actions and attitudes of the church seem to be seriously at fault. This<br>
covers most new thought in theology, modern worship styles, lifestyle<br>
issues and much more.<br>
<p>
It's easy for a liberal SDA to see various things happening, not all of<br>
which he/she agrees with personally, and to accept all of them as just<br>
variations on a theme. So the liberal SDA doesn't realize what the<br>
conservative SDA is going through.<br>
<p>
To understand what I mean, think of something which you yourself would<br>
feel totally uncomfortable with were it to happen in church. For me, an<br>
example would be if as part of the worship service the pastor was to<br>
consult with an astrologer and advise us on our actions for the following<br>
week. If this kind of thing was to happen regularly - or even just a few<br>
times - in my church, I would feel it my duty to make it known that I<br>
felt that we were not doing the right thing by God.<br>
<p>
The conservative SDA sees drama performed, hears gospel music played, <br>
is preached to on theology that has not been part of our historical<br>
message, and is not preached to on theology that has. He/she sees church<br>
members wearing jewellery and make-up, going to the movies, participating<br>
in competitive sport and so on. They see these things as just as offensive<br>
to God as I do astrology in the worship service. Therefore it is their<br>
responsibility to make a stand for the right.<br>
<p>
It is going to be very difficult to reconcile this situation. From the<br>
liberal perspective, it is easy to say "tolerance", "unity in diversity",<br>
"individuality" and so on. From the conservative perspective, these things<br>
are not so easy, because the conservative SDA is being asked to be<br>
tolerant of something which he/she believes is fundamentally wrong.<br>
<p>
I'm not saying this to excuse poor communication styles or unloving<br>
approaches to things. But it's certainly something to think about.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
