<!-- body="start" -->
[The words of Russell Yonkers]<br>
I think that it is important that in any conflict over worship<br>
observances that we need to be very careful not to use any sort of<br>
inflamitory words.  As soon as we start calling a perspn a zelot or that<br>
it was "wild" music we start to arrouse the passions of the paople<br>
involved in the confrontation.  This only leads to heartace and<br>
bitterness.  We are dealing with things that people feel deep down in<br>
their very hearts about God and thier responsibility.  This needs to be<br>
handled with great care.<br>
<p>
One person put into a post that some people that favor contemporary<br>
christian music use subterfuge and try to work around the system instead<br>
of through the system.  Although I don't condone thier actions I can<br>
understand why they are doing what they are doing.  So many people feel<br>
that thier particular way of worship and thier "values" are right and<br>
the only ones that should be used.  They thus will not open-mindedly<br>
listen to others ideas.  This makes people resentful and distrusting of<br>
the system.  <br>
<p>
I am not saying that there is not right and wrong.  I am very adament <br>
about the decline in moral values in our society.  I have noticed<br>
however that to often we confuse important value issues for unimportant<br>
ones.   Could it be that the unimportant ones give us greater visibility<br>
without putting ourselves personally at risk of sevear ridicule or could<br>
it be that Satan is trying to confuse us to keep us away from the real<br>
issues that would forward the gospel?<br>
<p>
Let us be careful how we deal with other people when "hot" issues come up.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
