<!-- body="start" -->
Why should there be any difference?  What makes us think--probably with a <br>
dash of pride--that we in the last times are any better than the generations <br>
gone before us?  <br>
On the other hand, God is a lot more flexible than we usually give him credit<br>
for being.  He can change the rules if he so chooses.  He only sees the heart.<br>
The idea that those who live past the end of probation will have a second<br>
angel to protect them or some special dose of grace does not seem to have a<br>
clear biblical basis.<br>
<p>
Nancy&gt; <br>
<i>&gt; In the last "translation faith", someone examined the question of whether </i><br>
<i>&gt; or not Jesus died for Enoch.  It was agreed that this answer was "yes."</i><br>
<i>&gt; Enoch stood no more or no less than anyone else in need of the grace of God.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Yet Enoch remains, along with Elijah, one of the few to be translated to </i><br>
<i>&gt; heaven without seeing death.  Let me state what I think everyone agrees on,</i><br>
<i>&gt; then try to phrase the question more carefully.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Agreed:  There will be some in heaven for whom the work of</i><br>
<i>&gt; sanctification was not complete at the time of their death</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Agreed:  There will be some alive at the second coming who keep the</i><br>
<i>&gt; commandments of God and the faith of Jesus, examples of the fact that God</i><br>
<i>&gt; can and does save from sin.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; The question:  Will all those translated (taken to heaven without seeing</i><br>
<i>&gt; death) be totally and completely sanctified before that time?  Is there</i><br>
<i>&gt; any</i><br>
<i>&gt; difference between the requirements for being translated without seeing death</i><br>
<i>&gt; and the requirements for being saved if one dies before the Second Coming?</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Steve Timm</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
