<title>Sep_1992: Re: More on translation faith</title>
<h1>Re: More on translation faith</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 22 Sep 1992 21:17:55 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#185">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#185">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#185">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#185">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0186.html">Steven Timm: "Comments on Translation Faith"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0184.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Re: More on translation faith"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0175.html">Steven Timm: "More on translation faith"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
[Russell Yonkers, quoting S. Timm]<br>
<i>&gt; Yet Enoch remains, along with Elijah, one of the few to be translated to </i><br>
<i>&gt; heaven without seeing death.  Let me state what I think everyone agrees on,</i><br>
<i>&gt; then try to phrase the question more carefully.</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Agreed:  There will be some in heaven for whom the work of</i><br>
<i>&gt; sanctification was not complete at the time of their death</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; Agreed:  There will be some alive at the second coming who keep the</i><br>
<i>&gt; commandments of God and the faith of Jesus, examples of the fact that God</i><br>
<i>&gt; can and does save from sin.</i><br>
<p>
I can only agree to the second statement only if that statement does not<br>
mean that the person is without sin i.e. that the person has never<br>
broken a single commandment.  <br>
<p>
Elijah, as stated above, was translated.  We do know that Elijah did<br>
fail God at times.  Thus he was not without sin.  In regards to Enoch we<br>
do not know much about his life and would be making an extreamly large<br>
error to assume that he was completely without sin!  <br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; The question:  Will all those translated (taken to heaven without seeing</i><br>
<i>&gt; death) be totally and completely sanctified before that time?  Is there</i><br>
<i>&gt; any</i><br>
<i>&gt; difference between the requirements for being translated without seeing death</i><br>
<i>&gt; and the requirements for being saved if one dies before the Second Coming?</i><br>
<p>
We know from the faith chapter in Hebrews that all that were saved<br>
before Jesus's first coming were saved by faith in him.  Jesus also said<br>
that it is only through him that we are saved.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
