<title>Sep_1992: Comments on Translation Faith</title>
<h1>Comments on Translation Faith</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 22 Sep 1992 21:48:05 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#186">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#186">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#186">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#186">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0187.html">Trevor Tompkins: "Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0185.html">Steven Timm: "Re: More on translation faith"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0189.html">Russell Yonkers: "Re: Comments on Translation Faith"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;&gt; Agreed:  There will be some alive at the second coming who keep the</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; commandments of God and the faith of Jesus, examples of the fact that God</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; can and does save from sin.</i><br>
<i>&gt;[Russell Yonkers]</i><br>
<i>&gt;I can only agree to the second statement only if that statement does not mean</i><br>
<i>&gt;that the person is without sin i.e. that the person has never broken a single </i><br>
<i>&gt;commandment. </i><br>
<i>&gt;Elijah, as stated above, was translated.  We do know that Elijah did fail God</i><br>
<i>&gt;at times.  Thus he was not without sin.  In regards to Enoch we do not know </i><br>
<i>&gt;much about his life and would be making an extreamly large error to assume</i><br>
<i>&gt; that he was completely without sin!</i><br>
  <br>
If God would wait until someone never sinned in their whole life, then we <br>
would really be in trouble.  Being without sin does not mean that you have<br>
never sinned in your life, or that you by definition cannot sin.  It does <br>
mean that God's redemptive grace has worked in your life so that you choose not<br>
to sin.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; The question:  Will all those translated (taken to heaven without seeing</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; death) be totally and completely sanctified before that time?  Is there</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; any</i><br>
<i>&gt;&gt; difference between the requirements for being translated without</i><br>
seeing death<br>
<i>&gt;&gt; and the requirements for being saved if one dies before the Second Coming?</i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;We know from the faith chapter in Hebrews that all that were saved before </i><br>
<i>&gt;Jesus's first coming were saved by faith in him.  Jesus also said that it is </i><br>
<i>&gt;only through him that we are saved.</i><br>
<p>
Yes, but the issue of translation, so far as I can tell, has nothing to do <br>
with salvation per se.  If being justified by faith were all that were required<br>
then why aren't we in the Kingdom already?  I think we need to see that<br>
God is more than the ambulance driver at the bottom of the cliff, picking up<br>
the pieces every time we crash.  He would like to train us to stop jumping off!<br>
<p>
I think the doctrine of justification by faith, as wonderful as it is, has led<br>
to a certain amount of idleness in the church because people were doing <br>
everything out of concern for salvation before, from diet to Ingathering, <br>
and now that they know these are not necessary for salvation they stopped doing<br>
them.  When are people going to learn that there is more than salvation to the<br>
Christian life?  (Or is there?  Talk to me!)<br>
<p>
[Nancy Vyhmeister]<br>
<i>&gt;Why should there be any difference?  What makes us think--probably with a </i><br>
<i>&gt;dash of pride--that we in the last times are any better than the generations </i><br>
<i>&gt;gone before us?  </i><br>
<p>
The world as a whole is watching Christians to see if we practice what we<br>
preach.   The answer they come up with is usually 'no'.  We're not any better<br>
than the generations that have gone before, but we need to be if the choice<br>
between God as Lord and self as lord is to be clear-cut for those who make the <br>
final decision.  We stand as much in need of the grace of God as any other<br>
generation.  I am wondering which generation will be the first to make full<br>
use of that grace and prove the truth of the Bible which affirms that God<br>
can save from sin.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;The idea that those who live past the end of probation will have a second</i><br>
<i>&gt;angel to protect them or some special dose of grace does not seem to have a</i><br>
<i>&gt;clear biblical basis.</i><br>
This latter idea was put forth by Brinsmead, who claimed that some miraculous<br>
transformation was necessary just after the close of probation so that the <br>
minds of the believers would not think of sinning again.  He later turned<br>
full circle and claimed that no transformation, miraculous or otherwise, <br>
was needed.<br>
<p>
What is the significance of the seal of God?  Who will receive it?<br>
Has anyone yet received it?  And what do the 144000 have to do with all of <br>
this?  Any answers are welcome.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
