<title>Sep_1992: Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set</title>
<h1>Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set</h1>
Trevor Tompkins (<i>tt17+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 22 Sep 1992 21:48:38 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#187">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#187">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#187">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#187">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0188.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0186.html">Steven Timm: "Comments on Translation Faith"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0183.html">Russell Yonkers: "Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0188.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have read a few comments on this issue and now feel obliged to speak<br>
up a little.  We need to understand that when passionate words are used<br>
against a particular action it is done so for a reason.  Mainly, that<br>
some persons beliefs have been attacked.  While some people tend to<br>
create their beliefs more restrictive than the church has set forward,<br>
the church needs to step up and take responsibility for these problems. <br>
It was the church that set forth beliefs that exclude certain segments<br>
of the population, and the church (any church) that pushes beliefs in<br>
the first place.  Therefore, when somone wants to change these beliefs<br>
it is completely understandable for someone else to be upset it.  This<br>
person's life is based on these beliefs, and now someone wants to change<br>
these beliefs.<br>
<p>
	If the church wants a more inclusive philosophy, one that gives to<br>
society, rather than asserts answers to society, it needs to adopt a<br>
methodologically based system of theology rather than a strict belief<br>
system of theology.  We can change the beliefs so that they fit society<br>
today, but then we will run into the same problem we currently face now<br>
a little later.  The church needs to decide which system it wants.  If<br>
the church truly believes that it has the correct concept of God and how<br>
he should be worshiped then it needs to stay with the current belief<br>
system.  If on the other hand the church believes that we learn more<br>
about God as time goes on, then it should develop a methodolgical based<br>
system.  A methodological system of theology would maintian a core<br>
methodology and therefore change its outlook on others in society<br>
through time, but not lose its identity due to old beleif states. <br>
Academic disciplines survive because of this.  Physics today is not the<br>
same as it was when Newton developed "Newtonian Physics."  Neither is<br>
mathematics the same as it was before Godel refuted Hilbert in his<br>
incompleteness theorem, or economics after Herbert Simon, or chemistry<br>
after...  A core methodology defines the church not the current belief<br>
state.  This will of course shock those of us who entered the church<br>
based soley on beliefs about God and Worship services.  Specifically<br>
those who feel there is only one way to think of God and Worship him.<br>
<p>
	Something to think about.<br>
<p>
--Trevor <br>
Graduate student in Logic and Computation<br>
Carnegie Mellon University<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
