<title>Sep_1992: Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set</title>
<h1>Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set</h1>
Bill Oblitey (<i>OBLITEY@grove.iup.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 23 Sep 1992 13:14 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#188">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#188">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#188">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#188">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0189.html">Russell Yonkers: "Re: Comments on Translation Faith"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0187.html">Trevor Tompkins: "Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0171.html">Steven Timm: "Making the church safe for the Geritol set"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;One of our church members teaches at Shippensburg State.  For the last </i><br>
<i>&gt;several years she has brought the girls choir she directs there to give</i><br>
<i>&gt;us a worship service of all sacred music, and they have always been well-</i><br>
<i>&gt;received and given an appropriate program.  None of them is to my knowledge</i><br>
<i>&gt;SDA.  This past spring they also brought along their gospel choir.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;   . . . . deleted text</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;A retired minister who was at one time our senior pastor got up while the </i><br>
<i>&gt;music was still continuing, marched up to the front of the church, and </i><br>
<i>&gt;said to the musicians "You can't do this in God's house."  He continued</i><br>
<i>&gt;to make noise and commotion until such time as the deacons restrained </i><br>
<i>&gt;him and removed him from the sanctuary.  The concert continued to its end.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;   . . . . more deleted text</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Personally, I feel we are challenged to the core by this incident.  If our</i><br>
<i>&gt;church is a loving, caring, affirming church (as we declare ourselves in </i><br>
<i>&gt;our local mission statement to be)  then it is our duty to affirm this man</i><br>
<i>&gt;as our brother in the Lord and find some way to open a channel of </i><br>
<i>&gt;communication with him.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;So I ask, how can you communicate with someone when the only way he knows </i><br>
<i>&gt;how to communicate is through appropriated authority?  He has worked his</i><br>
<i>&gt;     . . . . . &lt;yes more deleted text&gt;   </i><br>
<i>&gt;can we stoop to that level of using the Spirit of Prophecy as a club. </i><br>
<i>&gt;(There is in fact a Spirit of Prophecy quote against using the</i><br>
<i>&gt;Testimonies as a club, but for obvious reasons it can't be used against</i><br>
<i>&gt;anybody.) </i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;We will not build consensus and be of one accord by running roughshod</i><br>
<i>&gt;over any segment of the population of our church.  Yet the</i><br>
<i>&gt;misrepresentation of </i><br>
<i>&gt;God to 40 young people from Shippensburg plus other visitors that were</i><br>
<i>&gt;there is severe and we need to make sure it doesn't happen again.  Any</i><br>
<i>&gt;suggestions</i><br>
<i>&gt;are helpful.  I would appreciate if people would focus on the issue of</i><br>
<i>&gt;communication and not on whether the outrage over wild music was</i><br>
<i>&gt;justified or not.</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<i>&gt;Steve Timm</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
<p>
Steve,<br>
I think what was missed out is with BOTH groups - the liberals and the so<br>
called conservatives.  We all know the inclinations of our congregations<br>
and we know how people will feel when we bring a particular outside group<br>
into the church.  So, why not hold a meeting before bringing in the group.<br>
If it does not appear like the congregation wants the Shippensburg choir<br>
to come because of their guitars and drums, take the choir to the nearby<br>
church that can tolerate those musical instruments and hold a joint function<br>
to praise the Lord.<br>
<p>
In every situation, someone has to give in and yet if there is to be a<br>
blessing in what is being planned, then we have to move forward with it.<br>
<p>
If a new musical instrument is created in this decade, will out conservatives<br>
claim that EGW and the other "pioneers" did not worship with such instruments<br>
so we should not employ such instrument in our services?<br>
<p>
I think you need to convince the youth that the old pastor should not be<br>
disfellowshipped.  They may convey to him their opinion on what he did is<br>
not positive but they have to learn to tolerate him.<br>
<p>
<p>
Bill Oblitey<br>
[OBLITEY@OAK.GROVE.IUP.EDU]<br>
