<title>Sep_1992: Re: Comments on Translation Faith</title>
<h1>Re: Comments on Translation Faith</h1>
Russell Yonkers (<i>ryonkers@mis.mi04.zds.com</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 24 Sep 92 8:16:46 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#189">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#189">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#189">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#189">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0190.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: More on translation faith"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0188.html">Bill Oblitey: "Re: Making the church safe for the Geritol set"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0186.html">Steven Timm: "Comments on Translation Faith"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; I think the doctrine of justification by faith, as wonderful as it is, has led</i><br>
<i>&gt; to a certain amount of idleness in the church because people were doing </i><br>
<i>&gt; everything out of concern for salvation before, from diet to Ingathering, </i><br>
<i>&gt; and now that they know these are not necessary for salvation they stopped doing</i><br>
<i>&gt; them.  When are people going to learn that there is more than salvation to the</i><br>
<i>&gt; Christian life?  (Or is there?  Talk to me!)</i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
[Russell Yonkers]<br>
<p>
One of the problems that many people have is that they have forgotten<br>
that we are to have a relationship with God not just have our<br>
salvation ticket signed by his son.  Relationships mean that<br>
we modify behavior, that we work at becomming better persons.<br>
Too often we figure that in ANY relationship we can sit around idle<br>
and not grow into the relationship and the other person.  People<br>
have the wrong idea that God is some sort of pill that one can just<br>
t take and be saved. .  It is just like my relationship with my wife<br>
If I have things that I do that bother her I will change.  Not because<br>
she forces me to but because I lover her and want to make her happy.  <br>
My kids act the same way toward me.  (Well most of the time). <br>
Of course there are times that they do something just to upset me but<br>
for the most part they want to make me happy. <br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<i>&gt; </i><br>
<!-- body="end" -->
