<title>Sep_1992: Re: More on translation faith</title>
<h1>Re: More on translation faith</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 24 Sep 92 14:23:27 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#190">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#190">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#190">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#190">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0191.html">Ian Brown: "Spiritual Biography"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0189.html">Russell Yonkers: "Re: Comments on Translation Faith"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0192.html">Ian Brown: "More on translation faith"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0193.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: More on translation faith"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all,<br>
<p>
I have been requested to substantiate my previous post asserting <br>
an affirmative reply to Steves question below. I was also recommended<br>
to post these on SDAnet for all to judge and so I shall.<br>
<p>
I ask each of you to _fully_ read this very carefully. If ever there was<br>
present truth then this certainly qualifies.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; The question:  Will all those translated (taken to heaven without seeing</i><br>
<i>&gt; death) be totally and completely sanctified before that time?  Is there</i><br>
<i>&gt; any</i><br>
<i>&gt; difference between the requirements for being translated without seeing death</i><br>
<i>&gt; and the requirements for being saved if one dies before the Second Coming?</i><br>
<i>&gt;</i><br>
 <br>
An in another email Steve writes :<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;What is the significance of the seal of God?  Who will receive it?</i><br>
<i>&gt;Has anyone yet received it?  And what do the 144000 have to do with all of </i><br>
<i>&gt;this?  Any answers are welcome.</i><br>
<p>
<p>
Well now where do I start ?<br>
<p>
Well we know that the 144000 are those who have received the seal of God.<br>
Rev 7:3-4 and who are alive on the earth when Jesus comes and they have <br>
perfected Christian characters Rev 14:4-5.<br>
<p>
We also know that these have perfected Christ-like characters BEFORE<br>
Jesus comes because 1 John 3:2-3 tells us that <br>
	"Beloved, now are we the sons of God, and it doth not yet appear<br>
what we shall be: but we know that when he shall appear, we shall be like <br>
Him: for we shall see him as he is. And every man that hath this hope in <br>
him purifieth himself, even as he is pure." <br>
<p>
Please note that it does not say we shall be made like him at His appearing.<br>
it says we _shall_ be like him, because we have been purified.<br>
<p>
Likewise Zech and Isa tell us about a time when God Himself will work <br>
wonderfully on behalf of His people such that Mal 3:3 tells us that<br>
"He shall purify the sons of Levi and purge them as gold and silver, <br>
that they may offer unto the Lord an offering in righteousness."<br>
<p>
This purification is to take place in our lives now so that when He appears<br>
we shall be like he is in character.<br>
<p>
We also know that the time is coming when the Lord will say <br>
"He that is righteous, let him be righteous still and he that is holy<br>
let him be holy still..." Rev 22:11-12 and we know that this happens when<br>
Jesus stand up in Dan 12:1 from the investigative judgement outlined in <br>
Daniel and leaves the mercy seat in the most holy place in the sanctuary.<br>
The intercessory censor is cast to the ground Rev 8:5 indicating an end of <br>
intercession for sin, smoke fills the heavenly temple Rev 15:8, so that<br>
no one can enter and intercede on behalf of man and the time of trouble<br>
as there never was begins Dan 12:1 and Rev 16:1.<br>
<p>
Now we know that Jesus role in the heavenly sanctuary is that of forgiving<br>
sin as our high priest 1 John 2:1, Heb 4:14-16, Heb 7:24-27, Heb 8:1-5.<br>
Please note that your (and my) sins were not forgiven ~2000 years ago, yes the<br>
sacrifice was made for them but how can a sin be forgiven that has not<br>
yet been committed ? No, Jesus now forgives sin (He is now able to becuase<br>
of His sacrifice which He has already made ) not before we ask him<br>
but when we ask him because this is His role as our advocate and High Priest<br>
to forgive our sins.<br>
<p>
Now when our priest stops officiating on our behalf there can be no more<br>
forgiveness of sin obviously. So that if we sin after this time (close of<br>
probation) we can not be forgiven because there will be nobody there<br>
to forgive us our sins. Obviously if we have unforgiven sins then we are<br>
eternally lost. what then does this suggest regarding those who live <br>
at the time when there will be no mediator in the heavenly sanctuary ?<br>
<p>
<p>
Anyway there are many more texts in the scriptures which show these same<br>
things. Now I will present some of the things that EGW wrote regarding<br>
translation faith and the sealing and the close of probation.<br>
<p>
<p>
After the close of probation, "there will be no priest in the sanctuary<br>
to offer their sacrifices, their confessions, and their prayers before the<br>
Father's throne." (EW 48) " I saw that many did not realise what they must<br>
be in order to live in the sight of the Lord without a high Priest in the<br>
sanctuary in the time of trouble. Those who receive the seal of the living <br>
God and are protected in the time of trouble must reflect the image of<br>
Jesus fully.... There will be no time then to do it and no mediator to <br>
plead their cause before the Father" (EW 71) "Those who are living upon <br>
the earth when the intercession of Christ shall cease in the sanctuary<br>
above are to stand in the sight of a holy God without a mediator. Their <br>
robes must be spotless, their characters must be purified from sin by the <br>
blood of sprinkling. Through the grace of God and their own diligent effort<br>
they must be conquerors in the battle with evil." (GC 425)<br>
<p>
Please read the above quotations prayerfully again and consider well the <br>
full import of what she says.<br>
<p>
Here is some more ....<br>
<p>
"The rapidly diminishing space of time between us and eternity should<br>
more deeply impress us. Each day that passes makes one less left to us<br>
to complete our work of perfecting character ....." 5T 451<br>
<p>
"When he comes it is not to cleans us of our sins, to remove from us <br>
the defects in our characters, or to cure us of the infirmities of our <br>
tempers and dispositions. If wrought for us at all, this work shall be <br>
accomplished before that time. When the Lord comes those who are holy will<br>
be holy still. Those who have preserved theire bodies and spirits in holiness<br>
in sanctification and honour, will then receive the finishing touch of <br>
immortality. But those who are unjust, unsanctified and filthy will remain<br>
so forever. No work will then be done for them to remove their defects<br>
and give them holy characters. The refiner does not then sit to pursue<br>
His refining process and remove their sins and corruption. This is all to <br>
be done in these hours of probation. It is NOW that this work is to be <br>
accomplished for us." 2T 355,356<br>
<p>
"The time of trouble such as never was, is soon to open upon us; and we<br>
shall need an experience which we do not now posses, and which many are too<br>
indolent to obtain. It is often the case that trouble is greater in <br>
anticipation than in reality; but this is not true of the crisis before us.<br>
The most vivid presentation cannot reach the magnitude of the ordeal. And <br>
now, while the precious saviour is making an atonement for us, we should seek<br>
to become perfect in Christ....None can neglect or defer this work but at the <br>
most fearful peril to their souls." (Ev 704)<br>
<p>
"The season of distress and anguish before us will require a faith that can <br>
endure weariness, delay, and hunger - a faith that will not faint though <br>
severely tried. The period of probation is granted to all to prepare for<br>
that time..."  1 T 268<br>
<p>
"Are we seeking for His fullness, ever pressing toward the mark set before <br>
us-- the perfection of His character ? When the Lord's people reach this<br>
mark, they will be sealed in their forheads. Filled with the Spirit, they<br>
will be complete in Christ and the recoding angel will declare, 'It is<br>
finished.'" 6 BC 1118<br>
<p>
As you can plainly see the answer to Steve's question is affirmative.<br>
Yes we do require a faith which we do not now posses and many are too<br>
indolent to obtain - the Faith of Jesus. Rev 14:12.<br>
<p>
<p>
And there is much, much more of this in the SoP. To much for me<br>
to give an exaustive list. However just a few more pointers for those who <br>
wish: under 'Probation' in the EGW index we find<br>
<p>
PROBATION<br>
close : <br>
	Character cannot be made or transformed after: TM 235-6<br>
	Living righteous will receive seal of God prior to: 1 SM 66<br>
	No mercy for sinners after: GC 613-4<br>
	Perfection of character must be attained before: 2 T 355<br>
	Sin must be overcome before: 2 T 430-1<br>
Time of :<br>
	Defects of character must be overcome during : AH 319<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Regards,<br>
Ruben.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
