<title>Sep_1992: Spiritual Biography</title>
<h1>Spiritual Biography</h1>
Ian Brown (<i>Malachi.Robertson@lambada.oit.unc.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 24 Sep 92 0:34:21 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#191">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#191">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#191">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#191">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0192.html">Ian Brown: "More on translation faith"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0190.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: More on translation faith"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Raylene,<br>
<p>
I became an Adventist three years after hearing some evangelistic<br>
meetings.  I was quite astounded by the things I heard and saw in the<br>
Bible:  in particular the Sabbath and the view of eschatology.  I guess my<br>
feeling at the time was that since this was what the Bible really said,<br>
then it must be true.  Some how that doesn't make sense to me now.  I<br>
guess part of it was also this impression that the unfilled spots in my<br>
previous years of spiritual wandering were being fulfilled.  As I have<br>
grown, I have taken a step back to redefine why I am an Adventist and to<br>
see why I believe what I believe.  I firmlly believe that the God who was<br>
with me as a young man before I was a Christian has led me to the Bible as<br>
His written revelation to humanity.  As such I ought to believe what it<br>
says and ought not to take flights of fancy to traditions.  I believe that<br>
the Adventist Chruch is the only environment in which I can be with fellow<br>
believers and do this.  What other body of people on earth believes what<br>
we believe?  I see that what we preach is what the Bible says.  Although I<br>
question the firmness of some of the details concerning our beliefs (such<br>
as the millenium), I find that in the Adventist church there exists this<br>
dynamism where you search the Bible continually for truth.  You don't stop<br>
questioning yourself about what the Bible says (though the amount of<br>
question may decrease in some cases).  The founders of this denomination<br>
went to the Bible with a fresh mind to see what it had to say, and they<br>
allowed the Spirit to convict them of the truth.  This element I find very<br>
positive about the Adventist Church.  That and the true workers of the<br>
Lord that I meet in fellowship (and join in service with) are why I am<br>
still and Adventist today.<br>
<p>
Ian.<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
