<title>Sep_1992: Time Magazine on Dead Sea Scrolls</title>
<h1>Time Magazine on Dead Sea Scrolls</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Thu, 24 Sep 92 22:33:49 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#194">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#194">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#194">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#194">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0195.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Time Magazine on Dead Sea Scrolls"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0193.html">Fred Christiansen: "Re: More on translation faith"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0195.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Time Magazine on Dead Sea Scrolls"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
SDAnet,<br>
<p>
Did any of you catch the article in this weeks TIME magazine about new<br>
discoveries from the Dead Sea Scrolls?  The writer implies that this new<br>
information will either help the "liberals" who say the Gospels were written<br>
in the 2nd Century AD or "conversatives" who identify 1st Century dating.<br>
Interesting, there is now evidence that some of the Qumran manuscripts<br>
were written BEFORE Christ, as early as 200 BC.  There are several quotes<br>
almost identical to words of Christ.  Probably the only thing these<br>
"scholars" do agree on is that these new manuscripts emphasize the "Jewishness"<br>
of Jesus Christ.<br>
<p>
I'd like to hear any comments you may have on this.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
<ul>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0195.html">Steven Timm: "Re: Time Magazine on Dead Sea Scrolls"</a>
