<title>Sep_1992: Biography</title>
<h1>Biography</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+%ANDREW.CMU.EDU%CMU.EDU@bitnet.cc.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>28 Sep 1992 09:12:58 -0400</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#197">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#197">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#197">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#197">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0198.html">Tony: "Re: More on translation faith"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0196.html">Jim harris: "Re: Subculture,Superculture, or Counterculture?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have certainly been inspired by the delightful biographies of the<br>
network family on-line. Those of you other lingerers and lurkers,<br>
follow my example and post yours as well.<br>
<p>
I'm a second year Ph.D. student at the University of Tennessee in<br>
communications, journalism public relations and information science.<br>
The focus of my research is on electronic information, specifically<br>
the National Research and Education Network (NREN) established by<br>
Sen. Gore's High-Performance Computing Act of 1991 signed by Pres.<br>
Bush December 9, 1991. I am researching policy and legal issues including<br>
access, equity, intellectual property, privacy, censorship and the<br>
impact these will have on the communications industry.<br>
<p>
I graduated from Southern College of SDA (Southern Missionary College)<br>
in 1975, earned a master's in Libraries and Information Science from<br>
Vanderbilt University in 1979, spent my early career teaching English,<br>
speech, journalism, then became a magazine editor, newspaper reporter<br>
and editor, and worked in corporate communications.<br>
<p>
I am assistant professor of journalism and communnication on a two-<br>
year study leave from Southern College where I teach advanced<br>
expository writing, persuasion and propaganda, public relations<br>
theory, case studies and techniques, and public speaking.<br>
<p>
One of the nicest experiences that has happened to me at UTK has<br>
been related to this net. When Steve posted the directory, I was<br>
surprised to find someone else from my university on the net. I<br>
sent her an e-mail message. Later, in arranging for a class I<br>
teach (Writing for the Mass Media) to visit the library, who should<br>
it be that I make arrangements with? Jeanette Prescod, who is on<br>
this list. She is Government Documents Coordinator of the University<br>
of Tennessee Libraries and I told her this morning she needs to post<br>
her bio on the net.<br>
<p>
The Knoxville SDA Church has purchased the former home of the<br>
University President and operates a wonderful Advent House for<br>
Adventist students. Ron Pickell has an active outreach and students<br>
find a welcome place to visit, eat, worship, and live. More on this<br>
successful program if you'd like to hear about it. I'm writing an<br>
article for the Adventist Review about this Adventist University<br>
outreach.<br>
<p>
Last week at church I met two Adventist students. Vanessa Ruf<br>
discovered on her way to the University that Hurricane Andrew was<br>
hitting her hometown of Florida City. She lost her home. This<br>
was a front-page story in the University's daily newspaper.<br>
The other Adventist student, Gretchen Grimaud, is the discus-<br>
throwing champion from Pennsylvania and a member of UT's track<br>
team. The team has changed dates for their meets to accommodate<br>
her Sabbath-keeping schedule. The national dates have also been<br>
changed to accommodate her. The University of Tennessee was the<br>
only university to accommodate Gretchen. But UT has been known<br>
for its track team and its students' success in the Olympics.<br>
<p>
Spiritual Biography: I gave my heart to Jesus at camp at age 10.<br>
It's been a wonderful love affair. I have found answers to my<br>
questions about the faith/works issues, reaching perfection before<br>
Christ comes, and righteousness by a constant study of Galatians<br>
and Romans. Paul has addressed these issues eloquently.<br>
<p>
I just recently joined the net and am delighted to be on board.<br>
In fact, I hope to write about this network for an Adventist<br>
publication. It's exciting and one of the only places where<br>
one can have such pertinent conversations with so many far-flung<br>
brothers and sisters.<br>
<p>
Pamela Maize Harris<br>
HARRISP@UTKVX.UTK.EDU<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
