<title>Sep_1992: Re: More on translation faith</title>
<h1>Re: More on translation faith</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Sat, 26 Sep 1992 19:56 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#198">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#198">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#198">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#198">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0199.html">Steven Timm: "The church of the 70's"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0197.html">Steven Timm: "Biography"</a>
<li> <b>Maybe in reply to:</b> <a href="0192.html">Ian Brown: "More on translation faith"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
I have been experiencing quite some internal conflict over the issues<br>
raised in this discussion. This is clearly a good thing, since you only<br>
really learn and grow through internal conflict! (Cognitive dissonance<br>
I believe is a related term which educational theorists like.)<br>
<p>
After reading Ruben's last post, I decided it was high time I made an<br>
effort to sort this out for myself. I have subsequently spent a few hours<br>
speaking with various people, and reading Biblical and SoP passages referred<br>
to by Ruben, as well as some useful references which were given to me.<br>
<p>
I am far from being able to post anything myself which I could hope to<br>
back up, but I would like to share some references with others reading<br>
the discussion who may be as disturbed about the issue as myself.<br>
<p>
The most outstanding treatment I have found is a chapter in George Knight's <br>
extremely recent book. The book is entitled "The Pharisee's Guide to Perfect<br>
Holiness", and Chapter 9 is "Perfection and the Final Generation". So far<br>
I have only been able to read a photocopy of chapter 9, but as soon as<br>
the stores open after the weekend I will be purchasing the book. I give<br>
this material my strongest recommendation, as it is helping me understand<br>
just what all those quotes Ruben gave are trying to say to me.<br>
<p>
I also have a book called "Perfection. The Impossible Possibility" by<br>
Douglass, Heppenstall, La Rondelle and Maxwell. This one I haven't had<br>
a chance to read yet, but apparently the four authors each present their<br>
own treatments on the issue of perfection, with Douglass and Maxwell aligned<br>
with one view, and Heppenstall and La Rondelle with another. This material<br>
is probably not as specific to the translation faith discussion as the<br>
chapter by Knight, but it looks like it may be helpful all the same.<br>
Particularly when it comes to understanding what White meant when she<br>
referred to perfection, Christ's character and so on.<br>
<p>
Other references are the following papers.<br>
<p>
Polglase, J., "Doubly Perfect"<br>
Tolhurst, L.P., "Perfection of character and perfection of nature"<br>
Ford, D., "When probation closes: Absolute loyalty or absolute sinlessness?"<br>
<p>
I don't know where or even if these were published, my pastor had copies<br>
of them on file from the late 60s early 70s when they were written. For<br>
anyone concerned about the authorship of some of these, they were written<br>
well before any of the controversy which later ensued. <br>
<p>
If anybody does want copies of these papers, maybe I could type them in <br>
after I hand in my research project, or perhaps even mail you a copy.<br>
Both of these options are a bit of a pain, so don't ask unless you are<br>
really dead-set serious!<br>
<p>
I should say in closing that this discussion has actually done more to<br>
help my spiritual growth than anything in my recent past. And I really<br>
do recommend that book by George Knight! I believe the Lord is using this<br>
man to speak to our church.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
