<title>Sep_1992: The church of the 70's</title>
<h1>The church of the 70's</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 28 Sep 1992 09:33:52 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#199">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#199">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#199">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#199">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0200.html">David Plaisted: "Church where you grew up"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0198.html">Tony: "Re: More on translation faith"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
About a year ago you recall that I posted my feelings on going back to the<br>
church in which I grew up and being shocked to find it had liberalized.<br>
Again I went to Michigan over the weekend, again for a wedding, visiting <br>
a different SDA church which shall remain nameless (but not the one in <br>
which I grew up.)  <br>
<p>
I remembered the pastor from my days in Michigan--after a fairly successful<br>
career in business he had begun working as first a singing evangelist for<br>
a large Voice Of Prophecy crusade.  Twenty years later, he is still in the <br>
ministry, singing the same songs he sung then (and singing them better,<br>
I might add, his singing has actually improved with age.)  After a rousing<br>
rendition of "The Great Judgment Day" in song, he proceeded to preach on <br>
the seven last plagues, and the division of Babylon, and all those other <br>
good Adventist eschatology topics about which we hardly hear anymore.<br>
<p>
This and other impressions of the day at church left me with the impression<br>
that there are many churches who still live in the early 70's and like <br>
it that way.  Given the description of the "establishment" that runs this<br>
particular local church, I don't doubt that they wanted a pastor just like<br>
this man.  <br>
<p>
But then I thought a bit more:  What, if anything, was necessarily wrong<br>
with the church of the 70's?  We speak of the failed techniques of the past,<br>
but have they failed because they were essentially flawed or because people<br>
just stopped trying them?  I suspect the latter, because if we look in <br>
the Black and Spanish churches of today, these techniques are still being<br>
used and are flourishing.  In the early 70's the above pastor was part<br>
of a city-wide Voice of Prophecy effort where churches of both conferences<br>
cooperated.  The church growth which grew out of that hasn't been seen <br>
in that town in the twenty years since that time.  <br>
<p>
As the "new ideas" people claim that it is time for change, we need to <br>
ask as did Clara Peller and Walter Mondale, "Where's the beef?"  We need <br>
to remember that sometimes the older generation is resistant to change<br>
because they have seen the old ways work and know they could work again<br>
if given new blood.<br>
<p>
Often inside churches such as the one above I am forced to turn on my<br>
"Affirm" mode and continuously mutter to myself that these folks are<br>
my brothers and sisters in the Lord and that their way of worship is no <br>
better or worse than mine.  After such a weekend I think that this process<br>
is probably good for me.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
