<title>Sep_1992: Translation Faith</title>
<h1>Translation Faith</h1>
Nancy Vyhmeister (<i>vyhmeist@susan.cs.andrews.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 29 Sep 92 17:13:26 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#201">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#201">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#201">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#201">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0202.html">Daniel D Deavours: "Re: Motivations for Translation Faith"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0200.html">David Plaisted: "Church where you grew up"</a>
<li> <b>In reply to:</b> <a href="0206.html">Steven Timm: "Motivations for Translation Faith"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0128.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Re: Translation Faith"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Do I understand that there are two sets of divine expectations?  One is<br>
for those who get run over by a train two weeks after meeting Christ--and<br>
really, the standard is only to have accepted Christ's grace and forgiveness.<br>
The other is for those who have the fortune--whether good or bad--to be alive<br>
in the end days: total perfection and ability to stand on their own during<br>
the time of trouble.<br>
<p>
I'm troubled about the dichotomy.  Does this make for first and second class<br>
citizens?  Does God have different rulers to measure us by?  Is it not pre-<br>
sumption to think that I can do anything by myself, let alone depend on myself,<br>
with no help from Christ, during the time of trouble?  <br>
<p>
Do we really understand what it means to be without a mediator?  In the Old<br>
Testament times Christ was not functioning as now in the Sanctuary, yet we are<br>
clearly told that all the OT worthies were saved as they depended on Christ.<br>
<p>
Nancy<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
