<title>Sep_1992: Did NT Apostles worry about attaing perfection?</title>
<h1>Did NT Apostles worry about attaing perfection?</h1>
cheryl berthelsen (<i>cherylb@csd4.csd.uwm.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 29 Sep 92 09:34:59 -0500</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#203">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#203">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#203">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#203">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0204.html">Steven Timm: "America Online, Genie, Prodigy"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0202.html">Daniel D Deavours: "Re: Motivations for Translation Faith"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
SDAnet,<br>
<p>
Perhaps one reason there have not been many posts on the issue of perfection<br>
before translation is because this doctrine is under doubt by many SDAs.  I<br>
have had at least 4 SDA pastors tell me they personally could not teach this<br>
doctrine because of their own personal doubts but they had not come out with<br>
a public denouncement of it for obvious reasons.<br>
<p>
One reason I began to doubt this doctrine myself was the fact that the NT<br>
apostles did not seem to be concerned about attaining perfection.  Thye<br>
(They) sincerely believed the Jesus Christ would return very soon (in their<br>
generation).  But none of these seem to be preoccupied with purging their<br>
personal lives of sin.  Rather, they were feverishly trying to fulfill the<br>
gospel commission--to take the gospel to every tongue, kindred, and people.<br>
<p>
Paul aptly describes the human condition in Romans 3:9-18:<br>
<p>
	What then?  are we better than they?  No, in no wise:  for we<br>
	have before proved both Jews and Gentiles, that they are all<br>
	under sin;  AS IT IS WRITTEN&lt; THERE IS NONE RIGHTEOUS, NO, NOT<br>
	ONE;  There is none that understandeth, there is none that<br>
	seeketh after God.  They are all gone out of the way, they are<br>
	together become unprofitable; THERE IS NONE THAT DOETH GOOD, NO<br>
	NOT ONE.  Their throat is an open sepulchre; with their tongues<br>
	they have used deceit;  the poison of asps is under their lips;<br>
	Whose mouth is full of cursing and bitterness; Their feet are<br>
	swift to shed blood:  Destruction and misery are in their ways:<br>
	And the way of peave have they not known; There is no fear of<br>
	God before their eyes.<br>
<p>
Paul also laments his own weaknesses and shortcomings.  He knows he is<br>
fully committed to the gospel of Jesus Christ yet finds himself failing.<br>
This is during the supposed "last generation".<br>
<p>
I believe that all Christians need to quit introspecting about their<br>
personal spiritual condition and just live a victorious Christian life.<br>
Seek forgiveness when we fail, repenting of cherished personal sin, and<br>
moving toward fulfilling the great gospel commission.  Does it really<br>
matter to individuals whether they believe perfection is attainable on<br>
this earth or NOT?  If we look towards ourselves rather than our Savior<br>
we will certainly lose.  I believe this net discuss then meaning of the<br>
word perfection in the past.  The fact that it means complete for the<br>
level of development, whole rather than deformed.  Thus we can all be<br>
perfect in complete submission to Christ.  We can all be whole in perfect<br>
love for Him.  The application of the word to being "sinless, not sinnig<br>
(sinning) anymore" cannot be supported by the Bible.  Look to the Bible<br>
and find out what it, not the writings of other writers.<br>
<p>
Cheryl<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
