<title>Sep_1992: Re:  Nancy's comments on translation faith</title>
<h1>Re:  Nancy's comments on translation faith</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Tue, 29 Sep 1992 20:49:34 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#205">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#205">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#205">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#205">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0206.html">Steven Timm: "Motivations for Translation Faith"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0204.html">Steven Timm: "America Online, Genie, Prodigy"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0210.html">Victor Ortiz: "Adam &amp; Eve"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Nancy Vyhmeister raises some good points.  I can't speak for what Ruben <br>
is arguing--if I understand his point correctly he would probably say that<br>
the standard of complete and total obedience is required of everyone.<br>
<p>
On the other hand, I was implying almost what Nancy has accused me of<br>
implying.  The whole question I am trying to ask is "Are there extra <br>
requirements on those who will be translated alive, which have nothing<br>
to do with their salvation?"<br>
<p>
And everyone is answering "No, in whatever age you are only saved by faith."<br>
<p>
Now I say again, "Could it be that the issues of translation and salvation<br>
are separate issues?  Could it be that sanctification and salvation are<br>
separate issues?"  In Adventist circles (as with almost all other circles)<br>
we tend to focus myopically on our own salvation and ignore all other <br>
matters as unimportant.  <br>
<p>
Please, if I am wrong and these things are not separate, let me know.<br>
But don't answer questions that I'm not asking.<br>
<p>
Now to what Cheryl said--a very enlightened comment.  The apostles<br>
didn't sit and write about whether they  were perfect or not.  They<br>
spent their time <br>
serving others and sharing the gospel with them.  In my mind, this is the<br>
perfect expression of perfection, being able to love God and your neighbor<br>
as yourself.  So we find that perfection may at times best be attained <br>
through neglect of thought on the topic.<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
