<title>Sep_1992: Motivations for Translation Faith</title>
<h1>Motivations for Translation Faith</h1>
Steven Timm (<i>st0o+@andrew.cmu.edu</i>)<br>
<i>Mon, 28 Sep 1992 21:59:40 -0400 (EDT)</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#206">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#206">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#206">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#206">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0207.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Translation Faith - 2 standards"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0205.html">Steven Timm: "Re:  Nancy's comments on translation faith"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
<li> <b>Next in thread:</b> <a href="0201.html">Nancy Vyhmeister: "Translation Faith"</a>
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
The only two people that have really posted much on this, (me and Ruben)<br>
seem to agree that the time of the end while we are living without a <br>
mediator in the heavenly sanctuary will require a special kind of<br>
righteousness, a full and complete salvation from sin which most of us<br>
do not yet possess.  Most of us are also acquainted with statements from<br>
Ellen G.<br>
White which indicate that some of those for whom the time of trouble would<br>
be too traumatic will die shortly before the time of trouble.<br>
<p>
Two attitudes can arise from this knowledge, and I have personally heard <br>
them both.<br>
<p>
(1)  I could never be ready for the time of trouble, so I hope I die <br>
before it ever comes.<br>
<p>
(2)  I want to get all sin out of my life so I can go straight to heaven<br>
and not go via the "Underground Railroad" (death).<br>
<p>
So we are faced with a dilemma:  Not only should we seek to have Christ work<br>
in our lives, but it needs to be for the right reasons, not the selfish<br>
ones listed above.  Ideas on how to resolve this?<br>
<p>
Steve Timm<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
