<title>Sep_1992: Translation Faith - 2 standards</title>
<h1>Translation Faith - 2 standards</h1>
Ruben Gonzalez (<i>ruben@ee.uts.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 30 Sep 92 14:10:06 EST</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#207">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#207">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#207">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#207">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0208.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Did NT Apostles worry about attaing perfection?"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0206.html">Steven Timm: "Motivations for Translation Faith"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Hi all,<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Do I understand that there are two sets of divine expectations?  </i><br>
<p>
Nope there has only ever been 1 divine expectation, the same that<br>
was expected of Adam, perfect obedience to the law of God.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;One is</i><br>
<i>&gt;for those who get run over by a train two weeks after meeting Christ--and</i><br>
<i>&gt;really, the standard is only to have accepted Christ's grace and forgiveness.</i><br>
<p>
<p>
However the condition of salvation is the acceptance of the GRACE of God <br>
through faith as manifest in His Son. This grace not only forgives<br>
but transforms those who permit it into the likeness of Christ thus<br>
enabling them to conform to the divine expectation.<br>
<p>
<p>
<i>&gt;The other is for those who have the fortune--whether good or bad--to be alive</i><br>
<i>&gt;in the end days: total perfection and ability to stand on their own during</i><br>
<i>&gt;the time of trouble.</i><br>
<p>
Nope ! nobody has or ever will be able to "stand on their own".<br>
It is only "Christ in you" those who can say for a truth "nevertheless<br>
I live, yet not I but Christ who liveth in me." that will stand<br>
in that day. Not in their own strength but in Christ's revealing to the <br>
world the power of Christ to save from all sin. Does not Paul make this <br>
very clear in Rom 7 and 8 that man/woman in his/her own strenght <br>
(I alone/ego autos) [Rom 7:25] can never obey the law of God, however in <br>
Christ [Rom 8:1]  all things are possible.<br>
<p>
And it is a priviledge to live in those day when God's power will be so <br>
manifest. Don't we wish to overcome sin through God's power, what greater<br>
blessing could God give.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;I'm troubled about the dichotomy.  Does this make for first and second class</i><br>
<i>&gt;citizens?  Does God have different rulers to measure us by? </i><br>
There is no dichitomy those who are really saved by grace will experience<br>
God's transforming power. Those who are not transformed by God's grace<br>
simply have not experienced it. In that time when God's grace will be poured<br>
out without measure upon His children, their transformation will be complete<br>
into His own likeness.<br>
<p>
It is the same ruler, the condition is to be on that path which Isa says<br>
"shineth more and more unto the perfect day". Whether we have just begun this<br>
journey or have nearly completed it does not determine salvation. Being on that<br>
path does. Did not JEsus teach this very thing with His parable of the 11th<br>
hour labourers, the amount of work completed by the labourers was not important<br>
the important thing was that they had done work and all received the same<br>
wages.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt; Is it not pre-</i><br>
<i>&gt;sumption to think that I can do anything by myself, let alone depend on myself,</i><br>
<i>&gt;with no help from Christ, during the time of trouble?  </i><br>
<p>
Yep presumption indeed. Who said anything about doing anything by ourselves ?<br>
I certainly did not, neither does EGW. Lets not impose our own preconceptions.<br>
<p>
Only as Christ dwells in your heart "making you to will and to do of His good <br>
pleasure" (can't remember ref, in NT) does not Isa 26:12 say<br>
<p>
"Lord thou wilt ordain peace for us: for thou has wrought all our works in us"<br>
<p>
In fact read all of Isa 26 because it certainly is refering to this very time<br>
we speak about.<br>
<p>
So how many righteous works does a person do of him/herself. None. <br>
However when Christ lives in us, He does the works in us, without<br>
Christ we can do nothing.<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Do we really understand what it means to be without a mediator?  In the Old</i><br>
<i>&gt;Testament times Christ was not functioning as now in the Sanctuary, yet we are</i><br>
<i>&gt;clearly told that all the OT worthies were saved as they depended on Christ.</i><br>
<p>
No, He was not functioning as now in the most holy place you are correct,<br>
but they certainly did not live through the close of probation either.<br>
<p>
They were saved - like Enoch by faith in God's grace just like us. How <br>
do you think Enoch attained perfection of character ? He certainly did not<br>
do it by himself, relying on his own efforts apart from God.<br>
<p>
<p>
<p>
Ruben<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
