<title>Sep_1992: Broadening our mission</title>
<h1>Broadening our mission</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>30 Sep 1992 17:07:40 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#209">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#209">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#209">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#209">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0210.html">Victor Ortiz: "Adam &amp; Eve"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0208.html">Ruben Gonzalez: "Did NT Apostles worry about attaing perfection?"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Mime-Version: 1.0<br>
<p>
Steve writes:<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
What, if anything, was necessarily wrong<br>
with the church of the 70's?  We speak of the failed techniques of the past,<br>
but have they failed because they were essentially flawed or because people<br>
just stopped trying them?  I suspect the latter, because if we look in <br>
the Black and Spanish churches of today, these techniques are still being<br>
used and are flourishing.  In the early 70's the above pastor was part<br>
of a city-wide Voice of Prophecy effort where churches of both conferences<br>
cooperated.  The church growth which grew out of that hasn't been seen <br>
in that town in the twenty years since that time.  <br>
<p>
As the "new ideas" people claim that it is time for change, we need to <br>
ask as did Clara Peller and Walter Mondale, "Where's the beef?"  We need <br>
to remember that sometimes the older generation is resistant to change<br>
because they have seen the old ways work and know they could work again<br>
if given new blood.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
Dave adds:<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
I agree with your thought -- not necessarily your opinion -- that the<br>
techniques of the 70's were not flawed.  If tried now they still work,<br>
and produce more dedicated church members than those drawn in by<br>
other methods that I see used now.<br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
<p>
Now my turn:<br>
<p>
As Steve said, the traditional approach is clearly still extremely <br>
successful, as evidenced by the strong church growth amongst Black and<br>
Spanish churches where this approach is usually taken.<br>
<p>
Dave points out that people who are converted by the traditional techniques<br>
tend to be more dedicated to the church. I would propose that this is a<br>
function of the people rather than of the way they were witnessed to.<br>
<p>
Take the example of the traditional SDA evangelist who emphatically preaches<br>
on prophecy and end-time events. He is clearly convinced that what he is<br>
saying is right, and by his own personal charisma and the influence of the<br>
Holy Spirit others are often convinced of the same thing. Some people respond<br>
extremely well to this kind of approach, which goes from strength to strength<br>
and is confident and clear all the way.<br>
<p>
Others will look on and judge the evangelist to be dogmatic, one-sided and<br>
unrealistic. They will notice that he makes no bones about the fact that his<br>
view is the only correct one, and that others are clearly wrong. The absence<br>
of contentious issues will be noticed by them, and they will wonder whether<br>
the evangelist has ever considered these issues from all directions.<br>
<p>
Those converted by the evangelist will be very clear on what they believe,<br>
and will probably be very committed to Christ and the church. They will be<br>
the sort of people who like to hear a good traditional Adventist sermon from<br>
the pulpit, one that reminds them that they are right in their beliefs and<br>
that the SDA church is God's remnant faithful few. Disagreements over various<br>
areas of belief will confuse and upset these people, as they know how good<br>
it is to feel sure of what you believe.<br>
<p>
The others, those who didn't really identify with the evangelist, may become<br>
converted through another means. Perhaps it will be through a fine Christian<br>
friend they have who is willing to discuss things with them. Either way, these<br>
people are by nature always searching and testing. Although the onlooker may<br>
judge them to be less committed to the church than the more dogmatic believer,<br>
they tend to have a very strong personal faith which is not upset by small<br>
differences, and which is open to examination.<br>
<p>
I think there is a place for everyone in God's church, and I don't think he<br>
expects any of us to suddenly become somebody we're not. He created us<br>
individuals. By insisting that the old ways are the only ways, we are<br>
restricting our witness to the sorts of people who respond to those ways.<br>
By insisting that the old ways are outdated and that we must change, we are<br>
again narrowing our focus to particular kinds of people.<br>
<p>
Interestingly, the church progressed for many years using only certain types<br>
of evangelism. We should hardly be surprised when those who were converted<br>
during that time insist that the old ways are the best ways! I suspect that<br>
much of the motivation for trying new things is coming from people who<br>
were born into the church rather than being converted into it.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
