<title>Sep_1992: Re: Biblical Perfection</title>
<h1>Re: Biblical Perfection</h1>
Mark T Brower (<i>mtb@cblpo.att.com</i>)<br>
<i>Wed, 30 Sep 92 16:25 EDT</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#211">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#211">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#211">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#211">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0212.html">Tony: "Re: Adam and Eve"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0210.html">Victor Ortiz: "Adam &amp; Eve"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
<i>&gt;I'm sorry Cheryl but I just can not ignore the scripture when the Apostles,</i><br>
<i>&gt;Paul and Jesus say : </i><br>
<p>
<i>&gt;1 John 3:1 "My little children, these things I write unto you that</i><br>
<i>&gt;	     you sin not."</i><br>
<p>
..... (Lots of biblical references deleted for brevity.)<br>
<p>
<i>&gt;Ruben.</i><br>
<p>
{Ruben, please don't take this as a personal attack, I'm just trying<br>
to post a warning for all Christians.  I am just using this verse of<br>
this posting as an example of a bigger danger.}<br>
<p>
We've got to be more careful how we handle the Scriptures than this.<br>
We all know the dangers of taking verses out of context, yet it is so<br>
easy to do (I know that I often do it also, I only have certain verses<br>
memorized).<br>
<p>
In context, I John is much more complex than this posting would imply.<br>
For example, in 1:8-2:2, John specifically states that everyone sins.<br>
Anyone who won't admit it is deceiving themselves.<br>
<p>
Later, in 3:6, it says "No one who abides in Him sins; no one who sins<br>
has seen Him or knows Him." <br>
<p>
 From this we have very few options: either we assume that John was a<br>
schizophrenic who should have been locked up rather than followed as<br>
an Apostle (clearly an untenable position for a Christian who has <br>
already examined the truth of what the Bible claims).<br>
<p>
Or we assume that there is a complexity here that must be investigated<br>
to truly understand what John was getting at.  (The few commentaries <br>
that I've read state that this should be read as a reaction to the <br>
Gnostic heresy.)<br>
<p>
<p>
Bottom line:<br>
<p>
I'm pretty sure that this is what Cheryl was getting at when she<br>
talked about how perfection is viewed in the Bible - it's a complex<br>
subject, but (now my turn to quote verses out of context ;-) as<br>
James 3:2 says:<br>
<p>
	"For we all stumble in many ways.  If anyone does not stumble<br>
	 in what he says, he is a perfect man, able to bridle the<br>
	 whole body as well."<br>
<p>
Mark Brower<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
