<title>Sep_1992: Re: Adam and Eve</title>
<h1>Re: Adam and Eve</h1>
Tony (<i>PHTH1@cc.newcastle.edu.au</i>)<br>
<i>01 Oct 1992 08:34:34 +1000</i>
<p>
<ul>
<li> <b>Messages sorted by:</b> <a href="date.html#212">[ date ]</a><a href="index.html#212">[ thread ]</a><a href="subject.html#212">[ subject ]</a><a href="author.html#212">[ author ]</a>
<!-- next="start" -->
<li> <b>Next message:</b> <a href="0213.html">Steven Timm: "With this message we break the record"</a>
<li> <b>Previous message:</b> <a href="0211.html">Mark T Brower: "Re: Biblical Perfection"</a>
<!-- nextthread="start" -->
</ul>
<!-- body="start" -->
Mime-Version: 1.0<br>
<p>
----&gt;<br>
Question:<br>
  Does anybody know if Adam and/or Eve ever sinned on a "lesser" scale before <br>
they ate from the forbidden fruit.  <br>
&lt;----<br>
<p>
Let's see, sin is an inner state of being which is outwardly manifested as<br>
actions known as sins. Eve and Adam eating the forbidden fruit was an<br>
action which demonstrated their choice to distrust God's words to them<br>
and hence to disobey him.<br>
<p>
Why was Eve off near the tree in the first place? Could it be that she was<br>
already distrusting God's words? Perhaps the sin was creeping in to Adam<br>
and Eve's lives before they even left one another's side.<br>
<p>
It seems to me that the serpent could only have cultivated thoughts which<br>
were already present. This being the case, the eating of the fruit was the<br>
final display in Adam and Eve's small yet devastating display of independence<br>
from God. Whether or not any of their actions prior to this had indicated<br>
what was going on internally...well that was the question, wasn't it!<br>
<p>
This concept of being sinful without sinning...it has interesting implications<br>
in the "translation faith" discussion as well.<br>
<p>
Tony<br>
<!-- body="end" -->
<p>
